{"title_page": "Eric Garcetti", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Garcetti|his father, the former district attorney of Los Angeles County|Gil Garcetti|the U. S. Supreme Court case in which his father was lead complainant|Garcetti v. Ceballos}}\n{{short description|Mayor of Los Angeles}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Eric Garcetti\n|image        = Eric Garcetti in Suit and Tie.jpg\n|office       = 42nd [[Mayor of Los Angeles]]\n|term_start   = July 1, 2013\n|term_end     = \n|predecessor  = [[Antonio Villaraigosa]]\n|successor    = \n|office1      = [[President of the Los Angeles City Council]]\n|term_start1  = January 1, 2006\n|term_end1    = January 12, 2012\n|predecessor1 = [[Alex Padilla]]\n|successor1   = [[Herb Wesson]]\n|office2      = Member of the [[Los Angeles City Council]]<br>from the [[Los Angeles City Council District 13|13th]] district\n|term_start2  = July 1, 2001\n|term_end2    = July 1, 2013\n|predecessor2 = [[Jackie Goldberg]]\n|successor2   = [[Mitch O'Farrell]]\n|birth_name   = Eric Michael Garcetti\n|birth_date   = {{birth date|1971|2|4}}\n|birth_place  = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n|death_date   = {{death date|2020|4|26}} (aged 49)\n|death_place  = [[Buena Park, California]]\n|party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse       = {{marriage|Amy Wakeland|January 4, 2009}}\n|children     = 1\n|father       = [[Gil Garcetti]]\n|residence    = [[Getty House]]\n|education    = [[Columbia University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]], [[Master of International Affairs|MIA]])<br>[[The Queen's College, Oxford|Queen's College, Oxford]]<br>{{nowrap|[[London School of Economics]]}}\n|signature    = Eric Garcetti Signature.png\n|website      = {{url|lamayor.org|Government website}}<br>{{url|ericgarcetti.com|Campaign website}}\n|allegiance   = {{flag|United States}}\n|branch       = {{naval|United States}}\n|serviceyears = 2005\u20132013\n|rank         = {{Dodseal|USNO3|25}} [[Lieutenant (navy)|Lieutenant]]\n|unit         = [[Information Warfare Corps|Information Dominance Corps]]<br>[[United States Navy Reserve|U.S. Navy Reserve]]\n}}\n'''Eric Michael Garcetti''' (born February 4, 1971) is an American politician serving as the 42nd and current [[mayor of Los Angeles]] since 2013. A member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], he was first elected in the [[2013 Los Angeles mayoral election|2013 election]] and won reelection in [[2017 Los Angeles mayoral election|2017]]. A former member of the [[Los Angeles City Council]], Garcetti served as [[President of the Los Angeles City Council|council president]] from 2006 to 2012. He is the city's first elected [[American Jews|Jewish]] mayor, its youngest mayor in history, and its second consecutive [[Mexican Americans|Mexican American]] mayor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newsok.com/article/feed/560798/la-mayor-elect-eric-garcetti-at-a-glance|title=LA mayor-elect Eric Garcetti at a glance|date=June 30, 2013|accessdate=August 16, 2018|publisher=Associated Press}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nGarcetti was born on February 4, 1971 at [[Good Samaritan Hospital (Los Angeles)|Good Samaritan Hospital]]<ref name=\"PressReleases\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ericgarcetti.com/eric_garcetti_announces_run_mayor |title=Eric Garcetti Announces Run for L.A. Mayor |date=September 8, 2011 |website=Eric Garcetti \u2013 Los Angeles Mayor 2013 |accessdate=October 20, 2013 |quote=A fourth-generation Angeleno, Garcetti was born at Good Samaritan Hospital and was raised in the San Fernando Valley.&nbsp;...&nbsp; He also studied as a Rhodes Scholar at Oxford University and the London School of Economics and was a Rockefeller Foundation Next Generation Leadership Fellow. He taught public policy, diplomacy and world affairs at Occidental College and the University of Southern California before being elected to the City Council. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130519182221/http://www.ericgarcetti.com/eric_garcetti_announces_run_mayor |archivedate=May 19, 2013 }}</ref> in Los Angeles and was raised in [[Encino, Los Angeles|Encino]],<ref name=\"LAT\" /> in the [[San Fernando Valley]].<ref name=\"PressReleases\" /> He is the son of Sukey (n\u00e9e Roth) and [[Gil Garcetti]], the former [[Los Angeles County District Attorney]].\n\nGarcetti's paternal grandfather, Salvador, was born in [[Parral, Chihuahua]], Mexico. Salvador was brought by his family to the United States as a child after his father, Massimo \"Max\" Garcetti, was murdered by hanging during the [[Mexican Revolution]]. Max had [[Italian immigration to Mexico|immigrated to Mexico]] from [[Italy]], where he married a Mexican woman and became a judge.<ref name=\"Forward\">{{cite news |last=Weiner |first=Rex |date=October 7, 2011 |title=Jews and Latinos Seek Common Ground |url=http://forward.com/articles/143986/jews-and-latinos-seek-common-ground |newspaper=[[The Forward|The Jewish Daily Forward]] |location=New York City |publisher=Forward Association |accessdate=October 20, 2013 |quote=Garcetti is the product of an Italian\u2013Mexican marriage on his paternal side, while his maternal Russian Jewish grandparents founded Louis Roth Clothing, the first union shop in L.A.'s garment industry.}}</ref><ref name=\"JewishJournal\">{{cite news |last=Boyarsky |first=Bill |date=December 19, 2012 |title=Eric Garcetti: up close |url=http://www.jewishjournal.com/bill_boyarsky/article/eric_garcetti_up_close |newspaper=[[The Jewish Journal of Greater Los Angeles]] |access-date=October 20, 2013 |quote=His father, Gil Garcetti, the former district attorney, is of Mexican and Italian descent. His mother, the former Sukey Roth, is Jewish.}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news |last=Medina |first=Jennifer |date=October 7, 2013 |title=Garcetti, New Los Angeles Mayor, Reflects Changing City |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/10/08/us/garcetti-new-los-angeles-mayor-reflects-changing-city.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=October 20, 2013 |quote=His father, Gil Garcetti, who as district attorney in the 1990s prosecuted O. J. Simpson, is the son of Mexican immigrants who trace their roots to Italy. Mayor Garcetti's mother's family came from Russia in the early 20th century.}}</ref> His paternal grandmother, Juanita Iberri, was born in [[Arizona]], one of 19 children born to an immigrant father from [[Sonora, Mexico]] and an Arizona-born mother whose father and mother were both Mexican.<ref name=\"LAT\" />\n\nGarcetti's maternal grandparents were from [[History of the Jews in the United States#Immigration of Eastern European Jews|Russian Jewish]] immigrant families.<ref name=\"LAT\">{{cite news |last=Finnegan |first=Michael |date=January 2, 2013 |title=Eric Garcetti invokes Latino-Jewish ancestry in mayor's race |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2013/jan/02/local/la-me-garcetti-mayor-20130102 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |publisher=[[Tribune Company]] |accessdate=May 22, 2013 |quote=Eric's grandfather, Salvador Garcetti, was born in Mexico and grew up in Boyle Heights. Salvador was brought to the United States as a baby after his father, Massimo Garcetti, a judge who had emigrated from Italy, was hanged during the Mexican Revolution that began in 1910, Garcetti says. Eric's grandmother, Juanita Iberri, one of 19 children in a family that migrated from Sonora, Mexico, was born in Arizona.&nbsp;...&nbsp;Garcetti's maternal grandfather, Harry Roth, turned the family's Los Angeles clothing business, Louis Roth & Co., into a major national brand of high-end suits for men.&nbsp;...&nbsp;Garcetti, 41, was raised in Encino and attended a public elementary school at UCLA. From 7th to 12th grade, he went to Harvard, then a private boys' school in Studio City. |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130803052240/http://articles.latimes.com/2013/jan/02/local/la-me-garcetti-mayor-20130102 |archivedate=August 3, 2013 |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"Forward\" /><ref name=\"JewishJournal\" /><ref name=\"NYT\" /> His maternal grandfather, Harry Roth, founded and ran the clothing brand Louis Roth Clothes.<ref name=\"LAT\" />\n\nGarcetti attended elementary school at [[UCLA Lab School]], formerly University Elementary School; and middle and high school at [[Harvard-Westlake School]].<ref name=\"LAT\" /> While in high school, he was a member of the [[Junior State of America]], a national civic engagement and political debate organization for students.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hwchronicle.com/eric-garcetti-88-wins-reelection-as-l-a-mayor/|title=Eric Garcetti \u201988 wins second term as L.A. Mayor|publisher=The Chronicle|date=March 8, 2017|first=Anthony|last=Weinraub|accessdate=October 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\nGarcetti majored in political science and urban planning and received a [[Bachelor of Arts]] from [[Columbia University]] in 1992 as a [[John Jay Scholar]].<ref name=\"Columbia\">{{cite web |url=https://www.college.columbia.edu/news/los-angeles-mayor-eric-garcetti-cc-92-named-speaker-columbia-college-class-day-2015 |title=Mayor Garcetti named speaker college class day 2015 |last=Columbia College |date=February 24, 2015 |website=Columbia College Today |publisher=[[Columbia College, Columbia University]] |accessdate=October 8, 2012}}</ref> During that time, he served on the student council, was president of the [[St. Anthony Hall]] fraternity and literary society, founded the Columbia Urban Experience, and co-wrote and performed in three years of the ''[[Varsity Show]],'' a student-written musical, whose past co-writers include [[Richard Rodgers]], [[Oscar Hammerstein II]], and [[Lorenz Hart]]. He also received a [[Master of International Affairs|Masters of International Affairs]] from the [[School of International and Public Affairs, Columbia University|School of International and Public Affairs]] at [[Columbia University]], graduating in 1993.<ref name=\"Columbia\" /> He met his future wife while they were both studying as [[Rhodes Scholars]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://mobile.nytimes.com/1992/12/07/us/rhodes-scholars-selected-and-half-are-women.html |title=Rhodes Scholars Selected, and Half Are Women |date=1992 |newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Peter|last=Jamison |title=L.A. Mayor Eric Garcetti introduces himself to nation at DNC: 'I'm just your average Mexican American Jewish Italian' |url=https://www.latimes.com/politics/la-na-pol-garcetti-convention-20160728-snap-story.html |website=latimes.com |accessdate=July 30, 2016 |language=English |date=July 28, 2016 |quote=\u2019I\u2019m just your average Mexican-American Jewish Italian\u2019, Garcetti said. A Rhodes scholar who speaks fluent Spanish, he liberally sprinkled his address with Spanish phrases.}}</ref> at [[The Queen's College, Oxford]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/22656413.xml?dids=22656413:22656413&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Feb+20%2C+1995&author=GEORGE+RAMOS&pub=Los+Angeles+Times+(pre-1997+Fulltext)&desc=Prop.+187+Protest+Has+Sympathizers+an+Ocean+Away&pqatl=google |title=Prop. 187 Protest Has Sympathizers an Ocean Away |first=George |last=Ramos |date=February 20, 1995}}</ref> He later studied for a [[PhD]] in ethnicity and nationalism at the [[London School of Economics]].<ref name=\"PressReleases\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.college.columbia.edu/cct/archive/mar_apr10/features0|title=Making Tinseltown Green|first=Justin|last=Clark|work=Columbia College Today|date=April 2010|accessdate=November 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Professional career ==\nPrior to his election to the [[Los Angeles City Council]], Garcetti was a visiting instructor of international affairs at the [[University of Southern California]] and an assistant professor of diplomacy and world affairs at [[Occidental College]].<ref name=\"PressReleases\" /> His academic work focused on ethnic conflict and nationalism in [[Southeast Asia]] and [[Northeast Africa]]. During this time, he published articles and chapters of books on post-conflict societies, [[Eritrea]]n nationalism, and [[Nonviolence|non-violent]] [[Direct action|action]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://us.macmillan.com/regenerationofwartornsocieties/MichaelPugh |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120718163135/http://us.macmillan.com/regenerationofwartornsocieties/MichaelPugh |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-07-18 |title=Regeneration of War-Torn Societies }}</ref> He has served on the California board of [[Human Rights Watch]],<ref name=ourcampaigns>{{cite web|url=https://www.ourcampaigns.com/CandidateDetail.html?CandidateID=64251|title=Eric Garcetti|publisher=Our Campaigns|accessdate=July 2, 2018}}</ref> and currently serves on the [[advisory board]] for [[Young Storytellers Foundation|Young Storytellers]], an arts education nonprofit organization based in Los Angeles.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.youngstorytellers.com/team |title=Our Team \u2013 Young Storytellers |work=Young Storytellers |access-date=May 3, 2017 |language=en-US |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170422035242/https://www.youngstorytellers.com/team/ |archive-date=April 22, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== Los Angeles City Council (2001\u20132013) ==\n[[File:Eric Garcetti.jpg|thumb|Garcetti in December 2009.]]\n\n=== Elections ===\n{{see also|Electoral history of Eric Garcetti}}\n[[Los Angeles City Council District 13|City Council District 13]] was left vacant after incumbent [[Jackie Goldberg]] was elected to the [[California State Assembly|State Assembly]] in 2000. Garcetti ran for the open seat and was elected in 2001, narrowly defeating former city council member [[Michael Woo]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2001/jun/06/news/mn-7152|first1=Patrick|last1=McGreevey|first2=Sue|last2=Fox|title=Garcetti Defeats Woo|work=Los Angeles Times|date=June 6, 2001}}</ref>  He was re-elected again in 2005 and 2009.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/1065936571.xml?dids=1065936571:1065936571&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jun+25%2C+2006&author=James+Verini&pub=Los+Angeles+Times&desc=Style+%26+Culture%3B+SMALL+HOURS%3B+Garcetti%2C+walking+the+talk%3B+Hollywood+hardly+shuts+down+after+dark%2C+and+neither+does+the+councilman+who+represents+it.+Clubs%2C+plays%2C+gallery+openings+--+he+just+likes+getting+out.&pqatl=google |title=Style & Culture; SMALL HOURS; Garcetti, walking the talk; Hollywood hardly shuts down after dark, and neither does the councilman who represents it. Clubs, plays, gallery openings -- he just likes getting out |first=James |last=Verini |date=June 25, 2006}}</ref>\n\n=== Tenure ===\nGarcetti served as council president from January 1, 2006 to January 12, 2012. He was elected by his colleagues to succeed [[Alex Padilla]], who resigned after being elected to the [[California State Senate]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2005/nov/22/local/me-council22 |title=Quiet Transition Seen for Top Post on L.A. Council |first=Patrick|last=McGreevy |date=November 22, 2005 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022182419/http://articles.latimes.com/2005/nov/22/local/me-council22 |archivedate=October 22, 2012 |df= }}</ref> He was one of the first elected officials in Los Angeles to hold \"office hours\" each month, where constituents can meet with him face-to-face. He implemented a \"Constituent Bill of Rights\" that ensures that constituents' phone calls are returned within a single workday, that constituents are included in all land-use decisions in their neighborhood, and that all constituent concerns are tracked on a computer system that details all actions taken on that particular case.<ref>[https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/10/07/100-days-mayor-eric-garcetti_n_4059448.html \"After 100 Days in Office, LA Mayor Eric Garcetti Gets High Marks\"], ''[[Los Angeles Daily News]]'', October 7, 2013 (via ''[[The Huffington Post]]'').</ref> He ensured that the meetings started on time,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/A+NEW+COURSE+FOR+CITY+COUNCIL+ON-TIME+START+GETS+GARCETTI+PLAN+GOING-a0141304649 |title=A new course for city council on-time start gets garcetti plan going |first=Rick|last=Orlov |date=January 12, 2006 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Daily News]]}}</ref> and all past meetings were made available online. He has also helped more than 1,500 local constituents learn about the governmental process by hosting Government and Planning 101 courses throughout the city.<ref>[http://edpadgett.blogspot.com/2013/04/taking-education-in-los-angeles.html \"Taking Education in Los Angeles Personally\"], ''Los Angeles Times'', April 11, 2013.</ref>\n\n==== Environmental issues ====\nIn 2004, Garcetti authored Proposition O,<ref name=\"SmartVoter\">{{cite web |url=http://www.smartvoter.org/2004/11/02/ca/la/meas/O |title=Measure O: Clean Water, Ocean, River, Beach, Bay Storm Water Cleanup Measure |publisher=Smartvoter.org |accessdate=May 22, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131103182919/http://smartvoter.org/2004/11/02/ca/la/meas/O/ |archivedate=November 3, 2013 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://lacitypropo.org/about.php | title=Prop O | publisher=City of Los Angeles | work=Bureau of Engineering, Department of Public Works | accessdate=July 20, 2019}}</ref> a county stormwater bond which sought to clean the city's waterways. Voters approved the bond with just over 76% of the vote, making it the largest clean water bond in the United States.<ref name=\"SmartVoter\" />\n\nIn 2005, Garcetti helped found the Los Angeles Neighborhood Land Trust. He authored two of the nation's most far-reaching municipal green building ordinances: the first requires all city buildings to be built to the [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design|LEED-certified standard]], and the second mandates that all [[commercial buildings]] of more than {{convert|50000|sqft|m2|abbr=on}} in Los Angeles be built to a LEED standard. He supported changes in the city's landscape ordinance and plumbing codes to promote water conservation.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.asla.org/uploadedFiles/CMS/Media/News_Releases/EricGarcettiNomination.pdf |title=Honorary  Membership \u2013 Nomination  Narrative |publisher=[[American Society of Landscape Architects]] |accessdate=June 29, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180630085623/https://www.asla.org/uploadedFiles/CMS/Media/News_Releases/EricGarcettiNomination.pdf |archivedate=June 30, 2018 |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn July 2010, Garcetti, then council president, weakened a 2009 lawn watering ordinance, allowing watering three days per week instead of two. The ordinance restricting watering to two days a week had been passed 13 months earlier by Mayor [[Antonio Villaraigosa]]. While it helped the city cut its water use and cope with ongoing [[Droughts in California|drought]], the measure was unpopular and was accused of causing pressure fluctuations and water main breaks. A ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' editorial said that the city council's changes to the watering ordinance was a \"death knell for one of the best collective environmental efforts made by the citizens of Los Angeles\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2010/jul/27/opinion/la-oe-green-watering-20100727 |work=Los Angeles Times |first=Emily |last=Green |title=Politics and water conservation |date=July 27, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121111114052/http://articles.latimes.com/2010/jul/27/opinion/la-oe-green-watering-20100727 |archivedate=November 11, 2012 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==== Urban development ====\nGarcetti worked to have [[Historic Filipinotown, Los Angeles|Historic Filipinotown]] designated a [[Preserve America]] [[List of Preserve America Communities|Community]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bakitwhy.com/articles/first-lady-michelle-obama-designates-los-angeles%E2%80%99-historic-filipinotown-preserve-america |title=First Lady Michelle Obama Designates Los Angeles' Historic Filipinotown a Preserve America Community |publisher=BakitWhy |date=October 31, 2011 |accessdate=May 22, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120730224044/http://www.bakitwhy.com/articles/first-lady-michelle-obama-designates-los-angeles%E2%80%99-historic-filipinotown-preserve-america |archivedate=July 30, 2012 |df= }}</ref> He championed renovating the [[Hollywood Palladium]] by [[Live Nation Entertainment]], which was at risk of being demolished.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2007/apr/12/local/me-palladium12 |work=Los Angeles Times |first=Valerie |last=Reitman |title=Palladium operator plans major renovation |date=April 12, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121113160357/http://articles.latimes.com/2007/apr/12/local/me-palladium12 |archivedate=November 13, 2012 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://onlyinhollywood.org/hollywood-palladium-historic-status-historic-venue/|title=The Hollywood Palladium: Historic Status for an Historic Venue|first=Genie|last=Davis|work=Only in Hollywood|date=November 2, 2017|accessdate=November 24, 2018}}</ref> He has also faced public scrutiny for developments that unexpectedly demolished and built over cultural and historic landmarks.<ref>[http://www.citywatchla.com/archive/7674-commission-takes-a-dive-for-garcetti \"Commission Takes a Dive for Garcetti\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402121843/http://www.citywatchla.com/archive/7674-commission-takes-a-dive-for-garcetti |date=April 2, 2015 }}, citywatchla.com, October 7, 2014.</ref> One example is three small buildings at historic [[Sunset Junction]] that were demolished to make way for a large condominium development. A spokesperson for Garcetti expressed disappointment that the developer took action without first notifying the city council, which had discussed community concerns.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theeastsiderla.com/2011/09/silver-lake-demolition-takes-city-and-neighborhood-leaders-by-surprise |title=Silver Lake demolition takes city and neighborhood leaders by surprise |publisher=The Eastsider LA |accessdate=May 22, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130407195222/http://www.theeastsiderla.com/2011/09/silver-lake-demolition-takes-city-and-neighborhood-leaders-by-surprise/ |archivedate=April 7, 2013 |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn his district, Garcetti helped create the Neighborhood Leadership Institute, which trains constituents to be active citizens,<ref>[https://articles.latimes.com/2013/jan/29/opinion/la-oe-newton-mayoral-race-management-20130129 \"THE L.A. MAYOR'S RACE; Which team will it be?\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402164425/http://articles.latimes.com/2013/jan/29/opinion/la-oe-newton-mayoral-race-management-20130129 |date=2015-04-02 }}</ref> as well as the Uniting Neighborhoods to Abolish Graffiti (UNTAG) program, which has reduced graffiti in his district over 78% in its first four years.<ref name=\"Columbia\" />\n\nDuring his first term, as chair and member of the Housing, Community, and Economic Development Committee, he helped create a $100&nbsp;million [[housing trust fund]]. He has also worked to revitalize the [[Hollywood]] area<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.boston.com/news/nation/articles/2006/05/31/after_years_of_decline_hollywood_is_las_hot_new_address |title=After years of decline, Hollywood is LA's hot new address |first=Christina|last=Almeida |date=May 31, 2006 |newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025102856/http://www.boston.com/news/nation/articles/2006/05/31/after_years_of_decline_hollywood_is_las_hot_new_address/ |archivedate=October 25, 2012 |df= }}</ref> and reform the city business tax.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/03/la-council-eases-business-tax-to-keep-internet-firms-from-bolting.html |title=L.A. City Council eases business tax to keep Internet firms from bolting |first=Phil|last=Willon |date=March 5, 2010 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100308054408/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/03/la-council-eases-business-tax-to-keep-internet-firms-from-bolting.html |archivedate=March 8, 2010 |df= }}</ref>\n\n== Mayor of Los Angeles (2013\u2013present) ==\n[[File:A New Mayor (9347724334).jpg|thumb|200px|Garcetti with his wife, Amy Elaine Wakeland, in June 2013.]]\n\n=== Elections ===\n{{Main|2013 Los Angeles mayoral election|2017 Los Angeles mayoral election}}\nWith incumbent mayor [[Antonio Villaraigosa]] ineligible to run again because of [[term limit]]s, Garcetti declared his candidacy on September 8, 2011.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2011/09/eric-garcetti-mayor-candidate.html |work=Los Angeles Times |title=L.A. Now |date=September 8, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110908171322/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2011/09/eric-garcetti-mayor-candidate.html |archivedate=September 8, 2011 |df= }}</ref> The election was held on March 5, 2013. As no candidate received a majority of the primary votes to be elected outright, the top two finishers (Garcetti and [[Los Angeles City Controller|City Controller]] [[Wendy Greuel]]) advanced to a [[Two-round system|runoff vote]]. Bolstered by the [[United Teachers Los Angeles|Los Angeles Teachers Union]]'s endorsement,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailynews.com/general-news/20130131/teachers-union-backs-eric-garcetti-for-mayor |title=Teachers union backs Eric Garcetti |newspaper=Los Angeles Daily News |date=January 30, 2013 |first=Barbara |last=Jones |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808041227/http://www.dailynews.com/general-news/20130131/teachers-union-backs-eric-garcetti-for-mayor |archivedate=August 8, 2014 }}</ref> \nGarcetti was elected on May 21 with 53.9% of votes, defeating Greuel.<ref name=\"LATimes\">{{cite news |last1=Mehta |first1=Seema |last2=Nelson |first2=Laura J. |date=May 22, 2013 |title=Garcetti wins race for L.A. mayor; Greuel concedes |url=https://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-ln-garcetti-wins-race-for-mayor-20130522,0,6850215.story |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |publisher=[[Tribune Company]] |accessdate=May 22, 2013 |quote=Garcetti will be the first elected Jewish mayor of the city. At 42, he will also be the youngest in more than a century. |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130522122954/http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-ln-garcetti-wins-race-for-mayor-20130522,0,6850215.story |archivedate=May 22, 2013 |df= }}</ref> The next day, he met with Villaraigosa, who worked with him over the rest of his own tenure to better the transition. His term began on July 1, 2013.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-antonio-villaraigosa-congratulates-eric-garcetti-20130522,0,7469415.story |work=Los Angeles Times |first=Catherine |last=Saillant |date=May 22, 2013 |title=Antonio Villaraigosa congratulates Mayor-elect Eric Garcetti |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523161538/http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-antonio-villaraigosa-congratulates-eric-garcetti-20130522,0,7469415.story |archivedate=May 23, 2013 |df= }}</ref>\n\nGarcetti was re-elected with 81.4% of the vote on March 7, 2017. Although he avoided a runoff election this time, [[voter turnout]] was relatively low at 20%.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/local/california/la-me-ln-los-angeles-mayor-election-turnout-20170321-story.html|title=A 20% turnout in L.A.'s mayoral election wasn't a record low after all, final results show|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=2017-11-11|language=en-US}}</ref> Due to a change in the city's election calendar to align mayoral elections with statewide elections, his second term will last for five years and six months instead of the usual four years.<ref name=\"results\">{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-election-losangeles-idUSKBN16F171 |title=Los Angeles mayor wins re-election in landslide |work=Reuters |first=Brendan |last=O'Brien |date=March 8, 2017 |accessdate=March 10, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170310190740/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-election-losangeles-idUSKBN16F171 |archivedate=March 10, 2017 |df= }}</ref>\n\n=== Tenure ===\nGarcetti's tenure as mayor has been described as both [[Progressivism in the United States|progressive]] and [[Pragmatism|pragmatic]].<ref name=\"Reston\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/04/21/politics/eric-garcetti-la-mayor-iowa-south-carolina/index.html|title=Why LA's Mexican-American-Jewish-Italian mayor is spending time in Iowa and South Carolina|first=Maeve|last=Reston|work=CNN|date=April 21, 2018|accessdate=December 13, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/opinion/op-ed/la-oe-nazaryan-deblasio-garcetti-20180105-story.html|title=Let's compare Eric Garcetti and Bill de Blasio|work=Los Angeles Times|first=Alexander|last=Nazaryan|date=January 5, 2018|accessdate=December 13, 2018}}</ref> He cites his method as striking a balance on delivering on liberal goals for the city, while simultaneously taking a more [[Libertarianism in the United States|libertarian]] approach to government reform.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.governing.com/topics/mgmt/gov-eric-garcetti-los-angeles-mayor.html|title=Does Eric Garcetti Have a Big Enough Vision for L.A.?|work=Governing|first=John|last=Buntin|date=August 2014|accessdate=December 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== Budget policy ====\nIn a memo in October 2013, Garcetti instructed department heads to develop a \"starting point\" budget based on the 5% cut from the previous year.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.laweekly.com/informer/2014/05/14/eric-garcettis-first-budget-shows-that-changes-come-slowly-to-la-city-hall |title=Eric Garcetti's First Budget Shows That Changes Come Slowly to L.A. City Hall |date=May 14, 2014 |first=Gene |last=Maddaus |newspaper=LA Weekly |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140515052026/http://www.laweekly.com/informer/2014/05/14/eric-garcettis-first-budget-shows-that-changes-come-slowly-to-la-city-hall |archivedate=May 15, 2014 }}</ref> In April 2014, he unveiled a \"hold-the-line\" budget for the coming fiscal year, which proposed modest increases in a number of city services and zero reduction in the business tax. His financial proposal of $8.1&nbsp;billion required approval from the city council and closed the $242&nbsp;million gap \"in part by relying on increased tax revenue projections and reductions in vacant positions\".<ref name=GarcettiBudget /> That August, he announced he would begin his annual review of every city general manager as part of his commitment to improve accountability among Los Angeles officials.<ref name=citygeneralmanagers>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailynews.com/government-and-politics/20140805/la-mayor-eric-garcetti-begins-performance-reviews-of-city-general-managers |title=L.A. Mayor Eric Garcetti begins performance reviews of city general managers |first=Rick |last=Orlov |newspaper=Los Angeles Daily News |date=August 5, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923230908/http://www.dailynews.com/government-and-politics/20140805/la-mayor-eric-garcetti-begins-performance-reviews-of-city-general-managers |archivedate=September 23, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nThe financial plan assumed the city's workforce, which included police officers and firefighters, would not receive raises in the coming year. One of the proposed changes was to merge the city's police and fire dispatch centers to streamline and improve response time to 911 calls for emergencies and fires. Mayoral aides said such a change would take multiple years to complete.<ref name=GarcettiBudget /> Garcetti said he hoped to increase funding for the [[Los Angeles Police Department]], the department making up nearly 44% of the fund already and most of the increase would go towards new technology for officers.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lopez |first=Andrew |url=http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/Los-Angeles-Mayor-Eric-Garcetti-to-Unveil-Budget-Proposal-255197041.html |title=Los Angeles Mayor Eric Garcetti Unveils Budget Proposal |date=April 14, 2014 |publisher=NBC Southern California |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140505053453/http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/Los-Angeles-Mayor-Eric-Garcetti-to-Unveil-Budget-Proposal-255197041.html |archivedate=May 5, 2014 |df= }}</ref> The plan was scheduled to go into effect on July 1, adding eight hours per week to the city's branch library operations. The number of code enforcement officers assigned to look for unpermitted construction and other neighborhood issues, would increase from 25 to 38. He also announced other changes, such as creating a $1.4&nbsp;million innovation fund to transform city services, breaking the command structure at the [[Los Angeles Fire Department]] into four geographic regions, and hiring 140 firefighters to cope with attrition.<ref name=GarcettiBudget>{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-garcetti-budget-20140414,0,5027977.story#axzz2zTu15QmX |title=Eric Garcetti's 'Back to Basics' budget offers modest service upgrades |date=April 14, 2014 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140417130803/http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-garcetti-budget-20140414,0,5027977.story#axzz2zTu15QmX |archivedate=April 17, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==== Economic policy ====\nIn May 2014, Garcetti announced he was bringing aboard [[Krisztina Holly]] and Amir Tehrani, two [[Entrepreneur in Residence|entrepreneurs in residence]], to develop policies for \"helping business startup and entrepreneurs in Los Angeles grow\". \"We want L.A. to be the leading destination for people starting new businesses, and there are no better guides for our efforts than successful entrepreneurs themselves,\" he said.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://westsidetoday.com/2014/05/03/mayor-eric-garcetti-bring-two-entrepreneurs-residence/ |title=Mayor Eric Garcetti to Bring on Two Entrepreneurs in Residence |publisher=westsidetoday.com |date=May 3, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140503185932/http://westsidetoday.com/2014/05/03/mayor-eric-garcetti-bring-two-entrepreneurs-residence/ |archivedate=May 3, 2014 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailynews.com/government-and-politics/20140502/city-of-los-angeles-now-has-entrepreneurs-in-residence |last=Orlov |first=Rick |title=City of Los Angeles now has \u2018entrepreneurs in residence\u2019 |date=May 2, 2014 |newspaper=Los Angeles Daily News |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140503190009/http://www.dailynews.com/government-and-politics/20140502/city-of-los-angeles-now-has-entrepreneurs-in-residence |archivedate=May 3, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nThat summer, Garcetti met with [[Governor of California]] [[Jerry Brown]] and legislative leaders during his first visit to Sacramento since taking office as mayor. He pushed the governor to expand the current film production tax credit, awarding $100&nbsp;million annually, to stop productions from leaving the state.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-80421604/ |title=In Sacramento, L.A. Mayor Eric Garcetti talks water, film tax credit |date=June 5, 2014 |first=Melanie |last=Mason |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |url-status=live |archiveurl=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20121006015957/http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-80421604/ |archivedate=October 6, 2012 }}</ref> He later reported that Brown had agreed to support expanding the tax credit, though it was unclear how large the expansion would be. He wanted $420&nbsp;million, equal to [[New York (state)|New York's]] credit. The amount was also four times the size of California's current $100&nbsp;million offering.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-81077906 |title=Garcetti sees progress on film tax credit negotiations |first=Chris |last=Megerian |date=August 13, 2014 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |url-status=live |archiveurl=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20121006015957/http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-81077906 |archivedate=October 6, 2012 }}</ref>\n[[File:-RaisetheWageLA (15003971968).jpg|thumb|Garcetti speaking at a rally for increasing the minimum wage in 2014]]\nOn September 1, 2014, Garcetti led a rally at a park in [[South Los Angeles]], where he proposed creating a minimum wage in Los Angeles that could reach $13.25 after three years. He received support from several members of the city council, who would have to approve of the increase. He released an economic analysis, which was prepared by academics at [[University of California, Berkeley]], that stated an \"L.A. wage of $13.25\u2014$4.25 more than the state minimum of $9\u2014would significantly improve the lot of low-income workers and impose minimal burdens on business.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-81237432/ |title=Garcetti calls for boosting minimum wage to $13.25 after three years |first=James |last=Rainey |date=September 1, 2014 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |url-status=live |archiveurl=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20121006015957/http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-81237432/ |archivedate=October 6, 2012 }}</ref> Business leaders warned that boosting pay too quickly could stifle the slowly rebounding local economy (California's minimum wage then was $9, having increased from $8 on July 1). His proposed ordinance would require businesses to increase workers' pay from the state minimum to at least $10.25 in 2015, $11.75 in 2016 and $13.25 in 2017. Beginning in 2018, additional adjustments in Los Angeles would be automatically tied to an inflation index.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-81239079/ |title=Garcetti calls for $13.25 minimum wage by 2017 |date=September 1, 2014 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |url-status=live |archiveurl=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20121006015957/http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-81239079/ |archivedate=October 6, 2012 }}</ref> Later that month, he expressed his support for the city council to vote on a new citywide law requiring large hotels to pay $15.37 an hour, adding that it would not conflict with his drive to raise the city's minimum wage.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailynews.com/government-and-politics/20140919/mayor-eric-garcetti-raising-los-angeles-minimum-wage-is-part-of-an-american-moment |date=September 19, 2014 |first=Dakota |last=Smith |title=Mayor Eric Garcetti: Raising Los Angeles minimum wage is part of 'an American movement' |newspaper=Daily News |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140921060657/http://www.dailynews.com/government-and-politics/20140919/mayor-eric-garcetti-raising-los-angeles-minimum-wage-is-part-of-an-american-moment |archivedate=September 21, 2014 }}</ref> He aligned himself with the [[Fight for 15]] movement when he signed legislation in 2015 to gradually raise the minimum wage in Los Angeles to $15 per hour.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailynews.com/social-affairs/20160701/higher-minimum-wage-goes-into-effect-in-los-angeles |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2017-03-01 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170302115221/http://www.dailynews.com/social-affairs/20160701/higher-minimum-wage-goes-into-effect-in-los-angeles |archivedate=2017-03-02 |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, Garcetti officially proclaimed November 19 to be [[Women's Entrepreneurship Day]] in Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Gv3S6EXmUDw|title=Los Angeles mayor officially names Women's Entrepreneurship Day a celebration in LA!|work=Womens Entrepreneurship Day WED|publisher=[[YouTube]]|date=February 2, 2018|accessdate=October 16, 2018}}</ref> This followed similar declarations made by [[Mayor of New York City|New York City mayor]] [[Bill de Blasio]], [[List of mayors of Philadelphia|Philadelphia mayor]] [[Jim Kenney]], and [[Governor of New York|New York governor]] [[Andrew Cuomo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.womenseday.org/about-us/our-story/|title=Our Story|publisher=Women's Entrepreneurship Day}}</ref>\n\n==== Homelessness====\nA study released in June 2019 by the Los Angeles Homeless Service Authority (LAHSA) found that homelessness compared to the previous year surged by 16 percent to nearly 60,000 homeless on the streets of Los Angeles.<ref name=reutersgarcetti/> Recent legal decisions in the Ninth Circuit limiting enforcement capability of LAPD to remove homeless encampments has contributed to the crisis.  Garcetti responded to the report by saying \u201cSkyrocketing rents statewide and federal disinvestment in affordable housing, combined with an epidemic of untreated trauma and mental illness, is pushing people into homelessness faster than they can be lifted out\u201d.<ref name=reutersgarcetti>{{cite news |last1=Gorman |first1=Steve |title=Los Angeles homelessness rises sharply as housing crisis deepens |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-homeless-losangeles/los-angeles-homelessness-rises-sharply-as-housing-crisis-deepens-idUSKCN1T609L |agency=Reuters |work=Reuters |date=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Immigration policy ====\nIn July 2014, Garcetti announced the Los Angeles Police Department would stop honoring most federal requests for detaining arrestees so they can be investigated for deportation. He stated that Los Angeles was joining with other jurisdictions to end the practice of detaining people for being in the United States illegally with no judicial review and uttered that the detainment policy was expensive to local government and erodes public trust in the police department. \"The federal government has the luxury of waiting to act,\" he said. \"Here at the local level, we are carrying out what the federal government should be doing.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailynews.com/government-and-politics/20140707/garcetti-los-angeles-to-reject-federal-governments-requests-to-detain-immigrants?source=most_viewed |title=Garcetti: Los Angeles to reject federal government's requests to detain immigrants |date=July 7, 2014 |newspaper=Los Angeles Daily News |first=Rick |last=Orlov |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140711150856/http://www.dailynews.com/government-and-politics/20140707/garcetti-los-angeles-to-reject-federal-governments-requests-to-detain-immigrants?source=most_viewed |archivedate=July 11, 2014 }}</ref> Later that month, he confirmed Los Angeles would help shelter immigrant children who have been detained after crossing the border and had begun talks with a federal agency about doing so.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-80812940/ |title=L.A. to help shelter detained immigrant children, Mayor Garcetti says |date=July 15, 2014 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |first=Emily Albert |last=Reyes |url-status=live |archiveurl=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20121006015957/http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-80812940/ |archivedate=October 6, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nGarcetti worked together with [[Los Angeles County Board of Supervisors|Los Angeles County Supervisor]] [[Hilda Solis]] to create the $10 million  L.A. Justice Fund, which provides legal services to illegal immigrants facing deportation.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://ktla.com/2017/04/17/l-a-legal-fund-aims-to-help-immigrants-facing-deportation-draws-criticism-over-who-deserves-representation/ | title=L.A. Legal Fund Aims to Help Immigrants Facing Deportation, Draws Criticism Over Who Deserves Representation | agency=[[Los Angeles Times]] | publisher=[[KTLA]] | date=April 17, 2017 | accessdate=June 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== LAFD relations ====\nIn 2013, Garcetti pledged that 5% of the [[Los Angeles Fire Department]]'s firefighters would be women by 2020. As of 2018, 3.1% of the department's firefighters are women.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fireengineering.com/articles/pt/2018/03/los-angeles-mayor-struggling-to-expand-the-number-of-female-firefighters.html|title=Los Angeles Mayor Struggling to Expand the Number of Female Firefighters|website=www.fireengineering.com}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, 2014, Garcetti responded to criticism of the department's hiring system that eliminated thousands of qualified applicants by announcing he was canceling the process. He said he had \"determined that the Fire Department's recruiting process is fatally flawed\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-lafd-recruit-hiring-changes-20140320,0,5614238.story#axzz2xyC0bC99 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |title=Eric Garcetti scraps LAFD hiring process, says it's 'fatally flawed' |date=March 20, 2014 |first1=Robert J. |last1=Lopez |first2=Ben |last2=Welsh |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140327223725/http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-lafd-recruit-hiring-changes-20140320,0,5614238.story#axzz2xyC0bC99 |archivedate=March 27, 2014 }}</ref> The mayor's office announced that the next scheduled Fire Academy class of 70 cadets would not be held, and that no further hiring would be made from the current civil service list<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.myfoxatlanta.com/story/25037790/mayor-eric-garcetti-halts-flawed-la-fire-dept-recruiting#axzz2yWlrW69z |publisher=FOX 5 |title=Mayor Eric Garcetti Halts Flawed LA Fire Dept. Recruiting |date=March 21, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413142244/http://www.myfoxatlanta.com/story/25037790/mayor-eric-garcetti-halts-flawed-la-fire-dept-recruiting |archivedate=April 13, 2014}}</ref> (nearly 25% of the 70 recruits eventually hired were related to LAFD firefighters).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://ktla.com/2014/03/21/mayor-eric-garcetti-suspends-la-fire-department-recruitment-program/#axzz2yWmx78a5 |date=March 21, 2014 |title=Mayor Eric Garcetti Suspends LA Fire Department Recruit Program |publisher=KTLA |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413142149/http://ktla.com/2014/03/21/mayor-eric-garcetti-suspends-la-fire-department-recruitment-program/#axzz2yWmx78a5 |archivedate=April 13, 2014 |df= }}</ref> It later stated that the [[RAND Corporation]] had been asked to help in reforming the recruiting process.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.myfoxla.com/story/25037790/mayor-eric-garcetti-halts-flawed-la-fire-dept-recruiting |title=Mayor Eric Garcetti Halts Flawed LA Fire Dept. Recruiting |publisher=myFOXla.com |first=Jeffery Thomas |last=DeSocio |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140323085844/http://www.myfoxla.com/story/25037790/mayor-eric-garcetti-halts-flawed-la-fire-dept-recruiting |archivedate=March 23, 2014}}</ref> The decision was met with mixed reception.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://northridge.patch.com/groups/police-and-fire/p/la-fire-department-halts-recruitment-cancels-academy |title=L.A. Fire Department Halts Recruitment, Cancels Academy |date=March 20, 2014 |publisher=City News Service |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140723114641/http://northridge.patch.com/groups/police-and-fire/p/la-fire-department-halts-recruitment-cancels-academy |archivedate=July 23, 2014 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==== Olympic bid ====\n{{Main|Los Angeles bid for the 2024 Summer Olympics}}\nIn July 2016,  Garcetti was part of a 25-person contingent from Los Angeles to [[Rio de Janeiro]] to promote their city's bid for the [[2024 Summer Olympics]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/la-sp-oly-rio-2016-la-2024-brings-large-crew-to-rio-1469996962-htmlstory.html|title=LA 2024 brings large crew to Rio Olympics|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=July 2016|accessdate=July 31, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160731231145/http://www.latimes.com/sports/la-sp-oly-rio-2016-la-2024-brings-large-crew-to-rio-1469996962-htmlstory.html|archivedate=July 31, 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> That November, he led a presentation with six-time gold medalist sprinter [[Allyson Felix]] to an array of Olympic leaders and sports officials at a general assembly for the Association of [[National Olympic Committees]] in [[Doha]], [[Qatar]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2016/11/15/2024-olympics-la/|title=LA Committee Lobbies For 2024 Olympics In Qatar|access-date=May 18, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161223135831/http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2016/11/15/2024-olympics-la/|archivedate=December 23, 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nUltimately, the [[International Olympic Committee]] decided to make [[Paris]] the host of the 2024 games, while awarding Los Angeles the [[2028 Summer Olympics]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wharton|first1=David|title=Los Angeles makes deal to host 2028 Summer Olympics|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/sportsnow/la-sp-2028-olympics-deal-20170731-story.html|website=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=31 July 2017}}</ref> In preparation for hosting the games, Garcetti launched the [[Twenty-eight by '28]] initiative, which gives accelerated priority to the city's most crucial transit infrastructure projects.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sharp |first1=Steven |title=Here are the 28 Projects that Metro Could Complete Before the 2028 Olympics |url=https://urbanize.la/post/here-are-28-projects-metro-could-complete-2028-olympics |accessdate=July 2, 2018 |agency=Urbanize |date=November 27, 2018}}</ref> He also appointed former ambassador [[Nina Hachigian]] as Deputy Mayor for International Affairs to help coordinate the Olympics games as well as broadening the city's global relations in general.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.lamayor.org/mayor-garcetti-names-nina-hachigian-deputy-mayor-international-affairs|title=Mayor Garcetti names Nina Hachigian Deputy Mayor for International Affairs|last=|first=|date=2017-08-04|work=Office of Los Angeles Mayor Eric Garcetti|access-date=2018-01-23|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==== Police relations ====\n[[File:EricMichaelGarcetti.jpg|thumb|Garcetti with police chief [[Charlie Beck]] discussing crime statistics in 2014]]\nIn July 2014, the [[Los Angeles Police Protective League]] stated its plans to file an unfair labor practices complaint with the city's Employee Relations Board to block Garcetti and [[Chief of the Los Angeles Police Department|police chief]] [[Charlie Beck]] from discussing directly with officers the proposed one-year contract that had been previously rejected. The proposal provided $70&nbsp;million in overtime for that year and $50&nbsp;million to buy back some of the $120&nbsp;million in banked overtime while also containing no cost-of-living increase.\nProtective League President Tyler Izen said that while the union understood the mayor's intentions, he believed speaking directly to the officers could violate fair bargaining rules.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailynews.com/government-and-politics/20140722/union-objects-to-la-mayor-eric-garcetti-police-discussing-contract |title=Union objects to L.A. Mayor Eric Garcetti, police discussing contract |first=Rick |last=Orlov |date=July 22, 2014 |newspaper=Los Angeles Daily News |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140726192050/http://www.dailynews.com/government-and-politics/20140722/union-objects-to-la-mayor-eric-garcetti-police-discussing-contract |archivedate=July 26, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nGarcetti found a way around the legal threats by posting a video on [[YouTube]] on July 24, noting that under the proposed contract, salaries for officers hired during the recession would be increased and overtime would no longer be given as time off, instead paid in cash. \"The sacrifices you made on overtime were emergency measures\u2014never intended to be permanent. And I understand the toll these emergency measures have taken. Not just on your pocketbook but on the LAPD as a whole\", Garcetti said.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.scpr.org/news/2014/07/24/45552/mayor-garcetti-turns-to-youtube-to-communicate-dir/ |title=Mayor Garcetti turns to YouTube to communicate directly with LAPD officers about contract (updated) |date=July 24, 2014 |publisher=89.3 KPCC |first=Alice |last=Walton |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808221029/http://www.scpr.org/news/2014/07/24/45552/mayor-garcetti-turns-to-youtube-to-communicate-dir/ |archivedate=August 8, 2014 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.laobserved.com/archive/2014/07/mayor_video_takes_his_mes.php |title=Mayor's video takes his message directly to LAPD officers |first=Kevin |last=Roderick |publisher=LA Observed |date=July 24, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140725200747/http://www.laobserved.com/archive/2014/07/mayor_video_takes_his_mes.php |archivedate=July 25, 2014 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-80895904/ |title=Garcetti uses YouTube to appeal to LAPD officers on contract offer |date=July 24, 2014 |first=Catherine |last=Saillant |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |url-status=live |archiveurl=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20121006015957/http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-80895904/ |archivedate=October 6, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nOther major changes made to the department during Garcetti's tenure include purchasing 7,000 [[body-worn cameras]] for the city's patrol officers<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-mayor-to-announce-onbody-camera-rol-lout-for-lapd-20141216-story.html|title=L.A. will buy 7,000 body cameras for police officers |work=Los Angeles Times |publisher=Tribune Publishing |date=December 16, 2014|accessdate=December 18, 2014}}</ref> as well as adding more than 200 officers to the [[LAPD Metropolitan Division]] to control the crime rate, which had increased in 2014.<ref name=\"State of City: Eric Garcetti to double size of LAPD Metro Division; allow Uber, Lyft at airport\">{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-eric-garcetti-to-double-size-of-lapd-metro-division-20150414-story.html|last1=Jamison|first1=Peter|last2=Alpert Reyes|first2=Emily |title=State of City: Garcetti focuses on public safety; wants Uber, Lyft at airport |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=2015-04-14 |accessdate=2016-04-29}}</ref>\n\n==== Public utilities ====\nGarcetti nominated four new appointees to the Board of Water and Power Commissioners: Jill Banks Barad, Michael F. Fleming, William W. Funderburk Jr., and former [[congressman]] [[Mel Levine]]. The four commissioners were confirmed by the city council on September 11, 2013,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2013/sep/11/local/la-me-dwp-comish-20130912 |work=Los Angeles Times |first=David |last=Zahniser |title=L.A. City Council confirms Mayor Eric Garcetti's DWP commissioners |date=September 11, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20140426120242/http://articles.latimes.com/2013/sep/11/local/la-me-dwp-comish-20130912 |archivedate=April 26, 2014 |df=}}</ref> joining Villaraigosa appointee Christina E. Noonan on the panel.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2013/aug/16/local/la-me-ln-garcetti-dwp-board-20130816 |work=Los Angeles Times |first=David |last=Zahniser |title=Mayor Garcetti moves to 'shake up' DWP with four new board members |date=August 16, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20140429052849/http://articles.latimes.com/2013/aug/16/local/la-me-ln-garcetti-dwp-board-20130816 |archivedate=April 29, 2014 |df=}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2013, Garcetti said he would sign off on a proposed four-year contract with [[Los Angeles Department of Water and Power]] workers. Officials estimated the contract would save $6.1&nbsp;billion over 30 years.<ref name=LADN /> In large part, the deal was expected to save money by cutting the pension benefits of new hires and workers going without raises in pay for three years.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2013/aug/22/local/la-me-dwp-deal-struck-20130823 |date=August 22, 2013 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |title=DWP deal is a mixed win for Eric Garcetti in his 1st duel with labor |first1=David |last1=Zahniser |first2=Catherine |last2=Saillant |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407123432/http://articles.latimes.com/2013/aug/22/local/la-me-dwp-deal-struck-20130823 |archivedate=April 7, 2014 }}</ref> The deal was largely worked out before Garcetti took office the previous month; he initially balked at the contract before coming around when negotiators tweaked the proposal to allow for further talks on the issue.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.laweekly.com/informer/2013/08/22/mayor-eric-garcetti-trumpets-victory-on-new-contract-with-dwp-workers |title=Mayor Eric Garcetti Trumpets Victory on New Contract With DWP Workers |date=August 22, 2013 |first=Gene |last=Maddaus |newspaper=LA Weekly |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714181550/http://www.laweekly.com/informer/2013/08/22/mayor-eric-garcetti-trumpets-victory-on-new-contract-with-dwp-workers |archivedate=July 14, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nGarcetti accepted the agreement due to provisions, which included a labor-management council to review work rules that add to LADWP workers' salaries, a modified health care system and an added pension tier for new workers and a broadened effort to reduce the disparity in pay with other city workers.<ref name=LADN>{{cite news |first=Rick |last=Orlov |url=http://www.dailynews.com/government-and-politics/20130822/la-mayor-eric-garcetti-embraces-dwp-contract |title=L.A. Mayor Eric Garcetti embraces DWP contract |newspaper=Los Angeles Daily News |date=August 22, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407070007/http://www.dailynews.com/government-and-politics/20130822/la-mayor-eric-garcetti-embraces-dwp-contract |archivedate=April 7, 2014 }}</ref> In January 2014, he nominated Marcie Edwards to head the Department of Water and Power,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://abc7.com/archive/9414291/ |publisher=abc7.com |title=ERIC GARCETTI NOMINATES MARCIE EDWARDS TO HEAD LADWP |date=January 30, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140518212647/http://abc7.com/archive/9414291/ |archivedate=May 18, 2014 |df= }}</ref> who was confirmed on February 21.<ref>{{cite news |title=Los Angeles City Council Unanimously Confirms Marcie Edwards as LADWP General Manager |date=February 21, 2014 |publisher=LADWP}}</ref>\n\n==== Race relations ====\n[[File:Snoop Dogg speaking at press conference.jpg|thumb|Garcetti with rappers [[Snoop Dogg]] and [[The Game (rapper)|The Game]] addressing race relations in 2016]]\nIn July 2013, Garcetti called for \"calm in the streets\" after the [[acquittal]] of [[George Zimmerman]] three days earlier. While acknowledging the similarities between the [[Trial of George Zimmerman|Zimmerman case]] and the 1992 [[Rodney King riots]], he insisted the city had come a long way.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/17/us/los-angeles-protests-zimmerman.html?_r=0 |title=Call for Calm as Los Angeles Girds for More Unrest |date=July 16, 2013 |first=Ian |last=Lovett}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2014, the mayor was joined by current and former [[NBA]] players to praise the disciplinary actions taken by the league against [[Los Angeles Clippers|L.A. Clippers]] owner [[Donald Sterling]] for his publicized racist remarks, saying that the remarks \"do not represent Los Angeles\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailynews.com/government-and-politics/20140429/kareem-abdul-jabbar-los-angeles-mayor-eric-garcetti-pleased-with-nbas-lifetime-ban-on-donald-sterling |title=Kareem Abdul-Jabbar, Los Angeles Mayor Eric Garcetti pleased with NBA's lifetime ban on Donald Sterling |newspaper=Los Angeles Daily News |date=April 29, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140503190829/http://www.dailynews.com/government-and-politics/20140429/kareem-abdul-jabbar-los-angeles-mayor-eric-garcetti-pleased-with-nbas-lifetime-ban-on-donald-sterling |archivedate=May 3, 2014 }}</ref> He stated during an interview that the Sterling controversy was \"a defining issue\" for the city and required a strong response from elected leaders.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-80067095/ |title=Sterling furor presents test of L.A. Mayor Eric Garcetti's leadership |date=April 30, 2014 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |url-status=live |archiveurl=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20121006015957/http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-80067095/ |archivedate=October 6, 2012 }}</ref> He stated that he expected Sterling to put up a \"long, protracted fight\" and that his continued ownership could prove harmful to the franchise.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/05/04/eric-garcetti-donald-sterling_n_5263876.html |title=L.A. Mayor Eric Garcetti Foresees Lengthy Battle With Donald Sterling |date=May 4, 2014 |work=Reuters |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140505022124/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/05/04/eric-garcetti-donald-sterling_n_5263876.html |archivedate=May 5, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-garcetti-sterling-sell-clippers-20140504,0,1410762.story#axzz30nv8uw2p |title=Donald Sterling will fight to keep Clippers, Garcetti predicts |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=May 4, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140505055320/http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-garcetti-sterling-sell-clippers-20140504,0,1410762.story#axzz30nv8uw2p |archivedate=May 5, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailynews.com/sports/20140504/los-angeles-mayor-eric-garcetti-believes-donald-sterling-will-fight-clippers-sale |title=Los Angeles Mayor Eric Garcetti believes Donald Sterling will fight Clippers sale |date=May 4, 2014 |newspaper=Los Angeles Daily News |first=Dakota |last=Smith |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140507040935/http://www.dailynews.com/sports/20140504/los-angeles-mayor-eric-garcetti-believes-donald-sterling-will-fight-clippers-sale |archivedate=May 7, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.pasadenastarnews.com/government-and-politics/20140509/mayor-eric-garcetti-opposes-shelly-sterlings-continued-clippers-ownership |last=Smith |first=Dakota |title=Mayor Eric Garcetti opposes Shelly Sterling's continued Clippers ownership |date=May 9, 2014 |newspaper=Pasadena Star-News |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140512232443/http://www.pasadenastarnews.com/government-and-politics/20140509/mayor-eric-garcetti-opposes-shelly-sterlings-continued-clippers-ownership |archivedate=May 12, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn May 2014, Officer Shaun Hillmann received a 65-day suspension after recorded remarks of him referring to an African-American man as a \"monkey\" were aired on television. The next day, Garcetti said Hillmann's statements were \"reprehensible\" and that the officer should have received a \"stiffer\" punishment.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-garcetti-lapd-discipline-20140509-story.html |date=May 9, 2014 |title=Officer accused of racial slur deserved more punishment, Garcetti says |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170224211358/http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-garcetti-lapd-discipline-20140509-story.html |archivedate=February 24, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==== Sustainability ====\nOn his first full day as mayor, Garcetti proclaimed that Los Angeles was beginning to leave behind its culture of [[car ownership]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/13/us/In-Los-Angeles-Where-Car-Is-King-Smartphones-May-Cut-Traffic.html |title=Where Car Is King, Smartphones May Cut Traffic |date=July 12, 2013 |newspaper=New York Times |first=Ian |last=Lovett |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171102180639/http://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/13/us/In-Los-Angeles-Where-Car-Is-King-Smartphones-May-Cut-Traffic.html |archivedate=November 2, 2017 }}</ref> Promoting the Great Streets Initiative, he said the effort represents \"a shift from the way that our neighborhoods have been planned in Los Angeles\", with a new focus on \"walkability and transit\". Seeking to bolster the street-level health of the city, he encouraged developing plans to make several dozen boulevards more hospitable to pedestrians, cyclists and small businesses. A pedestrian-friendly project in downtown on [[Broadway (Los Angeles)|Broadway]] finished up in December 2014 that widened the sidewalks and replaced the parking lane with planters, chairs and round caf\u00e9 tables with red umbrellas.<ref>Hawthorne, Christopher (December 6, 2014) [https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/la-et-cm-latino-immigration-architecture-20141206-story.html \"'LATINO URBANISM' INFLUENCES A LOS ANGELES IN FLUX\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141208115952/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/la-et-cm-latino-immigration-architecture-20141206-story.html |date=2014-12-08 }} ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''; accessed December 8, 2017.</ref>\n\nIn April 2014, Garcetti signed into law a new waste franchise agreement, which was planned to expanded recycling to businesses and apartments. He had first proposed the program three years earlier, when he was serving on the city council. Contrasting it with the recycling program used in the city's residential areas, he said, \"What we have had on the commercial and apartment side has been the Wild West, with multiple trucks on the same street, with no standards.\" He stated his goal was to have 90% of all trash recycled by 2025.<ref>{{cite news |last=Orlov |first=Rick |url=http://www.dailynews.com/government-and-politics/20140415/eric-garcetti-signs-waste-franchise-plan-to-expand-recycling |title=Eric Garcetti signs waste franchise plan to expand recycling |date=April 15, 2014 |newspaper=Los Angeles Daily News |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140506163554/http://www.dailynews.com/government-and-politics/20140415/eric-garcetti-signs-waste-franchise-plan-to-expand-recycling |archivedate=May 6, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nThat same year, Garcetti co-founded [[Mayors National Climate Action Agenda]], along with [[List of mayors of Houston|Houston mayor]] [[Annise Parker]] and [[List of mayors of Philadelphia|Philadelphia mayor]] [[Michael Nutter]]. The association is composed of 379 United States mayors with the stated goal of reducing [[Greenhouse gas emissions by the United States|greenhouse gas emissions]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Mayors National Climate Action Agenda |url=http://www.climate-mayors.org/ |website=Mayors National Climate Action Agenda |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170420145222/http://www.climate-mayors.org/ |archivedate=2017-04-20 |df= }}</ref> It is committed to upholding the emissions goals of the [[Paris Agreement]] on climate change, and opposes the [[Trump Administration]]'s decision to withdraw from the pact.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Climate Mayors |title=#ClimateMayors adopt, honor and uphold #ParisAgreement goals |url=https://medium.com/@ClimateMayors/climate-mayors-commit-to-adopt-honor-and-uphold-paris-climate-agreement-goals-ba566e260097 |website=Medium |date=June 1, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170602000135/https://medium.com/@ClimateMayors/climate-mayors-commit-to-adopt-honor-and-uphold-paris-climate-agreement-goals-ba566e260097 |archivedate=June 2, 2017 |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, Garcetti released a long-range plan for making the city more economically and environmentally sustainable. The city's first-ever 'Sustainable City Plan' consists of both short-term (by 2017) and long-term (by 2025 and 2035) goals in 14 categories related to our environment, our economy, and equity encompassing water conservation, clean energy, waste, green jobs, transportation, housing, and neighborhood livability.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mayor Launches L.A.'s First-Ever Sustainable City Plan |url=http://www.lamayor.org/mayor_launches_l_a_s_first_ever_sustainable_city_plan |website=lamayor.org |accessdate=April 9, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150412050503/http://www.lamayor.org/mayor_launches_l_a_s_first_ever_sustainable_city_plan |archivedate=April 12, 2015 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Mayor Launches \u2018First-Ever\u2019 Sustainability Plan For LA Economy, Environment |url=http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2015/04/08/la-mayor-to-outline-plan-for-economic-environmental-sustainability |publisher=CBS Local |accessdate=April 9, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150411021750/http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2015/04/08/la-mayor-to-outline-plan-for-economic-environmental-sustainability/ |archivedate=April 11, 2015 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==== Urban development and transit ====\n[[File:Mayor Garcetti announces new LADOT mobile app. (16573068632).jpg|thumb|Garcetti announcing LADOT's new mobile app while riding public transportation in 2015]]\nIn January 2014, Garcetti announced a new plan to tackle earthquake safety, marking the 20th anniversary of the destructive [[1994 Northridge earthquake|Northridge earthquake]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2014/jan/14/local/la-me-ln-earthquake-safety-los-angeles-20140114 |title=L.A. Mayor Garcetti calls for aggressive earthquake safety effort |date=January 14, 2014 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |first1=Rong-Gong |last1=Lin II |first2=Rosanna |last2=Xia |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413194126/http://articles.latimes.com/2014/jan/14/local/la-me-ln-earthquake-safety-los-angeles-20140114 |archivedate=April 13, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, Garcetti picked Seleta Reynolds to run the [[Los Angeles Department of Transportation]] (LADOT).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-80573471 |title=Garcetti picks San Francisco official for L.A. transportation agency |date=June 20, 2014 |first=David |last=Zahniser |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |url-status=live |archiveurl=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20121006015957/http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-80573471 |archivedate=October 6, 2012 }}</ref> Later that year, the mayor's office and LADOT released a strategic plan with a [[Vision Zero]] goal to eliminate all traffic deaths by the year 2025. Vision Zero is a multi-national [[road traffic safety]] project that aims to achieve a [[highway]] system with no fatalities or serious injuries involving road traffic.<ref>{{cite news |last=Orlov |first=Rick |title=Making Los Angeles streets \u2018great,\u2019 ending pedestrian deaths are Mayor Eric Garcetti and LADOT\u2019s goals |url=http://www.dailynews.com/government-and-politics/20140929/making-los-angeles-streets-great-ending-pedestrian-deaths-are-mayor-eric-garcetti-and-ladots-goals |accessdate=September 20, 2015 |newspaper=Los Angeles Daily News |date=September 29, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/241388359/Great-Streets-for-Los-Angeles |title=Great Streets for Los Angeles &#124; Bus |website=Scribd.com |date= |accessdate=December 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\nGarcetti publicly encouraged the Los Angeles River Revitalization Corporation's collaboration with architect [[Frank Gehry]] on the [[River LA]] project.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/24/us/frank-gehry-draws-ire-for-joining-los-angeles-river-restoration-project.html |title=Frank Gehry Draws Ire for Joining Los Angeles River Restoration Project |last=Nagourney |first=Adam |date=September 23, 2015| work=The New York Times |access-date=August 23, 2017 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/la-et-cm-la-river-gehry-20160613-snap-story.html |title=Frank Gehry's controversial L.A. River plan gets cautious, low-key rollout |date=June 18, 2016 |work=Los Angeles Times |access-date=August 23, 2017 |language=en-US |issn=0458-3035}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.dezeen.com/2015/08/10/frank-gehry-designer-masterplan-la-river-los-angeles/ |title=Frank Gehry revealed as designer of masterplan for LA River |date=August 10, 2015 |work=Dezeen |access-date=August 23, 2017 |language=en-US}}</ref> River LA is a nonprofit organization working to revitalize the [[Los Angeles River]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/24/us/frank-gehry-draws-ire-for-joining-los-angeles-river-restoration-project.html |title=Frank Gehry Draws Ire for Joining Los Angeles River Restoration Project |last=Nagourney |first=Adam |date=September 23, 2015 |work=The New York Times |access-date=August 23, 2017 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-river-la-session-20160514-snap-story.html |title=River LA to hold first public listening session today in South Gate |date=May 14, 2016 |work=Los Angeles Times |access-date=August 23, 2017 |language=en-US |issn=0458-3035}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/opinion/op-ed/la-ol-lariver-frank-gehry-20160629-snap-htmlstory.html |title=Can Frank Gehry and a coalition of advocates bring the L.A. River back to life? |last=Morrison |first=Patt |work=Los Angeles Times |access-date=August 23, 2017 |language=en-US |issn=0458-3035}}</ref>\n\nGarcetti opposed [[Measure S]] (originally known as the Neighborhood Integrity Initiative).<ref name=\"LA Weekly effect on council campaign article\">{{cite news |last=Aron |first=Hillel |title=Anti-Development Ballot Measure Befuddles Candidates |url=http://www.laweekly.com/news/anti-development-ballot-measure-befuddles-candidates-7816053 |newspaper=[[LA Weekly]] |date=January 14, 2017 |accessdate=April 7, 2017}}</ref> The referendum would have imposed a two-year [[moratorium (law)|moratorium]] on [[land development|development]] projects seeking [[variance (land use)|variances]] from some aspects of the city's [[zoning in the United States|zoning]] code, made changes to the [[environmental impact statement]] requirements in the code, and required the city to update its [[comprehensive plan]] during the moratorium. On March 7, 2017, the measure failed with over two-thirds of voters rejecting it.<ref name=\"LA Measure S result\">{{cite web |title=Los Angeles County Election Results |url=http://rrcc.co.la.ca.us/elect/17032619/rr2619p02.htm#5019 |publisher=[[Los Angeles County, California|Los Angeles County]] Clerk's Office |date=March 7, 2017 |accessdate=March 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==== Veterans affairs ====\n[[File:\"10,000 Strong\" Veterans Career Summit (19753912845).jpg|thumb|Garcetti celebrating the anniversary of the \"10,000 Strong\" Veteran Hiring Initiative]]\nIn June 2014, while calling the long wait times at the [[Veterans Health Administration|VA]]'s Greater Los Angeles Healthcare System unacceptable,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailynews.com/government-and-politics/20140609/mayor-eric-garcetti-calls-los-angeles-va-wait-times-unacceptable |title=Mayor Eric Garcetti calls Los Angeles VA wait times \u2018unacceptable\u2019 |date=June 9, 2014 |newspaper=Los Angeles Daily News |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140612010609/http://www.dailynews.com/government-and-politics/20140609/mayor-eric-garcetti-calls-los-angeles-va-wait-times-unacceptable |archivedate=June 12, 2014 }}</ref> Garcetti pledged to secure 10,000 jobs for veterans by 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-80453705/ |title=Garcetti promises 10,000 jobs for veterans by 2017 |first=Soumya |last=Karlamangla |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=June 9, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20121006015957/http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-80453705/ |archivedate=October 6, 2012 }}</ref> He also embraced the [[Obama administration]]'s challenge to end veteran [[homelessness]] in Los Angeles within 17 months, stating that he would not accept that \"veterans live in our city without a place of their own.\"<ref name=veteranhomelessness>\n\n*{{cite news |url=http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-80816395/ |title=Mayor Eric Garcetti pledges to end veteran homelessness in 2015 |first=Gale |last=Holland |date=July 16, 2014 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |url-status=live |archiveurl=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20121006015957/http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-80816395/ |archivedate=October 6, 2012 }}\n\n*{{cite news |url=http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-80770927 |title=Michelle Obama scheduled to speak at L.A. summit on homeless veterans |first=Gale |last=Holland |date=July 11, 2014 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |url-status=live |archiveurl=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20121006015957/http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-80770927 |archivedate=October 6, 2012 }}\n\n*{{cite news |url=http://www.kfbk.com/articles/kfbk-news-461777/first-lady-michelle-obama-to-speak-in-los-angeles-12571981 |title=First Lady Michelle Obama to Speak in Los Angeles |date=July 16, 2014 |publisher=NewsRadio KFBK |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808114426/http://www.kfbk.com/articles/kfbk-news-461777/first-lady-michelle-obama-to-speak-in-los-angeles-12571981/ |archivedate=August 8, 2014 |df= }}\n*{{cite news |url=http://www.dailynews.com/20140716/first-lady-michelle-obama-tells-la-leaders-that-homeless-vets-should-horrify-all-of-us |title=First Lady Michelle Obama tells L.A. leaders that homeless vets should \u2018horrify all of us\u2019 |date=July 16, 2014 |first=Brenda |last=Gazzar |newspaper=Los Angeles Daily News |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140727195043/http://www.dailynews.com/20140716/first-lady-michelle-obama-tells-la-leaders-that-homeless-vets-should-horrify-all-of-us |archivedate=July 27, 2014 }}\n\n*{{cite news |url=http://wavenewspapers.com/news/article_81ef89ca-0de7-11e4-9dac-001a4bcf6878.html |archive-url=https://archive.today/20140805122745/http://wavenewspapers.com/news/article_81ef89ca-0de7-11e4-9dac-001a4bcf6878.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=August 5, 2014 |title=First lady speaks out for veterans and teachers |publisher=Los Angeles Wave |date=July 17, 2014}}\n*{{cite magazine |url=http://washingtonexaminer.com/michelle-obamas-veterans-affairs-scandal-distraction/article/2551006 |title=Michelle Obama's Veterans Affairs scandal distraction |date=July 18, 2014 |first=Michelle |last=Malkin |magazine=Washington Examiner |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140726125822/http://washingtonexaminer.com/michelle-obamas-veterans-affairs-scandal-distraction/article/2551006 |archivedate=July 26, 2014 }}</ref>\nResults from the initiatives have been mixed. On the one hand, the jobs initiative, which offers tax credits to employers who hire veterans, has been generally successful, even surpassing Garcetti's original goal.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://labusinessjournal.com/news/2017/aug/30/l-businesses-hire-10500-veterans-beating-mayor-eri/|title=L.A. Businesses Hire 10,500 Veterans, Beating Mayor Eric Garcetti\u2019s Goal|first=Howard|last=Fine|date=August 30, 2017|accessdate=December 28, 2018|work=Los Angeles Business Journal}}</ref> On the other hand, the housing initiative has been more complicated.<ref name=curbed>{{cite web|url=https://la.curbed.com/2018/7/23/17588852/measure-hhh-los-angeles-homelessness-unit-cost|title=Ballot measure to help homeless in LA may fall short of its goal|first=Elijah|last=Chiland|date=July 23, 2018|accessdate=December 28, 2018|work=Curbed Los Angeles}}</ref> In a 2017 interview with the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', Garcetti said that he deserved credit for housing 8,000 veterans, as well as persuading voters to pass Proposition HHH in 2016, which sought to drastically expand the number of apartment units built in the city.<ref name=\"LAT 2017-02-09\">{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/california/la-me-ln-garcetti-mayor-election-2017-story.html |title='He's pretty darn lucky.' Garcetti's riding the wave of L.A's. 'renaissance' as he runs for reelection |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |first=Michael |last=Finnegan |date=February 9, 2017 |access-date=February 10, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170210071635/http://www.latimes.com/local/california/la-me-ln-garcetti-mayor-election-2017-story.html |archivedate=February 10, 2017 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-homeless-tax-measure-20160913-snap-story.html |title=A fix for L.A.'s homeless crisis isn't cheap. Will voters go for $1.2&nbsp;billion in borrowing |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |first=Doug |last=Smith |date=October 20, 2016 |access-date=February 10, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170211081319/http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-homeless-tax-measure-20160913-snap-story.html |archivedate=February 11, 2017 |df= }}</ref> However, while the measure was approved overwhelmingly, the funding appropriated by Proposition HHH could potentially fall short of the 10,000 apartment units it was intended to build.<ref name=curbed2>{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/local/california/la-me-ln-homeless-housing-count-20190511-story.html|title=L.A. spent $619 million on homelessness last year. Has it made a difference?|last=Holland|first=Gale|date=May 11, 2019|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=2019-05-15|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Other incidents ===\nOn January 14, 2014, Garcetti was in the passenger seat of an LAPD vehicle when the vehicle struck a pedestrian. The mayor's office said that the mayor had been on his phone and not seen the crash, and had been interviewed by investigators.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/Los-Angeles-LA-Mayor-Eric-Garcetti-LAPD-Crash-Pedestrian-240185231.html |date=January 14, 2014 |first=Samantha |last=Tata |publisher=NBC Southern California |title=LA Mayor Garcetti Was Passenger in Police Car That Struck Pedestrian |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116110711/http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/Los-Angeles-LA-Mayor-Eric-Garcetti-LAPD-Crash-Pedestrian-240185231.html |archivedate=January 16, 2014 |df= }}</ref> Battalion Chief Stephen J. Ruda of the LAFD reported the female pedestrian \"was stable and alert, responding to our paramedics\" before she was rushed to [[LAC+USC Medical Center|Los Angeles County-USC Medical Center]]. Hospital spokesperson Rosa Saca said the woman was stable and had been admitted overnight.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2014/jan/14/local/la-me-garcetti-accident-20140115 |title=.A. Mayor Garcetti's vehicle hits woman crossing street |date=January 14, 2014 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |first1=Michael |last1=Finnegan |first2=David |last2=Zahniser |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140406214112/http://articles.latimes.com/2014/jan/14/local/la-me-garcetti-accident-20140115 |archivedate=April 6, 2014 }}</ref> Garcetti visited the woman in the hospital the next day and stated \"We had a nice conversation and I am very pleased that she is in good spirits. I wish her a speedy recovery.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Jason |last=Kandel |url=http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/LA-Mayor-Garcetti-Visits-Woman-in-Hospital-After-Crash-240350431.html |title=LA Mayor Garcetti Visits Woman in Hospital After Crash |publisher=NBC Southern California |date=January 15, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140928003259/http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/LA-Mayor-Garcetti-Visits-Woman-in-Hospital-After-Crash-240350431.html |archivedate=September 28, 2014 |df= }}</ref>\n\nOn June 16, 2014, while speaking at the championship celebration for the [[Los Angeles Kings]] hockey team, Garcetti cautioned: \"There are two rules in politics \u2013 never be pictured with a drink in your hand, and never swear.\" He then held up an empty beer bottle and said, \"But this is a big fucking<!--LA Times dodges the word but makes it clear what it is--> day\", prompting a standing ovation from the Kings players and the crowd.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/cityhall/la-me-garcetti-f-word-20140617-story.html |title=Garcetti drops an F-bomb at Kings celebration \u2013 and there's fallout |first=David |last=Zahniser |first2=Emily |last2=Alpert Reyes |first3=Hailey |last3=Branson-Potts |work=Los Angeles Times |date=June 16, 2014 |accessdate=June 18, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140617233020/http://www.latimes.com/local/cityhall/la-me-garcetti-f-word-20140617-story.html |archivedate=June 17, 2014 |df= }}</ref> The incident attracted some controversy. When he appeared on ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]'' later that evening, Garcetti told the late night TV host, \"It was hockey; it wasn't a match of lawn bowls.\" The following day, speaking at a luncheon at the [[Baldwin Hills Crenshaw Plaza]], he apologized to those who found what he said offensive and suggested they lighten up. He argued that it was \"something that plenty of people have heard in their lives for sure\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-80541680 |title=To any offended by his Kings' party F-bomb, Garcetti says lighten up |first=Michael |last=Finnegan |date=June 17, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20121006015957/http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-80541680 |archivedate=October 6, 2012 |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, local CBS affiliate [[KCBS-TV]] reported that in the month before Garcetti's [[State of the City address]], where he praised landscaping company Turf Terminators, the company's employees, friends, and relatives had donated $45,000 to his re-election campaign and to his nonprofit Mayor's Fund for Los Angeles. Garcetti told KCBS-TV that the donations were legal and the sequence of events was a coincidence.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2015/11/09/only-on-2-cbs2-investigates-l-a-mayors-campaign-donations-tied-to-landscaping-company |title=CBS2 Investigates L.A. Mayor's Campaign Donations Tied To Landscaping Company |access-date=October 12, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012225645/http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2015/11/09/only-on-2-cbs2-investigates-l-a-mayors-campaign-donations-tied-to-landscaping-company/ |archivedate=October 12, 2016 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/features/2016-turf-terminators-grass-war |title=There's a Grass Warfare Going On in L.A. |newspaper=Bloomberg.com |access-date=October 12, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012162758/https://www.bloomberg.com/features/2016-turf-terminators-grass-war/ |archivedate=October 12, 2016 |df= }}</ref>\n\nA 2019 [[Los Angeles County]] report on missteps in the government's handling of the 2018 [[Woolsey Fire]] response cited the unavailability of firefighting units during critical times of the fire, which was the most destructive in county history. During this time, Garcetti personally made a request to fire officials to check the status of a private residence in [[Bell Canyon, California|Bell Canyon]]. The report states: \"a significant number of requests by political figures to check on specific addresses of homes to ensure their protection distracted from Department leadership to accomplish priority objectives.\"<ref>https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2019-08-09/woolsey-fire-mayor-garcetti-texts</ref><ref>https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2019-10-23/woolsey-fire-cause-report-malibu?_amp=true</ref>\n\n== National and international politics ==\nGarcetti endorsed [[Barack Obama]] in early spring 2007 and was the southern California chairman and one of six state co-chairs for the [[Barack Obama 2008 presidential campaign|Obama campaign]]. He traveled to [[Iowa]], [[Nevada]], and six other states, and was a frequent surrogate (in [[English language|English]] and [[Spanish language|Spanish]]) for the campaign. He served as a [[superdelegate]] during the [[2008 Democratic National Convention]] and was elected to serve as the Chair of Democratic Municipal Officials,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thedmo.org |title=Democratic Municipal Officials |publisher=Thedmo.org |accessdate=May 22, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728093211/http://www.thedmo.org/ |archivedate=July 28, 2011 |df= }}</ref> an organization affiliated with the [[Democratic National Committee]] that represents all local elected Democrats in the United States.\n\nOn April 3, 2014, Garcetti was joined by [[Bill Clinton]] in hosting a half-day conference on alternate energy and improvements of infrastructure. It was the first time the two men had appeared together since his run for mayor the previous year, where Clinton had endorsed Wendy Greuel. Referencing the election, the former president accidentally said that Garcetti had been elected president, not mayor. Clinton told Garcetti that he \"may become president one day\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailynews.com/environment-and-nature/20140403/president-bill-clinton-mayor-eric-garcetti-talk-environmental-issues |title=President Bill Clinton, Mayor Eric Garcetti talk environmental issues |newspaper=Los Angeles Daily News |date=April 3, 2014 |first=Dakota |last=Smith |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407065455/http://www.dailynews.com/environment-and-nature/20140403/president-bill-clinton-mayor-eric-garcetti-talk-environmental-issues |archivedate=April 7, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.myfoxla.com/story/25159872/bill-clinton-and-eric-garcetti-ake-us-into-the-future-at-city-hall |title=Bill Clinton and Eric Garcetti Take Us into The Future at City Hall |publisher=FOX 11 LA KTTV |date=April 3, 2014 |first=Phil |last=Shuman |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407084725/http://www.myfoxla.com/story/25159872/bill-clinton-and-eric-garcetti-ake-us-into-the-future-at-city-hall |archivedate=April 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn November 5, 2015, Garcetti's office issued a statement endorsing [[Hillary Clinton]] in the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 presidential election]]. Controversy later emerged about the office using government resources to distribute a campaign-related proclamation.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-garcetti-clinton-endorsement-20151105-story.html |title=L.A. Mayor Eric Garcetti's endorsement of Hillary Clinton hits embarrassing snag |date=November 6, 2015 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106014644/http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-garcetti-clinton-endorsement-20151105-story.html |archivedate=November 6, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nGarcetti is a vocal opponent of the [[Yes California]] [[secessionist movement]], saying, \"I love this country too much to even consider an exit. I want to be a part of an America that continues to stand up for all of us, not bail on all our friends across the country.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Edwards |first=Chelsea |url=http://abc7.com/politics/calexit-supporters-hold-forum-as-effort-to-collect-signatures-continues/1753174/ |title=Calexit supporters hold forum in LA as effort to collect ballot signatures continues |work=KABC |date=February 13, 2017 |accessdate=June 29, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107005057/http://abc7.com/politics/calexit-supporters-hold-forum-as-effort-to-collect-signatures-continues/1753174/ |archivedate=November 7, 2017 |df= }}</ref>\n\nAs early as 2017, speculation had swirled around Garcetti's potential [[2020 United States presidential election|presidential run in 2020]]. In 2018, rumors continued about his political ambitions as he has made visits to early primary states. In April, he spent two days attending political events across [[Iowa]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/2018/03/21/2020-watch-la-mayor-eric-garcetti-visit-iowa-april/446233002/ |title=2020 watch: LA Mayor Eric Garcetti to visit Iowa in April |work=Des Moines Register |access-date=April 1, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> In May, he delivered the commencement address at [[Southern New Hampshire University]] in [[Manchester, New Hampshire]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wmur.com/article/rumored-2020-contender-la-mayor-eric-garcetti-speaks-at-snhu-graduation/20676696 |title=Rumored 2020 contender L.A. Mayor Eric Garcetti speaks at SNHU graduation |last=Leclerc|first=Cherise |publisher=WMUR |date=May 13, 2018 |accessdate=May 15, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180514204755/http://www.wmur.com/article/rumored-2020-contender-la-mayor-eric-garcetti-speaks-at-snhu-graduation/20676696 |archivedate=May 14, 2018 |df= }}</ref> However, on January 29, 2019, Garcetti announced he would not run for president in 2020, opting to finish his term as mayor.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Daniels |first1=Jeff |title=LA Mayor Eric Garcetti ends months of speculation, decides against 2020 Democratic presidential run |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/01/30/la-mayor-eric-garcetti-decides-against-2020-democratic-presidential-run.html |accessdate=30 January 2019 |publisher=CNBC |date=January 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Arango |first1=Tim |title=L.A. Mayor Eric Garcetti Decides Against Presidential Bid |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/29/us/eric-garcetti-president.html |accessdate=30 January 2019 |newspaper=New York Times |date=January 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Dakota |last2=Finnegan |first2=Michael |title=Los Angeles Mayor Eric Garcetti skips presidential race to 'finish the job' at home |url=https://www.latimes.com/politics/la-na-pol-eric-garcetti-president-decision-20190129-story.html |accessdate=30 January 2019 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=January 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, Garcetti met with [[Saudi Arabia]]'s Crown Prince [[Mohammed bin Salman]]. The meeting focused on continuing efforts to advance [[Women's rights in Saudi Arabia|women's rights]], and raised concerns about [[Human rights in Saudi Arabia|human rights]] and the ongoing [[Famine in Yemen (2016\u2013present)|humanitarian crisis]] in Yemen.<ref>\"[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/saudi-prince-mohammed-us-tour-hollywood-harvard-silicon-valley-dwayne-johnson-rupert-murdoch-oprah-a8293456.html Saudi Arabia's Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman toured Hollywood, Harvard and Silicon Valley on US visit] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180523102053/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/saudi-prince-mohammed-us-tour-hollywood-harvard-silicon-valley-dwayne-johnson-rupert-murdoch-oprah-a8293456.html |date=2018-05-23 }}\". ''The Independent''. April 7, 2018.</ref>\n\nOn September 22, 2019, Garcetti attended the rally of Armenia's prime minister [[Nikol Pashinyan]] at the [[Grand Park]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Karapetyan |first1=Araksya |authorlink1=Araksya Karapetyan |title=Thousands gathered in downtown L.A. as Armenian Prime Minister holds rally |url=https://www.foxla.com/news/thousands-gathered-in-downtown-l-a-as-armenian-prime-minister-holds-rally |work=foxla.com |agency=[[KTTV]] |date=22 September 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190924184331/https://www.foxla.com/news/thousands-gathered-in-downtown-l-a-as-armenian-prime-minister-holds-rally |archivedate=24 September 2019}}</ref> He stated, \"With this prime minister, a new day of sunshine has come to Armenia, a day of democracy, a day of openness, a day of no more corruption, a day where we can say in Los Angeles, it is time for us to pick up to visit, invest, to support, to help the new Armenia rise, and rise, and rise under the leadership of this prime minister.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kucera |first1=Joshua |title=Pashinyan takes \"Velvet Revolution\" on the road to L.A. |url=https://eurasianet.org/pashinyan-takes-velvet-revolution-on-the-road-to-la |agency=[[EurasiaNet]] |date=23 September 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190924184416/https://eurasianet.org/pashinyan-takes-velvet-revolution-on-the-road-to-la |archivedate=24 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Media appearances ==\nFrom 2010 to 2012, then Councilor Garcetti appeared as \"Ramon Quintero\", the mayor of Los Angeles, on the fictional [[TNT (U.S. TV network)|TNT]] television show ''[[The Closer]]'' and its spin-off ''[[Major Crimes (TV series)|Major Crimes]]''. His first appearance after becoming mayor was a 2016 episode of ''Major Crimes''.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Eng |first1=Joyce |title=Exclusive Major Crimes Sneak Peek: Look Who's Marrying Provenza and Patrice |url=https://www.tvguide.com/news/exclusive-major-crimes-sneak-peek-eric-garcetti-provenza-patrice-wedding/ |accessdate=June 16, 2016 |work=TV Guide |date=March 4, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160617064343/http://www.tvguide.com/news/exclusive-major-crimes-sneak-peek-eric-garcetti-provenza-patrice-wedding/ |archivedate=June 17, 2016 |df= }}</ref> His father, [[Gil Garcetti]], is a consulting producer on both series. Garcetti also made a cameo appearance, as a desk security guard working in the mayor's office, in the pilot episode of the [[TBS (U.S. TV channel)|TBS]] series ''[[Angie Tribeca]]''.\n\nOn April 16, 2014, Garcetti was joined by [[Jay Z]] in announcing during a news conference the [[Made in America Festival]], scheduled to take place in the upcoming summer. \"On Labor Day weekend, we\u2019re going to celebrate our golden state of mind right here in L.A. with a sellout crowd, right here on the steps of [[Los Angeles City Hall|City Hall]] and into [[Grand Park]],\" Garcetti said during the news conference. [[Jay Z]], addressing the city of Los Angeles as a whole, said \"you all should be very proud of this incredible mayor you have\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://ktla.com/2014/04/16/jay-z-mayor-eric-garcetti-expected-to-announce-music-festival/#axzz312MDJr7H |title=Jay Z, Mayor Garcetti Announce Summer L.A. Music Festival |date=April 16, 2014 |publisher=KTLA 5 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140429124422/http://ktla.com/2014/04/16/jay-z-mayor-eric-garcetti-expected-to-announce-music-festival/#axzz312MDJr7H |archivedate=April 29, 2014 |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, Garcetti recorded a [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] song \"101SlowJam\", backed by musicians from the city's [[Theodore Roosevelt High School (Los Angeles)|Roosevelt High School]], issuing it via a video on his own [[YouTube]] channel. The [[public service announcement]] video advertised the closure of parts of the [[U.S. Route 101 in California|101 Freeway]]. The 84-year-old [[Sixth Street Viaduct]] bridge is slated to be demolished and replaced by a new bridge.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Pedersen |first=Erik |url=https://deadline.com/2016/02/101-freeway-closure-los-angeles-mayor-eric-garcetti-slow-jam-video-1201697381/ |title=[WATCH&#93; 101 Freeway Closure: LA Mayor Eric Garcetti Slow-Jams Reminder |magazine=Deadline |date=January 28, 2016 |accessdate=February 6, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160206135557/http://deadline.com/2016/02/101-freeway-closure-los-angeles-mayor-eric-garcetti-slow-jam-video-1201697381/ |archivedate=February 6, 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=a_3tTv4lPds|title=#101SlowJam|work=Eric Garcetti|publisher=[[YouTube]]|date=February 4, 2016|accessdate=October 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, Garcetti briefly appeared in one of the recurring segments on ''[[The Late Late Show with James Corden]]'' called \"Take a Break\", where host [[James Corden]] pretended to take over his position for a few hours.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/james-corden-mayor-los-angeles-874528 |title=James Corden Jokes About Drought, Cuts Ribbons as He Plays L.A. Mayor for Day |newspaper=The Hollywood Reporter |access-date=January 3, 2017}}</ref> At the end of the segment, Garcetti takes back control from Corden having him escorted away by some security officers.<ref>{{Citation |last=The Late Late Show with James Corden |title=Take a Break: Mayor of Los Angeles |date=March 10, 2016 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OHaOcXDZDX4 |accessdate=January 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nGarcetti is an avid photographer, jazz pianist, and composer.<ref>{{cite web|\nurl=https://www.scpr.org/events/2013/02/06/1003/airtalk-los-angeles-mayoral-debate/|title=Who Will Be L.A.\u2019s Next Mayor? AirTalk\u2019s 2013 Live Mayoral Debate (video)|date=February 6, 2013|publisher=89.3 KPCC|accessdate=October 5, 2018}}</ref> He served as a lieutenant in the [[United States Navy Reserve]] [[Information Dominance Corps]] from 2005 to 2013.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2013/apr/04/local/la-me-garcetti-navy-20130405 |title=Garcetti has a side commitment: the U.S. Naval Reserve |publisher=Articles.latimes.com |date=April 4, 2013 |accessdate=May 22, 2013 |first1=James |last1=Rainey |first2=Michael |last2=Finnegan |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130422080914/http://articles.latimes.com/2013/apr/04/local/la-me-garcetti-navy-20130405 |archivedate=April 22, 2013 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-garcetti-reserve-20130820-story.html |title=Mayor Garcetti to end his Naval Reserve active duty this year |last=Saillant |first=Catherine |work=Los Angeles Times |date=August 20, 2013 |accessdate=June 28, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180628183117/http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-garcetti-reserve-20130820-story.html |archivedate=June 28, 2018 |df= }}</ref> On January 4, 2009, he married his longtime girlfriend Amy Elaine Wakeland.<ref name=\"Columbia\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.laist.com/2009/01/06/eric_garcetti_gets_married_young_wo.php|title=Eric Garcetti Gets Married, Young Women Depressed Across LA|date=January 6, 2009|first=Zach|last=Behrens|work=LAist|accessdate=October 22, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023034728/http://www.laist.com/2009/01/06/eric_garcetti_gets_married_young_wo.php|archive-date=October 23, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> A Rhodes Scholar herself, the couple first met while studying at Oxford.<ref>[http://www.jewishjournal.com/bill_boyarsky/article/eric_garcetti_up_close The Jewish Journal: \"Eric Garcetti: up close\" By Bill Boyarsky] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131026182148/http://www.jewishjournal.com/bill_boyarsky/article/eric_garcetti_up_close |date=2013-10-26 }} December 19, 2012 | \"''Garcetti's wife, whom he met at Oxford when they were Rhodes scholars, is not Jewish''\"</ref> They have one daughter, Maya Juanita, who is adopted.<ref>{{cite news |first=Maeve|last=Reston |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2013/may/10/news/la-mayor-garcetti-woos-female-voters-says-his-campaign-will-finish-strong-20130510 |title=Eric Garcetti woos female voters; says campaign will finish strong |publisher=Articles.latimes.com |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=May 10, 2013 |accessdate=May 22, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130518231151/http://articles.latimes.com/2013/may/10/news/la-mayor-garcetti-woos-female-voters-says-his-campaign-will-finish-strong-20130510 |archivedate=May 18, 2013 |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"partner\">{{cite news |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2013/may/25/local/la-me-amy-wakeland-20130526 |title=The mayor-elect's partner in life |date=May 25, 2013 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate=June 16, 2016 |first1=Michael |last1=Finnegan |first2=James |last2=Rainey |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160616162840/http://articles.latimes.com/2013/may/25/local/la-me-amy-wakeland-20130526 |archivedate=June 16, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Her godfather is actor [[Evan Arnold]], who has been a friend of Garcetti's since junior high school.<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Powers|first1=John|title=Los Angeles Mayor Eric Garcetti on Immigrants, Angels Flight, & More|url=https://www.vogue.com/article/los-angeles-mayor-eric-garcetti-interview-politics|accessdate=31 October 2017|work=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]|date=17 April 2017}}</ref> Garcetti and his wife have also [[foster care|fostered]] seven children.<ref name=\"partner\" /> Before being elected mayor, he and his family lived in [[Echo Park, Los Angeles|Echo Park]].<ref name=ourcampaigns/> \n \nHe attends services at [[IKAR (Jewish congregation)|IKAR]], a [[Post-Denominational Judaism|post-denominational Jewish]] congregation founded by Rabbi [[Sharon Brous]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Weiner |first=Rex |date=July 3, 2012 |title=Eric Garcetti Embodies L.A. Melting Pot |url=http://forward.com/articles/158762/eric-garcetti-embodies-la-melting-pot/?p=all |newspaper=[[The Forward|The Jewish Daily Forward]] |location=New York City |publisher=Forward Association |accessdate=October 20, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131103095545/http://forward.com/articles/158762/eric-garcetti-embodies-la-melting-pot/?p=all |archivedate=November 3, 2013 |df= }}</ref> Speaking about his religion, Garcetti has said, \"My parents aren't practicing, either of them... we celebrated [[Passover]] and [[Chanukah]]. I went to Jewish camp. I think I have become more of a practicing Jew or observant later in life. I came to my faith in college.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.jewishjournal.com/bill_boyarsky/article/eric_garcetti_up_close |title=Eric Garcetti: up close |first=Bill |last=Boyarsky |date=December 19, 2012 |work=Jewish Journal |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131026182148/http://www.jewishjournal.com/bill_boyarsky/article/eric_garcetti_up_close |archivedate=October 26, 2013 |df= }}</ref> His sister, Dana Garcetti-Boldt, is a former Los Angeles County [[deputy district attorney]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://articles.latimes.com/1997-02-11/local/me-35985_1_district-attorney|work=Los Angeles Times|first=Deborah|last=Belgum|title=D.A.'s Daughter Makes Own Way|date=February 11, 1997}}</ref> who later became an [[acupuncturist]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acupuncture.com/newsletters/m_dec08/attorney%20acupuncturist.htm |title=Deputy District Attorney Turned Acupuncturist - December 2008 |website=Acupuncture.com |date= |accessdate=2016-03-07}}</ref> She currently works as an advisor to [[Los Angeles County Board of Supervisors|Los Angeles County Supervisor]] [[Janice Hahn]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hahn.lacounty.gov/dana-garcetti-2/|title=Dana Garcetti|website=Hahn.lacounty.gov}}</ref>\n\nGarcetti has been the recipient of the [[Green Cross International|Green Cross Millennium Award]] for Local Environmental Leadership in 2003,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.globalgreen.org/events/millennium-awards/|title=Past Millennium Award Recipients|accessdate=July 26, 2018|publisher=Global Green}}</ref> the New Frontier Award presented by the [[John F. Kennedy Presidential Library and Museum]] in 2006,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jfklibrary.org/Events-and-Awards/New-Frontier-Award/Recipients/Eric-Garcetti-2006.aspx|title=Eric Garcetti 2006|publisher=John F. Kennedy Presidential Library and Museum|accessdate=July 26, 2018}}</ref> and the [[NAACP]] \"Person of the Year\" in 2014.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailynews.com/government-and-politics/20140516/los-angeles-mayor-eric-garcetti-honored-by-naacp-as-a-person-of-the-year |title=Los Angeles Mayor Eric Garcetti honored by NAACP as a Person of the Year |date=May 16, 2014 |first=Rick |last=Orlov |newspaper=Los Angeles Daily News |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140517153205/http://www.dailynews.com/government-and-politics/20140516/los-angeles-mayor-eric-garcetti-honored-by-naacp-as-a-person-of-the-year |archivedate=May 17, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nGarcetti was awarded the honorary Doctor of Humane Letters (L.H.D.) from [[Whittier College]] in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whittier.edu/alumni/poetnation/honorary|title=Honorary Degrees {{!}} Whittier College|website=www.whittier.edu|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of Jewish American politicians]]\n* [[List of mayors of the 50 largest cities in the United States]]\n* [[List of Mexican Americans#Political figures]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Sister project links |wikt=no |b=no |s=no |d=Q5386557 |v=no}}\n* [http://www.lamayor.org/ Office of Mayor Eric Garcetti] official mayoral website\n* [http://www.ericgarcetti.com/ Eric Garcetti for Mayor] official campaign website\n* {{Ballotpedia}}\n* {{C-SPAN|ericgarcetti}}\n* [https://www.britannica.com/biography/Eric-Garcetti Eric Garcetti] at ''[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]]''\n* {{imdb name|1553568}}\n* [http://www.ontheissues.org/Eric_Garcetti.htm Eric Garcetti] at [[On the Issues]]\n*{{CongLinks|votesmart=70499}}\n*\"[https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2017/06/25/most-interesting-mayors-america-215295 America\u2019s 11 Most Interesting Mayors]\" from ''Politico'' magazine\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Offices and distinctions\n|list1=\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-civ}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jackie Goldberg]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[Los Angeles City Council]]<br />from the [[Los Angeles City Council District 13|13th]] district|years=2001\u20132013}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Mitch O'Farrell]]}}\n\n{{s-bef|before=[[Alex Padilla]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[President of the Los Angeles City Council]] | years=2006\u20132012}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Herb Wesson]]}}\n\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Antonio Villaraigosa]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Mayor of Los Angeles]] | years=2013\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Articles related to Eric Garcetti\n|list1=\n{{LosAngelesMayor}}\n{{California cities and mayors of 100,000 population}}\n{{Mayors of the largest cities in the world by GDP}}\n{{Mayors of the 50 largest U.S. cities}}\n{{LACCPresidents}}\n}}\n{{portal bar|Biography|Greater Los Angeles|California|Politics|Hispanic and Latino American}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Garcetti, Eric}}\n[[Category:Eric Garcetti|*]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles City Council members]]\n[[Category:California Democrats]]\n[[Category:Climate change environmentalists]]\n[[Category:Human Rights Watch people]]\n[[Category:Joe Biden 2020 presidential campaign]]\n\n<!-- academic categories -->\n[[Category:Harvard-Westlake School alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the London School of Economics]]\n[[Category:Alumni of The Queen's College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:American Rhodes Scholars]]\n[[Category:School of International and Public Affairs, Columbia University alumni]]\n[[Category:Columbia College (New York) alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Southern California faculty]]\n[[Category:Occidental College faculty]]\n\n<!-- hobby & avocation categories -->\n[[Category:American jazz pianists]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American jazz composers]]\n[[Category:Photographers from California]]\n\n<!-- military categories -->\n[[Category:United States Navy reservists]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from California]]\n\n<!-- biographical information -->\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:People from Echo Park, Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:People from Encino, Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n<!-- ethnicity and religion categories (see the [[Wikipedia:Categorization/Ethnicity, gender, religion and sexuality]] guideline) -->\n[[Category:American Reform Jews]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American politicians of Mexican descent]]\n[[Category:Hispanic and Latino American mayors]]\n[[Category:Jewish mayors of places in the United States]]\n[[Category:Jewish American military personnel]]\n\n<!-- chronology categories -->\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American naval officers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Garcetti|his father, the former district attorney of Los Angeles County|Gil Garcetti|the U. S. Supreme Court case in which his father was lead complainant|Garcetti v. Ceballos}}\n{{short description|Mayor of Los Angeles}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Eric Garcetti\n|image        = Eric Garcetti in Suit and Tie.jpg\n|office       = 42nd [[Mayor of Los Angeles]]\n|term_start   = July 1, 2013\n|term_end     = \n|predecessor  = [[Antonio Villaraigosa]]\n|successor    = \n|office1      = [[President of the Los Angeles City Council]]\n|term_start1  = January 1, 2006\n|term_end1    = January 12, 2012\n|predecessor1 = [[Alex Padilla]]\n|successor1   = [[Herb Wesson]]\n|office2      = Member of the [[Los Angeles City Council]]<br>from the [[Los Angeles City Council District 13|13th]] district\n|term_start2  = July 1, 2001\n|term_end2    = July 1, 2013\n|predecessor2 = [[Jackie Goldberg]]\n|successor2   = [[Mitch O'Farrell]]\n|birth_name   = Eric Michael Garcetti\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1971|2|4}}\n|birth_place  = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse       = {{marriage|Amy Wakeland|January 4, 2009}}\n|children     = 1\n|father       = [[Gil Garcetti]]\n|residence    = [[Getty House]]\n|education    = [[Columbia University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]], [[Master of International Affairs|MIA]])<br>[[The Queen's College, Oxford|Queen's College, Oxford]]<br>{{nowrap|[[London School of Economics]]}}\n|signature    = Eric Garcetti Signature.png\n|website      = {{url|lamayor.org|Government website}}<br>{{url|ericgarcetti.com|Campaign website}}\n|allegiance   = {{flag|United States}}\n|branch       = {{naval|United States}}\n|serviceyears = 2005\u20132013\n|rank         = {{Dodseal|USNO3|25}} [[Lieutenant (navy)|Lieutenant]]\n|unit         = [[Information Warfare Corps|Information Dominance Corps]]<br>[[United States Navy Reserve|U.S. Navy Reserve]]\n}}\n'''Eric Michael Garcetti''' (born February 4, 1971) is an American politician serving as the 42nd and current [[mayor of Los Angeles]] since 2013. A member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], he was first elected in the [[2013 Los Angeles mayoral election|2013 election]] and won reelection in [[2017 Los Angeles mayoral election|2017]]. A former member of the [[Los Angeles City Council]], Garcetti served as [[President of the Los Angeles City Council|council president]] from 2006 to 2012. He is the city's first elected [[American Jews|Jewish]] mayor, its youngest mayor in history, and its second consecutive [[Mexican Americans|Mexican American]] mayor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newsok.com/article/feed/560798/la-mayor-elect-eric-garcetti-at-a-glance|title=LA mayor-elect Eric Garcetti at a glance|date=June 30, 2013|accessdate=August 16, 2018|publisher=Associated Press}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nGarcetti was born on February 4, 1971 at [[Good Samaritan Hospital (Los Angeles)|Good Samaritan Hospital]]<ref name=\"PressReleases\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ericgarcetti.com/eric_garcetti_announces_run_mayor |title=Eric Garcetti Announces Run for L.A. Mayor |date=September 8, 2011 |website=Eric Garcetti \u2013 Los Angeles Mayor 2013 |accessdate=October 20, 2013 |quote=A fourth-generation Angeleno, Garcetti was born at Good Samaritan Hospital and was raised in the San Fernando Valley.&nbsp;...&nbsp; He also studied as a Rhodes Scholar at Oxford University and the London School of Economics and was a Rockefeller Foundation Next Generation Leadership Fellow. He taught public policy, diplomacy and world affairs at Occidental College and the University of Southern California before being elected to the City Council. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130519182221/http://www.ericgarcetti.com/eric_garcetti_announces_run_mayor |archivedate=May 19, 2013 }}</ref> in Los Angeles and was raised in [[Encino, Los Angeles|Encino]],<ref name=\"LAT\" /> in the [[San Fernando Valley]].<ref name=\"PressReleases\" /> He is the son of Sukey (n\u00e9e Roth) and [[Gil Garcetti]], the former [[Los Angeles County District Attorney]].\n\nGarcetti's paternal grandfather, Salvador, was born in [[Parral, Chihuahua]], Mexico. Salvador was brought by his family to the United States as a child after his father, Massimo \"Max\" Garcetti, was murdered by hanging during the [[Mexican Revolution]]. Max had [[Italian immigration to Mexico|immigrated to Mexico]] from [[Italy]], where he married a Mexican woman and became a judge.<ref name=\"Forward\">{{cite news |last=Weiner |first=Rex |date=October 7, 2011 |title=Jews and Latinos Seek Common Ground |url=http://forward.com/articles/143986/jews-and-latinos-seek-common-ground |newspaper=[[The Forward|The Jewish Daily Forward]] |location=New York City |publisher=Forward Association |accessdate=October 20, 2013 |quote=Garcetti is the product of an Italian\u2013Mexican marriage on his paternal side, while his maternal Russian Jewish grandparents founded Louis Roth Clothing, the first union shop in L.A.'s garment industry.}}</ref><ref name=\"JewishJournal\">{{cite news |last=Boyarsky |first=Bill |date=December 19, 2012 |title=Eric Garcetti: up close |url=http://www.jewishjournal.com/bill_boyarsky/article/eric_garcetti_up_close |newspaper=[[The Jewish Journal of Greater Los Angeles]] |access-date=October 20, 2013 |quote=His father, Gil Garcetti, the former district attorney, is of Mexican and Italian descent. His mother, the former Sukey Roth, is Jewish.}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news |last=Medina |first=Jennifer |date=October 7, 2013 |title=Garcetti, New Los Angeles Mayor, Reflects Changing City |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/10/08/us/garcetti-new-los-angeles-mayor-reflects-changing-city.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=October 20, 2013 |quote=His father, Gil Garcetti, who as district attorney in the 1990s prosecuted O. J. Simpson, is the son of Mexican immigrants who trace their roots to Italy. Mayor Garcetti's mother's family came from Russia in the early 20th century.}}</ref> His paternal grandmother, Juanita Iberri, was born in [[Arizona]], one of 19 children born to an immigrant father from [[Sonora, Mexico]] and an Arizona-born mother whose father and mother were both Mexican.<ref name=\"LAT\" />\n\nGarcetti's maternal grandparents were from [[History of the Jews in the United States#Immigration of Eastern European Jews|Russian Jewish]] immigrant families.<ref name=\"LAT\">{{cite news |last=Finnegan |first=Michael |date=January 2, 2013 |title=Eric Garcetti invokes Latino-Jewish ancestry in mayor's race |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2013/jan/02/local/la-me-garcetti-mayor-20130102 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |publisher=[[Tribune Company]] |accessdate=May 22, 2013 |quote=Eric's grandfather, Salvador Garcetti, was born in Mexico and grew up in Boyle Heights. Salvador was brought to the United States as a baby after his father, Massimo Garcetti, a judge who had emigrated from Italy, was hanged during the Mexican Revolution that began in 1910, Garcetti says. Eric's grandmother, Juanita Iberri, one of 19 children in a family that migrated from Sonora, Mexico, was born in Arizona.&nbsp;...&nbsp;Garcetti's maternal grandfather, Harry Roth, turned the family's Los Angeles clothing business, Louis Roth & Co., into a major national brand of high-end suits for men.&nbsp;...&nbsp;Garcetti, 41, was raised in Encino and attended a public elementary school at UCLA. From 7th to 12th grade, he went to Harvard, then a private boys' school in Studio City. |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130803052240/http://articles.latimes.com/2013/jan/02/local/la-me-garcetti-mayor-20130102 |archivedate=August 3, 2013 |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"Forward\" /><ref name=\"JewishJournal\" /><ref name=\"NYT\" /> His maternal grandfather, Harry Roth, founded and ran the clothing brand Louis Roth Clothes.<ref name=\"LAT\" />\n\nGarcetti attended elementary school at [[UCLA Lab School]], formerly University Elementary School; and middle and high school at [[Harvard-Westlake School]].<ref name=\"LAT\" /> While in high school, he was a member of the [[Junior State of America]], a national civic engagement and political debate organization for students.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hwchronicle.com/eric-garcetti-88-wins-reelection-as-l-a-mayor/|title=Eric Garcetti \u201988 wins second term as L.A. Mayor|publisher=The Chronicle|date=March 8, 2017|first=Anthony|last=Weinraub|accessdate=October 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\nGarcetti majored in political science and urban planning and received a [[Bachelor of Arts]] from [[Columbia University]] in 1992 as a [[John Jay Scholar]].<ref name=\"Columbia\">{{cite web |url=https://www.college.columbia.edu/news/los-angeles-mayor-eric-garcetti-cc-92-named-speaker-columbia-college-class-day-2015 |title=Mayor Garcetti named speaker college class day 2015 |last=Columbia College |date=February 24, 2015 |website=Columbia College Today |publisher=[[Columbia College, Columbia University]] |accessdate=October 8, 2012}}</ref> During that time, he served on the student council, was president of the [[St. Anthony Hall]] fraternity and literary society, founded the Columbia Urban Experience, and co-wrote and performed in three years of the ''[[Varsity Show]],'' a student-written musical, whose past co-writers include [[Richard Rodgers]], [[Oscar Hammerstein II]], and [[Lorenz Hart]]. He also received a [[Master of International Affairs|Masters of International Affairs]] from the [[School of International and Public Affairs, Columbia University|School of International and Public Affairs]] at [[Columbia University]], graduating in 1993.<ref name=\"Columbia\" /> He met his future wife while they were both studying as [[Rhodes Scholars]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://mobile.nytimes.com/1992/12/07/us/rhodes-scholars-selected-and-half-are-women.html |title=Rhodes Scholars Selected, and Half Are Women |date=1992 |newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Peter|last=Jamison |title=L.A. Mayor Eric Garcetti introduces himself to nation at DNC: 'I'm just your average Mexican American Jewish Italian' |url=https://www.latimes.com/politics/la-na-pol-garcetti-convention-20160728-snap-story.html |website=latimes.com |accessdate=July 30, 2016 |language=English |date=July 28, 2016 |quote=\u2019I\u2019m just your average Mexican-American Jewish Italian\u2019, Garcetti said. A Rhodes scholar who speaks fluent Spanish, he liberally sprinkled his address with Spanish phrases.}}</ref> at [[The Queen's College, Oxford]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/22656413.xml?dids=22656413:22656413&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Feb+20%2C+1995&author=GEORGE+RAMOS&pub=Los+Angeles+Times+(pre-1997+Fulltext)&desc=Prop.+187+Protest+Has+Sympathizers+an+Ocean+Away&pqatl=google |title=Prop. 187 Protest Has Sympathizers an Ocean Away |first=George |last=Ramos |date=February 20, 1995}}</ref> He later studied for a [[PhD]] in ethnicity and nationalism at the [[London School of Economics]].<ref name=\"PressReleases\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.college.columbia.edu/cct/archive/mar_apr10/features0|title=Making Tinseltown Green|first=Justin|last=Clark|work=Columbia College Today|date=April 2010|accessdate=November 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Professional career ==\nPrior to his election to the [[Los Angeles City Council]], Garcetti was a visiting instructor of international affairs at the [[University of Southern California]] and an assistant professor of diplomacy and world affairs at [[Occidental College]].<ref name=\"PressReleases\" /> His academic work focused on ethnic conflict and nationalism in [[Southeast Asia]] and [[Northeast Africa]]. During this time, he published articles and chapters of books on post-conflict societies, [[Eritrea]]n nationalism, and [[Nonviolence|non-violent]] [[Direct action|action]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://us.macmillan.com/regenerationofwartornsocieties/MichaelPugh |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120718163135/http://us.macmillan.com/regenerationofwartornsocieties/MichaelPugh |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-07-18 |title=Regeneration of War-Torn Societies }}</ref> He has served on the California board of [[Human Rights Watch]],<ref name=ourcampaigns>{{cite web|url=https://www.ourcampaigns.com/CandidateDetail.html?CandidateID=64251|title=Eric Garcetti|publisher=Our Campaigns|accessdate=July 2, 2018}}</ref> and currently serves on the [[advisory board]] for [[Young Storytellers Foundation|Young Storytellers]], an arts education nonprofit organization based in Los Angeles.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.youngstorytellers.com/team |title=Our Team \u2013 Young Storytellers |work=Young Storytellers |access-date=May 3, 2017 |language=en-US |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170422035242/https://www.youngstorytellers.com/team/ |archive-date=April 22, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== Los Angeles City Council (2001\u20132013) ==\n[[File:Eric Garcetti.jpg|thumb|Garcetti in December 2009.]]\n\n=== Elections ===\n{{see also|Electoral history of Eric Garcetti}}\n[[Los Angeles City Council District 13|City Council District 13]] was left vacant after incumbent [[Jackie Goldberg]] was elected to the [[California State Assembly|State Assembly]] in 2000. Garcetti ran for the open seat and was elected in 2001, narrowly defeating former city council member [[Michael Woo]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2001/jun/06/news/mn-7152|first1=Patrick|last1=McGreevey|first2=Sue|last2=Fox|title=Garcetti Defeats Woo|work=Los Angeles Times|date=June 6, 2001}}</ref>  He was re-elected again in 2005 and 2009.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/1065936571.xml?dids=1065936571:1065936571&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jun+25%2C+2006&author=James+Verini&pub=Los+Angeles+Times&desc=Style+%26+Culture%3B+SMALL+HOURS%3B+Garcetti%2C+walking+the+talk%3B+Hollywood+hardly+shuts+down+after+dark%2C+and+neither+does+the+councilman+who+represents+it.+Clubs%2C+plays%2C+gallery+openings+--+he+just+likes+getting+out.&pqatl=google |title=Style & Culture; SMALL HOURS; Garcetti, walking the talk; Hollywood hardly shuts down after dark, and neither does the councilman who represents it. Clubs, plays, gallery openings -- he just likes getting out |first=James |last=Verini |date=June 25, 2006}}</ref>\n\n=== Tenure ===\nGarcetti served as council president from January 1, 2006 to January 12, 2012. He was elected by his colleagues to succeed [[Alex Padilla]], who resigned after being elected to the [[California State Senate]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2005/nov/22/local/me-council22 |title=Quiet Transition Seen for Top Post on L.A. Council |first=Patrick|last=McGreevy |date=November 22, 2005 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022182419/http://articles.latimes.com/2005/nov/22/local/me-council22 |archivedate=October 22, 2012 |df= }}</ref> He was one of the first elected officials in Los Angeles to hold \"office hours\" each month, where constituents can meet with him face-to-face. He implemented a \"Constituent Bill of Rights\" that ensures that constituents' phone calls are returned within a single workday, that constituents are included in all land-use decisions in their neighborhood, and that all constituent concerns are tracked on a computer system that details all actions taken on that particular case.<ref>[https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/10/07/100-days-mayor-eric-garcetti_n_4059448.html \"After 100 Days in Office, LA Mayor Eric Garcetti Gets High Marks\"], ''[[Los Angeles Daily News]]'', October 7, 2013 (via ''[[The Huffington Post]]'').</ref> He ensured that the meetings started on time,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/A+NEW+COURSE+FOR+CITY+COUNCIL+ON-TIME+START+GETS+GARCETTI+PLAN+GOING-a0141304649 |title=A new course for city council on-time start gets garcetti plan going |first=Rick|last=Orlov |date=January 12, 2006 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Daily News]]}}</ref> and all past meetings were made available online. He has also helped more than 1,500 local constituents learn about the governmental process by hosting Government and Planning 101 courses throughout the city.<ref>[http://edpadgett.blogspot.com/2013/04/taking-education-in-los-angeles.html \"Taking Education in Los Angeles Personally\"], ''Los Angeles Times'', April 11, 2013.</ref>\n\n==== Environmental issues ====\nIn 2004, Garcetti authored Proposition O,<ref name=\"SmartVoter\">{{cite web |url=http://www.smartvoter.org/2004/11/02/ca/la/meas/O |title=Measure O: Clean Water, Ocean, River, Beach, Bay Storm Water Cleanup Measure |publisher=Smartvoter.org |accessdate=May 22, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131103182919/http://smartvoter.org/2004/11/02/ca/la/meas/O/ |archivedate=November 3, 2013 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://lacitypropo.org/about.php | title=Prop O | publisher=City of Los Angeles | work=Bureau of Engineering, Department of Public Works | accessdate=July 20, 2019}}</ref> a county stormwater bond which sought to clean the city's waterways. Voters approved the bond with just over 76% of the vote, making it the largest clean water bond in the United States.<ref name=\"SmartVoter\" />\n\nIn 2005, Garcetti helped found the Los Angeles Neighborhood Land Trust. He authored two of the nation's most far-reaching municipal green building ordinances: the first requires all city buildings to be built to the [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design|LEED-certified standard]], and the second mandates that all [[commercial buildings]] of more than {{convert|50000|sqft|m2|abbr=on}} in Los Angeles be built to a LEED standard. He supported changes in the city's landscape ordinance and plumbing codes to promote water conservation.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.asla.org/uploadedFiles/CMS/Media/News_Releases/EricGarcettiNomination.pdf |title=Honorary  Membership \u2013 Nomination  Narrative |publisher=[[American Society of Landscape Architects]] |accessdate=June 29, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180630085623/https://www.asla.org/uploadedFiles/CMS/Media/News_Releases/EricGarcettiNomination.pdf |archivedate=June 30, 2018 |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn July 2010, Garcetti, then council president, weakened a 2009 lawn watering ordinance, allowing watering three days per week instead of two. The ordinance restricting watering to two days a week had been passed 13 months earlier by Mayor [[Antonio Villaraigosa]]. While it helped the city cut its water use and cope with ongoing [[Droughts in California|drought]], the measure was unpopular and was accused of causing pressure fluctuations and water main breaks. A ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' editorial said that the city council's changes to the watering ordinance was a \"death knell for one of the best collective environmental efforts made by the citizens of Los Angeles\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2010/jul/27/opinion/la-oe-green-watering-20100727 |work=Los Angeles Times |first=Emily |last=Green |title=Politics and water conservation |date=July 27, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121111114052/http://articles.latimes.com/2010/jul/27/opinion/la-oe-green-watering-20100727 |archivedate=November 11, 2012 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==== Urban development ====\nGarcetti worked to have [[Historic Filipinotown, Los Angeles|Historic Filipinotown]] designated a [[Preserve America]] [[List of Preserve America Communities|Community]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bakitwhy.com/articles/first-lady-michelle-obama-designates-los-angeles%E2%80%99-historic-filipinotown-preserve-america |title=First Lady Michelle Obama Designates Los Angeles' Historic Filipinotown a Preserve America Community |publisher=BakitWhy |date=October 31, 2011 |accessdate=May 22, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120730224044/http://www.bakitwhy.com/articles/first-lady-michelle-obama-designates-los-angeles%E2%80%99-historic-filipinotown-preserve-america |archivedate=July 30, 2012 |df= }}</ref> He championed renovating the [[Hollywood Palladium]] by [[Live Nation Entertainment]], which was at risk of being demolished.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2007/apr/12/local/me-palladium12 |work=Los Angeles Times |first=Valerie |last=Reitman |title=Palladium operator plans major renovation |date=April 12, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121113160357/http://articles.latimes.com/2007/apr/12/local/me-palladium12 |archivedate=November 13, 2012 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://onlyinhollywood.org/hollywood-palladium-historic-status-historic-venue/|title=The Hollywood Palladium: Historic Status for an Historic Venue|first=Genie|last=Davis|work=Only in Hollywood|date=November 2, 2017|accessdate=November 24, 2018}}</ref> He has also faced public scrutiny for developments that unexpectedly demolished and built over cultural and historic landmarks.<ref>[http://www.citywatchla.com/archive/7674-commission-takes-a-dive-for-garcetti \"Commission Takes a Dive for Garcetti\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402121843/http://www.citywatchla.com/archive/7674-commission-takes-a-dive-for-garcetti |date=April 2, 2015 }}, citywatchla.com, October 7, 2014.</ref> One example is three small buildings at historic [[Sunset Junction]] that were demolished to make way for a large condominium development. A spokesperson for Garcetti expressed disappointment that the developer took action without first notifying the city council, which had discussed community concerns.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theeastsiderla.com/2011/09/silver-lake-demolition-takes-city-and-neighborhood-leaders-by-surprise |title=Silver Lake demolition takes city and neighborhood leaders by surprise |publisher=The Eastsider LA |accessdate=May 22, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130407195222/http://www.theeastsiderla.com/2011/09/silver-lake-demolition-takes-city-and-neighborhood-leaders-by-surprise/ |archivedate=April 7, 2013 |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn his district, Garcetti helped create the Neighborhood Leadership Institute, which trains constituents to be active citizens,<ref>[https://articles.latimes.com/2013/jan/29/opinion/la-oe-newton-mayoral-race-management-20130129 \"THE L.A. MAYOR'S RACE; Which team will it be?\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402164425/http://articles.latimes.com/2013/jan/29/opinion/la-oe-newton-mayoral-race-management-20130129 |date=2015-04-02 }}</ref> as well as the Uniting Neighborhoods to Abolish Graffiti (UNTAG) program, which has reduced graffiti in his district over 78% in its first four years.<ref name=\"Columbia\" />\n\nDuring his first term, as chair and member of the Housing, Community, and Economic Development Committee, he helped create a $100&nbsp;million [[housing trust fund]]. He has also worked to revitalize the [[Hollywood]] area<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.boston.com/news/nation/articles/2006/05/31/after_years_of_decline_hollywood_is_las_hot_new_address |title=After years of decline, Hollywood is LA's hot new address |first=Christina|last=Almeida |date=May 31, 2006 |newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025102856/http://www.boston.com/news/nation/articles/2006/05/31/after_years_of_decline_hollywood_is_las_hot_new_address/ |archivedate=October 25, 2012 |df= }}</ref> and reform the city business tax.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/03/la-council-eases-business-tax-to-keep-internet-firms-from-bolting.html |title=L.A. City Council eases business tax to keep Internet firms from bolting |first=Phil|last=Willon |date=March 5, 2010 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100308054408/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/03/la-council-eases-business-tax-to-keep-internet-firms-from-bolting.html |archivedate=March 8, 2010 |df= }}</ref>\n\n== Mayor of Los Angeles (2013\u2013present) ==\n[[File:A New Mayor (9347724334).jpg|thumb|200px|Garcetti with his wife, Amy Elaine Wakeland, in June 2013.]]\n\n=== Elections ===\n{{Main|2013 Los Angeles mayoral election|2017 Los Angeles mayoral election}}\nWith incumbent mayor [[Antonio Villaraigosa]] ineligible to run again because of [[term limit]]s, Garcetti declared his candidacy on September 8, 2011.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2011/09/eric-garcetti-mayor-candidate.html |work=Los Angeles Times |title=L.A. Now |date=September 8, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110908171322/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2011/09/eric-garcetti-mayor-candidate.html |archivedate=September 8, 2011 |df= }}</ref> The election was held on March 5, 2013. As no candidate received a majority of the primary votes to be elected outright, the top two finishers (Garcetti and [[Los Angeles City Controller|City Controller]] [[Wendy Greuel]]) advanced to a [[Two-round system|runoff vote]]. Bolstered by the [[United Teachers Los Angeles|Los Angeles Teachers Union]]'s endorsement,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailynews.com/general-news/20130131/teachers-union-backs-eric-garcetti-for-mayor |title=Teachers union backs Eric Garcetti |newspaper=Los Angeles Daily News |date=January 30, 2013 |first=Barbara |last=Jones |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808041227/http://www.dailynews.com/general-news/20130131/teachers-union-backs-eric-garcetti-for-mayor |archivedate=August 8, 2014 }}</ref> \nGarcetti was elected on May 21 with 53.9% of votes, defeating Greuel.<ref name=\"LATimes\">{{cite news |last1=Mehta |first1=Seema |last2=Nelson |first2=Laura J. |date=May 22, 2013 |title=Garcetti wins race for L.A. mayor; Greuel concedes |url=https://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-ln-garcetti-wins-race-for-mayor-20130522,0,6850215.story |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |publisher=[[Tribune Company]] |accessdate=May 22, 2013 |quote=Garcetti will be the first elected Jewish mayor of the city. At 42, he will also be the youngest in more than a century. |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130522122954/http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-ln-garcetti-wins-race-for-mayor-20130522,0,6850215.story |archivedate=May 22, 2013 |df= }}</ref> The next day, he met with Villaraigosa, who worked with him over the rest of his own tenure to better the transition. His term began on July 1, 2013.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-antonio-villaraigosa-congratulates-eric-garcetti-20130522,0,7469415.story |work=Los Angeles Times |first=Catherine |last=Saillant |date=May 22, 2013 |title=Antonio Villaraigosa congratulates Mayor-elect Eric Garcetti |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523161538/http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-antonio-villaraigosa-congratulates-eric-garcetti-20130522,0,7469415.story |archivedate=May 23, 2013 |df= }}</ref>\n\nGarcetti was re-elected with 81.4% of the vote on March 7, 2017. Although he avoided a runoff election this time, [[voter turnout]] was relatively low at 20%.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/local/california/la-me-ln-los-angeles-mayor-election-turnout-20170321-story.html|title=A 20% turnout in L.A.'s mayoral election wasn't a record low after all, final results show|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=2017-11-11|language=en-US}}</ref> Due to a change in the city's election calendar to align mayoral elections with statewide elections, his second term will last for five years and six months instead of the usual four years.<ref name=\"results\">{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-election-losangeles-idUSKBN16F171 |title=Los Angeles mayor wins re-election in landslide |work=Reuters |first=Brendan |last=O'Brien |date=March 8, 2017 |accessdate=March 10, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170310190740/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-election-losangeles-idUSKBN16F171 |archivedate=March 10, 2017 |df= }}</ref>\n\n=== Tenure ===\nGarcetti's tenure as mayor has been described as both [[Progressivism in the United States|progressive]] and [[Pragmatism|pragmatic]].<ref name=\"Reston\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/04/21/politics/eric-garcetti-la-mayor-iowa-south-carolina/index.html|title=Why LA's Mexican-American-Jewish-Italian mayor is spending time in Iowa and South Carolina|first=Maeve|last=Reston|work=CNN|date=April 21, 2018|accessdate=December 13, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/opinion/op-ed/la-oe-nazaryan-deblasio-garcetti-20180105-story.html|title=Let's compare Eric Garcetti and Bill de Blasio|work=Los Angeles Times|first=Alexander|last=Nazaryan|date=January 5, 2018|accessdate=December 13, 2018}}</ref> He cites his method as striking a balance on delivering on liberal goals for the city, while simultaneously taking a more [[Libertarianism in the United States|libertarian]] approach to government reform.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.governing.com/topics/mgmt/gov-eric-garcetti-los-angeles-mayor.html|title=Does Eric Garcetti Have a Big Enough Vision for L.A.?|work=Governing|first=John|last=Buntin|date=August 2014|accessdate=December 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== Budget policy ====\nIn a memo in October 2013, Garcetti instructed department heads to develop a \"starting point\" budget based on the 5% cut from the previous year.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.laweekly.com/informer/2014/05/14/eric-garcettis-first-budget-shows-that-changes-come-slowly-to-la-city-hall |title=Eric Garcetti's First Budget Shows That Changes Come Slowly to L.A. City Hall |date=May 14, 2014 |first=Gene |last=Maddaus |newspaper=LA Weekly |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140515052026/http://www.laweekly.com/informer/2014/05/14/eric-garcettis-first-budget-shows-that-changes-come-slowly-to-la-city-hall |archivedate=May 15, 2014 }}</ref> In April 2014, he unveiled a \"hold-the-line\" budget for the coming fiscal year, which proposed modest increases in a number of city services and zero reduction in the business tax. His financial proposal of $8.1&nbsp;billion required approval from the city council and closed the $242&nbsp;million gap \"in part by relying on increased tax revenue projections and reductions in vacant positions\".<ref name=GarcettiBudget /> That August, he announced he would begin his annual review of every city general manager as part of his commitment to improve accountability among Los Angeles officials.<ref name=citygeneralmanagers>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailynews.com/government-and-politics/20140805/la-mayor-eric-garcetti-begins-performance-reviews-of-city-general-managers |title=L.A. Mayor Eric Garcetti begins performance reviews of city general managers |first=Rick |last=Orlov |newspaper=Los Angeles Daily News |date=August 5, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923230908/http://www.dailynews.com/government-and-politics/20140805/la-mayor-eric-garcetti-begins-performance-reviews-of-city-general-managers |archivedate=September 23, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nThe financial plan assumed the city's workforce, which included police officers and firefighters, would not receive raises in the coming year. One of the proposed changes was to merge the city's police and fire dispatch centers to streamline and improve response time to 911 calls for emergencies and fires. Mayoral aides said such a change would take multiple years to complete.<ref name=GarcettiBudget /> Garcetti said he hoped to increase funding for the [[Los Angeles Police Department]], the department making up nearly 44% of the fund already and most of the increase would go towards new technology for officers.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lopez |first=Andrew |url=http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/Los-Angeles-Mayor-Eric-Garcetti-to-Unveil-Budget-Proposal-255197041.html |title=Los Angeles Mayor Eric Garcetti Unveils Budget Proposal |date=April 14, 2014 |publisher=NBC Southern California |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140505053453/http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/Los-Angeles-Mayor-Eric-Garcetti-to-Unveil-Budget-Proposal-255197041.html |archivedate=May 5, 2014 |df= }}</ref> The plan was scheduled to go into effect on July 1, adding eight hours per week to the city's branch library operations. The number of code enforcement officers assigned to look for unpermitted construction and other neighborhood issues, would increase from 25 to 38. He also announced other changes, such as creating a $1.4&nbsp;million innovation fund to transform city services, breaking the command structure at the [[Los Angeles Fire Department]] into four geographic regions, and hiring 140 firefighters to cope with attrition.<ref name=GarcettiBudget>{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-garcetti-budget-20140414,0,5027977.story#axzz2zTu15QmX |title=Eric Garcetti's 'Back to Basics' budget offers modest service upgrades |date=April 14, 2014 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140417130803/http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-garcetti-budget-20140414,0,5027977.story#axzz2zTu15QmX |archivedate=April 17, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==== Economic policy ====\nIn May 2014, Garcetti announced he was bringing aboard [[Krisztina Holly]] and Amir Tehrani, two [[Entrepreneur in Residence|entrepreneurs in residence]], to develop policies for \"helping business startup and entrepreneurs in Los Angeles grow\". \"We want L.A. to be the leading destination for people starting new businesses, and there are no better guides for our efforts than successful entrepreneurs themselves,\" he said.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://westsidetoday.com/2014/05/03/mayor-eric-garcetti-bring-two-entrepreneurs-residence/ |title=Mayor Eric Garcetti to Bring on Two Entrepreneurs in Residence |publisher=westsidetoday.com |date=May 3, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140503185932/http://westsidetoday.com/2014/05/03/mayor-eric-garcetti-bring-two-entrepreneurs-residence/ |archivedate=May 3, 2014 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailynews.com/government-and-politics/20140502/city-of-los-angeles-now-has-entrepreneurs-in-residence |last=Orlov |first=Rick |title=City of Los Angeles now has \u2018entrepreneurs in residence\u2019 |date=May 2, 2014 |newspaper=Los Angeles Daily News |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140503190009/http://www.dailynews.com/government-and-politics/20140502/city-of-los-angeles-now-has-entrepreneurs-in-residence |archivedate=May 3, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nThat summer, Garcetti met with [[Governor of California]] [[Jerry Brown]] and legislative leaders during his first visit to Sacramento since taking office as mayor. He pushed the governor to expand the current film production tax credit, awarding $100&nbsp;million annually, to stop productions from leaving the state.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-80421604/ |title=In Sacramento, L.A. Mayor Eric Garcetti talks water, film tax credit |date=June 5, 2014 |first=Melanie |last=Mason |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |url-status=live |archiveurl=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20121006015957/http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-80421604/ |archivedate=October 6, 2012 }}</ref> He later reported that Brown had agreed to support expanding the tax credit, though it was unclear how large the expansion would be. He wanted $420&nbsp;million, equal to [[New York (state)|New York's]] credit. The amount was also four times the size of California's current $100&nbsp;million offering.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-81077906 |title=Garcetti sees progress on film tax credit negotiations |first=Chris |last=Megerian |date=August 13, 2014 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |url-status=live |archiveurl=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20121006015957/http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-81077906 |archivedate=October 6, 2012 }}</ref>\n[[File:-RaisetheWageLA (15003971968).jpg|thumb|Garcetti speaking at a rally for increasing the minimum wage in 2014]]\nOn September 1, 2014, Garcetti led a rally at a park in [[South Los Angeles]], where he proposed creating a minimum wage in Los Angeles that could reach $13.25 after three years. He received support from several members of the city council, who would have to approve of the increase. He released an economic analysis, which was prepared by academics at [[University of California, Berkeley]], that stated an \"L.A. wage of $13.25\u2014$4.25 more than the state minimum of $9\u2014would significantly improve the lot of low-income workers and impose minimal burdens on business.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-81237432/ |title=Garcetti calls for boosting minimum wage to $13.25 after three years |first=James |last=Rainey |date=September 1, 2014 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |url-status=live |archiveurl=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20121006015957/http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-81237432/ |archivedate=October 6, 2012 }}</ref> Business leaders warned that boosting pay too quickly could stifle the slowly rebounding local economy (California's minimum wage then was $9, having increased from $8 on July 1). His proposed ordinance would require businesses to increase workers' pay from the state minimum to at least $10.25 in 2015, $11.75 in 2016 and $13.25 in 2017. Beginning in 2018, additional adjustments in Los Angeles would be automatically tied to an inflation index.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-81239079/ |title=Garcetti calls for $13.25 minimum wage by 2017 |date=September 1, 2014 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |url-status=live |archiveurl=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20121006015957/http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-81239079/ |archivedate=October 6, 2012 }}</ref> Later that month, he expressed his support for the city council to vote on a new citywide law requiring large hotels to pay $15.37 an hour, adding that it would not conflict with his drive to raise the city's minimum wage.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailynews.com/government-and-politics/20140919/mayor-eric-garcetti-raising-los-angeles-minimum-wage-is-part-of-an-american-moment |date=September 19, 2014 |first=Dakota |last=Smith |title=Mayor Eric Garcetti: Raising Los Angeles minimum wage is part of 'an American movement' |newspaper=Daily News |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140921060657/http://www.dailynews.com/government-and-politics/20140919/mayor-eric-garcetti-raising-los-angeles-minimum-wage-is-part-of-an-american-moment |archivedate=September 21, 2014 }}</ref> He aligned himself with the [[Fight for 15]] movement when he signed legislation in 2015 to gradually raise the minimum wage in Los Angeles to $15 per hour.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailynews.com/social-affairs/20160701/higher-minimum-wage-goes-into-effect-in-los-angeles |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2017-03-01 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170302115221/http://www.dailynews.com/social-affairs/20160701/higher-minimum-wage-goes-into-effect-in-los-angeles |archivedate=2017-03-02 |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, Garcetti officially proclaimed November 19 to be [[Women's Entrepreneurship Day]] in Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Gv3S6EXmUDw|title=Los Angeles mayor officially names Women's Entrepreneurship Day a celebration in LA!|work=Womens Entrepreneurship Day WED|publisher=[[YouTube]]|date=February 2, 2018|accessdate=October 16, 2018}}</ref> This followed similar declarations made by [[Mayor of New York City|New York City mayor]] [[Bill de Blasio]], [[List of mayors of Philadelphia|Philadelphia mayor]] [[Jim Kenney]], and [[Governor of New York|New York governor]] [[Andrew Cuomo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.womenseday.org/about-us/our-story/|title=Our Story|publisher=Women's Entrepreneurship Day}}</ref>\n\n==== Homelessness====\nA study released in June 2019 by the Los Angeles Homeless Service Authority (LAHSA) found that homelessness compared to the previous year surged by 16 percent to nearly 60,000 homeless on the streets of Los Angeles.<ref name=reutersgarcetti/> Recent legal decisions in the Ninth Circuit limiting enforcement capability of LAPD to remove homeless encampments has contributed to the crisis.  Garcetti responded to the report by saying \u201cSkyrocketing rents statewide and federal disinvestment in affordable housing, combined with an epidemic of untreated trauma and mental illness, is pushing people into homelessness faster than they can be lifted out\u201d.<ref name=reutersgarcetti>{{cite news |last1=Gorman |first1=Steve |title=Los Angeles homelessness rises sharply as housing crisis deepens |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-homeless-losangeles/los-angeles-homelessness-rises-sharply-as-housing-crisis-deepens-idUSKCN1T609L |agency=Reuters |work=Reuters |date=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Immigration policy ====\nIn July 2014, Garcetti announced the Los Angeles Police Department would stop honoring most federal requests for detaining arrestees so they can be investigated for deportation. He stated that Los Angeles was joining with other jurisdictions to end the practice of detaining people for being in the United States illegally with no judicial review and uttered that the detainment policy was expensive to local government and erodes public trust in the police department. \"The federal government has the luxury of waiting to act,\" he said. \"Here at the local level, we are carrying out what the federal government should be doing.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailynews.com/government-and-politics/20140707/garcetti-los-angeles-to-reject-federal-governments-requests-to-detain-immigrants?source=most_viewed |title=Garcetti: Los Angeles to reject federal government's requests to detain immigrants |date=July 7, 2014 |newspaper=Los Angeles Daily News |first=Rick |last=Orlov |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140711150856/http://www.dailynews.com/government-and-politics/20140707/garcetti-los-angeles-to-reject-federal-governments-requests-to-detain-immigrants?source=most_viewed |archivedate=July 11, 2014 }}</ref> Later that month, he confirmed Los Angeles would help shelter immigrant children who have been detained after crossing the border and had begun talks with a federal agency about doing so.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-80812940/ |title=L.A. to help shelter detained immigrant children, Mayor Garcetti says |date=July 15, 2014 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |first=Emily Albert |last=Reyes |url-status=live |archiveurl=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20121006015957/http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-80812940/ |archivedate=October 6, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nGarcetti worked together with [[Los Angeles County Board of Supervisors|Los Angeles County Supervisor]] [[Hilda Solis]] to create the $10 million  L.A. Justice Fund, which provides legal services to illegal immigrants facing deportation.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://ktla.com/2017/04/17/l-a-legal-fund-aims-to-help-immigrants-facing-deportation-draws-criticism-over-who-deserves-representation/ | title=L.A. Legal Fund Aims to Help Immigrants Facing Deportation, Draws Criticism Over Who Deserves Representation | agency=[[Los Angeles Times]] | publisher=[[KTLA]] | date=April 17, 2017 | accessdate=June 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== LAFD relations ====\nIn 2013, Garcetti pledged that 5% of the [[Los Angeles Fire Department]]'s firefighters would be women by 2020. As of 2018, 3.1% of the department's firefighters are women.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fireengineering.com/articles/pt/2018/03/los-angeles-mayor-struggling-to-expand-the-number-of-female-firefighters.html|title=Los Angeles Mayor Struggling to Expand the Number of Female Firefighters|website=www.fireengineering.com}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, 2014, Garcetti responded to criticism of the department's hiring system that eliminated thousands of qualified applicants by announcing he was canceling the process. He said he had \"determined that the Fire Department's recruiting process is fatally flawed\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-lafd-recruit-hiring-changes-20140320,0,5614238.story#axzz2xyC0bC99 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |title=Eric Garcetti scraps LAFD hiring process, says it's 'fatally flawed' |date=March 20, 2014 |first1=Robert J. |last1=Lopez |first2=Ben |last2=Welsh |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140327223725/http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-lafd-recruit-hiring-changes-20140320,0,5614238.story#axzz2xyC0bC99 |archivedate=March 27, 2014 }}</ref> The mayor's office announced that the next scheduled Fire Academy class of 70 cadets would not be held, and that no further hiring would be made from the current civil service list<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.myfoxatlanta.com/story/25037790/mayor-eric-garcetti-halts-flawed-la-fire-dept-recruiting#axzz2yWlrW69z |publisher=FOX 5 |title=Mayor Eric Garcetti Halts Flawed LA Fire Dept. Recruiting |date=March 21, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413142244/http://www.myfoxatlanta.com/story/25037790/mayor-eric-garcetti-halts-flawed-la-fire-dept-recruiting |archivedate=April 13, 2014}}</ref> (nearly 25% of the 70 recruits eventually hired were related to LAFD firefighters).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://ktla.com/2014/03/21/mayor-eric-garcetti-suspends-la-fire-department-recruitment-program/#axzz2yWmx78a5 |date=March 21, 2014 |title=Mayor Eric Garcetti Suspends LA Fire Department Recruit Program |publisher=KTLA |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413142149/http://ktla.com/2014/03/21/mayor-eric-garcetti-suspends-la-fire-department-recruitment-program/#axzz2yWmx78a5 |archivedate=April 13, 2014 |df= }}</ref> It later stated that the [[RAND Corporation]] had been asked to help in reforming the recruiting process.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.myfoxla.com/story/25037790/mayor-eric-garcetti-halts-flawed-la-fire-dept-recruiting |title=Mayor Eric Garcetti Halts Flawed LA Fire Dept. Recruiting |publisher=myFOXla.com |first=Jeffery Thomas |last=DeSocio |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140323085844/http://www.myfoxla.com/story/25037790/mayor-eric-garcetti-halts-flawed-la-fire-dept-recruiting |archivedate=March 23, 2014}}</ref> The decision was met with mixed reception.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://northridge.patch.com/groups/police-and-fire/p/la-fire-department-halts-recruitment-cancels-academy |title=L.A. Fire Department Halts Recruitment, Cancels Academy |date=March 20, 2014 |publisher=City News Service |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140723114641/http://northridge.patch.com/groups/police-and-fire/p/la-fire-department-halts-recruitment-cancels-academy |archivedate=July 23, 2014 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==== Olympic bid ====\n{{Main|Los Angeles bid for the 2024 Summer Olympics}}\nIn July 2016,  Garcetti was part of a 25-person contingent from Los Angeles to [[Rio de Janeiro]] to promote their city's bid for the [[2024 Summer Olympics]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/la-sp-oly-rio-2016-la-2024-brings-large-crew-to-rio-1469996962-htmlstory.html|title=LA 2024 brings large crew to Rio Olympics|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=July 2016|accessdate=July 31, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160731231145/http://www.latimes.com/sports/la-sp-oly-rio-2016-la-2024-brings-large-crew-to-rio-1469996962-htmlstory.html|archivedate=July 31, 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> That November, he led a presentation with six-time gold medalist sprinter [[Allyson Felix]] to an array of Olympic leaders and sports officials at a general assembly for the Association of [[National Olympic Committees]] in [[Doha]], [[Qatar]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2016/11/15/2024-olympics-la/|title=LA Committee Lobbies For 2024 Olympics In Qatar|access-date=May 18, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161223135831/http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2016/11/15/2024-olympics-la/|archivedate=December 23, 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nUltimately, the [[International Olympic Committee]] decided to make [[Paris]] the host of the 2024 games, while awarding Los Angeles the [[2028 Summer Olympics]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wharton|first1=David|title=Los Angeles makes deal to host 2028 Summer Olympics|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/sportsnow/la-sp-2028-olympics-deal-20170731-story.html|website=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=31 July 2017}}</ref> In preparation for hosting the games, Garcetti launched the [[Twenty-eight by '28]] initiative, which gives accelerated priority to the city's most crucial transit infrastructure projects.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sharp |first1=Steven |title=Here are the 28 Projects that Metro Could Complete Before the 2028 Olympics |url=https://urbanize.la/post/here-are-28-projects-metro-could-complete-2028-olympics |accessdate=July 2, 2018 |agency=Urbanize |date=November 27, 2018}}</ref> He also appointed former ambassador [[Nina Hachigian]] as Deputy Mayor for International Affairs to help coordinate the Olympics games as well as broadening the city's global relations in general.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.lamayor.org/mayor-garcetti-names-nina-hachigian-deputy-mayor-international-affairs|title=Mayor Garcetti names Nina Hachigian Deputy Mayor for International Affairs|last=|first=|date=2017-08-04|work=Office of Los Angeles Mayor Eric Garcetti|access-date=2018-01-23|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==== Police relations ====\n[[File:EricMichaelGarcetti.jpg|thumb|Garcetti with police chief [[Charlie Beck]] discussing crime statistics in 2014]]\nIn July 2014, the [[Los Angeles Police Protective League]] stated its plans to file an unfair labor practices complaint with the city's Employee Relations Board to block Garcetti and [[Chief of the Los Angeles Police Department|police chief]] [[Charlie Beck]] from discussing directly with officers the proposed one-year contract that had been previously rejected. The proposal provided $70&nbsp;million in overtime for that year and $50&nbsp;million to buy back some of the $120&nbsp;million in banked overtime while also containing no cost-of-living increase.\nProtective League President Tyler Izen said that while the union understood the mayor's intentions, he believed speaking directly to the officers could violate fair bargaining rules.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailynews.com/government-and-politics/20140722/union-objects-to-la-mayor-eric-garcetti-police-discussing-contract |title=Union objects to L.A. Mayor Eric Garcetti, police discussing contract |first=Rick |last=Orlov |date=July 22, 2014 |newspaper=Los Angeles Daily News |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140726192050/http://www.dailynews.com/government-and-politics/20140722/union-objects-to-la-mayor-eric-garcetti-police-discussing-contract |archivedate=July 26, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nGarcetti found a way around the legal threats by posting a video on [[YouTube]] on July 24, noting that under the proposed contract, salaries for officers hired during the recession would be increased and overtime would no longer be given as time off, instead paid in cash. \"The sacrifices you made on overtime were emergency measures\u2014never intended to be permanent. And I understand the toll these emergency measures have taken. Not just on your pocketbook but on the LAPD as a whole\", Garcetti said.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.scpr.org/news/2014/07/24/45552/mayor-garcetti-turns-to-youtube-to-communicate-dir/ |title=Mayor Garcetti turns to YouTube to communicate directly with LAPD officers about contract (updated) |date=July 24, 2014 |publisher=89.3 KPCC |first=Alice |last=Walton |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808221029/http://www.scpr.org/news/2014/07/24/45552/mayor-garcetti-turns-to-youtube-to-communicate-dir/ |archivedate=August 8, 2014 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.laobserved.com/archive/2014/07/mayor_video_takes_his_mes.php |title=Mayor's video takes his message directly to LAPD officers |first=Kevin |last=Roderick |publisher=LA Observed |date=July 24, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140725200747/http://www.laobserved.com/archive/2014/07/mayor_video_takes_his_mes.php |archivedate=July 25, 2014 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-80895904/ |title=Garcetti uses YouTube to appeal to LAPD officers on contract offer |date=July 24, 2014 |first=Catherine |last=Saillant |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |url-status=live |archiveurl=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20121006015957/http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-80895904/ |archivedate=October 6, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nOther major changes made to the department during Garcetti's tenure include purchasing 7,000 [[body-worn cameras]] for the city's patrol officers<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-mayor-to-announce-onbody-camera-rol-lout-for-lapd-20141216-story.html|title=L.A. will buy 7,000 body cameras for police officers |work=Los Angeles Times |publisher=Tribune Publishing |date=December 16, 2014|accessdate=December 18, 2014}}</ref> as well as adding more than 200 officers to the [[LAPD Metropolitan Division]] to control the crime rate, which had increased in 2014.<ref name=\"State of City: Eric Garcetti to double size of LAPD Metro Division; allow Uber, Lyft at airport\">{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-eric-garcetti-to-double-size-of-lapd-metro-division-20150414-story.html|last1=Jamison|first1=Peter|last2=Alpert Reyes|first2=Emily |title=State of City: Garcetti focuses on public safety; wants Uber, Lyft at airport |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=2015-04-14 |accessdate=2016-04-29}}</ref>\n\n==== Public utilities ====\nGarcetti nominated four new appointees to the Board of Water and Power Commissioners: Jill Banks Barad, Michael F. Fleming, William W. Funderburk Jr., and former [[congressman]] [[Mel Levine]]. The four commissioners were confirmed by the city council on September 11, 2013,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2013/sep/11/local/la-me-dwp-comish-20130912 |work=Los Angeles Times |first=David |last=Zahniser |title=L.A. City Council confirms Mayor Eric Garcetti's DWP commissioners |date=September 11, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20140426120242/http://articles.latimes.com/2013/sep/11/local/la-me-dwp-comish-20130912 |archivedate=April 26, 2014 |df=}}</ref> joining Villaraigosa appointee Christina E. Noonan on the panel.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2013/aug/16/local/la-me-ln-garcetti-dwp-board-20130816 |work=Los Angeles Times |first=David |last=Zahniser |title=Mayor Garcetti moves to 'shake up' DWP with four new board members |date=August 16, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20140429052849/http://articles.latimes.com/2013/aug/16/local/la-me-ln-garcetti-dwp-board-20130816 |archivedate=April 29, 2014 |df=}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2013, Garcetti said he would sign off on a proposed four-year contract with [[Los Angeles Department of Water and Power]] workers. Officials estimated the contract would save $6.1&nbsp;billion over 30 years.<ref name=LADN /> In large part, the deal was expected to save money by cutting the pension benefits of new hires and workers going without raises in pay for three years.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2013/aug/22/local/la-me-dwp-deal-struck-20130823 |date=August 22, 2013 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |title=DWP deal is a mixed win for Eric Garcetti in his 1st duel with labor |first1=David |last1=Zahniser |first2=Catherine |last2=Saillant |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407123432/http://articles.latimes.com/2013/aug/22/local/la-me-dwp-deal-struck-20130823 |archivedate=April 7, 2014 }}</ref> The deal was largely worked out before Garcetti took office the previous month; he initially balked at the contract before coming around when negotiators tweaked the proposal to allow for further talks on the issue.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.laweekly.com/informer/2013/08/22/mayor-eric-garcetti-trumpets-victory-on-new-contract-with-dwp-workers |title=Mayor Eric Garcetti Trumpets Victory on New Contract With DWP Workers |date=August 22, 2013 |first=Gene |last=Maddaus |newspaper=LA Weekly |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714181550/http://www.laweekly.com/informer/2013/08/22/mayor-eric-garcetti-trumpets-victory-on-new-contract-with-dwp-workers |archivedate=July 14, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nGarcetti accepted the agreement due to provisions, which included a labor-management council to review work rules that add to LADWP workers' salaries, a modified health care system and an added pension tier for new workers and a broadened effort to reduce the disparity in pay with other city workers.<ref name=LADN>{{cite news |first=Rick |last=Orlov |url=http://www.dailynews.com/government-and-politics/20130822/la-mayor-eric-garcetti-embraces-dwp-contract |title=L.A. Mayor Eric Garcetti embraces DWP contract |newspaper=Los Angeles Daily News |date=August 22, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407070007/http://www.dailynews.com/government-and-politics/20130822/la-mayor-eric-garcetti-embraces-dwp-contract |archivedate=April 7, 2014 }}</ref> In January 2014, he nominated Marcie Edwards to head the Department of Water and Power,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://abc7.com/archive/9414291/ |publisher=abc7.com |title=ERIC GARCETTI NOMINATES MARCIE EDWARDS TO HEAD LADWP |date=January 30, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140518212647/http://abc7.com/archive/9414291/ |archivedate=May 18, 2014 |df= }}</ref> who was confirmed on February 21.<ref>{{cite news |title=Los Angeles City Council Unanimously Confirms Marcie Edwards as LADWP General Manager |date=February 21, 2014 |publisher=LADWP}}</ref>\n\n==== Race relations ====\n[[File:Snoop Dogg speaking at press conference.jpg|thumb|Garcetti with rappers [[Snoop Dogg]] and [[The Game (rapper)|The Game]] addressing race relations in 2016]]\nIn July 2013, Garcetti called for \"calm in the streets\" after the [[acquittal]] of [[George Zimmerman]] three days earlier. While acknowledging the similarities between the [[Trial of George Zimmerman|Zimmerman case]] and the 1992 [[Rodney King riots]], he insisted the city had come a long way.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/17/us/los-angeles-protests-zimmerman.html?_r=0 |title=Call for Calm as Los Angeles Girds for More Unrest |date=July 16, 2013 |first=Ian |last=Lovett}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2014, the mayor was joined by current and former [[NBA]] players to praise the disciplinary actions taken by the league against [[Los Angeles Clippers|L.A. Clippers]] owner [[Donald Sterling]] for his publicized racist remarks, saying that the remarks \"do not represent Los Angeles\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailynews.com/government-and-politics/20140429/kareem-abdul-jabbar-los-angeles-mayor-eric-garcetti-pleased-with-nbas-lifetime-ban-on-donald-sterling |title=Kareem Abdul-Jabbar, Los Angeles Mayor Eric Garcetti pleased with NBA's lifetime ban on Donald Sterling |newspaper=Los Angeles Daily News |date=April 29, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140503190829/http://www.dailynews.com/government-and-politics/20140429/kareem-abdul-jabbar-los-angeles-mayor-eric-garcetti-pleased-with-nbas-lifetime-ban-on-donald-sterling |archivedate=May 3, 2014 }}</ref> He stated during an interview that the Sterling controversy was \"a defining issue\" for the city and required a strong response from elected leaders.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-80067095/ |title=Sterling furor presents test of L.A. Mayor Eric Garcetti's leadership |date=April 30, 2014 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |url-status=live |archiveurl=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20121006015957/http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-80067095/ |archivedate=October 6, 2012 }}</ref> He stated that he expected Sterling to put up a \"long, protracted fight\" and that his continued ownership could prove harmful to the franchise.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/05/04/eric-garcetti-donald-sterling_n_5263876.html |title=L.A. Mayor Eric Garcetti Foresees Lengthy Battle With Donald Sterling |date=May 4, 2014 |work=Reuters |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140505022124/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/05/04/eric-garcetti-donald-sterling_n_5263876.html |archivedate=May 5, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-garcetti-sterling-sell-clippers-20140504,0,1410762.story#axzz30nv8uw2p |title=Donald Sterling will fight to keep Clippers, Garcetti predicts |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=May 4, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140505055320/http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-garcetti-sterling-sell-clippers-20140504,0,1410762.story#axzz30nv8uw2p |archivedate=May 5, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailynews.com/sports/20140504/los-angeles-mayor-eric-garcetti-believes-donald-sterling-will-fight-clippers-sale |title=Los Angeles Mayor Eric Garcetti believes Donald Sterling will fight Clippers sale |date=May 4, 2014 |newspaper=Los Angeles Daily News |first=Dakota |last=Smith |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140507040935/http://www.dailynews.com/sports/20140504/los-angeles-mayor-eric-garcetti-believes-donald-sterling-will-fight-clippers-sale |archivedate=May 7, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.pasadenastarnews.com/government-and-politics/20140509/mayor-eric-garcetti-opposes-shelly-sterlings-continued-clippers-ownership |last=Smith |first=Dakota |title=Mayor Eric Garcetti opposes Shelly Sterling's continued Clippers ownership |date=May 9, 2014 |newspaper=Pasadena Star-News |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140512232443/http://www.pasadenastarnews.com/government-and-politics/20140509/mayor-eric-garcetti-opposes-shelly-sterlings-continued-clippers-ownership |archivedate=May 12, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn May 2014, Officer Shaun Hillmann received a 65-day suspension after recorded remarks of him referring to an African-American man as a \"monkey\" were aired on television. The next day, Garcetti said Hillmann's statements were \"reprehensible\" and that the officer should have received a \"stiffer\" punishment.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-garcetti-lapd-discipline-20140509-story.html |date=May 9, 2014 |title=Officer accused of racial slur deserved more punishment, Garcetti says |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170224211358/http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-garcetti-lapd-discipline-20140509-story.html |archivedate=February 24, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==== Sustainability ====\nOn his first full day as mayor, Garcetti proclaimed that Los Angeles was beginning to leave behind its culture of [[car ownership]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/13/us/In-Los-Angeles-Where-Car-Is-King-Smartphones-May-Cut-Traffic.html |title=Where Car Is King, Smartphones May Cut Traffic |date=July 12, 2013 |newspaper=New York Times |first=Ian |last=Lovett |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171102180639/http://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/13/us/In-Los-Angeles-Where-Car-Is-King-Smartphones-May-Cut-Traffic.html |archivedate=November 2, 2017 }}</ref> Promoting the Great Streets Initiative, he said the effort represents \"a shift from the way that our neighborhoods have been planned in Los Angeles\", with a new focus on \"walkability and transit\". Seeking to bolster the street-level health of the city, he encouraged developing plans to make several dozen boulevards more hospitable to pedestrians, cyclists and small businesses. A pedestrian-friendly project in downtown on [[Broadway (Los Angeles)|Broadway]] finished up in December 2014 that widened the sidewalks and replaced the parking lane with planters, chairs and round caf\u00e9 tables with red umbrellas.<ref>Hawthorne, Christopher (December 6, 2014) [https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/la-et-cm-latino-immigration-architecture-20141206-story.html \"'LATINO URBANISM' INFLUENCES A LOS ANGELES IN FLUX\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141208115952/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/la-et-cm-latino-immigration-architecture-20141206-story.html |date=2014-12-08 }} ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''; accessed December 8, 2017.</ref>\n\nIn April 2014, Garcetti signed into law a new waste franchise agreement, which was planned to expanded recycling to businesses and apartments. He had first proposed the program three years earlier, when he was serving on the city council. Contrasting it with the recycling program used in the city's residential areas, he said, \"What we have had on the commercial and apartment side has been the Wild West, with multiple trucks on the same street, with no standards.\" He stated his goal was to have 90% of all trash recycled by 2025.<ref>{{cite news |last=Orlov |first=Rick |url=http://www.dailynews.com/government-and-politics/20140415/eric-garcetti-signs-waste-franchise-plan-to-expand-recycling |title=Eric Garcetti signs waste franchise plan to expand recycling |date=April 15, 2014 |newspaper=Los Angeles Daily News |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140506163554/http://www.dailynews.com/government-and-politics/20140415/eric-garcetti-signs-waste-franchise-plan-to-expand-recycling |archivedate=May 6, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nThat same year, Garcetti co-founded [[Mayors National Climate Action Agenda]], along with [[List of mayors of Houston|Houston mayor]] [[Annise Parker]] and [[List of mayors of Philadelphia|Philadelphia mayor]] [[Michael Nutter]]. The association is composed of 379 United States mayors with the stated goal of reducing [[Greenhouse gas emissions by the United States|greenhouse gas emissions]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Mayors National Climate Action Agenda |url=http://www.climate-mayors.org/ |website=Mayors National Climate Action Agenda |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170420145222/http://www.climate-mayors.org/ |archivedate=2017-04-20 |df= }}</ref> It is committed to upholding the emissions goals of the [[Paris Agreement]] on climate change, and opposes the [[Trump Administration]]'s decision to withdraw from the pact.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Climate Mayors |title=#ClimateMayors adopt, honor and uphold #ParisAgreement goals |url=https://medium.com/@ClimateMayors/climate-mayors-commit-to-adopt-honor-and-uphold-paris-climate-agreement-goals-ba566e260097 |website=Medium |date=June 1, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170602000135/https://medium.com/@ClimateMayors/climate-mayors-commit-to-adopt-honor-and-uphold-paris-climate-agreement-goals-ba566e260097 |archivedate=June 2, 2017 |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, Garcetti released a long-range plan for making the city more economically and environmentally sustainable. The city's first-ever 'Sustainable City Plan' consists of both short-term (by 2017) and long-term (by 2025 and 2035) goals in 14 categories related to our environment, our economy, and equity encompassing water conservation, clean energy, waste, green jobs, transportation, housing, and neighborhood livability.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mayor Launches L.A.'s First-Ever Sustainable City Plan |url=http://www.lamayor.org/mayor_launches_l_a_s_first_ever_sustainable_city_plan |website=lamayor.org |accessdate=April 9, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150412050503/http://www.lamayor.org/mayor_launches_l_a_s_first_ever_sustainable_city_plan |archivedate=April 12, 2015 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Mayor Launches \u2018First-Ever\u2019 Sustainability Plan For LA Economy, Environment |url=http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2015/04/08/la-mayor-to-outline-plan-for-economic-environmental-sustainability |publisher=CBS Local |accessdate=April 9, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150411021750/http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2015/04/08/la-mayor-to-outline-plan-for-economic-environmental-sustainability/ |archivedate=April 11, 2015 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==== Urban development and transit ====\n[[File:Mayor Garcetti announces new LADOT mobile app. (16573068632).jpg|thumb|Garcetti announcing LADOT's new mobile app while riding public transportation in 2015]]\nIn January 2014, Garcetti announced a new plan to tackle earthquake safety, marking the 20th anniversary of the destructive [[1994 Northridge earthquake|Northridge earthquake]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2014/jan/14/local/la-me-ln-earthquake-safety-los-angeles-20140114 |title=L.A. Mayor Garcetti calls for aggressive earthquake safety effort |date=January 14, 2014 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |first1=Rong-Gong |last1=Lin II |first2=Rosanna |last2=Xia |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413194126/http://articles.latimes.com/2014/jan/14/local/la-me-ln-earthquake-safety-los-angeles-20140114 |archivedate=April 13, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, Garcetti picked Seleta Reynolds to run the [[Los Angeles Department of Transportation]] (LADOT).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-80573471 |title=Garcetti picks San Francisco official for L.A. transportation agency |date=June 20, 2014 |first=David |last=Zahniser |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |url-status=live |archiveurl=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20121006015957/http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-80573471 |archivedate=October 6, 2012 }}</ref> Later that year, the mayor's office and LADOT released a strategic plan with a [[Vision Zero]] goal to eliminate all traffic deaths by the year 2025. Vision Zero is a multi-national [[road traffic safety]] project that aims to achieve a [[highway]] system with no fatalities or serious injuries involving road traffic.<ref>{{cite news |last=Orlov |first=Rick |title=Making Los Angeles streets \u2018great,\u2019 ending pedestrian deaths are Mayor Eric Garcetti and LADOT\u2019s goals |url=http://www.dailynews.com/government-and-politics/20140929/making-los-angeles-streets-great-ending-pedestrian-deaths-are-mayor-eric-garcetti-and-ladots-goals |accessdate=September 20, 2015 |newspaper=Los Angeles Daily News |date=September 29, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/241388359/Great-Streets-for-Los-Angeles |title=Great Streets for Los Angeles &#124; Bus |website=Scribd.com |date= |accessdate=December 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\nGarcetti publicly encouraged the Los Angeles River Revitalization Corporation's collaboration with architect [[Frank Gehry]] on the [[River LA]] project.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/24/us/frank-gehry-draws-ire-for-joining-los-angeles-river-restoration-project.html |title=Frank Gehry Draws Ire for Joining Los Angeles River Restoration Project |last=Nagourney |first=Adam |date=September 23, 2015| work=The New York Times |access-date=August 23, 2017 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/la-et-cm-la-river-gehry-20160613-snap-story.html |title=Frank Gehry's controversial L.A. River plan gets cautious, low-key rollout |date=June 18, 2016 |work=Los Angeles Times |access-date=August 23, 2017 |language=en-US |issn=0458-3035}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.dezeen.com/2015/08/10/frank-gehry-designer-masterplan-la-river-los-angeles/ |title=Frank Gehry revealed as designer of masterplan for LA River |date=August 10, 2015 |work=Dezeen |access-date=August 23, 2017 |language=en-US}}</ref> River LA is a nonprofit organization working to revitalize the [[Los Angeles River]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/24/us/frank-gehry-draws-ire-for-joining-los-angeles-river-restoration-project.html |title=Frank Gehry Draws Ire for Joining Los Angeles River Restoration Project |last=Nagourney |first=Adam |date=September 23, 2015 |work=The New York Times |access-date=August 23, 2017 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-river-la-session-20160514-snap-story.html |title=River LA to hold first public listening session today in South Gate |date=May 14, 2016 |work=Los Angeles Times |access-date=August 23, 2017 |language=en-US |issn=0458-3035}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/opinion/op-ed/la-ol-lariver-frank-gehry-20160629-snap-htmlstory.html |title=Can Frank Gehry and a coalition of advocates bring the L.A. River back to life? |last=Morrison |first=Patt |work=Los Angeles Times |access-date=August 23, 2017 |language=en-US |issn=0458-3035}}</ref>\n\nGarcetti opposed [[Measure S]] (originally known as the Neighborhood Integrity Initiative).<ref name=\"LA Weekly effect on council campaign article\">{{cite news |last=Aron |first=Hillel |title=Anti-Development Ballot Measure Befuddles Candidates |url=http://www.laweekly.com/news/anti-development-ballot-measure-befuddles-candidates-7816053 |newspaper=[[LA Weekly]] |date=January 14, 2017 |accessdate=April 7, 2017}}</ref> The referendum would have imposed a two-year [[moratorium (law)|moratorium]] on [[land development|development]] projects seeking [[variance (land use)|variances]] from some aspects of the city's [[zoning in the United States|zoning]] code, made changes to the [[environmental impact statement]] requirements in the code, and required the city to update its [[comprehensive plan]] during the moratorium. On March 7, 2017, the measure failed with over two-thirds of voters rejecting it.<ref name=\"LA Measure S result\">{{cite web |title=Los Angeles County Election Results |url=http://rrcc.co.la.ca.us/elect/17032619/rr2619p02.htm#5019 |publisher=[[Los Angeles County, California|Los Angeles County]] Clerk's Office |date=March 7, 2017 |accessdate=March 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==== Veterans affairs ====\n[[File:\"10,000 Strong\" Veterans Career Summit (19753912845).jpg|thumb|Garcetti celebrating the anniversary of the \"10,000 Strong\" Veteran Hiring Initiative]]\nIn June 2014, while calling the long wait times at the [[Veterans Health Administration|VA]]'s Greater Los Angeles Healthcare System unacceptable,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailynews.com/government-and-politics/20140609/mayor-eric-garcetti-calls-los-angeles-va-wait-times-unacceptable |title=Mayor Eric Garcetti calls Los Angeles VA wait times \u2018unacceptable\u2019 |date=June 9, 2014 |newspaper=Los Angeles Daily News |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140612010609/http://www.dailynews.com/government-and-politics/20140609/mayor-eric-garcetti-calls-los-angeles-va-wait-times-unacceptable |archivedate=June 12, 2014 }}</ref> Garcetti pledged to secure 10,000 jobs for veterans by 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-80453705/ |title=Garcetti promises 10,000 jobs for veterans by 2017 |first=Soumya |last=Karlamangla |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=June 9, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20121006015957/http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-80453705/ |archivedate=October 6, 2012 }}</ref> He also embraced the [[Obama administration]]'s challenge to end veteran [[homelessness]] in Los Angeles within 17 months, stating that he would not accept that \"veterans live in our city without a place of their own.\"<ref name=veteranhomelessness>\n\n*{{cite news |url=http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-80816395/ |title=Mayor Eric Garcetti pledges to end veteran homelessness in 2015 |first=Gale |last=Holland |date=July 16, 2014 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |url-status=live |archiveurl=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20121006015957/http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-80816395/ |archivedate=October 6, 2012 }}\n\n*{{cite news |url=http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-80770927 |title=Michelle Obama scheduled to speak at L.A. summit on homeless veterans |first=Gale |last=Holland |date=July 11, 2014 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |url-status=live |archiveurl=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20121006015957/http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-80770927 |archivedate=October 6, 2012 }}\n\n*{{cite news |url=http://www.kfbk.com/articles/kfbk-news-461777/first-lady-michelle-obama-to-speak-in-los-angeles-12571981 |title=First Lady Michelle Obama to Speak in Los Angeles |date=July 16, 2014 |publisher=NewsRadio KFBK |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808114426/http://www.kfbk.com/articles/kfbk-news-461777/first-lady-michelle-obama-to-speak-in-los-angeles-12571981/ |archivedate=August 8, 2014 |df= }}\n*{{cite news |url=http://www.dailynews.com/20140716/first-lady-michelle-obama-tells-la-leaders-that-homeless-vets-should-horrify-all-of-us |title=First Lady Michelle Obama tells L.A. leaders that homeless vets should \u2018horrify all of us\u2019 |date=July 16, 2014 |first=Brenda |last=Gazzar |newspaper=Los Angeles Daily News |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140727195043/http://www.dailynews.com/20140716/first-lady-michelle-obama-tells-la-leaders-that-homeless-vets-should-horrify-all-of-us |archivedate=July 27, 2014 }}\n\n*{{cite news |url=http://wavenewspapers.com/news/article_81ef89ca-0de7-11e4-9dac-001a4bcf6878.html |archive-url=https://archive.today/20140805122745/http://wavenewspapers.com/news/article_81ef89ca-0de7-11e4-9dac-001a4bcf6878.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=August 5, 2014 |title=First lady speaks out for veterans and teachers |publisher=Los Angeles Wave |date=July 17, 2014}}\n*{{cite magazine |url=http://washingtonexaminer.com/michelle-obamas-veterans-affairs-scandal-distraction/article/2551006 |title=Michelle Obama's Veterans Affairs scandal distraction |date=July 18, 2014 |first=Michelle |last=Malkin |magazine=Washington Examiner |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140726125822/http://washingtonexaminer.com/michelle-obamas-veterans-affairs-scandal-distraction/article/2551006 |archivedate=July 26, 2014 }}</ref>\nResults from the initiatives have been mixed. On the one hand, the jobs initiative, which offers tax credits to employers who hire veterans, has been generally successful, even surpassing Garcetti's original goal.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://labusinessjournal.com/news/2017/aug/30/l-businesses-hire-10500-veterans-beating-mayor-eri/|title=L.A. Businesses Hire 10,500 Veterans, Beating Mayor Eric Garcetti\u2019s Goal|first=Howard|last=Fine|date=August 30, 2017|accessdate=December 28, 2018|work=Los Angeles Business Journal}}</ref> On the other hand, the housing initiative has been more complicated.<ref name=curbed>{{cite web|url=https://la.curbed.com/2018/7/23/17588852/measure-hhh-los-angeles-homelessness-unit-cost|title=Ballot measure to help homeless in LA may fall short of its goal|first=Elijah|last=Chiland|date=July 23, 2018|accessdate=December 28, 2018|work=Curbed Los Angeles}}</ref> In a 2017 interview with the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', Garcetti said that he deserved credit for housing 8,000 veterans, as well as persuading voters to pass Proposition HHH in 2016, which sought to drastically expand the number of apartment units built in the city.<ref name=\"LAT 2017-02-09\">{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/california/la-me-ln-garcetti-mayor-election-2017-story.html |title='He's pretty darn lucky.' Garcetti's riding the wave of L.A's. 'renaissance' as he runs for reelection |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |first=Michael |last=Finnegan |date=February 9, 2017 |access-date=February 10, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170210071635/http://www.latimes.com/local/california/la-me-ln-garcetti-mayor-election-2017-story.html |archivedate=February 10, 2017 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-homeless-tax-measure-20160913-snap-story.html |title=A fix for L.A.'s homeless crisis isn't cheap. Will voters go for $1.2&nbsp;billion in borrowing |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |first=Doug |last=Smith |date=October 20, 2016 |access-date=February 10, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170211081319/http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-homeless-tax-measure-20160913-snap-story.html |archivedate=February 11, 2017 |df= }}</ref> However, while the measure was approved overwhelmingly, the funding appropriated by Proposition HHH could potentially fall short of the 10,000 apartment units it was intended to build.<ref name=curbed2>{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/local/california/la-me-ln-homeless-housing-count-20190511-story.html|title=L.A. spent $619 million on homelessness last year. Has it made a difference?|last=Holland|first=Gale|date=May 11, 2019|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=2019-05-15|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Other incidents ===\nOn January 14, 2014, Garcetti was in the passenger seat of an LAPD vehicle when the vehicle struck a pedestrian. The mayor's office said that the mayor had been on his phone and not seen the crash, and had been interviewed by investigators.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/Los-Angeles-LA-Mayor-Eric-Garcetti-LAPD-Crash-Pedestrian-240185231.html |date=January 14, 2014 |first=Samantha |last=Tata |publisher=NBC Southern California |title=LA Mayor Garcetti Was Passenger in Police Car That Struck Pedestrian |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116110711/http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/Los-Angeles-LA-Mayor-Eric-Garcetti-LAPD-Crash-Pedestrian-240185231.html |archivedate=January 16, 2014 |df= }}</ref> Battalion Chief Stephen J. Ruda of the LAFD reported the female pedestrian \"was stable and alert, responding to our paramedics\" before she was rushed to [[LAC+USC Medical Center|Los Angeles County-USC Medical Center]]. Hospital spokesperson Rosa Saca said the woman was stable and had been admitted overnight.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2014/jan/14/local/la-me-garcetti-accident-20140115 |title=.A. Mayor Garcetti's vehicle hits woman crossing street |date=January 14, 2014 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |first1=Michael |last1=Finnegan |first2=David |last2=Zahniser |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140406214112/http://articles.latimes.com/2014/jan/14/local/la-me-garcetti-accident-20140115 |archivedate=April 6, 2014 }}</ref> Garcetti visited the woman in the hospital the next day and stated \"We had a nice conversation and I am very pleased that she is in good spirits. I wish her a speedy recovery.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Jason |last=Kandel |url=http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/LA-Mayor-Garcetti-Visits-Woman-in-Hospital-After-Crash-240350431.html |title=LA Mayor Garcetti Visits Woman in Hospital After Crash |publisher=NBC Southern California |date=January 15, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140928003259/http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/LA-Mayor-Garcetti-Visits-Woman-in-Hospital-After-Crash-240350431.html |archivedate=September 28, 2014 |df= }}</ref>\n\nOn June 16, 2014, while speaking at the championship celebration for the [[Los Angeles Kings]] hockey team, Garcetti cautioned: \"There are two rules in politics \u2013 never be pictured with a drink in your hand, and never swear.\" He then held up an empty beer bottle and said, \"But this is a big fucking<!--LA Times dodges the word but makes it clear what it is--> day\", prompting a standing ovation from the Kings players and the crowd.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/cityhall/la-me-garcetti-f-word-20140617-story.html |title=Garcetti drops an F-bomb at Kings celebration \u2013 and there's fallout |first=David |last=Zahniser |first2=Emily |last2=Alpert Reyes |first3=Hailey |last3=Branson-Potts |work=Los Angeles Times |date=June 16, 2014 |accessdate=June 18, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140617233020/http://www.latimes.com/local/cityhall/la-me-garcetti-f-word-20140617-story.html |archivedate=June 17, 2014 |df= }}</ref> The incident attracted some controversy. When he appeared on ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]'' later that evening, Garcetti told the late night TV host, \"It was hockey; it wasn't a match of lawn bowls.\" The following day, speaking at a luncheon at the [[Baldwin Hills Crenshaw Plaza]], he apologized to those who found what he said offensive and suggested they lighten up. He argued that it was \"something that plenty of people have heard in their lives for sure\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-80541680 |title=To any offended by his Kings' party F-bomb, Garcetti says lighten up |first=Michael |last=Finnegan |date=June 17, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20121006015957/http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-80541680 |archivedate=October 6, 2012 |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, local CBS affiliate [[KCBS-TV]] reported that in the month before Garcetti's [[State of the City address]], where he praised landscaping company Turf Terminators, the company's employees, friends, and relatives had donated $45,000 to his re-election campaign and to his nonprofit Mayor's Fund for Los Angeles. Garcetti told KCBS-TV that the donations were legal and the sequence of events was a coincidence.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2015/11/09/only-on-2-cbs2-investigates-l-a-mayors-campaign-donations-tied-to-landscaping-company |title=CBS2 Investigates L.A. Mayor's Campaign Donations Tied To Landscaping Company |access-date=October 12, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012225645/http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2015/11/09/only-on-2-cbs2-investigates-l-a-mayors-campaign-donations-tied-to-landscaping-company/ |archivedate=October 12, 2016 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/features/2016-turf-terminators-grass-war |title=There's a Grass Warfare Going On in L.A. |newspaper=Bloomberg.com |access-date=October 12, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012162758/https://www.bloomberg.com/features/2016-turf-terminators-grass-war/ |archivedate=October 12, 2016 |df= }}</ref>\n\nA 2019 [[Los Angeles County]] report on missteps in the government's handling of the 2018 [[Woolsey Fire]] response cited the unavailability of firefighting units during critical times of the fire, which was the most destructive in county history. During this time, Garcetti personally made a request to fire officials to check the status of a private residence in [[Bell Canyon, California|Bell Canyon]]. The report states: \"a significant number of requests by political figures to check on specific addresses of homes to ensure their protection distracted from Department leadership to accomplish priority objectives.\"<ref>https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2019-08-09/woolsey-fire-mayor-garcetti-texts</ref><ref>https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2019-10-23/woolsey-fire-cause-report-malibu?_amp=true</ref>\n\n== National and international politics ==\nGarcetti endorsed [[Barack Obama]] in early spring 2007 and was the southern California chairman and one of six state co-chairs for the [[Barack Obama 2008 presidential campaign|Obama campaign]]. He traveled to [[Iowa]], [[Nevada]], and six other states, and was a frequent surrogate (in [[English language|English]] and [[Spanish language|Spanish]]) for the campaign. He served as a [[superdelegate]] during the [[2008 Democratic National Convention]] and was elected to serve as the Chair of Democratic Municipal Officials,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thedmo.org |title=Democratic Municipal Officials |publisher=Thedmo.org |accessdate=May 22, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728093211/http://www.thedmo.org/ |archivedate=July 28, 2011 |df= }}</ref> an organization affiliated with the [[Democratic National Committee]] that represents all local elected Democrats in the United States.\n\nOn April 3, 2014, Garcetti was joined by [[Bill Clinton]] in hosting a half-day conference on alternate energy and improvements of infrastructure. It was the first time the two men had appeared together since his run for mayor the previous year, where Clinton had endorsed Wendy Greuel. Referencing the election, the former president accidentally said that Garcetti had been elected president, not mayor. Clinton told Garcetti that he \"may become president one day\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailynews.com/environment-and-nature/20140403/president-bill-clinton-mayor-eric-garcetti-talk-environmental-issues |title=President Bill Clinton, Mayor Eric Garcetti talk environmental issues |newspaper=Los Angeles Daily News |date=April 3, 2014 |first=Dakota |last=Smith |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407065455/http://www.dailynews.com/environment-and-nature/20140403/president-bill-clinton-mayor-eric-garcetti-talk-environmental-issues |archivedate=April 7, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.myfoxla.com/story/25159872/bill-clinton-and-eric-garcetti-ake-us-into-the-future-at-city-hall |title=Bill Clinton and Eric Garcetti Take Us into The Future at City Hall |publisher=FOX 11 LA KTTV |date=April 3, 2014 |first=Phil |last=Shuman |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407084725/http://www.myfoxla.com/story/25159872/bill-clinton-and-eric-garcetti-ake-us-into-the-future-at-city-hall |archivedate=April 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn November 5, 2015, Garcetti's office issued a statement endorsing [[Hillary Clinton]] in the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 presidential election]]. Controversy later emerged about the office using government resources to distribute a campaign-related proclamation.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-garcetti-clinton-endorsement-20151105-story.html |title=L.A. Mayor Eric Garcetti's endorsement of Hillary Clinton hits embarrassing snag |date=November 6, 2015 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106014644/http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-garcetti-clinton-endorsement-20151105-story.html |archivedate=November 6, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nGarcetti is a vocal opponent of the [[Yes California]] [[secessionist movement]], saying, \"I love this country too much to even consider an exit. I want to be a part of an America that continues to stand up for all of us, not bail on all our friends across the country.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Edwards |first=Chelsea |url=http://abc7.com/politics/calexit-supporters-hold-forum-as-effort-to-collect-signatures-continues/1753174/ |title=Calexit supporters hold forum in LA as effort to collect ballot signatures continues |work=KABC |date=February 13, 2017 |accessdate=June 29, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107005057/http://abc7.com/politics/calexit-supporters-hold-forum-as-effort-to-collect-signatures-continues/1753174/ |archivedate=November 7, 2017 |df= }}</ref>\n\nAs early as 2017, speculation had swirled around Garcetti's potential [[2020 United States presidential election|presidential run in 2020]]. In 2018, rumors continued about his political ambitions as he has made visits to early primary states. In April, he spent two days attending political events across [[Iowa]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/2018/03/21/2020-watch-la-mayor-eric-garcetti-visit-iowa-april/446233002/ |title=2020 watch: LA Mayor Eric Garcetti to visit Iowa in April |work=Des Moines Register |access-date=April 1, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> In May, he delivered the commencement address at [[Southern New Hampshire University]] in [[Manchester, New Hampshire]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wmur.com/article/rumored-2020-contender-la-mayor-eric-garcetti-speaks-at-snhu-graduation/20676696 |title=Rumored 2020 contender L.A. Mayor Eric Garcetti speaks at SNHU graduation |last=Leclerc|first=Cherise |publisher=WMUR |date=May 13, 2018 |accessdate=May 15, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180514204755/http://www.wmur.com/article/rumored-2020-contender-la-mayor-eric-garcetti-speaks-at-snhu-graduation/20676696 |archivedate=May 14, 2018 |df= }}</ref> However, on January 29, 2019, Garcetti announced he would not run for president in 2020, opting to finish his term as mayor.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Daniels |first1=Jeff |title=LA Mayor Eric Garcetti ends months of speculation, decides against 2020 Democratic presidential run |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/01/30/la-mayor-eric-garcetti-decides-against-2020-democratic-presidential-run.html |accessdate=30 January 2019 |publisher=CNBC |date=January 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Arango |first1=Tim |title=L.A. Mayor Eric Garcetti Decides Against Presidential Bid |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/29/us/eric-garcetti-president.html |accessdate=30 January 2019 |newspaper=New York Times |date=January 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Dakota |last2=Finnegan |first2=Michael |title=Los Angeles Mayor Eric Garcetti skips presidential race to 'finish the job' at home |url=https://www.latimes.com/politics/la-na-pol-eric-garcetti-president-decision-20190129-story.html |accessdate=30 January 2019 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=January 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, Garcetti met with [[Saudi Arabia]]'s Crown Prince [[Mohammed bin Salman]]. The meeting focused on continuing efforts to advance [[Women's rights in Saudi Arabia|women's rights]], and raised concerns about [[Human rights in Saudi Arabia|human rights]] and the ongoing [[Famine in Yemen (2016\u2013present)|humanitarian crisis]] in Yemen.<ref>\"[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/saudi-prince-mohammed-us-tour-hollywood-harvard-silicon-valley-dwayne-johnson-rupert-murdoch-oprah-a8293456.html Saudi Arabia's Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman toured Hollywood, Harvard and Silicon Valley on US visit] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180523102053/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/saudi-prince-mohammed-us-tour-hollywood-harvard-silicon-valley-dwayne-johnson-rupert-murdoch-oprah-a8293456.html |date=2018-05-23 }}\". ''The Independent''. April 7, 2018.</ref>\n\nOn September 22, 2019, Garcetti attended the rally of Armenia's prime minister [[Nikol Pashinyan]] at the [[Grand Park]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Karapetyan |first1=Araksya |authorlink1=Araksya Karapetyan |title=Thousands gathered in downtown L.A. as Armenian Prime Minister holds rally |url=https://www.foxla.com/news/thousands-gathered-in-downtown-l-a-as-armenian-prime-minister-holds-rally |work=foxla.com |agency=[[KTTV]] |date=22 September 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190924184331/https://www.foxla.com/news/thousands-gathered-in-downtown-l-a-as-armenian-prime-minister-holds-rally |archivedate=24 September 2019}}</ref> He stated, \"With this prime minister, a new day of sunshine has come to Armenia, a day of democracy, a day of openness, a day of no more corruption, a day where we can say in Los Angeles, it is time for us to pick up to visit, invest, to support, to help the new Armenia rise, and rise, and rise under the leadership of this prime minister.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kucera |first1=Joshua |title=Pashinyan takes \"Velvet Revolution\" on the road to L.A. |url=https://eurasianet.org/pashinyan-takes-velvet-revolution-on-the-road-to-la |agency=[[EurasiaNet]] |date=23 September 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190924184416/https://eurasianet.org/pashinyan-takes-velvet-revolution-on-the-road-to-la |archivedate=24 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Media appearances ==\nFrom 2010 to 2012, then Councilor Garcetti appeared as \"Ramon Quintero\", the mayor of Los Angeles, on the fictional [[TNT (U.S. TV network)|TNT]] television show ''[[The Closer]]'' and its spin-off ''[[Major Crimes (TV series)|Major Crimes]]''. His first appearance after becoming mayor was a 2016 episode of ''Major Crimes''.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Eng |first1=Joyce |title=Exclusive Major Crimes Sneak Peek: Look Who's Marrying Provenza and Patrice |url=https://www.tvguide.com/news/exclusive-major-crimes-sneak-peek-eric-garcetti-provenza-patrice-wedding/ |accessdate=June 16, 2016 |work=TV Guide |date=March 4, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160617064343/http://www.tvguide.com/news/exclusive-major-crimes-sneak-peek-eric-garcetti-provenza-patrice-wedding/ |archivedate=June 17, 2016 |df= }}</ref> His father, [[Gil Garcetti]], is a consulting producer on both series. Garcetti also made a cameo appearance, as a desk security guard working in the mayor's office, in the pilot episode of the [[TBS (U.S. TV channel)|TBS]] series ''[[Angie Tribeca]]''.\n\nOn April 16, 2014, Garcetti was joined by [[Jay Z]] in announcing during a news conference the [[Made in America Festival]], scheduled to take place in the upcoming summer. \"On Labor Day weekend, we\u2019re going to celebrate our golden state of mind right here in L.A. with a sellout crowd, right here on the steps of [[Los Angeles City Hall|City Hall]] and into [[Grand Park]],\" Garcetti said during the news conference. [[Jay Z]], addressing the city of Los Angeles as a whole, said \"you all should be very proud of this incredible mayor you have\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://ktla.com/2014/04/16/jay-z-mayor-eric-garcetti-expected-to-announce-music-festival/#axzz312MDJr7H |title=Jay Z, Mayor Garcetti Announce Summer L.A. Music Festival |date=April 16, 2014 |publisher=KTLA 5 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140429124422/http://ktla.com/2014/04/16/jay-z-mayor-eric-garcetti-expected-to-announce-music-festival/#axzz312MDJr7H |archivedate=April 29, 2014 |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, Garcetti recorded a [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] song \"101SlowJam\", backed by musicians from the city's [[Theodore Roosevelt High School (Los Angeles)|Roosevelt High School]], issuing it via a video on his own [[YouTube]] channel. The [[public service announcement]] video advertised the closure of parts of the [[U.S. Route 101 in California|101 Freeway]]. The 84-year-old [[Sixth Street Viaduct]] bridge is slated to be demolished and replaced by a new bridge.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Pedersen |first=Erik |url=https://deadline.com/2016/02/101-freeway-closure-los-angeles-mayor-eric-garcetti-slow-jam-video-1201697381/ |title=[WATCH&#93; 101 Freeway Closure: LA Mayor Eric Garcetti Slow-Jams Reminder |magazine=Deadline |date=January 28, 2016 |accessdate=February 6, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160206135557/http://deadline.com/2016/02/101-freeway-closure-los-angeles-mayor-eric-garcetti-slow-jam-video-1201697381/ |archivedate=February 6, 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=a_3tTv4lPds|title=#101SlowJam|work=Eric Garcetti|publisher=[[YouTube]]|date=February 4, 2016|accessdate=October 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, Garcetti briefly appeared in one of the recurring segments on ''[[The Late Late Show with James Corden]]'' called \"Take a Break\", where host [[James Corden]] pretended to take over his position for a few hours.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/james-corden-mayor-los-angeles-874528 |title=James Corden Jokes About Drought, Cuts Ribbons as He Plays L.A. Mayor for Day |newspaper=The Hollywood Reporter |access-date=January 3, 2017}}</ref> At the end of the segment, Garcetti takes back control from Corden having him escorted away by some security officers.<ref>{{Citation |last=The Late Late Show with James Corden |title=Take a Break: Mayor of Los Angeles |date=March 10, 2016 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OHaOcXDZDX4 |accessdate=January 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nGarcetti is an avid photographer, jazz pianist, and composer.<ref>{{cite web|\nurl=https://www.scpr.org/events/2013/02/06/1003/airtalk-los-angeles-mayoral-debate/|title=Who Will Be L.A.\u2019s Next Mayor? AirTalk\u2019s 2013 Live Mayoral Debate (video)|date=February 6, 2013|publisher=89.3 KPCC|accessdate=October 5, 2018}}</ref> He served as a lieutenant in the [[United States Navy Reserve]] [[Information Dominance Corps]] from 2005 to 2013.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2013/apr/04/local/la-me-garcetti-navy-20130405 |title=Garcetti has a side commitment: the U.S. Naval Reserve |publisher=Articles.latimes.com |date=April 4, 2013 |accessdate=May 22, 2013 |first1=James |last1=Rainey |first2=Michael |last2=Finnegan |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130422080914/http://articles.latimes.com/2013/apr/04/local/la-me-garcetti-navy-20130405 |archivedate=April 22, 2013 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-garcetti-reserve-20130820-story.html |title=Mayor Garcetti to end his Naval Reserve active duty this year |last=Saillant |first=Catherine |work=Los Angeles Times |date=August 20, 2013 |accessdate=June 28, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180628183117/http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-garcetti-reserve-20130820-story.html |archivedate=June 28, 2018 |df= }}</ref> On January 4, 2009, he married his longtime girlfriend Amy Elaine Wakeland.<ref name=\"Columbia\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.laist.com/2009/01/06/eric_garcetti_gets_married_young_wo.php|title=Eric Garcetti Gets Married, Young Women Depressed Across LA|date=January 6, 2009|first=Zach|last=Behrens|work=LAist|accessdate=October 22, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023034728/http://www.laist.com/2009/01/06/eric_garcetti_gets_married_young_wo.php|archive-date=October 23, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> A Rhodes Scholar herself, the couple first met while studying at Oxford.<ref>[http://www.jewishjournal.com/bill_boyarsky/article/eric_garcetti_up_close The Jewish Journal: \"Eric Garcetti: up close\" By Bill Boyarsky] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131026182148/http://www.jewishjournal.com/bill_boyarsky/article/eric_garcetti_up_close |date=2013-10-26 }} December 19, 2012 | \"''Garcetti's wife, whom he met at Oxford when they were Rhodes scholars, is not Jewish''\"</ref> They have one daughter, Maya Juanita, who is adopted.<ref>{{cite news |first=Maeve|last=Reston |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2013/may/10/news/la-mayor-garcetti-woos-female-voters-says-his-campaign-will-finish-strong-20130510 |title=Eric Garcetti woos female voters; says campaign will finish strong |publisher=Articles.latimes.com |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=May 10, 2013 |accessdate=May 22, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130518231151/http://articles.latimes.com/2013/may/10/news/la-mayor-garcetti-woos-female-voters-says-his-campaign-will-finish-strong-20130510 |archivedate=May 18, 2013 |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"partner\">{{cite news |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2013/may/25/local/la-me-amy-wakeland-20130526 |title=The mayor-elect's partner in life |date=May 25, 2013 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate=June 16, 2016 |first1=Michael |last1=Finnegan |first2=James |last2=Rainey |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160616162840/http://articles.latimes.com/2013/may/25/local/la-me-amy-wakeland-20130526 |archivedate=June 16, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Her godfather is actor [[Evan Arnold]], who has been a friend of Garcetti's since junior high school.<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Powers|first1=John|title=Los Angeles Mayor Eric Garcetti on Immigrants, Angels Flight, & More|url=https://www.vogue.com/article/los-angeles-mayor-eric-garcetti-interview-politics|accessdate=31 October 2017|work=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]|date=17 April 2017}}</ref> Garcetti and his wife have also [[foster care|fostered]] seven children.<ref name=\"partner\" /> Before being elected mayor, he and his family lived in [[Echo Park, Los Angeles|Echo Park]].<ref name=ourcampaigns/> \n \nHe attends services at [[IKAR (Jewish congregation)|IKAR]], a [[Post-Denominational Judaism|post-denominational Jewish]] congregation founded by Rabbi [[Sharon Brous]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Weiner |first=Rex |date=July 3, 2012 |title=Eric Garcetti Embodies L.A. Melting Pot |url=http://forward.com/articles/158762/eric-garcetti-embodies-la-melting-pot/?p=all |newspaper=[[The Forward|The Jewish Daily Forward]] |location=New York City |publisher=Forward Association |accessdate=October 20, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131103095545/http://forward.com/articles/158762/eric-garcetti-embodies-la-melting-pot/?p=all |archivedate=November 3, 2013 |df= }}</ref> Speaking about his religion, Garcetti has said, \"My parents aren't practicing, either of them... we celebrated [[Passover]] and [[Chanukah]]. I went to Jewish camp. I think I have become more of a practicing Jew or observant later in life. I came to my faith in college.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.jewishjournal.com/bill_boyarsky/article/eric_garcetti_up_close |title=Eric Garcetti: up close |first=Bill |last=Boyarsky |date=December 19, 2012 |work=Jewish Journal |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131026182148/http://www.jewishjournal.com/bill_boyarsky/article/eric_garcetti_up_close |archivedate=October 26, 2013 |df= }}</ref> His sister, Dana Garcetti-Boldt, is a former Los Angeles County [[deputy district attorney]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://articles.latimes.com/1997-02-11/local/me-35985_1_district-attorney|work=Los Angeles Times|first=Deborah|last=Belgum|title=D.A.'s Daughter Makes Own Way|date=February 11, 1997}}</ref> who later became an [[acupuncturist]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acupuncture.com/newsletters/m_dec08/attorney%20acupuncturist.htm |title=Deputy District Attorney Turned Acupuncturist - December 2008 |website=Acupuncture.com |date= |accessdate=2016-03-07}}</ref> She currently works as an advisor to [[Los Angeles County Board of Supervisors|Los Angeles County Supervisor]] [[Janice Hahn]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hahn.lacounty.gov/dana-garcetti-2/|title=Dana Garcetti|website=Hahn.lacounty.gov}}</ref>\n\nGarcetti has been the recipient of the [[Green Cross International|Green Cross Millennium Award]] for Local Environmental Leadership in 2003,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.globalgreen.org/events/millennium-awards/|title=Past Millennium Award Recipients|accessdate=July 26, 2018|publisher=Global Green}}</ref> the New Frontier Award presented by the [[John F. Kennedy Presidential Library and Museum]] in 2006,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jfklibrary.org/Events-and-Awards/New-Frontier-Award/Recipients/Eric-Garcetti-2006.aspx|title=Eric Garcetti 2006|publisher=John F. Kennedy Presidential Library and Museum|accessdate=July 26, 2018}}</ref> and the [[NAACP]] \"Person of the Year\" in 2014.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailynews.com/government-and-politics/20140516/los-angeles-mayor-eric-garcetti-honored-by-naacp-as-a-person-of-the-year |title=Los Angeles Mayor Eric Garcetti honored by NAACP as a Person of the Year |date=May 16, 2014 |first=Rick |last=Orlov |newspaper=Los Angeles Daily News |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140517153205/http://www.dailynews.com/government-and-politics/20140516/los-angeles-mayor-eric-garcetti-honored-by-naacp-as-a-person-of-the-year |archivedate=May 17, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nGarcetti was awarded the honorary Doctor of Humane Letters (L.H.D.) from [[Whittier College]] in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whittier.edu/alumni/poetnation/honorary|title=Honorary Degrees {{!}} Whittier College|website=www.whittier.edu|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of Jewish American politicians]]\n* [[List of mayors of the 50 largest cities in the United States]]\n* [[List of Mexican Americans#Political figures]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Sister project links |wikt=no |b=no |s=no |d=Q5386557 |v=no}}\n* [http://www.lamayor.org/ Office of Mayor Eric Garcetti] official mayoral website\n* [http://www.ericgarcetti.com/ Eric Garcetti for Mayor] official campaign website\n* {{Ballotpedia}}\n* {{C-SPAN|ericgarcetti}}\n* [https://www.britannica.com/biography/Eric-Garcetti Eric Garcetti] at ''[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]]''\n* {{imdb name|1553568}}\n* [http://www.ontheissues.org/Eric_Garcetti.htm Eric Garcetti] at [[On the Issues]]\n*{{CongLinks|votesmart=70499}}\n*\"[https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2017/06/25/most-interesting-mayors-america-215295 America\u2019s 11 Most Interesting Mayors]\" from ''Politico'' magazine\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Offices and distinctions\n|list1=\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-civ}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jackie Goldberg]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[Los Angeles City Council]]<br />from the [[Los Angeles City Council District 13|13th]] district|years=2001\u20132013}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Mitch O'Farrell]]}}\n\n{{s-bef|before=[[Alex Padilla]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[President of the Los Angeles City Council]] | years=2006\u20132012}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Herb Wesson]]}}\n\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Antonio Villaraigosa]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Mayor of Los Angeles]] | years=2013\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Articles related to Eric Garcetti\n|list1=\n{{LosAngelesMayor}}\n{{California cities and mayors of 100,000 population}}\n{{Mayors of the largest cities in the world by GDP}}\n{{Mayors of the 50 largest U.S. cities}}\n{{LACCPresidents}}\n}}\n{{portal bar|Biography|Greater Los Angeles|California|Politics|Hispanic and Latino American}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Garcetti, Eric}}\n[[Category:Eric Garcetti|*]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles City Council members]]\n[[Category:California Democrats]]\n[[Category:Climate change environmentalists]]\n[[Category:Human Rights Watch people]]\n[[Category:Joe Biden 2020 presidential campaign]]\n\n<!-- academic categories -->\n[[Category:Harvard-Westlake School alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the London School of Economics]]\n[[Category:Alumni of The Queen's College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:American Rhodes Scholars]]\n[[Category:School of International and Public Affairs, Columbia University alumni]]\n[[Category:Columbia College (New York) alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Southern California faculty]]\n[[Category:Occidental College faculty]]\n\n<!-- hobby & avocation categories -->\n[[Category:American jazz pianists]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American jazz composers]]\n[[Category:Photographers from California]]\n\n<!-- military categories -->\n[[Category:United States Navy reservists]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from California]]\n\n<!-- biographical information -->\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:People from Echo Park, Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:People from Encino, Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n<!-- ethnicity and religion categories (see the [[Wikipedia:Categorization/Ethnicity, gender, religion and sexuality]] guideline) -->\n[[Category:American Reform Jews]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American politicians of Mexican descent]]\n[[Category:Hispanic and Latino American mayors]]\n[[Category:Jewish mayors of places in the United States]]\n[[Category:Jewish American military personnel]]\n\n<!-- chronology categories -->\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American naval officers]]\n", "name_user": "2605:e000:1527:1102:8df4:aa9e:a651:4118", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(I Like Eric Garcetti)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eric_Garcetti"}
{"title_page": "Johan de Beer", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox tennis biography\n| name = Johan de Beer\n| image =\n| fullname = Johan de Beer\n| country_represented = {{flag|South Africa|1928}}\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1972|6|1}}\n| birth_place = [[Pretoria]], Transvaal Province\n| death_date =\n| death_place = \n| plays =\n| retired = 1994\n| careerprizemoney = $53,581\n| singlesrecord = 0\u20132\n| singlestitles = 0\n| highestsinglesranking = No. 397 (15 November 1993)\n| currentsinglesranking = \n| AustralianOpenresult =\n| FrenchOpenresult = \n| Wimbledonresult =\n| USOpenresult =\n| doublesrecord = 11\u201317\n| doublestitles = 0\n| highestdoublesranking = No. 92 (21 February 1994)\n| currentdoublesranking = \n| AustralianOpenDoublesresult = 2R ([[1994 Australian Open \u2013 Men's Doubles|1994]])\n| FrenchOpenDoublesresult = \n| WimbledonDoublesresult =\n| USOpenDoublesresult = 1R ([[1993 US Open \u2013 Men's Doubles|1993]])\n}}\n'''Johan \"Joey\" de Beer''' (born 1 June 1972) is a former professional [[tennis]] player from South Africa.\n\n==Biography==\nDe Beer, a doubles specialist from [[Pretoria]], was coached by Kobus Botha. He won a total of four [[ATP Challenger Tour|Challenger]] doubles titles during his career.\n\nIn 1993 he reached the doubles final of the [[South African Open (tennis)|South African Open]], an ATP Tour tournament in Durban, with [[Marcos Ondruska]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itftennis.com/procircuit/tournaments/men's-tournament/info.aspx?tournamentid=1010004751|title=ITF Tennis \u2013 Pro Circuit \u2013 Durban \u2013 29 March \u2013 05 April 1993|publisher=[[International Tennis Federation]]|accessdate=12 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe appeared twice in the main draw of a [[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]] event. He partnered [[Cristian Brandi]] at the [[1993 US Open (tennis)|1993 US Open]], for a first round exit, to 16th seeds [[Hendrik-Jan Davids]] and [[Piet Norval]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/141622004/|title=New York (AP)|date=1 September 1993|work=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]|page=28|accessdate=12 February 2016}}</ref> At the [[1994 Australian Open]] he made the second round with [[John-Laffnie de Jager]]. In the opening round, de Beer again faced the 16th seeds, but he and de Jager were victorious in straight sets, over [[Wayne Ferreira]] and [[Javier S\u00e1nchez (tennis)|Javier S\u00e1nchez]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article126923940 |title=Tennis|work=[[The Canberra Times]]|date=21 January 1994 |accessdate=13 February 2016 |page=20}}</ref> They lost an all South African second round match to [[Ellis Ferreira]] and [[Christo van Rensburg]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-page13950799|title=Tennis|work=[[The Canberra Times]]|date=22 January 1994 |accessdate=13 February 2016 |page=50}}</ref>\n\nEarly in the 1994 season he broke into the world's 100 ranked doubles players. It was also his final year on the circuit, he retired from tennis to complete a Physiotherapy degree at the [[University of Pretoria]].\n\nHe was at one time coach of [[Wayne Ferreira]] and a trainer for [[Tim Henman]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1980&dat=20020308&id=bAMuAAAAIBAJ&sjid=uakFAAAAIBAJ&pg=5000,982731&hl=en|title=Ferreira upsets Sampras in 2nd round|date=8 March 2002|work=[[The Item]]|page=4B|accessdate=12 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nCurrently he works for the [[Lawn Tennis Association]] in England as a coach and physiotherapist. He was [[Andy Murray]]'s physiotherapist when he won the Wimbledon title in 2013.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2013/jul/07/andy-murray-backup-team-wimbledon|title=Lendl and Judy the star players in Team Murray's triumph|last=Gibson|first=Owen|date=8 July 2013|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=12 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n==ATP Tour career finals==\n===Doubles: 1 (0\u20131)===\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=font-size:97%\n!style=\"width:75px\"|Outcome\n!style=\"width:30px\"|No.\n!style=\"width:50px\"|Year\n!style=\"width:200px\"|Tournament\n!style=\"width:50px\"|Surface\n!style=\"width:200px\"|Partner\n!style=\"width:200px\"|Opponents\n!style=\"width:140px\"|Score\n|-\n| style=\"background:#ffa07a;\"|Runner-up\n|1.\n|1993\n|[[South African Open (tennis)|Durban]], South Africa\n|Hard\n|{{flagicon|RSA|1928}} [[Marcos Ondruska]]\n|{{flagicon|RSA|1928}} [[Lan Bale]]<br />{{flagicon|ZIM}} [[Byron Black]]  \n|6\u20137, 2\u20136\n|}\n\n==Challenger titles==\n===Doubles: (4)===\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=font-size:97%\n!width=40|No.\n!width=50|Year\n!width=200|Tournament\n!width=60|Surface\n!width=160|Partner\n!width=200|Opponents\n!width=160|Score\n|-\n|1.\n|1993\n|[[Cincinnati]], US\n|Hard\n|{{flagicon|ZIM}} [[Kevin Ullyett]]\n|{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Wayne Arthurs (tennis)|Wayne Arthurs]]<br />{{flagicon|IND}} [[Leander Paes]]\n|7\u20136, 6\u20134\n|-\n|2.\n|1993\n|[[GHI Bronx Tennis Classic|Bronx]], US\n|Hard\n|{{flagicon|ZIM}} [[Kevin Ullyett]]\n|{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Wayne Arthurs (tennis)|Wayne Arthurs]]<br />{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Grant Doyle (tennis)|Grant Doyle]]\n|7\u20136, 7\u20136\n|-\n|3.\n|1993\n|[[Porto Challenger|Porto]], Portugal\n|Clay\n|{{flagicon|RSA|1928}} [[Brent Haygarth]]\n|{{flagicon|ITA}} [[Cristian Brandi]]<br />{{flagicon|ITA}} [[Federico Mordegan]]\n|6\u20132, 2\u20136, 7\u20136\n|-\n|4.\n|1994\n|[[Challenger La Manche|Cherbourg]], France\n|Carpet\n|{{flagicon|GBR}} [[Neil Broad]]\n|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Donald Johnson]]<br />{{flagicon|USA}} [[Kent Kinnear]]\n|7\u20136, 2\u20136, 6\u20133\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{ATP}}\n* {{ITF}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:de Beer, Johan}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:South African male tennis players]]\n[[Category:South African physiotherapists]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Pretoria]]\n[[Category:University of Pretoria alumni]]\n[[Category:South African tennis coaches]]\n[[Category:South African expatriates in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox tennis biography\n| name = Johan de Beer\n| image =\n| fullname = Johan de Beer\n| country_represented = {{flag|South Africa|1928}}\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1972|6|1}}\n| birth_place = [[Pretoria]], Transvaal Province\n| death_date =\n| death_place = \n| plays =\n| retired = 1994\n| careerprizemoney = $53,581\n| singlesrecord = 0\u20132\n| singlestitles = 0\n| highestsinglesranking = No. 397 (15 November 1993)\n| currentsinglesranking = \n| AustralianOpenresult =\n| FrenchOpenresult = \n| Wimbledonresult =\n| USOpenresult =\n| doublesrecord = 11\u201317\n| doublestitles = 0\n| highestdoublesranking = No. 92 (21 February 1994)\n| currentdoublesranking = \n| AustralianOpenDoublesresult = 2R ([[1994 Australian Open \u2013 Men's Doubles|1994]])\n| FrenchOpenDoublesresult = \n| WimbledonDoublesresult =\n| USOpenDoublesresult = 1R ([[1993 US Open \u2013 Men's Doubles|1993]])\n}}\n'''Johan \"Joey\" de Beer''' (born 1 June 1972) is a former professional [[tennis]] player from South Africa.\n\n==Biography==\nDe Beer, a doubles specialist from [[Pretoria]], was coached by Kobus Botha. He won a total of four [[ATP Challenger Tour|Challenger]] doubles titles during his career.\n\nIn 1993 he reached the doubles final of the [[South African Open (tennis)|South African Open]], an ATP Tour tournament in Durban, with [[Marcos Ondruska]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itftennis.com/procircuit/tournaments/men's-tournament/info.aspx?tournamentid=1010004751|title=ITF Tennis \u2013 Pro Circuit \u2013 Durban \u2013 29 March \u2013 05 April 1993|publisher=[[International Tennis Federation]]|accessdate=12 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe appeared twice in the main draw of a [[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]] event. He partnered [[Cristian Brandi]] at the [[1993 US Open (tennis)|1993 US Open]], for a first round exit, to 16th seeds [[Hendrik-Jan Davids]] and [[Piet Norval]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/141622004/|title=New York (AP)|date=1 September 1993|work=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]|page=28|accessdate=12 February 2016}}</ref> At the [[1994 Australian Open]] he made the second round with [[John-Laffnie de Jager]]. In the opening round, de Beer again faced the 16th seeds, but he and de Jager were victorious in straight sets, over [[Wayne Ferreira]] and [[Javier S\u00e1nchez]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article126923940 |title=Tennis|work=[[The Canberra Times]]|date=21 January 1994 |accessdate=13 February 2016 |page=20}}</ref> They lost an all South African second round match to [[Ellis Ferreira]] and [[Christo van Rensburg]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-page13950799|title=Tennis|work=[[The Canberra Times]]|date=22 January 1994 |accessdate=13 February 2016 |page=50}}</ref>\n\nEarly in the 1994 season he broke into the world's 100 ranked doubles players. It was also his final year on the circuit, he retired from tennis to complete a Physiotherapy degree at the [[University of Pretoria]].\n\nHe was at one time coach of [[Wayne Ferreira]] and a trainer for [[Tim Henman]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1980&dat=20020308&id=bAMuAAAAIBAJ&sjid=uakFAAAAIBAJ&pg=5000,982731&hl=en|title=Ferreira upsets Sampras in 2nd round|date=8 March 2002|work=[[The Item]]|page=4B|accessdate=12 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nCurrently he works for the [[Lawn Tennis Association]] in England as a coach and physiotherapist. He was [[Andy Murray]]'s physiotherapist when he won the Wimbledon title in 2013.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2013/jul/07/andy-murray-backup-team-wimbledon|title=Lendl and Judy the star players in Team Murray's triumph|last=Gibson|first=Owen|date=8 July 2013|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=12 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n==ATP Tour career 