h football|2010\u201311]],<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_div_1/9465306.stm | work=BBC News | title=Arbroath 4\u20131 Montrose | date=23 April 2011}}</ref> [[2016\u201317 in Scottish football|2016\u201317]] Runners-up: [[1997\u201398 in Scottish football|1997\u201398]], [[2006\u201307 in Scottish football|2006\u201307]] Play-off winners [[2007\u201308 in Scottish football|2007\u201308]]\n\n===National cup competitions===\nScottish Cup Semi-finalists: 1946\u201347\n\nScottish League Cup Semi-finalists: 1959\u201360\n\nScottish Youth Cup Semi-finalists: 2001\u201302\n\nScottish Challenge Cup Semi-finalists: 2012\u201313\n\nScottish Qualifying Cup:<ref>[http://www.rsssf.com/tabless/scotqualcuphist.html]</ref> Winners [[1902\u201303 in Scottish football|1903]] Runners-up: [[1898\u201399 in Scottish football|1899]], [[1911\u201312 in Scottish football|1912]]\n\n===Minor===\nReserve League Cup 2003, Combined Reserve League 1964, Northern League 1891\u201392, Forfarshire County League (joint) 1908\u201309, Dewar Shield 1937\u201338\n\nArbroath were the first winners of the Forfarshire Cup in 1883 and have won the trophy 17 times since then.\nWinners in 1883\u201384, 1887\u201388, 1889\u201390, 1892\u201393, 1895\u201396, 1896\u201397, 1906\u201307, 1913\u201314, 1920\u201321, 1923\u201324, 1933\u201334, 1935\u201336, 1938\u201339, 1939\u201340, 1957\u201358, 1993\u201394, 1995\u201396\n\n==Club records==\n*'''Biggest win:''' [[Arbroath 36\u20130 Bon Accord|36\u20130]] vs [[Bon Accord F.C.|Bon Accord]], 12 September 1885, [[Scottish Cup]] (World record)\n*'''Biggest defeat:''' 1\u20139 vs [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]], 25 August [[1993\u201394 in Scottish football|1993]], [[Scottish League Cup|League Cup]]\n*'''Highest home [[Scottish football attendance records|attendance]]:''' 13,510 vs [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]], 23 February [[1951\u201352 in Scottish football|1952]], Scottish Cup\n*'''Highest average home attendance:''' 4,780, [[1959\u201360 in Scottish football|1959\u201360 season]] (17 games)<ref>{{cite book| first=David| last=Ross| title=The Roar of the Crowd: Following Scottish football down the years| publisher=Argyll publishing| year=2005| isbn=978-1-902831-83-1| pages=96}}</ref>\n*'''Most capped player:''' [[Ned Doig]], 5 (2 whilst with Arbroath), [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]]\n*'''Most league appearances:''' 426, Tom Cargill, 1966\u201380\n*'''Most league goals in a season by a player:''' 45, David Easson, [[1958\u201359 in Scottish football|1958\u201359]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.arbroath-mad.co.uk/ Arbroath Mad fan site]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071016214744/http://relichtie.mysite.orange.co.uk/ Relichtie historic nostalgia site]\n\n{{Arbroath F.C.}}\n{{Scottish Professional Football League}}\n{{Scottish Football League}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n\n[[Category:Arbroath F.C.]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1878]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in Angus]]\n[[Category:1878 establishments in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League teams]]\n[[Category:Scottish Professional Football League teams]]\n", "name_user": "StatSearcher", "label": "safe", "comment": "Corrected an error", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arbroath_F.C."}
{"title_page": "Rich Cohen", "text_new": "{{short description|American non-fiction writer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name         = Rich Cohen\n| image        =\n| pseudonym    = \n| birth_name   =\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1968|7|30}}\n| birth_place  = [[Lake Forest, Illinois|Lake Forest]], [[Illinois]], U.S.\n| death_date   = \n| death_place  = \n| occupation   = Non-fiction writer, journalist, screenplay writer\n| period       = 1992\u2013present\n| subject      = \n| movement     = \n| notableworks = ''Tough Jews'' (1998)<br>''Sweet and Low'' (2006)<br> ''Monsters'' (2013)<br>''[[Vinyl (TV series)|Vinyl]]'' (2016)\n| spouse       = \n| partner      = \n| children     = \n| relatives    = \n| awards       = \n| signature    = \n}}\n\n'''Rich Cohen''' (born July 30, 1968) is an American [[non-fiction]] writer. He is a contributing editor at ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' and ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazines. He is co-creator, with [[Martin Scorsese]], [[Mick Jagger]] and [[Terence Winter]], of the [[HBO]] series ''[[Vinyl (TV series)|Vinyl]]''.<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/6865927/vinyl-tv-review-hbo Tim Goodmen, \"'Vinyl': TV Review\", ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', February 2, 2016.]</ref> His works have been ''[[New York Times]]'' bestsellers, ''New York Times'' Notable Books, and have been collected in the [[The Best American Essays|Best American Essays]] series. He lives in [[Ridgefield, Connecticut]], with four sons, Aaron, Nate, Micah and Elia.\n\n==Early life==\nCohen was born in [[Lake Forest, Illinois|Lake Forest]], [[Illinois]], and grew up in [[Chicago]]'s [[North Shore (Chicago)|North Shore]] suburb of [[Glencoe, Illinois|Glencoe]].<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Barnes and Noble |title=Machers And Rockers by Rich Cohen |url=http://search.barnesandnoble.com/Machers-and-Rockers/Rich-Cohen/e/9780393052800 |accessdate=2008-03-20}}</ref> He received his [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] from [[Tulane University]] in 1990. His father, the negotiator [[Herb Cohen (Negotiator)|Herb Cohen]], grew up with the broadcaster [[Larry King]]; Cohen worked on King's [[CNN]] show for a short time after graduation.<ref>Cohen, Rich, \"King and I\", ''Rolling Stone'', November 14, 1996.</ref> His sister, Sharon Cohen Levin, is an Assistant United States Attorney of the Southern District of New York. His brother, Steve Cohen, a former top aide to New York governor [[Andrew Cuomo]], is a partner at the law firm Zuckerman Spaeder in New York City.<ref>Lovett, Ken, [http://www.nydailynews.com/blogs/dailypolitics/2011/09/steve-cohen-lands \"Daily Politics: Steve Cohen Lands\"], ''New York Daily News'', September 20, 2011.</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Journalism===\nAn admirer of the works of [[journalism|journalists]] [[A. J. Liebling]], [[Ian Frazier]] and [[Joseph Mitchell (writer)|Joseph Mitchell]], Cohen took a job as a messenger at the offices of ''[[The New Yorker]]'' magazine,<ref>Ledbetter, C. S., [http://www.randomhouse.com/knopf/authors/cohen/csledbetter.html \"The Education of A Writer\"], Author's Desktop, Random House, retrieved 3-20-2008.</ref> where he published twelve stories in the \"Talk of the Town\" section in eighteen months.<ref>Cohen, Richard, ''Lake Effect: A Memoir'', New York: Knopf, 2001. p. 180.</ref> After working as a reporter for the ''[[New York Observer]]'', Cohen joined the staff of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' in 1994. Since 2007, he has been a contributing editor at [[Vanity Fair (magazine)|''Vanity Fair'']]. In 2008, Cohen's essay on German history was selected for inclusion in ''[[The Best American Essays|The Best American Essays of 2008]]''. In 2013, on NPR's Morning Edition, [[Newsweek]] and [[Daily Beast]] editor [[Tina Brown]] called Cohen's essay on the financier Ted Forstmann \"very entertaining\" and a \"must read\".<ref>[https://www.npr.org/2013/01/22/169355935/tina-browns-must-reads-hidden-lives NPR Staff, \"Tina Brown's Must-Reads: Hidden Lives\"], ''Morning Edition'', January 22, 2013.</ref>\n\n===Books===\n\n====''Tough Jews''====\nCohen published his first book ''Tough Jews''\u2014a [[non-fiction]] account of the [[Jewish-American organized crime|Jewish gangsters]] of 1930s [[Brooklyn]], notably those involved with [[Murder, Inc.]]\u2014in 1998. In ''[[The New York Times Book Review]]'', writer [[Vincent Patrick]] called the book \"marvelous and colorful\" with \"writing good enough to cause one, at times, to reread a page in order to savor the description\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/98/04/12/reviews/980412.12patrict.html?_r=1&oref=login |title=This You Call A Stick-up? |first=Vincent |last=Patrick |newspaper=The New York Times |date=1998-04-12 |accessdate=2008-03-20}}</ref> ''Newsweek'' critic [[Jack Kroll]] called the book a \"bloodstained fairy tale for adults ... entertaining and defiantly romantic\".<ref>[[Jack Kroll]], \"Welcome to the Kosher Nostra\", ''Newsweek'', April 20, 1998.</ref> In [[The New York Times]], critic [[Christopher Lehmann-Haupt]] called it \"exuberant\" and \"a vivid narrative\"; Cohen's book had \"taken the noise of these facts and turned it from gunfire into a kind of music\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/04/16/books/books-of-the-times-hardly-our-crowd-a-jewish-underworld.html |title=Hardly 'Our Crowd': A Jewish Underworld |first=Christopher |last=Lehmann-Haupt |newspaper=The New York Times |date=1998-04-16 |accessdate=2013-01-31}}</ref>\n\n====''The Avengers''====\nHis second work, ''The Avengers: A Jewish War Story'' (2000), follows a group of [[Jewish partisans|anti-Nazi partisans]] in the forests of [[Lithuania]] at the close of [[World War II]]. The book was excerpted in ''[[Newsweek]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.newsweek.com/id/86093 |title=A Final Mission |first=Rich |last=Cohen |work=Newsweek |date=2000-09-11 |accessdate=2008-03-20}}</ref> ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'' called the non-fiction work \"a terrific narrative of courage and tenacity\",<ref>''Publishers Weekly'', \"The Avengers: A Jewish War Story\", July 17, 2000</ref> and ''[[The Washington Post]]'' called it \"a tremendous story\".<ref>Goldsmith, Martin, \"Fighters and Fugues\", ''The Washington Post'', September 24, 2000</ref>\n\n====''Lake Effect''====\nHis third work, the memoir ''Lake Effect'' (2002), received the 2002 Great Lakes Book Award<ref>[http://news.bookweb.org/news/great-lakes-book-award-winners-announced American Booksellers Association, \"Great Lakes Book Award Winners Announced\", August 29, 2002.]</ref> and was a ''New York Times'' [[The New York Times Book Review#notable|Notable Book]].\n\n====''Sweet and Low''====\nCohen's 2006 book ''Sweet and Low'' is a memoir about the creation of the [[Sweet'n Low|artificial sweetener]], a product invented by [[Benjamin Eisenstadt]], the author's grandfather. ''Newsweek'' praised the book as \"sad, true and hilarious\";<ref>''Newsweek'', \"Sweet and Low\", April 17, 2006</ref> ''The Washington Post'' called it \"superb\",<ref>Powers, Katherine, \"Today's business world is cut-throat but often hilarious\", ''The Washington Post'', June 18, 2006.</ref> and \"a wildly addictive, high-octane narrative\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/04/09/AR2006040900956_pf.html |title=Sweet and Sour Dreams |first=John |last=Barlow |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=2006-04-10 |accessdate=2008-03-20}}</ref> Writing in ''The New York Times'', [[critic]] [[Michiko Kakutani]] called the book \"a classic\": \"A telling\u2014and often hilarious\u2014parable about the pursuit and costs of the American Dream\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/04/04/books/04kaku.html |title=Problems That Come in Little Packets |first=Michiko |last=Kakutani |newspaper=The New York Times |date=2006-04-04 |accessdate=2008-03-20}}</ref> Writing in [[Salon.com|Salon]], critic Laura Miller noted \"[Cohen] describes it all with an economical, pugnacious wit that never falters. The heart of the book is a long, complicated and darkly funny family feud encompassing intrigues, sabotage and widely divergent stories about what really happened and when, and of course, who it can all be blamed on.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.salon.com/2006/12/14/nonfiction/ |title=Best Nonfiction of 2006 |first=Laura |last=Miller |work=Salon |date=2006-12-14 |accessdate=2013-01-31}}</ref> The book was a ''New York Times'' Notable Book and received a 2006 [[Salon Book Awards#Salon Book Awards|Salon Book Award]].\n\n====''Israel is Real''====\nIn 2009, Cohen published ''Israel is Real: An Obsessive Quest to Understand the Jewish Nation and its History''. In ''[[The New York Times Book Review]]'', the writer [[Tony Horwitz]] said the book \"accomplished the miraculous. It made a subject that has vexed me since childhood into a riveting story.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/07/26/books/review/Horwitz-t.html |title=A Land and a People |first=Tony |last=Horwitz |newspaper=The New York Times |date=2009-07-26 |accessdate=2009-07-26}}</ref> Writing in ''[[Newsweek]]'', critic [[Sara Nelson (editor)|Sara Nelson]] called the book \"Iconoclastic and provocative.... Part history, part polemic, and all original, it is hard to categorize politically, which may be why readers will be arguing about it for years to come.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2009/05/21/the-13-hottest-summer-reads.html |title=The 13 Hottest Summer Reads |first=Sara |last=Nelson |work=Newsweek |date=2009-05-21 |accessdate=2013-01-31}}</ref> In ''[[The Jerusalem Post]]'', Elaine Margolin called the book \"an intoxicating narrative ... Cohen claims his book is about his 'obsessive quest to understand the Jewish nation and its history,' but it seems far more complex and personal than that. Beneath his perceptive and provocative prose about Jewish history, religion, identity and memory is his own heartfelt struggle to become a good Jew.... Cohen is a fearless time-traveler, an acrobat of sorts, who is equally adept at commenting on ancient Jewish history and biblical stories as he is about the contemporary appeal of Larry David or Woody Allen, and he often draws breathtaking comparisons between past and present Jewish life.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.jpost.com/LandedPages/PrintArticle.aspx?id=149656 |title=Reality Checks |first=Elaine |last=Margolin |newspaper=The Jerusalem Post |date=2009-07-24 |accessdate=2013-01-31}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Cohen co-wrote the memoir ''When I Stop Talking, You'll Know I'm Dead'', the story of American film producer [[Jerry Weintraub]]; the book was a ''New York Times'' bestseller.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/02/books/review/InsideList-t.html Jennifer Schuessler, \"Inside the List\", ''The New York Times Book Review'', April 23, 2010.]</ref>\n\n====''The Fish That Ate the Whale''====\nCohen's story of [[United Fruit]] president and banana king [[Sam Zemurray]], ''The Fish That Ate the Whale'', was published by [[Farrar, Straus & Giroux]] in 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2012-06-07/book-review-the-fish-that-ate-the-whale-by-rich-cohen |title=Book Review: 'The Fish That Ate the Whale,' by Rich Cohen |first=Daniel |last=Grushkin |publisher=Bloomberg Businessweek |date=2012-06-07 |accessdate=2012-07-02}}</ref> Writing in [[The New York Times Book Review]], critic and historian Mark Lewis called the book \"[[Rudyard Kipling|Kiplingesque]]\" and \"fascinating\", and provided an overview of Cohen's work. \"Rich Cohen books constitute a genre unto themselves: pungent, breezy, vividly written psychodramas about rough-edged, tough-minded Jewish ''machers'' who vanquish their rivals, and sometimes change the world in the process.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/09/16/books/review/the-fish-that-ate-the-whale-by-rich-cohen.html |title=Banana Republican: 'The Fish That Ate the Whale,' by Rich Cohen |first=Mark |last=Lewis |newspaper=The New York Times |date=2012-09-16 |accessdate=2012-09-16}}</ref> In [[The Christian Science Monitor]], critic Chris Hartman called the book \"masterful and elegantly written ... a cautionary tale for the ages\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/Books/Book-Reviews/2012/1018/The-Fish-That-Ate-the-Whale |title=Book Review: The Fish That Ate the Whale |first=Chris |last=Hartman |newspaper=The Christian Science Monitor|date=2012-10-18 |accessdate=2012-10-18}}</ref> In ''[[The Washington Post]]'', James Auley called it \"immensely readable\" and \"as good an example of the American promise as one could imagine\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://articles.washingtonpost.com/2012-07-21/entertainment/35489383_1_whale-american-promise-rich-cohen |title= The Life and Times of America's Banana King |first=James |last=Auley |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=2012-07-21 |accessdate=2012-07-21}}</ref> The [[Jerusalem Post|Jerusalem Post's]] Elaine Margolin called the book \"piercing and terrifically intuitive.... Cohen is a beautifully talented and vibrant writer who seems to effortlessly brings his pages to life.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jpost.com/Magazine/Books/Article.aspx?id=275611 |title=The Fruits of His Labor |first=Elaine |last=Margolin |newspaper=The Jerusalem Post Magazine|date=2012-06-28 |accessdate=2013-01-31}}</ref>\n\n====''Monsters''====\nOn October 29, 2013, Cohen published ''Monsters'': a story of football through the eyes of the 1985 [[Chicago Bears]]. In an advance review, [[Kirkus Reviews]] called the book \"devastating and moving\", \"engaging yet ultimately melancholy\"; \"ideal for anyone who wonders, 'What happens when you have a dream and that dream comes true?'\"<ref>[https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/rich-cohen/monsters-chicago/ \"Monsters: The 1985 Chicago Bears and the Wild Heart of Football\"], Kirkus, October 15, 2013.</ref> Writer [[Dave Eggers]] said ''Monsters'' was \"not just a great sports book, but a great book, period\", [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] selected it as a Best Book of the Month. At [[Grantland]], Kevin Nguyen wrote, \"As much as it is about the '85 Bears, ''Monsters'' is an emotional education of football\"; he continues, \"Cohen writes, 'It was [George] Halas, as much as anyone, who invented the modern NFL offense and lifted the game from the ground into the air.' You can't help but think that Cohen's doing the same thing here for sports narratives.\"<ref>Kevin Nguyen, [http://grantland.com/hollywood-prospectus/november-book-recommendations-monsters-the-isle-of-youth-anything-that-moves/ \"Monsters\"], Grantland, November 5, 2013.</ref> In a review for ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', writer and critic [[Joseph Epstein (writer)|Joseph Epstein]] wrote, \"Rich Cohen's ''Monsters'' is the best book on professional football I know.\"<ref>Joseph Epstein, \"Book Review: 'Monsters' by Rich Cohen\", ''The Wall Street Journal'', October 25, 2013.</ref> The book is a [[New York Times]] best seller.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/best-sellers-books/2013-11-24/hardcover-nonfiction/list.html \"Best Sellers Hardcover Nonfiction\"]. ''The New York Times'' November 24, 2013.</ref>\n\n====''The Sun and the Moon and the Rolling Stones''====\nCohen's next book, a narrative history of [[The Rolling Stones]] called ''The Sun and The Moon and the Rolling Stones'', was published by [[Spiegel and Grau]] in May 2016.<ref>[http://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/237039/the-sun-and-the-moon-and-the-rolling-stones-by-rich-cohen/9780804179232/ ''The Sun and the Moon and the Rolling Stone''], Penguin Random House Website. Accessed 2016-01-03.</ref> Cohen had been on close terms with the band since the mid-1990s.<ref>[http://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/warring-stones-stay-together-for-the-money-5hmw22n0s \"Warring Stones\"], ''[[The Times]]'' (U.K.), April 2, 2016.</ref> In a pre-publication review, ''[[Kirkus Reviews]]'' wrote, \"Cohen weaves together the peak events with a supple sense of the inner dynamics,\" calling the work, \"A compact and conversant history that makes the story new again, capturing the Rolling Stones in all their Faustian glory\".<ref>Kirkus, \"The Sun and the Moon and the Rolling Stones\", April 19, 2016.</ref> Writer [[Richard Price (writer)|Richard Price]] wrote of the book, \"With ''The Sun & The Moon & The Rolling Stones'', Rich Cohen has arrived as one of the greatest social and cultural historians of postwar twentieth century America.\"<ref>[http://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/237039/the-sun-and-the-moon-and-the-rolling-stones-by-rich-cohen/9780804179232/ ''The Sun and the Moon and the Rolling Stone''], Penguin Random House Website. Accessed 2016-04-08.</ref>\n\n====''The Last Pirate of New York''====\nThis book details the life and times of [[Albert W. Hicks]], an American criminal active from about 1840 to 1860. Cohen grew up hearing legendary stories of New York gangsters and found those legends had grown up hearing stories of even older gangster legends. He traced these legends back to the earliest, and contends Hicks was the transition between pirates of old and the new world of gangsters\u2014the last pirate and first gangster. Reviewing the book in the ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'', Rinker Buck wrote, \"'The Last Pirate of New York' is history-lite at its best, and readers will finish it with a satisfaction deeply relevant today. The truth about America's past\u2014the greasy pole of making a living, the lovable felons, the Barnum-esque self-promoters\u2014is a lot more interesting and useful to know than those patriotic fairy tales we were fed in school.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Ruck |first=Rinker|title=New York's Original Gangster: The Last Pirate of New York by Rich Cohen|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-last-pirate-of-new-york-review-new-yorks-original-gangster-11561732127|accessdate=July 2, 2019|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=June 28, 2019}}</ref> On [[CBS This Morning]], host [[Jeff Glor]] said, \"I'm not sure there's a better nonfiction writer in America than Rich Cohen.\"<ref>CBS This Morning, Jeff Glor; CBS-TV, June 29, 2019.</ref>\n\n===Movies and television===\nOn February 26, 2007, [[Paramount Pictures]] announced it had closed a deal to produce ''The Long Play'', a screenplay Cohen had written for [[Mick Jagger]] and director [[Martin Scorsese]], with Scorsese directing.<ref>Fleming, Michael and McClintock, Pamela, \"Scorsese, Monahan ready to 'Play,'\" ''Variety'', February 26, 2007.</ref> He has worked on the [[Starz (TV channel)|Starz]] series ''[[Magic City (TV series)|Magic City]]'', and is currently developing a project for [[HBO]].<ref>Daniel Brook, [http://forward.com/articles/154101/jewish-gangsters-get-their-day-at-museum/?p=all \"Jewish Gangsters Get Their Museum\"], ''The Forward'', April 13, 2012</ref>\n\nCohen is co-creator, with [[Martin Scorsese]], [[Mick Jagger]] and [[Terence Winter]], of the [[HBO]] series ''[[Vinyl (TV series)|Vinyl]]''.<ref>Tim Goodmen, [http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/6865927/vinyl-tv-review-hbo \"'Vinyl': TV Review\"], ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', February 2, 2016.</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n*2002 Great Lakes Book Award (General Nonfiction), ''Lake Effect''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bookweb.org/news/great-lakes-book-award-winners-announced |title=Great Lakes Book Award Winners Announced |work=bookweb.org |author= |date=August 29, 2002 |accessdate=January 19, 2019}}</ref>\n*2006 ASCAP-Deems Taylor Award for Music Writing (Special Recognition), ''Machers and Rockers''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ascap.com/press/2005/101205_deems |title=38th Annual ASCAP Deems Taylor Award Winners Announced |work=ASCAP.com |author= |date=October 12, 2005 |accessdate=January 19, 2019}}</ref>\n*2006 [[New York Times Notable Book of the Year]], ''Sweet and Low''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://archive.nytimes.com/www.nytimes.com/ref/books/review/20061203notable-books.html? |title=100 Notable Books of the Year  |work=[[The New York Times]] |author= |date=December 4, 2006 |accessdate=January 19, 2019}}</ref>\n*2006 [[Salon Book Awards|Salon Book Award]] (Nonfiction), ''Sweet and Low''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.salon.com/books/awards/2006/12/14/nonfiction/index.html |title=Best Nonfiction of 2006 |work=[[Salon (website)|Salon]] |author=Laura Miller |date=December 14, 2006 |accessdate=January 19, 2019}}</ref>\n*2012 San Francisco Chronicle 100 Best Books of the Year (Nonfiction), ''The Fish That Ate the Whale''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sfgate.com/books/article/Best-books-of-2012-100-recommended-books-4139185.php |title=Best books of 2012: 100 recommended books |work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |author=John McMurtrie |date=February 11, 2013 |accessdate=January 19, 2019}}</ref>\n*2012 Booklist Editor's Choice (Biography), ''The Fish That Ate the Whale''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ala.org/awardsgrants/fish-ate-whale-life-and-times-america%E2%80%99s-banana-king |title=The Fish That Ate the Whale |publisher=[[American Library Association]] |author= |date=2012 |accessdate=January 19, 2019}}</ref>\n*2013 Bank Street CBC Best Children's Book of the Year (Age 9-12), ''Alex and the Amazing Time Machine''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://us.macmillan.com/books/9781466816046 |title=Alex and the Amazing Time Machine |publisher=MacMillan |author= |date= |accessdate=January 19, 2019|quote=Bank Street Best Children's Book of the Year (bottom of page)}}</ref>\n*2016 Kirkus Reviews Best Books of the Year (Nonfiction), ''The Sun & The Moon & The Rolling Stones''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/rich-cohen/the-sun-and-the-moon-and-the-rolling-stones/ |title=The Sun The Moon and the Rolling Stones, Best Books of 2016 |work=[[Kirkus Reviews]] |author= |date=May 1, 2016 |accessdate=January 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''Tough Jews : Fathers, Sons, and Gangster Dreams '' (1998)\n* ''The Avengers: A Jewish War Story'' (2000)\n* ''Lake Effect'' (2002)\n* ''Machers and Rockers: Chess Records and the Business of Rock & Roll'' (2004)\n* ''Sweet and Low: A Family Story'' (2006)\n* ''Israel Is Real: An Obsessive Quest to Understand the Jewish Nation and Its History'' (2009)\n* ''The Fish That Ate The Whale: The Life and Times of America's Banana King'' (2012)\n* ''Alex and the Amazing Time Machine'' (juvenile) with ill. by [[Kelly Murphy]] (2012)\n* ''Monsters: The 1985 Chicago Bears and the Wild Heart of Football'' (2013)\n* ''The Sun & The Moon & The Rolling Stones'' (2016)\n* ''The Chicago Cubs: Story of a Curse'' (2017)\n* ''The Last Pirate of New York: A Ghost Ship, a Killer, and the Birth of a Gangster Nation'' (2019)\n\n'''[[Ghostwriter|Ghostwritten]]'''\n* ''When I Stop Talking, You'll Know I'm Dead'' by [[Jerry Weintraub]] with Rich Cohen (2010)\n* ''Unstoppable: My Life So Far'' by [[Maria Sharapova]] with Rich Cohen (2017)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://authorrichcohen.com/ Author Rich Cohen Web Site]\n*[https://www.npr.org/2012/06/02/154153252/americas-gone-bananas-heres-how-it-happened Rich Cohen on NPR's Weekend Edition, ''The Fish That Ate The Whale'']\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2012/09/16/books/review/the-fish-that-ate-the-whale-by-rich-cohen.html The New York Times Book Review, ''The Fish That Ate The Whale'']\n*[http://www.cbsnews.com/video/watch/?id=7418014n Rich Cohen on CBS News, ''The Fish That Ate The Whale'']\n*[https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=5418961 Rich Cohen on All Things Considered]\n*[http://www.wnyc.org/shows/lopate/episodes/2006/05/15 Rich Cohen on NPR's The Leonard Lopate Show 2006]\n*[http://www.wnyc.org/shows/lopate/episodes/2004/12/15 Rich Cohen on NPR's The Leonard Lopate Show 2005]\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2005/04/17/books/review/17COHENRE.html Rich Cohen on Hunter S. Thompson in ''The New York Times Book Review'']\n*[http://www.newsweek.com/id/86093 ''The Avengers'' Excerpt, Newsweek Magazine]\n*[http://www.randomhouse.com/knopf/authors/cohen/desktopnew.html Rich Cohen Author Page, Random House]\n*[http://search.barnesandnoble.com/Machers-and-Rockers/Rich-Cohen/e/9780393052800#TABS Rich Cohen Author Page, Barnes and Noble]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cohen, Rich}}\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Tulane University alumni]]\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American magazine journalists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American non-fiction writer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name         = Rich Cohen\n| image        =\n| pseudonym    = \n| birth_name   =\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1968|7|30}}\n| birth_place  = [[Lake Forest, Illinois|Lake Forest]], [[Illinois]], U.S.\n| death_date   = \n| death_place  = \n| occupation   = Non-fiction writer, journalist, screenplay writer\n| period       = 1992\u2013present\n| subject      = \n| movement     = \n| notableworks = ''Tough Jews'' (1998)<br>''Sweet and Low'' (2006)<br> ''Monsters'' (2013)<br>''[[Vinyl (TV series)|Vinyl]]'' (2016)\n| spouse       = \n| partner      = \n| children     = \n| relatives    = \n| awards       = \n| signature    = \n}}\n\n'''Rich Cohen''' (born July 30, 1968) is an American [[non-fiction]] writer. He is a contributing editor at ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' and ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazines. He is co-creator, with [[Martin Scorsese]], [[Mick Jagger]] and [[Terence Winter]], of the [[HBO]] series ''[[Vinyl (TV series)|Vinyl]]''.<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/6865927/vinyl-tv-review-hbo Tim Goodmen, \"'Vinyl': TV Review\", ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', February 2, 2016.]</ref> His works have been ''[[New York Times]]'' bestsellers, ''New York Times'' Notable Books, and have been collected in the [[The Best American Essays|Best American Essays]] series. He lives in [[Ridgefield, Connecticut]], with four sons, Aaron, Nate, Micah and Elia.\n\n==Early life==\nCohen was born in [[Lake Forest, Illinois|Lake Forest]], [[Illinois]], and grew up in [[Chicago]]'s [[North Shore (Chicago)|North Shore]] suburb of [[Glencoe, Illinois|Glencoe]].<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Barnes and Noble |title=Machers And Rockers by Rich Cohen |url=http://search.barnesandnoble.com/Machers-and-Rockers/Rich-Cohen/e/9780393052800 |accessdate=2008-03-20}}</ref> He received his [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] from [[Tulane University]] in 1990. His father, the negotiator [[Herb Cohen (Negotiator)|Herb Cohen]], grew up with the broadcaster [[Larry King]]; Cohen worked on King's [[CNN]] show for a short time after graduation.<ref>Cohen, Rich, \"King and I\", ''Rolling Stone'', November 14, 1996.</ref> His sister, Sharon Cohen Levin, is an Assistant United States Attorney of the Southern District of New York. His brother, Steve Cohen, a former top aide to New York governor [[Andrew Cuomo]], is a partner at the law firm Zuckerman Spaeder in New York City.<ref>Lovett, Ken, [http://www.nydailynews.com/blogs/dailypolitics/2011/09/steve-cohen-lands \"Daily Politics: Steve Cohen Lands\"], ''New York Daily News'', September 20, 2011.</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Journalism===\nAn admirer of the works of [[journalism|journalists]] [[A. J. Liebling]], [[Ian Frazier]] and [[Joseph Mitchell (writer)|Joseph Mitchell]], Cohen took a job as a messenger at the offices of ''[[The New Yorker]]'' magazine,<ref>Ledbetter, C. S., [http://www.randomhouse.com/knopf/authors/cohen/csledbetter.html \"The Education of A Writer\"], Author's Desktop, Random House, retrieved 3-20-2008.</ref> where he published twelve stories in the \"Talk of the Town\" section in eighteen months.<ref>Cohen, Richard, ''Lake Effect: A Memoir'', New York: Knopf, 2001. p. 180.</ref> After working as a reporter for the ''[[New York Observer]]'', Cohen joined the staff of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' in 1994. Since 2007, he has been a contributing editor at [[Vanity Fair (magazine)|''Vanity Fair'']]. In 2008, Cohen's essay on German history was selected for inclusion in ''[[The Best American Essays|The Best American Essays of 2008]]''. In 2013, on NPR's Morning Edition, [[Newsweek]] and [[Daily Beast]] editor [[Tina Brown]] called Cohen's essay on the financier Ted Forstmann \"very entertaining\" and a \"must read\".<ref>[https://www.npr.org/2013/01/22/169355935/tina-browns-must-reads-hidden-lives NPR Staff, \"Tina Brown's Must-Reads: Hidden Lives\"], ''Morning Edition'', January 22, 2013.</ref>\n\n===Books===\n\n====''Tough Jews''====\nCohen published his first book ''Tough Jews''\u2014a [[non-fiction]] account of the [[Jewish-American organized crime|Jewish gangsters]] of 1930s [[Brooklyn]], notably those involved with [[Murder, Inc.]]\u2014in 1998. In ''[[The New York Times Book Review]]'', writer [[Vincent Patrick]] called the book \"marvelous and colorful\" with \"writing good enough to cause one, at times, to reread a page in order to savor the description\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/98/04/12/reviews/980412.12patrict.html?_r=1&oref=login |title=This You Call A Stick-up? |first=Vincent |last=Patrick |newspaper=The New York Times |date=1998-04-12 |accessdate=2008-03-20}}</ref> ''Newsweek'' critic [[Jack Kroll]] called the book a \"bloodstained fairy tale for adults ... entertaining and defiantly romantic\".<ref>[[Jack Kroll]], \"Welcome to the Kosher Nostra\", ''Newsweek'', April 20, 1998.</ref> In [[The New York Times]], critic [[Christopher Lehmann-Haupt]] called it \"exuberant\" and \"a vivid narrative\"; Cohen's book had \"taken the noise of these facts and turned it from gunfire into a kind of music\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/04/16/books/books-of-the-times-hardly-our-crowd-a-jewish-underworld.html |title=Hardly 'Our Crowd': A Jewish Underworld |first=Christopher |last=Lehmann-Haupt |newspaper=The New York Times |date=1998-04-16 |accessdate=2013-01-31}}</ref>\n\n====''The Avengers''====\nHis second work, ''The Avengers: A Jewish War Story'' (2000), follows a group of [[Jewish partisans|anti-Nazi partisans]] in the forests of [[Lithuania]] at the close of [[World War II]]. The book was excerpted in ''[[Newsweek]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.newsweek.com/id/86093 |title=A Final Mission |first=Rich |last=Cohen |work=Newsweek |date=2000-09-11 |accessdate=2008-03-20}}</ref> ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'' called the non-fiction work \"a terrific narrative of courage and tenacity\",<ref>''Publishers Weekly'', \"The Avengers: A Jewish War Story\", July 17, 2000</ref> and ''[[The Washington Post]]'' called it \"a tremendous story\".<ref>Goldsmith, Martin, \"Fighters and Fugues\", ''The Washington Post'', September 24, 2000</ref>\n\n====''Lake Effect''====\nHis third work, the memoir ''Lake Effect'' (2002), received the 2002 Great Lakes Book Award<ref>[http://news.bookweb.org/news/great-lakes-book-award-winners-announced American Booksellers Association, \"Great Lakes Book Award Winners Announced\", August 29, 2002.]</ref> and was a ''New York Times'' [[The New York Times Book Review#notable|Notable Book]].\n\n====''Sweet and Low''====\nCohen's 2006 book ''Sweet and Low'' is a memoir about the creation of the [[Sweet'n Low|artificial sweetener]], a product invented by [[Benjamin Eisenstadt]], the author's grandfather. ''Newsweek'' praised the book as \"sad, true and hilarious\";<ref>''Newsweek'', \"Sweet and Low\", April 17, 2006</ref> ''The Washington Post'' called it \"superb\",<ref>Powers, Katherine, \"Today's business world is cut-throat but often hilarious\", ''The Washington Post'', June 18, 2006.</ref> and \"a wildly addictive, high-octane narrative\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/04/09/AR2006040900956_pf.html |title=Sweet and Sour Dreams |first=John |last=Barlow |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=2006-04-10 |accessdate=2008-03-20}}</ref> Writing in ''The New York Times'', [[critic]] [[Michiko Kakutani]] called the book \"a classic\": \"A telling\u2014and often hilarious\u2014parable about the pursuit and costs of the American Dream\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/04/04/books/04kaku.html |title=Problems That Come in Little Packets |first=Michiko |last=Kakutani |newspaper=The New York Times |date=2006-04-04 |accessdate=2008-03-20}}</ref> Writing in [[Salon.com|Salon]], critic Laura Miller noted \"[Cohen] describes it all with an economical, pugnacious wit that never falters. The heart of the book is a long, complicated and darkly funny family feud encompassing intrigues, sabotage and widely divergent stories about what really happened and when, and of course, who it can all be blamed on.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.salon.com/2006/12/14/nonfiction/ |title=Best Nonfiction of 2006 |first=Laura |last=Miller |work=Salon |date=2006-12-14 |accessdate=2013-01-31}}</ref> The book was a ''New York Times'' Notable Book and received a 2006 [[Salon Book Awards#Salon Book Awards|Salon Book Award]].\n\n====''Israel is Real''====\nIn 2009, Cohen published ''Israel is Real: An Obsessive Quest to Understand the Jewish Nation and its History''. In ''[[The New York Times Book Review]]'', the writer [[Tony Horwitz]] said the book \"accomplished the miraculous. It made a subject that has vexed me since childhood into a riveting story.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/07/26/books/review/Horwitz-t.html |title=A Land and a People |first=Tony |last=Horwitz |newspaper=The New York Times |date=2009-07-26 |accessdate=2009-07-26}}</ref> Writing in ''[[Newsweek]]'', critic [[Sara Nelson]] called the book \"Iconoclastic and provocative.... Part history, part polemic, and all original, it is hard to categorize politically, which may be why readers will be arguing about it for years to come.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2009/05/21/the-13-hottest-summer-reads.html |title=The 13 Hottest Summer Reads |first=Sara |last=Nelson |work=Newsweek |date=2009-05-21 |accessdate=2013-01-31}}</ref> In ''[[The Jerusalem Post]]'', Elaine Margolin called the book \"an intoxicating narrative ... Cohen claims his book is about his 'obsessive quest to understand the Jewish nation and its history,' but it seems far more complex and personal than that. Beneath his perceptive and provocative prose about Jewish history, religion, identity and memory is his own heartfelt struggle to become a good Jew.... Cohen is a fearless time-traveler, an acrobat of sorts, who is equally adept at commenting on ancient Jewish history and biblical stories as he is about the contemporary appeal of Larry David or Woody Allen, and he often draws breathtaking comparisons between past and present Jewish life.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.jpost.com/LandedPages/PrintArticle.aspx?id=149656 |title=Reality Checks |first=Elaine |last=Margolin |newspaper=The Jerusalem Post |date=2009-07-24 |accessdate=2013-01-31}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Cohen co-wrote the memoir ''When I Stop Talking, You'll Know I'm Dead'', the story of American film producer [[Jerry Weintraub]]; the book was a ''New York Times'' bestseller.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/02/books/review/InsideList-t.html Jennifer Schuessler, \"Inside the List\", ''The New York Times Book Review'', April 23, 2010.]</ref>\n\n====''The Fish That Ate the Whale''====\nCohen's story of [[United Fruit]] president and banana king [[Sam Zemurray]], ''The Fish That Ate the Whale'', was published by [[Farrar, Straus & Giroux]] in 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2012-06-07/book-review-the-fish-that-ate-the-whale-by-rich-cohen |title=Book Review: 'The Fish That Ate the Whale,' by Rich Cohen |first=Daniel |last=Grushkin |publisher=Bloomberg Businessweek |date=2012-06-07 |accessdate=2012-07-02}}</ref> Writing in [[The New York Times Book Review]], critic and historian Mark Lewis called the book \"[[Rudyard Kipling|Kiplingesque]]\" and \"fascinating\", and provided an overview of Cohen's work. \"Rich Cohen books constitute a genre unto themselves: pungent, breezy, vividly written psychodramas about rough-edged, tough-minded Jewish ''machers'' who vanquish their rivals, and sometimes change the world in the process.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/09/16/books/review/the-fish-that-ate-the-whale-by-rich-cohen.html |title=Banana Republican: 'The Fish That Ate the Whale,' by Rich Cohen |first=Mark |last=Lewis |newspaper=The New York Times |date=2012-09-16 |accessdate=2012-09-16}}</ref> In [[The Christian Science Monitor]], critic Chris Hartman called the book \"masterful and elegantly written ... a cautionary tale for the ages\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/Books/Book-Reviews/2012/1018/The-Fish-That-Ate-the-Whale |title=Book Review: The Fish That Ate the Whale |first=Chris |last=Hartman |newspaper=The Christian Science Monitor|date=2012-10-18 |accessdate=2012-10-18}}</ref> In ''[[The Washington Post]]'', James Auley called it \"immensely readable\" and \"as good an example of the American promise as one could imagine\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://articles.washingtonpost.com/2012-07-21/entertainment/35489383_1_whale-american-promise-rich-cohen |title= The Life and Times of America's Banana King |first=James |last=Auley |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=2012-07-21 |accessdate=2012-07-21}}</ref> The [[Jerusalem Post|Jerusalem Post's]] Elaine Margolin called the book \"piercing and terrifically intuitive.... Cohen is a beautifully talented and vibrant writer who seems to effortlessly brings his pages to life.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jpost.com/Magazine/Books/Article.aspx?id=275611 |title=The Fruits of His Labor |first=Elaine |last=Margolin |newspaper=The Jerusalem Post Magazine|date=2012-06-28 |accessdate=2013-01-31}}</ref>\n\n====''Monsters''====\nOn October 29, 2013, Cohen published ''Monsters'': a story of football through the eyes of the 1985 [[Chicago Bears]]. In an advance review, [[Kirkus Reviews]] called the book \"devastating and moving\", \"engaging yet ultimately melancholy\"; \"ideal for anyone who wonders, 'What happens when you have a dream and that dream comes true?'\"<ref>[https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/rich-cohen/monsters-chicago/ \"Monsters: The 1985 Chicago Bears and the Wild Heart of Football\"], Kirkus, October 15, 2013.</ref> Writer [[Dave Eggers]] said ''Monsters'' was \"not just a great sports book, but a great book, period\", [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] selected it as a Best Book of the Month. At [[Grantland]], Kevin Nguyen wrote, \"As much as it is about the '85 Bears, ''Monsters'' is an emotional education of football\"; he continues, \"Cohen writes, 'It was [George] Halas, as much as anyone, who invented the modern NFL offense and lifted the game from the ground into the air.' You can't help but think that Cohen's doing the same thing here for sports narratives.\"<ref>Kevin Nguyen, [http://grantland.com/hollywood-prospectus/november-book-recommendations-monsters-the-isle-of-youth-anything-that-moves/ \"Monsters\"], Grantland, November 5, 2013.</ref> In a review for ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', writer and critic [[Joseph Epstein (writer)|Joseph Epstein]] wrote, \"Rich Cohen's ''Monsters'' is the best book on professional football I know.\"<ref>Joseph Epstein, \"Book Review: 'Monsters' by Rich Cohen\", ''The Wall Street Journal'', October 25, 2013.</ref> The book is a [[New York Times]] best seller.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/best-sellers-books/2013-11-24/hardcover-nonfiction/list.html \"Best Sellers Hardcover Nonfiction\"]. ''The New York Times'' November 24, 2013.</ref>\n\n====''The Sun and the Moon and the Rolling Stones''====\nCohen's next book, a narrative history of [[The Rolling Stones]] called ''The Sun and The Moon and the Rolling Stones'', was published by [[Spiegel and Grau]] in May 2016.<ref>[http://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/237039/the-sun-and-the-moon-and-the-rolling-stones-by-rich-cohen/9780804179232/ ''The Sun and the Moon and the Rolling Stone''], Penguin Random House Website. Accessed 2016-01-03.</ref> Cohen had been on close terms with the band since the mid-1990s.<ref>[http://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/warring-stones-stay-together-for-the-money-5hmw22n0s \"Warring Stones\"], ''[[The Times]]'' (U.K.), April 2, 2016.</ref> In a pre-publication review, ''[[Kirkus Reviews]]'' wrote, \"Cohen weaves together the peak events with a supple sense of the inner dynamics,\" calling the work, \"A compact and conversant history that makes the story new again, capturing the Rolling Stones in all their Faustian glory\".<ref>Kirkus, \"The Sun and the Moon and the Rolling Stones\", April 19, 2016.</ref> Writer [[Richard Price (writer)|Richard Price]] wrote of the book, \"With ''The Sun & The Moon & The Rolling Stones'', Rich Cohen has arrived as one of the greatest social and cultural historians of postwar twentieth century America.\"<ref>[http://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/237039/the-sun-and-the-moon-and-the-rolling-stones-by-rich-cohen/9780804179232/ ''The Sun and the Moon and the Rolling Stone''], Penguin Random House Website. Accessed 2016-04-08.</ref>\n\n====''The Last Pirate of New York''====\nThis book details the life and times of [[Albert W. Hicks]], an American criminal active from about 1840 to 1860. Cohen grew up hearing legendary stories of New York gangsters and found those legends had grown up hearing stories of even older gangster legends. He traced these legends back to the earliest, and contends Hicks was the transition between pirates of old and the new world of gangsters\u2014the last pirate and first gangster. Reviewing the book in the ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'', Rinker Buck wrote, \"'The Last Pirate of New York' is history-lite at its best, and readers will finish it with a satisfaction deeply relevant today. The truth about America's past\u2014the greasy pole of making a living, the lovable felons, the Barnum-esque self-promoters\u2014is a lot more interesting and useful to know than those patriotic fairy tales we were fed in school.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Ruck |first=Rinker|title=New York's Original Gangster: The Last Pirate of New York by Rich Cohen|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-last-pirate-of-new-york-review-new-yorks-original-gangster-11561732127|accessdate=July 2, 2019|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=June 28, 2019}}</ref> On [[CBS This Morning]], host [[Jeff Glor]] said, \"I'm not sure there's a better nonfiction writer in America than Rich Cohen.\"<ref>CBS This Morning, Jeff Glor; CBS-TV, June 29, 2019.</ref>\n\n===Movies and television===\nOn February 26, 2007, [[Paramount Pictures]] announced it had closed a deal to produce ''The Long Play'', a screenplay Cohen had written for [[Mick Jagger]] and director [[Martin Scorsese]], with Scorsese directing.<ref>Fleming, Michael and McClintock, Pamela, \"Scorsese, Monahan ready to 'Play,'\" ''Variety'', February 26, 2007.</ref> He has worked on the [[Starz (TV channel)|Starz]] series ''[[Magic City (TV series)|Magic City]]'', and is currently developing a project for [[HBO]].<ref>Daniel Brook, [http://forward.com/articles/154101/jewish-gangsters-get-their-day-at-museum/?p=all \"Jewish Gangsters Get Their Museum\"], ''The Forward'', April 13, 2012</ref>\n\nCohen is co-creator, with [[Martin Scorsese]], [[Mick Jagger]] and [[Terence Winter]], of the [[HBO]] series ''[[Vinyl (TV series)|Vinyl]]''.<ref>Tim Goodmen, [http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/6865927/vinyl-tv-review-hbo \"'Vinyl': TV Review\"], ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', February 2, 2016.</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n*2002 Great Lakes Book Award (General Nonfiction), ''Lake Effect''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bookweb.org/news/great-lakes-book-award-winners-announced |title=Great Lakes Book Award Winners Announced |work=bookweb.org |author= |date=August 29, 2002 |accessdate=January 19, 2019}}</ref>\n*2006 ASCAP-Deems Taylor Award for Music Writing (Special Recognition), ''Machers and Rockers''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ascap.com/press/2005/101205_deems |title=38th Annual ASCAP Deems Taylor Award Winners Announced |work=ASCAP.com |author= |date=October 12, 2005 |accessdate=January 19, 2019}}</ref>\n*2006 [[New York Times Notable Book of the Year]], ''Sweet and Low''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://archive.nytimes.com/www.nytimes.com/ref/books/review/20061203notable-books.html? |title=100 Notable Books of the Year  |work=[[The New York Times]] |author= |date=December 4, 2006 |accessdate=January 19, 2019}}</ref>\n*2006 [[Salon Book Awards|Salon Book Award]] (Nonfiction), ''Sweet and Low''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.salon.com/books/awards/2006/12/14/nonfiction/index.html |title=Best Nonfiction of 2006 |work=[[Salon (website)|Salon]] |author=Laura Miller |date=December 14, 2006 |accessdate=January 19, 2019}}</ref>\n*2012 San Francisco Chronicle 100 Best Books of the Year (Nonfiction), ''The Fish That Ate the Whale''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sfgate.com/books/article/Best-books-of-2012-100-recommended-books-4139185.php |title=Best books of 2012: 100 recommended books |work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |author=John McMurtrie |date=February 11, 2013 |accessdate=January 19, 2019}}</ref>\n*2012 Booklist Editor's Choice (Biography), ''The Fish That Ate the Whale''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ala.org/awardsgrants/fish-ate-whale-life-and-times-america%E2%80%99s-banana-king |title=The Fish That Ate the Whale |publisher=[[American Library Association]] |author= |date=2012 |accessdate=January 19, 2019}}</ref>\n*2013 Bank Street CBC Best Children's Book of the Year (Age 9-12), ''Alex and the Amazing Time Machine''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://us.macmillan.com/books/9781466816046 |title=Alex and the Amazing Time Machine |publisher=MacMillan |author= |date= |accessdate=January 19, 2019|quote=Bank Street Best Children's Book of the Year (bottom of page)}}</ref>\n*2016 Kirkus Reviews Best Books of the Year (Nonfiction), ''The Sun & The Moon & The Rolling Stones''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/rich-cohen/the-sun-and-the-moon-and-the-rolling-stones/ |title=The Sun The Moon and the Rolling Stones, Best Books of 2016 |work=[[Kirkus Reviews]] |author= |date=May 1, 2016 |accessdate=January 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''Tough Jews : Fathers, Sons, and Gangster Dreams '' (1998)\n* ''The Avengers: A Jewish War Story'' (2000)\n* ''Lake Effect'' (2002)\n* ''Machers and Rockers: Chess Records and the Business of Rock & Roll'' (2004)\n* ''Sweet and Low: A Family Story'' (2006)\n* ''Israel Is Real: An Obsessive Quest to Understand the Jewish Nation and Its History'' (2009)\n* ''The Fish That Ate The Whale: The Life and Times of America's Banana King'' (2012)\n* ''Alex and the Amazing Time Machine'' (juvenile) with ill. by [[Kelly Murphy]] (2012)\n* ''Monsters: The 1985 Chicago Bears and the Wild Heart of Football'' (2013)\n* ''The Sun & The Moon & The Rolling Stones'' (2016)\n* ''The Chicago Cubs: Story of a Curse'' (2017)\n* ''The Last Pirate of New York: A Ghost Ship, a Killer, and the Birth of a Gangster Nation'' (2019)\n\n'''[[Ghostwriter|Ghostwritten]]'''\n* ''When I Stop Talking, You'll Know I'm Dead'' by [[Jerry Weintraub]] with Rich Cohen (2010)\n* ''Unstoppable: My Life So Far'' by [[Maria Sharapova]] with Rich Cohen (2017)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://authorrichcohen.com/ Author Rich Cohen Web Site]\n*[https://www.npr.org/2012/06/02/154153252/americas-gone-bananas-heres-how-it-happened Rich Cohen on NPR's Weekend Edition, ''The Fish That Ate The Whale'']\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2012/09/16/books/review/the-fish-that-ate-the-whale-by-rich-cohen.html The New York Times Book Review, ''The Fish That Ate The Whale'']\n*[http://www.cbsnews.com/video/watch/?id=7418014n Rich Cohen on CBS News, ''The Fish That Ate The Whale'']\n*[https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=5418961 Rich Cohen on All Things Considered]\n*[http://www.wnyc.org/shows/lopate/episodes/2006/05/15 Rich Cohen on NPR's The Leonard Lopate Show 2006]\n*[http://www.wnyc.org/shows/lopate/episodes/2004/12/15 Rich Cohen on NPR's The Leonard Lopate Show 2005]\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2005/04/17/books/review/17COHENRE.html Rich Cohen on Hunter S. Thompson in ''The New York Times Book Review'']\n*[http://www.newsweek.com/id/86093 ''The Avengers'' Excerpt, Newsweek Magazine]\n*[http://www.randomhouse.com/knopf/authors/cohen/desktopnew.html Rich Cohen Author Page, Random House]\n*[http://search.barnesandnoble.com/Machers-and-Rockers/Rich-Cohen/e/9780393052800#TABS Rich Cohen Author Page, Barnes and Noble]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cohen, Rich}}\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Tulane University alumni]]\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American magazine journalists]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toSara Nelson(link changed toSara Nelson (editor)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rich_Cohen"}
{"title_page": "Chicago Teachers Union", "text_new": "{{Infobox Union\n|name= Chicago Teachers Union \n|country= [[United States]]\n|affiliation=[[American Federation of Teachers|AFT]], [[Illinois Federation of Teachers|IFT]], [[Chicago Federation of Labor|CFL]], [[AFL-CIO]], [[Illinois AFL-CIO|IL AFL-CIO]]\n|members= 25,000  (2018)\n|full_name= \n|native_name=\n|founded= 1937\n|current= \n|head=[[Jesse Sharkey]] (president)\n|dissolved_date=\n|dissolved_state= \n|merged_into= \n|office= 1901 West Carroll Avenue<br/>[[Chicago, Illinois]] 60612\n|people=[[Margaret Haley]]<br/>[[Jacqueline B. Vaughn]]<br/>[[Karen Lewis (labor leader)|Karen Lewis]]\n|website=[http://www.ctulocal1.org/ ctulocal1.org]\n|footnotes= \n}}\n\nThe '''Chicago Teachers Union''' ('''CTU''') is a [[Trade union|labor union]] representing teachers, paraprofessionals, and clinicians in the [[Chicago Public Schools|Chicago public school system]]. The union has consistently fought for improved pay, benefits, and job security for its members, and it has resisted efforts to vary teacher pay based on performance evaluations. It has also pushed for improvements in the Chicago schools, and since its inception argued that its activities benefited students as well as teachers.<ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), pp. 3\u20134. \"In addition to the issue of unionization, scholars have debated whether teachers joined unions to pursue monetary gains or to reform the public schools. Since teachers founded the AFT in 1916, the organization has portrayed itself as a union fighting for better salaries and benefits for its members and improvements in the public schools. Indeed, teachers' unions across the land asserted that they wanted improved pay and conditions for teachers in order to provide quality education for the students.\"</ref>\n\nThe CTU united several teachers' organizations in Chicago in the wake of a teachers' revolt against banks during the [[Great Depression]]. It was chartered in 1937 as Local 1 of the [[American Federation of Teachers]] (AFT), in which it played a founding role. It was the largest and most active AFT Local until the 1960s.<ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), pp. 1\u20132. \"In the early years of the twentieth century, the center of teacher unionism was found in Chicago. [...]  The CTU attracted a majority of Chicago teachers and remained the largest and most influential AFT local until the 1960s.\"</ref> The CTU won [[collective bargaining]] rights in 1966 and conducted several [[Strike action|strikes]] during the 1970s and 1980s. In September 2012, the union began its first strike in 25 years.\n\nThe CTU is also affiliated with the Illinois Federation of Teachers, the [[Chicago Federation of Labor]], and the [[AFL-CIO]]. It has more than 25,000 members. Current officers come from the Caucus of Rank-and-File Educators, elected in 2010 to replace the longstanding United Progressive Caucus. From that point until her 2018 retirement, [[Karen Lewis (labor leader)|Karen Lewis]] was president. Through a successors election the new officer slate became: President [[Jesse Sharkey]], Vice President Stacy Davis Gates, Recording Secretary Michael Brunson and Financial Secretary Maria Moreno.<ref name=\"CTU Contacts\">{{cite web|title=For Members \u00bb CTU Contacts|url=http://www.ctunet.com/for-members/contacts|publisher=Chicago Teachers Union|accessdate=20 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"CT - Key Players\">{{cite news|title=Key players Sketches of negotiators in teachers contract talks|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2012-09-11/news/ct-met-teachers-strike-thumbnails-20120911_1_alicia-winckler-jesse-sharkey-cps|accessdate=20 September 2012|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=11 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Origins==\n\n===Chicago Teachers Federation===\nThe CTU originated from the Chicago Teachers Federation (CTF), an organization of women elementary school teachers founded in 1897. In its first few years, it ran a successful campaign to increase teacher pay, and its membership grew to 2500.<ref name=\"West 1971\">{{cite web|last=West|first=Lucy|title=Chicago Teachers' Federation records, 1864-1968 (bulk 1897-1968)|url=http://chsmedia.org/media/fa/fa/M-C/CTF-inv.htm|work=Descriptive Inventory for the Collection|publisher=Chicago Historical Society|accessdate=11 September 2012|date=July 1971}}</ref> In 1900, the CTF elected Catherine Goggin and [[Margaret Haley]] as its officers, deciding to pay them the same wages as those made by teachers.<ref name=\"West 1971\" />\n\n[[File:Chicagoteachers1900.jpg|thumb|[[Margaret Haley]] and Catherine Goggin, two early leaders of the CTF, prompted the investigation of corporate [[Tax evasion|tax evaders]] as a means of restoring the city's funds.|262x262px]]\n\nUnder the leadership of Haley and Goggin, the CTF struggled for [[Women's suffrage in the United States|women's suffrage]], for women's rights within the labor movement, and for the right of woman workers to earn as much as their male counterparts.<ref name=\"Rousmaniere - CHS encyc\">{{cite web|last=Rousmaniere|first=Kate|title=Chicago Teachers Federation|url=http://www.encyclopedia.chicagohistory.org/pages/271.html|encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Chicago|publisher=Chicago Historical Society|accessdate=11 September 2012|year=2005}}</ref><ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), p. 7. \"With two-thirds of the teaching workforce female, teacher unionism was firmly located in the context of women's work and women's struggles to enhance the status and rewards of teaching. For most of this century, boards of education denied female teachers equal pay with men, the right to marry, and access to leadership positions in the schools. In Chicago, female elementary school teachers used the union as a vehicle to campaign for equal pay with high school teachers.\"</ref> The CTF also launched a successful campaign against corporate tax evasion, the compensation for which was used to pay back salaries upon which the city had reneged.<ref name=\"West 1971\" />\n\nIn 1902, the CTF joined the [[Chicago Federation of Labor]] (CFL). It was the first time that a teachers' group had affiliated with a larger labor organization.<ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), p. 22.</ref>  In 1916, Haley and the CTF helped to found the [[American Federation of Teachers]] (AFT), in which the CTF became Local 1.<ref name=\"Rousmaniere - CHS encyc\" />  However, the Chicago Board of Education, led by Jacob Loeb, had recently passed a rule against teacher unions:<ref name=\"ILHS Hall of Honor 2007\">{{cite web|title=Hall of Honor|url=http://illinoislaborhistory.com/hall-of-honor/200-2007-hall-of-honor.html?fontstyle=f-smaller|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130126131111/http://illinoislaborhistory.com/hall-of-honor/200-2007-hall-of-honor.html?fontstyle=f-smaller|url-status=dead|archive-date=26 January 2013|year=2007|publisher=Illinois Labor History Society|accessdate=11 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n<blockquote>Membership by teachers in labor unions or in organizations of teachers affiliated with a trade union or a federation or association of trade unions, as well as teachers' organizations which have officers, business agents, or other representatives who are not members of the teaching force, is inimical to proper discipline, prejudicial to the efficiency of the teaching force, and detrimental to the welfare of the public school system.  Therefore, such membership, affiliation, or representation is hereby prohibited.</blockquote>\n\nThis rule, which became known as the Loeb rule, further stated that teachers would be fired unless they stated in writing that they did not belong to any such organization.<ref name=\"Survey - 20 Oct 1915\">{{cite news|title=Shall school teachers join labor unions?|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RfsqAAAAMAAJ&lpg=PA1&ots=5PDkfBnT4M&dq=%22Membership%20by%20teachers%20in%20labor%20unions%20or%20in%20organizations%20of%20teachers%20affiliated%20with%20a%20trade%20union%22&pg=PA1#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=11 September 2012|newspaper=The Survey|date=2 October 1915|publisher=Charity Organization Society of the City of New York|pages=1\u20132}}</ref> The Loeb rule allowed the city to fire 68 teachers, including the CTF leadership, who refused to leave the union.<ref name=\"ILHS Hall of Honor 2007\" /> By 1917, the CTF was forced to withdraw from both the CFL and the AFT.<ref name=\"West 1971\" /><ref name=\"Rousmaniere - CHS encyc\" />\n\nSubsequent passage of the Otis rule placed education in the hands of a centralized Board of Education. However, the board was still appointed by city politicians. In the coming years, the city and School Board were accused of rampant corruption, particularly in connection with two-time mayor [[William Hale Thompson]].<ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), p. 12. \"At no time was this political control of Chicago public education more apparent than under the regime of Republican mayor William H. Thompson. Mayor of the city from 1915 to 1923 and again from 1927 to 1931, Thompson had connections with organized crime and presided over some of the worst political corruption in Chicago's history.\"</ref> Many CPS employees were appointed by the Mayor, and a 1931 study found that Chicago spent more money than any other major city on operations costs outside of education.<ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), p. 13.</ref> The proliferation of bureaucracy was a serious concern: when the Elementary Teachers Union formed in 1928, one of its stated goals was \"freeing of teachers from the increasingly intolerable burden of red tape and clerical work.<ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), p. 21.</ref>\n\n=== Great Depression ===\n\nChicago teachers became exceptionally militant during the Great Depression, when teachers and many of their students faced extreme poverty and miserable school conditions.<ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), p. 9. \"Chicago was one of the only cities in the Great Depression where public school teachers actively challenged the policies of school authorities and built a united teachers' organization, the Chicago Teachers Union (CTU). Although divided by gender, ethnicity, and religion and between lowered paid elementary and higher paid high school teachers, still more than two-thirds of the teachers joined the CTU, making it the largest teachers union in the country.\"</ref><ref name=\"Simpson - 2 Aug 2012\" /> Particularly in the inner city, classrooms were undersupplied and overcrowded. \"Too many city classrooms still resemble enlarged prison cells,\" according to a 1931 report.<ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), p. 20.</ref> The city neglected to pay its teachers on 37 out of 46 paydays.<ref name=\"West 1971\" /> Teachers also claimed of egregious class sizes and poorly maintained schools.<ref name=\"Burbank 1971\" /><ref name=\"The Day - 7 Dec 1931\">{{cite news|title=Chicago Teachers Demand Smaller Units, Shorter Day|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=xpErAAAAIBAJ&sjid=nXEFAAAAIBAJ&pg=5577,2611273&dq=chicago+teachers&hl=en|accessdate=19 September 2012|newspaper=The Day|date=7 December 1931|agency=AP|page=1}}</ref>  Most stayed in the classroom teaching, although one committed suicide.<ref name=\"TNB - 27 April 1933\">{{cite news|title=Chicago School Teacher, Unpaid for Eight Long Months, Kills Self as Promises from the Mayor Halt Demonstrations|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=hppXAAAAIBAJ&sjid=20QNAAAAIBAJ&dq=chicago%20teachers%20union&pg=6637%2C2090447|accessdate=11 September 2012|newspaper=Toledo News-Bee|date=27 April 1933}}</ref> Teachers organized independently to procure food and clothing for their students, giving large sums from their own shrinking paychecks.<ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), p. 32\u201333. \"To alleviate the suffering of the Depression, teachers organized committees within schools to collect and distribute money and clothing to the poorer students and served breakfast to hungry children. During the school year of 1930\u201331, the teachers of Chicago contributed more than $112,000 for food and clothing for their students. Yet teachers agonized because they could not contribute more to student financial welfare.\"</ref>\n\n====Contested municipal reforms====\nOnce again, supporters of the public schools (including Haley) launched a campaign against local tax dodgers, who they said had owed taxes on hundreds of millions of dollars worth of new construction.<ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), p. 29. \"Additionally, local politicians and assessors throughout the 1920s failed to tax major property holders and large corporations. Between 1915 and 1925, as Chicago's population increased by 28 percent and there was unprecedented new construction in the city worth some $200 million a year, the official assessed valuation of property increased by only $29 million per annum.\"</ref> This time, business leaders retaliated, in February 1932 forming a group called the Citizen's Committee on Public Expenditures (CCPE), which pushed the city to cut its education budget.<ref name=\"Burbank 1971\">{{cite journal|last=Burbank|first=Lyman|title=Chicago Public Schools and the Depression Years of 1928\u20131937|journal=Journal of the Illinois State Historical Society|date=Winter 1971|volume=64|url=http://dig.lib.niu.edu/ISHS/ishs-1971winter/ishs-1971winter-365.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100806230641/http://dig.lib.niu.edu/ISHS/ishs-1971winter/ishs-1971winter-365.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=2010-08-06|accessdate=12 September 2012}}</ref> The banks, which controlled millions of dollars worth of city tax anticipation warrants, announced (and possessed) de facto control over city policy. In a statement published in the ''Saturday Evening Post'', railroad president and CCPE secretary Fred Sargent wrote that banks \"positively will not lend money for any municipal function which does not have our active support. This has been a powerful lever in dealing with the really small number of recalcitrants in public office who still cling to a faith in a Santa Claus.\" And: \"business men of Chicago have learned their lesson. We shall not again let the mechanism run wild.\"<ref name=\"Sargent SEP 1933\">{{cite news|last=Sargent|first=Fred W.|title=The Taxpayer Takes Charge|url=http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/articles/21597600/taxpayer-takes-charge|accessdate=21 September 2012|newspaper=Saturday Evening Post|date=14 January 1933|page=21}}. Partly quoted in Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), p. 30. Sargent also advocated an end to income taxes.</ref> Sargent and the CCPE were accused of \"financial fascism\" for taking control of the city government through financial blackmail \"with little regard for the needs of the masses and their children.\"<ref name=\"Stillman 1933\">{{cite journal|last=Stillman|first=Charles B.|title=Financial Fascism in Control|journal=The Phi Delta Kappan|date=February 1933|volume=15|issue=5|pages=132\u2013134|jstor=20258189}}</ref>\n\n====Teachers unhappy====\nTeachers, with support from students and parents, began an escalating campaign to restore funding to the schools and paychecks to the teachers. They believed that Chicago's banks had access to millions of dollars in unpaid taxes that might balance the city's budget; they were angry about the CCPE's explicitly anti-school agenda, and they were also provoked by a $90 million bank bailout from the [[Reconstruction Finance Corporation]] that did nothing to help the schools.<ref name=\"Simpson - 2 Aug 2012\" /> More generally, teachers were alarmed by an apparent corporate attack on education; they believed that the nation's ruling class wanted to dismantle education for the public and reserve it only for the wealthy.<ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), p. 36\u201337. \"Teachers began to express the idea that they were defending democracy and the public education system from self-serving business and political elites. Reflecting a general public optimism with the promise of education, teachers viewed the schools as avenues for social mobility and bulwarks of a more democratic society. [...] Many teachers believed there was a nationwide plot by people of power and wealth to cripple public education and to restrict schooling to those who could afford it.\"</ref>\n\nProtests and petitions mounted from 1931\u20131932. Students planned a solidarity demonstration, and although many were convinced to stay in school, 13,000 students actually walked out.<ref name=\"CSM 6 April 133\">{{cite news|title=Chicago Students Strike in Protest To Help Teachers: Thousands Walk Out of High Schools to Force Paying Back Salaries|newspaper=Christian Science Monitor|date=6 April 1933|id={{ProQuest|513352228}}}}</ref> Teachers became frustrated with union leaders who urged restraint for the teachers and argued amongst each other; new rank-and-file organizations emerged. Historian John F. Lyons describes these groups as key in the development of solidarity among the city's teachers:\n\n<blockquote>Many began to see the weak and divided position of the unions as the main reason for lack of success in the dispute. Accordingly, between 1931 and 1933, ordinary teachers founded a number of temporary groups to unify their ranks and actively pursue their demands. In November 1931, the South Side Teachers organized a number of mass meetings, publicity campaigns, and voting drives, and appealed without success to various teachers' unions to cooperate in framing a legislative program. Three more rank-and-file teachers' organizations emerged in 1932: The Civic Education Association of Chicago, initially organized by teachers from Senn High School on the North Side, aimed \"to bring all of the teachers of Chicago, organized and unorganized, into one effective unit.\" The Chicago Teacher Voter Association set out with the sole aim of campaigning for politicians sympathetic to the teachers' plight. The South Side Teachers called for a boycott of stores, hotels, and other businesses that had participated in the tax strike.<ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), p. 35\u201336.</ref></blockquote>\n\nTeachers increasingly began to feel singled out for bad treatment by the city. This feeling was amplified in March 1933 when teachers learned that, as teacher pay was being further cut by 15%, school janitors had received a secret raise. The city announced furthermore that on the next pay day all municipal employees except teachers would be paid.<ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), p. 38.</ref>\n\n====Teachers revolt====\nIn April 1933, teachers targeted banks in the downtown [[Chicago Loop|Loop]], which they held \"financially responsible\" for the $30 million deficit in teacher payments.<ref name=\"NYT - 25 April 1933\">{{cite news|title=5,000 Chicago Teachers Storm Five Banks; Dawes Heckled as He Argues With Crowd|newspaper=New York Times|date=25 April 1933|agency=AP|id={{ProQuest|100724303}}}}</ref>  On April 24, 1933 (the beginning of spring break), thousands of teachers entered bank offices and began causing mayhem. They chanted \"Pay us! Pay us!\"<ref name=\"Simpson - 2 Aug 2012\" /> At City National Bank, they chanted \"We want Dawes! We Want Dawes!\", referring to bank chairman and recent US vice president [[Charles G. Dawes]]. Dawes appeared, surrounded by guards, and attempted to appease the mob over shouts.<ref name=\"MontGaz 25 April 1933\" /> Police, who had also experienced a number of payless paydays, were reluctant to interfere.<ref name=\"MontGaz 25 April 1933\">{{cite news|title=Chicago Teachers Storm Loop Banks|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=2H8uAAAAIBAJ&sjid=PJkFAAAAIBAJ&dq=chicago%20teachers&pg=5763%2C3096246|accessdate=19 September 2012|newspaper=Montreal Gazette|date=25 April 1933|agency=AP|page=6}}</ref>\n\nTeachers conducted more 'raids' on 27 April, demanding of bankers: \"Pay your taxes!\" and \"We want food!\" After joining city meetings en masse, they proceeded to the Chicago Title and Trust Company, which held $10 million of property taxes in escrow. President Holman Pettibone spoke to the crowd from a second-story window and attempted to convince them that the company owed nothing to the city.<ref name=\"NYT - 27 April 1933\">{{cite news|title=Teachers Stage New Chicago Riot: Over 3,000 Defy Police and Guards to Demand Tax Payments by Bank \u2013 Bank Accounting Ordered \u2013 Trust Company Must Report Funds Held in Escrow For Property Taxes|newspaper=New York Times|date=27 April 1933|page=19|id={{ProQuest|100715239}}}}</ref> (In fact, Chicago Title and Trust did possess $10 million of unpaid property tax money, held in escrow accounts for tax evaders; Pettibone argued that the bank could not legitimately hand them over to the city.)<ref name=\"CDT - 27 April 1933\">{{cite news|title=Mayor and AIDS Take Pay Fight to Springfield: Postpone Action on School Closing \u2013 First Bill Passed \u2013 Board Defers Action on School Closing. Teachers Put on New Demonstration As Officials Seek Pay Funds \u2013 Roosevelt and MacDonald Reach Agreement|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=27 April 1933|pages=1, 6|id={{ProQuest|181382209}}}}</ref> Here, they clashed directly with police and bankers; several teachers were beaten and a large plate-glass window was broken.<ref name=\"WP - 27 April 1933\">{{cite news|title=Unpaid Chicago Police Club Unpaid Teachers in Rioting: Patrolmen, on Horses, Injure Many Women as Hundreds Again Stage Protest in Loop Area for $30,000,000 Due on Pay|newspaper=Washington Post|date=27 April 1933|agency=UP|page=1|id={{ProQuest|150407999}}}}</ref> The [[National Education Association]] telegraphed bankers directly, threatening to move the organization's convention (with its 10,000 attendees) away from Chicago\u2014a potential blow for the upcoming [[World's Fair]].)<ref name=\"LDS - 2 May 1933\">{{cite news|title=Says Teachers Might Embarrass Chicago|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=mcwgAAAAIBAJ&sjid=z2oFAAAAIBAJ&dq=chicago%20teachers&pg=5733%2C2316328|accessdate=19 September 2012|newspaper=Lewiston Daily Sun|date=2 May 1933|agency=AP|page=Eleven}}</ref>\n\nIn early May, bankers agreed to buy tax anticipation warrants from the city. (Practically, this meant the banks were loaning the city money.) Bankers issued a collective statement suggesting that further demonstrations from teachers would provoke them to reverse their decision. Mayor Edward J. Kelly echoed the statement.<ref name=\"LDS 13 May 1933\">{{cite news|title=Bankers Warn Chicago Teachers Not to Parade: Teachers Get pay for Last September and Promise of More Money Soon|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ocwgAAAAIBAJ&sjid=z2oFAAAAIBAJ&dq=chicago%20teachers&pg=2648%2C3059286|accessdate=19 September 2012|newspaper=Lewiston Daily Sun|date=13 May 1933|agency=AP|page=1}}</ref> Yet in July, the school board announced further pay cuts, provoking demonstrations from ''tens'' of thousands of teachers.<ref name=\"Simpson - 2 Aug 2012\">{{cite web|last=Simpson|first=Bob|title=The Chicago Teacher Revolt of 1933|url=http://www.laborheritage.org/?p=2581&iact=hc&vpx=341&vpy=177&dur=474&hovh=192&hovw=260&tx=185&ty=133&sig=108900284445453467695&ei=asJOUIGDPeLm0QGN1oD4BQ&page=2&tbnh=131&tbnw=200&start=7&ndsp=11&ved=1t:429,r:5,s:7,i:119|publisher=Labor Heritage Foundation|accessdate=11 September 2012|date=2 August 2012}}</ref> 25,000 people gathered on July 21, 1933, for a \"Save Our Schools\" protest. Banners read \"Don't let the bankers cheat your children out of an education\" and \"Gratitude\u2014months with no pay\u2014now fired\".<ref name=\"WP 15 July 1933\">{{cite news|title=Unpaid Chicago Teachers Protest Retirement Plan|newspaper=Washington Post|date=15 July 1933|agency=AP|page=2|id={{ProQuest|150369363}}}}</ref>  Teachers marched on [[Grant Park (Chicago)|Grant Park]] and tore down a [[Century of Progress]] banner anticipating the coming [[World's Fair]]. Teachers and parents also sought legal injunctions against the Board of Education. The School Board nevertheless fired hundreds of teachers in September, leaving remaining teachers to teach more classes\u2014of larger size. In October, the city received a $35 million federal loan, which it used to issue back pay.<ref name=\"Burbank 1971\" />\n\n===Consolidation and charter===\nChicago teachers had formed several different unions, some of which were still segregated by gender.<ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), p. 23.</ref> The unrest in the early 1930s served to unite these groups, which previously had difficulty cooperating.<ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), p. 28.</ref> Chicago teachers played an active role in the AFT and retained their status as Local 1. In 1937, Local 1 battled New York's Local 5 over whether the AFT would remain in the [[American Federation of Labor]] (AFL) or join the newer and more inclusive [[Congress of Industrial Organizations]] (CIO).<ref name=\"NYT - 22 Aug 1937\">{{cite news|title=Nation's Teachers to Debate C.I.O. Tie|newspaper=New York Times|date=22 August 1937|page=N5|quote=As preliminary lines formed for the battle over union affiliation, it appeared certain that delegates of New York City Local 5, representing 6,000 members, would take the leadership in the drive for C.I.O. affiliation. It became equally evident that the Chicago delegation, representing 7,000 members, would fight to the last ditch to remain in the A.F.L.|id={{ProQuest|102136795}}}}</ref> (New York's Local 5 was at that time the Teachers' Union, which was soon expelled from the AFT after accusations of communism, and replaced by the more moderate [[United Federation of Teachers]].) Soon after the convention (which decided to stay in the AFL), the Chicago Teachers Union was officially chartered by the AFT as an amalgamation of Chicago's multiple teacher unions in Chicago.<ref name=\"CSM - 30 Oct 1937\">{{cite news|title=Chicago Teachers Form Union To Loosen Grip of Politics|newspaper=Christian Science Monitor|date=30 October 1937|page=4|id={{ProQuest|515388274}}}}</ref><ref name=\"ChiTrib - 13 Oct 1937\">{{cite news|title=A. F. of L. Affiliate Will Charter Teachers' Union|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=13 October 1937|id={{ProQuest|181891987}}}}</ref> At this point about 3,500 teachers were members of the new Local.<ref name=\"CDT - 2 June 1938\" /> By September, it was the largest teachers union in the U.S., with over 8500 members.<ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), p. 44.</ref> The CTF, still under Haley's leadership, remained separate for some years, based on concerns that the CTU would disproportionately represent the interests of males and high school teachers.<ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), p. 45.</ref>\n\n== Before collective bargaining: 1937\u20131967  ==\nWhen the CTU formed, teachers had become disillusioned about their status as a special class of workers. Some elementary school teachers were paid less than janitors, and more teachers came to agree that they experienced discrimination because they were female. (Meanwhile, male teachers felt shortchanged and emasculated.) Teachers also resented the constantly increasing bureaucratic control over their classrooms.<ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), pp. 18\u201321.</ref>\n\n=== Goals  ===\nThe CTU sought [[collective bargaining]] rights early on, but Superintendent William Johnson refused to grant them.<ref name=\"CDT - 2 June 1938\">{{cite news|title=Teachers' Union Rebuffed in Plea For Recognition|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=2 June 1938|page=8|id={{ProQuest|182001977}}}}</ref> The union also targeted evaluations (for teachers who wanted to become principals) that it said were administered in a corrupt fashion.<ref name=\"CDT - 20 May 1938\">{{cite news|title=Air Both Sides in Controversy Over Schools: The School Question|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=20 May 1938|pages=1, 4|id={{ProQuest|181954866}}}}</ref> By 1939, the CTU had more than doubled in size, to 8,500 members, and organized its members for actions such as mass letter-writing.<ref name=\"CDT - 7 June 1939\">{{cite news|title=Teachers Turn on Heat to Pass Pay Boost Bill: Union Starts Letter Wave Toward Springfield|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=7 June 1939|page=6|id={{ProQuest|175298294}}}}</ref>\n\nIn 1948, amid small-scale sickouts and walkouts, the CTU authorized a strike when teachers experienced still more 'payless paydays' due to city neglect.<ref name=\"NYT - 24 Jan 1948\">{{cite news|title=Chicago Teachers Payless 5 Weeks: Threaten to Strike as City Refuses to Use $9,500,000 Reserve For Salaries|newspaper=New York Times|date=24 January 1948|page=13|id={{ProQuest|108122113}}}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT - 25 Jan 1948\">{{cite news|title=Chicago Teachers VOte Strike Call: Walkout Tuesday Sanctioned By Union Unless Pay is Freed and School Budget Passed|url=http://search.proquest.com/docview/108112634/|accessdate=11 September 2012|newspaper=New York Times|date=25 January 1948|page=20}}</ref> The strike was averted hours before it was scheduled to begin, when the school board approved a new budget and announced that the checks due to the teachers had been mailed with all possible haste.<ref name=\"Thompson - 27 Jan 1948\">{{cite news|last=Thompson|first=John|title=Pay Teachers; Strike Off: Aldermen O.K. Record '48 Budget \u2013 Board to Consider Cut in Levy \u2013 Call School Strike Off; Pay Mailed Record Budget is O.K.'d By City|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=27 January 1948|pages=1, 12|id={{ProQuest|177541248}}}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to perennial requests for salary increases, the CTU began demanding more direct changes to Chicago's public schools. It asked the [[Chicago Police Department]] to station an officer in each of Chicago's 43 high schools; CPD refused.<ref name=\"CDT - 22 Sept 1954\">{{cite news|title=Police Refuse to Station Men in High Schools: Reject Request From Teachers' Union|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=22 September 1954|page=1|id={{ProQuest|178798437}}}}</ref> The CTU continued to pursue the school violence issue, insisting that teachers were being attacked by dangerous youths.<ref name=\"CDT - 1 March 1955\">{{cite news|title=Union to Seek More Police in High Schools: Terrorist Attacks Told by Fewkes|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=1 March 1955|page=7|id={{ProQuest|179400663}}}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Teachers 'Hush Up' Violence in Chicago|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=VRQfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EJsEAAAAIBAJ&dq=chicago%20teachers%20union&pg=7252%2C586487|accessdate=11 September 2012|newspaper=The Tuscaloosa News|date=5 February 1965|agency=AP|page=9}}</ref>  During this period the union also sought shorter hours for students and teachers.<ref name=\"CDT - 2 Feb 1954\">{{cite news|title=Teacher Union Fights Longer Day For Pupils: OK's Increase in Hours For Instructors|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=19 February 1954|page=B4|id={{ProQuest|178672818}}}}</ref><ref name=\"CDT - 3 Dec 1954\">{{cite news|title=Teachers Sign Petitions for Shorter Hours|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=3 December 1954|page=A8|id={{ProQuest|178832872}}}}</ref> It also called attention to a mounting teacher shortage, citing over a hundred classrooms without regular or substitute teachers.<ref name=\"CDT - 15 March 1955\">{{cite news|title=Cite Teacher Need as Grade Classes Grow: Shortage is Called More Serious|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=15 March 1955|page=1|id={{ProQuest|178839067}}}}</ref>\n\nDuring this period, Fewkes and the CTU consistently opposed [[merit pay]] policies, proposals which would vary teachers salaries based on evaluations.<ref name=\"CT Fewkes obit\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Teacher Union Head Opposes Merit Ratings|url=http://search.proquest.com/docview/179535769/|accessdate=12 September 2012|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=23 August 1955|page=A10}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Gowran|first=Clay|title=Pay Teachers on Merit Basis? It's Ticklish Topic: Even Some Who Would Benefit Fear System|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=6 March 1959|page=15|id={{ProQuest|182281261}}}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Fewkes Rips Merit Pay Idea For Teachers: Union Chief Says It Won't Work|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=18 March 1962|page=36|id={{ProQuest|183122887}}}}</ref>\n\n=== John Fewkes and anticommunism===\nThe CTU's first president was John Fewkes.<ref name=\"CT Fewkes obit\">{{cite news|title=John M. Fewkes, 91, Teachers Union Founder|last=Heise|first=Kenan|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1992-07-25/news/9203060964_1_chicago-teachers-union-strike-merit-system|accessdate=11 September 2012|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=25 July 1992}}</ref> Fewkes had been the most prominent leader of \"Voluntary Emergency Committee\" (VEC), a male-dominated group that formed in 1933 and gained prominence by advocating and coordinating militant action. The VEC had been aggressive but not radical, and explicitly sought to exclude communists.<ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), pp. 38\u201339.</ref>\n\nThe union, urged on by Fewkes,<ref name=\"CT Fewkes obit\" /> participated in the AFL's anti-communist purges, and in 1941 voted 5,258 to 892 to expel the New York City [[Teachers Union]], the New York College Teachers Union and Philadelphia Teachers Union from the AFT.<ref name=\"CDT - 21 May 1941\">{{cite news|title=Chicago Union Teachers Back Red Expulsions|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=21 May 1941|id={{ProQuest|176484275}}}}</ref> The three expelled Locals were large, representing about one quarter of the AFT's members, but the CTU was larger, and its votes were decisive in accomplishing the expulsion.<ref name=\"NYT - 21 May 1941\">{{cite news|title=Chicago Teachers Vote For Ouster: 5,258 to 892 For Dropping 3 Locals That Union COuncil Accused of Communism|newspaper=New York Times|date=21 May 1941|page=25|id={{ProQuest|106074842}}}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT - 7 June 1941\">{{cite news|title=Federation Votes 3 Teacher Unions Out As Red-Ruled|newspaper=New York Times|date=7 June 1941|pages=1, 32|id={{ProQuest|106067900}}}}</ref>\n\nFewkes remained CTU President for most of this period. He left the CTU in 1943 to serve as AFT president. In 1944, he took a position with the federal [[War Production Board]].<ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), p. 82.</ref> By 1947, he had returned to the CTU for a second term as its president.<ref name=\"CT Fewkes obit\" />  In 1950, the CTU governing board approved a constitutional amendment to remove limitations on presidential terms; John Fewkes was thereby allowed to run again, and remained CTU president until 1966.<ref name=\"CT Fewkes obit\" /><ref name=\"CDT - 22 Nov 1950\">{{cite news|title=Teachers' Union Heads Kill Time Limit on Chief|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=22 November 1950|id={{ProQuest|178046295}}}}</ref>\n\n===Demographics and civil rights===\nMost of Chicago's public school teachers were white single women. Public school teacher was also the most common occupation for black women in Chicago, who were treated by CPS as second-class job candidates: qualified black high school teachers worked in elementary schools or as substitutes; some could not get jobs at all.<ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), p. 15. \"Black teachers also enjoyed fewer career prospects than did white teachers. With only two black high schools in the city, DuSable and Wendell Phillips, the vast majority of black teachers worked in elementary schools even if they were trained for better-paying high school work. Out of 321 black teachers who worked in the Chicago public school system in 1934, 285 of them taught in the elementary schools. With fewer opportunities for African American high school teachers, many qualified teachers from the South had to work as substitutes or take other jobs in Chicago until teaching positions opened up for them.\"</ref> Teachers came from a shifting mix of white-collar and blue-collar families.<ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), pp. 16.</ref>\n\n===Campaign for collective bargaining===\nThe CTU intensified its campaign for [[collective bargaining]] rights in the 1960s, staging huge demonstrations at the Chicago Board of Education.<ref name=\"CDD - 11 Jan 1961\">{{cite news|title=4,000 Teachers Stage Protest March: Pay Hike, Bargaining Top Issues|newspaper=Chicago Daily Defender|date=11 January 1961|pages=1, 2|id={{ProQuest|493808486}}}}</ref> Pressure increased after the New York recognized collective bargaining rights for the UFT in 1961,<ref name=\"Tavel - 23 Aug 1963\">{{cite news|last=Tavel|first=Emile|title=Teachers Demand Bargaining Right: Strike Threat Dangles|url=http://search.proquest.com/docview/510553518/|accessdate=12 September 2012|newspaper=Christian Science Monitor|date=23 August 1963|page=3}}</ref> and the CTU threatened an illegal strike in 1963\u20131964 if the School Board would not grant it the same status.<ref>{{cite news|title=Teacher Union Asks Board to Change Stand: Hint at Strike Vote Next Month|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=7 November 1963|page=C1|id={{ProQuest|89097422}}}}</ref> The city averted a strike by agreeing to negotiate,<ref>{{cite news|title=Strike Vote is Withheld by Teachers: Board Agrees to Bargain \u2013 School Union Delays Balloting on Strike|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=27 February 1964|page=1|id={{ProQuest|179375855}}}}</ref> and, after long delays (including litigation from a rival union, the Chicago Education Association),<ref>{{cite news|last=Yuenger|first=James|title=Delay Ruling on Vote for School Union: Board Asks Time to File Reply|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=9 October 1965|page=N3|id={{ProQuest|170023590}}}}</ref> the CTU became the official bargaining agent of Chicago teachers in April 1966.<ref>{{cite news|last=Banas|first=Casey|title=Union Elected by Teachers as Their Bargaining Agent|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=4 June 1966|page=3|id={{ProQuest|178997581}}}}</ref>\n\n== Internal politics and organization ==\n\n=== Caucus of Rank and File Educators ===\nIn 2010, the Caucus of Rank and File Educators (CORE), led by President Karen Lewis gained control over the CTU by winning 60% of the vote in a run-off election.<ref name=\"Canon - 12 June 2010\">{{cite news|last=Canon|first=Ramsin|title=Caucus of Rank-and-File Educators (CORE) Takes Over Chicago Teachers Union|url=http://gapersblock.com/mechanics/2010/06/12/caucus-of-rank-and-file-educators-core-takes-over-chicago-teachers-union/|accessdate=11 September 2012|newspaper=Gapers Block|date=12 June 2010}}</ref>  CORE ran an aggressive grassroots organizing campaign, and took a strong stance against school privatization.<ref name=\"Canon 2010\">{{cite news|last=Canon|first=Ramsin|title=The Education Revolt: The Chicago Model's Fallout|url=http://gapersblock.com/mechanics/2010/05/03/the-education-revolt-the-chicago-models-fallout/|accessdate=11 September 2012|newspaper=Gapers Block|date=3 May 2010}}</ref> CORE accused the incumbent United Progressive Caucus (UPC) of capitulating to corporate interests, silencing dissent within the union, and collaborating with the city to prevent union outreach at schools.<ref name=\"Abowd - 7 June 2010\">{{cite news|last=Abowd|first=Paul|title=Chicago's Rank and File Educators Well-Positioned Against \"Play it Safe\" Incumbents|url=http://labornotes.org/2010/06/chicagos-rank-and-file-educators-well-positioned-against-play-it-safe-incumbents|accessdate=11 September 2012|newspaper=Labor Notes|date=7 June 2010}}</ref>\n\nCORE quickly took action to distinguish itself from UPC, reaffirm its grassroots support, and launch a campaign to defend public education. The new leadership cut pay for union officers and used the savings to expand outreach.<ref name=\"Sustar - 31 Aug 2012\">{{cite news|last=Sustar|first=Lee|title=Chicago Teachers Draw a Line|url=http://www.indypendent.org/2012/08/31/chicago-teachers-draw-line|accessdate=11 September 2012|newspaper=The Indypendent|date=31 August 2012}}</ref> Former CTU member John A. Ostenburg criticized Lewis and CORE in 2011 for inexperience and political recklessness, arguing that they will not successfully be able to combat Mayor [[Rahm Emanuel]]'s entrenched power.<ref name=\"Ostenburg - 19 Nov 2011\">{{cite news|title=Leading 'Ugly' Not The Answer For Organized Labor, Chicago Teachers Union, Karen Lewis|url=http://www.enewspf.com/component/ijoomla_archive/archive/author/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=28974:leading-quglyq-not-the-answer-for-organized-labor-chicago-teachers-union&catid=88888891&Itemid=88890121|accessdate=11 September 2012|newspaper=ENews Park Forest|date=19 November 2011}}</ref> CORE represented a major bloc of dissent at the 2012 AFT convention, and held signs in protest of [[Race to the Top]] during a speech from Vice President [[Joseph Biden|Joe Biden]].<ref name=\"Scott - 30 July 2012\">{{cite news|last=Scott|first=Norm|title=@AFT - Chicago Teachers Protest RTTT During/After Biden Speech|url=http://ednotesonline.blogspot.com/2012/07/aft-chicago-teachers-protest-rttt.html|accessdate=11 September 2012|newspaper=Ed Notes Online|date=30 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n===2018 merger with Charter Union Local===\nIn spring of 2018, the Chicago Teachers Union and Chicago Association of Charter Teachers and Staff Local 4343 voted to merge, with the charter educators forming a new division within the CTU. On December 4, 2018, CTU members at the Acero charter school network initiated the first strike at a unionized charter school in US history. The strike ended December 9, 2018, in a major victory with the strikers who won sanctuary school protections for their students, enforceable reductions in class size and parity with the existing pay scale at district-run schools.\n\n==Collective bargaining and strikes==\n\n=== Strikes 1968\u20131987 ===\n\nChicago teachers went on strike multiple times in the 1970s and 1980s:<ref name=\"Schmidt - 29 Aug 2012\">{{cite news|last=Schmidt|first=George N.|title=CORE hosts final 'Successful Chicago Strikes' forum following CTU notice of intent to strike.... Veteran teachers describe how CTU overcame racism and thwarted the CPS attempts to 'play the race card'|url=http://www.substancenews.net/articles.php?page=3543|accessdate=12 September 2012|newspaper=Substance News|date=29 August 2012}}</ref> \n* 1968: \"Concerned FTBs\" (long-term substitutes) and others engage in [[Wildcat strike action|wildcat strikes]] against school segregation and racism\u2014particularly systemic unfairness in the certification, hiring, and promotion of black teachers.<ref name=\"Schmidt - 5 March 2012\">{{cite news|last=Schmidt|first=George N.|title=Strikewatch: The first Chicago strikes were 'illegal...' How Chicago teachers make a strike.... The first thing it's about is no longer working on the boss's terms for the boss's offer and taking the boss's insults|url=http://www.substancenews.net/articles.php?page=3124|accessdate=12 September 2012|newspaper=Substance News|date=5 March 2012}}</ref> \n* 1969: Two-day strike results in salary increases, teacher aides, and class size maximum.\n* 1971: Four-day strike results in salary increases and full health benefits.\n* 1973: Two strikes, of 12 and 11 days, yield improved salary, benefits, preparation time, supplies, and class sizes.\n* 1979-1980: Multiple strikes over a payless payday during holiday break in 1979, results in salary increase and improved sick leave and maternity/paternity leave.\n* 1984: Four-day strike results in medical care increase and PAC checkoff.\n* 1985: Two-day strike for salary and sick leave.\n* 1987: Record-breaking 19-day strike under CTU President [[Jacqueline B. Vaughn]] wins raises and improvements to health care.\n\n===2012 strike===\n[[File:2012ChicagoTeachersUnionStrikeMarch.jpg|thumb|left|Striking members of the Chicago Teachers Union marching through the [[Chicago Loop]] on September 11, 2012.|290x290px]]{{Commons category|Chicago teachers strike of 2012|2012 Chicago teachers strike}}Under the leadership of CORE, the CTU pushed hard in negotiations with the city. Early on, the CTU made the decision to decline an offer of pay increases combined with layoffs.<ref name=\"Sustar - 31 Aug 2012\" /> When the city would not agree to the CTU's core demands, including an expansion of programs like art and music at the city's most underfunded high schools, CTU members voted overwhelmingly (90% of teachers and 98% of those who cast ballots) to authorize a strike.<ref name=\"Moran - 28 Aug 2012\">{{cite news|last=Moran|first=Theresa|title=Chicago Teachers Say They'll Strike for the Kids|url=http://labornotes.org/2012/08/chicago-teachers-say-theyll-strike-kids|accessdate=11 September 2012|newspaper=Labor Notes|date=28 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn September 10, 2012, the Chicago Teachers Union began a strike<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timeoutchicagokids.com/things-to-do/hipsqueak-blog/180381/chicago-teachers-union-rally-photos|title=Chicago teachers union rally|publisher=Time Out Chicago Kids|accessdate=September 10, 2012}}</ref> after CTU President Lewis declared that negotiations with the city were not succeeding.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/thetwo-way/2012/09/09/160855857/no-deal-chicago-teachers-to-strike-after-contract-talks-fail|title=No Deal: Chicago Teachers To Strike After Contract Talks Fail|publisher=NPR|date=September 9, 2012|accessdate=September 10, 2012}}</ref> This strike was the CTU's first since  1987, and the first strike ever for many of the teachers involved.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/nation/story/2012/09/9/chicago-teachers-school-board-halt-strike-talks/57720772/1|title=Chicago teachers strike for first time in 25 years|publisher=USA Today|accessdate=September 10, 2012|date=11 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Solidarity - 10 Sept 2012\">{{cite news|title=Windy City Fights Back: Live blogging the Chicago Teachers Strike|url=http://solidarity-us.org/site/node/3695|accessdate=11 September 2012|newspaper=Solidarity|date=10 September 2012|author=Editorial Committee}}</ref>  Regulations required them to make contract negotiations an issue in the strike, and the teachers indeed sought better pay, better benefits, and protections for teachers who lose their jobs due to school closures.<ref name=\"Moran - 28 Aug 2012\" />\n\nThe striking teachers also wanted to call attention to a number of education issues, particularly what they defined as a broad attack on public schooling by corporate privatizers.<ref name=\"DN school model - 10 Sept 2012\">{{cite news|title=Striking Teachers, Parents Join Forces to Oppose \"Corporate\" Education Model in Chicago|url=http://www.democracynow.org/2012/9/10/striking_teachers_parents_join_forces_to|accessdate=10 September 2012|newspaper=Democracy Now!|date=10 September 2012}}</ref>  In particular they demand a decrease in high-stakes testing for students, and an increase in music, art, and gym programs available at public schools.<ref name=\"DN - reforms - 10 Sept 2012\">{{cite news|title=Chicago Public Teachers Stage Historic Strike in Clash with Mayor Rahm Emanuel on Education Reforms|url=http://www.democracynow.org/2012/9/10/chicago_public_teachers_stage_historic_strike|accessdate=10 September 2012|newspaper=Democracy Now|date=10 September 2012}}</ref> They also called for smaller class sizes and paid preparation time.<ref name=\"Moran - 28 Aug 2012\" />\n\nOn September 11, 2012, the Service Employees International Union Local 1 informed companies that some of their members might go on strike with the teachers.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/politics/clout/chi-some-chicago-public-schools-custodians-may-strike-20120911,0,595858.story|title=Some Chicago Public Schools custodians may strike|publisher=The Chicago Tribune|accessdate=September 11, 2012|first=John|last=Byrne}}</ref>\n\nOn September 14, 2012, the teachers reached a tentative agreement with the city, which included preferences for teachers who have been laid off due to a school closing to be hired in another school, and student test scores having less of a role in teacher evaluations than the city had originally planned.<ref name=\"striketentativeend\">{{cite news|title=Chicago teachers reach tentative agreement to end strike|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/decision2012/chicago-teachers-reach-tentative-agreement-to-end-strike/2012/09/14/b0d01452-feae-11e1-8adc-499661afe377_story.html?hpid=z4 | work=The Washington Post | first=Lyndsey|last=Layton|date=15 September 2012}}</ref> This tentative agreement did not hold, however, and the strike continued, at which point Mayor Emanuel announced his intention to seek a legal injunction, forcing teachers back to work.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kelleher |first=James B. |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/09/17/us-usa-chicago-schools-idUSBRE88E0IV20120917 |title=Emanuel's court bid to end strike stalls, teachers call it vindictive |publisher=Reuters |date= 17 September 2012|accessdate=2012-10-05}}</ref> On September 17, 2012, Mayor Emanuel's efforts to end the strike stalled as the walkout went into the second week.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://usnews.nbcnews.com/_news/2012/09/17/13915011-judge-declines-to-expedite-hearing-in-chicago-teacher-strike|title=Judge declines to expedite hearing in Chicago teacher strike|publisher=NBC News|date=September 17, 2012|accessdate= September 18, 2012}}</ref> Delegates from the CTU voted to end the strike on September 18, 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.blogs.cnn.com/2012/09/18/chicago-teachers-vote-to-end-strike/|title=Chicago teachers vote to suspend strike|publisher=CNN|accessdate=18 September 2012|date=18 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/nation/story/2012/09/18/chicago-teachers-are-suspending-seven-day-strike/57799352/1|title=Chicago teachers suspend seven-day strike|publisher=USA Today|accessdate=September 18, 2012|date=18 September 2012}}</ref> Students began their return to the schools on Wednesday, September 19, 2012. The CTU was still required to ratify the contract with the Union's 29,000 teachers.<ref>{{cite news|title=School Days Resume in Chicago as the Lessons From a Strike Are Assessed|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/09/20/us/chicago-strike-ends-and-schoolchildren-return-to-class.html?ref=us|work=The New York Times|date=September 19, 2012|accessdate=September 19, 2012|first1=Monica|last1=Davey|first2=Steven|last2=Greenhouse}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the end of the strike, leaders of the Union held [[town hall meetings]] in major U.S. cities to underscore the belief that community collaboration is key in creating beneficial changes in education, as opposed to top-down imposition by governors or mayors. The Union planned to hold town hall meetings in Chicago, Cleveland, Minneapolis, New Orleans, New York, Philadelphia, Pittsburgh, San Francisco, St. Paul, and Tampa.<ref>{{cite news|title=After Chicago success, teachers unions spread their message|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/education/after-chicago-success-union-leaders-spread-their-message/2012/09/21/cad16290-0424-11e2-9b24-ff730c7f6312_story.html|work=Washington Post|accessdate=September 22, 2012|first=Lyndsey|last=Layton|date=22 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n===2015\u20132016 contract dispute===\nFollowing the expiration of the contract in June 2015, CPS teachers continued to work without a contract for a year while the union and district negotiated. In September 2016, union members voted overwhelmingly to strike if an agreement could not be reached, setting a deadline of October 11. Minutes before midnight on October 10, the district and union reached a tentative agreement, avoiding a strike.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/breaking/ct-chicago-teachers-contract-talks-20161010-story.html |title = Chicago Teachers Union, school board reach tentative contract agreement}}</ref>\n\n=== 2019 strike ===\n{{main|2019 Chicago Public Schools Strike}}\n\n[[File:Chicago Teachers Union Rally 10-14-19 3748 (48906578637).jpg|thumb|364x364px|Chicago teachers marching during a demonstration on October 14, 2019.]]After the expiration of the CPS contract with CTU in June 2019, a contract dispute emerged.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.wttw.com/2019/08/09/fact-finder-s-report-sheds-light-ctu-contract-negotiations-cps|title=Fact-Finder's Report Sheds Light on CTU Contract Negotiations With City|last=|first=|date=2019-08-12|website=WTTW News|language=en|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref> Vermont Senator [[Bernie Sanders]] spoke at a rally hosted by CTU and SEIU Local 73 in preparation of the strike on September 24. On September 27, 2019, CTU members voted to authorize a potential strike starting on October 17 if a contract deal is not reached.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/breaking/ct-chicago-teachers-union-strike-vote-last-day-20190926-ilgd5djc4zcjjp5pj3gusbbxnu-story.html|title=Chicago Teachers Union votes to authorize strike; walkout could begin Oct. 7|last=Pratt|first=Hannah Leone, Gregory|date=2019-09-27|website=chicagotribune.com|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref> The union's top priorities in contract negotiations are reducing classroom size and increasing the number of support staff (such as nurses and social workers).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nbcchicago.com/news/local/Key-Issues-in-Chicago-Teachers-Union-Strike-562933871.html|title=Key Issues in Potential Chicago Teachers Union Strike|last=|first=|date=2019-10-12|website=NBC Chicago|language=en|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref> On October 16, 2019 CPS cancelled classes for October 17, 2019 in anticipation of the CTU strike.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/10/16/770660821/chicago-cancels-public-school-classes-as-teachers-prepare-to-strike|title=Chicago Cancels Public School Classes As Teachers' Strike Looms|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref> CTU delegates officially voted to go on strike hours afterwards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wgntv.com/2019/10/16/last-day-of-negotiations-before-potential-cps-teacher-strike/|title=CTU rejects latest contract proposal, teachers to strike Thursday|date=2019-10-16|website=WGN-TV|language=en|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref> Mayor [[Lori Lightfoot]] announced that CPS would not add any makeup days for any school days lost during the strike, stating that \"There\u2019s no plan to make up any days...We want to make sure we get a deal done.\" At the time, Illinois state law required that all school districts in Illinois include at least 176 days in the school year. Lightfoot's decision broke this mandate, as the 2019\u20132020 school year was ''exactly'' 176 days long. Additionally, it was noted that teachers could lose pay if the strike days were not added back to the district calendar.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/2019/10/3/20897902/cps-teachers-strike-lightfoot-lori-chicago-public-ctu|title=Kids rejoice: CPS won't add makeup days if teachers strike, Lightfoot says|last=Issa|first=Nader|date=2019-10-03|website=Chicago Sun-Times|language=en|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\nOn Thursday, October 17, 2019, teachers took to picket lines early in the morning, and the CTU stated that it planned to resume negotiations with the city at [[Malcolm X College]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/breaking/ct-cps-strike-chicago-teachers-union-updates-20191016-mo2oqq4fxbezxct62kijuujzeq-story.html|title=Chicago Teachers Union strike updates: CPS teachers join picket lines across the city as negotiations are set to resume|last=staff|first=Chicago Tribune|website=chicagotribune.com|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref> Later that afternoon, CPS announced that classes had been cancelled for the following day, as even though negotiations seemed to be progressing, there was no foreseeable agreement in the near feature. On Friday, October 18, 2019, teachers continued on the second day of the strike, meaning that students had attended school two days (Tuesday and Wednesday) out of the five days from October 14\u201318 (CPS students did not go to school on Monday due to the observance of [[Columbus Day]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abc7chicago.com/5627963/|title=Chicago Teachers Strike: Thousands of teachers to return to picket lines for 2nd day Friday, CPS classes remain canceled|date=2019-10-18|website=ABC7 Chicago|language=en|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref> That weekend, CTU and CPS continued negotiating. While both sides noted progress over Saturday, Lightfoot noted that she would be \"...very surprised if classes [would] open on Monday.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/news/2019/10/20/20923461/chicago-teachers-union-strike-day-4-negotiations-continue-monday-classes-uncertain|title=CTU strike, Day 4: Talks continue, but Monday classes still uncertain|last=Wittich|first=Jake|date=2019-10-20|website=Chicago Sun-Times|language=en|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref> The following day, Sunday, October 20, 2019, CPS canceled school for Monday the 21st. Even though tentative agreements had been made on eight points, CPS canceled school for Monday as CTU had not voted to end the strike yet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wgntv.com/2019/10/20/classes-not-anticipated-to-resume-monday-as-teachers-contract-talks-continue/|title=CPS cancels classes Monday as teachers' strike, contract talks continue|date=2019-10-20|website=WGN-TV|language=en|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\nOn Monday, October 21, 2019, CTU members entered the third school day and second calendar week of the strike. Negotiations between CPS and CTU continued, and Lightfoot sent the union a letter asking them to end the strike while negotiations continued. CTU president Jesse Sharkey noted that \"...the letter [from Lightfoot] I received today dashed my hope for a quick settlement.\" That afternoon, Mayor Lightfoot canceled CPS classes for Tuesday, stating that \"...CTU has not scheduled a House of Delegates vote, which would be necessary to end their strike...As a result, it will not be possible to hold classes tomorrow.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wgntv.com/2019/10/21/3rd-day-without-classes-for-cps-students-as-teachers-strike-continues/|title='We are likely not going to see a quick settlement': Tuesday classes canceled as CPS strike drags on|date=2019-10-21|website=WGN-TV|language=en|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref> The next day, Tuesday, October 22, 2019, negotiations continued, and 2020 democratic presidential primary candidate [[Elizabeth Warren]] joined the striking teachers. Later, Mayor Lightfoot canceled CPS classes for Wednesday, October 23, stating once again that \"...CTU has not scheduled a House of Delegates vote, which would be necessary to end their strike...As a result, it will not be possible to hold classes tomorrow.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wgntv.com/2019/10/22/elizabeth-warren-to-rally-with-ctu-as-teachers-strike-enters-6th-day/|title=Wednesday classes canceled as CTU members rally in downtown Chicago|date=2019-10-22|website=WGN-TV|language=en|access-date=2019-10-23}}</ref> It was noted that on Tuesday, negotiations appeared to be \"at an impasse\", and the majority of CTU's 40-person bargaining team was not expected to return to the negotiating table. CTU President Sharkey expressed that the proposed contract did \"...not have adequate enforcement mechanisms on staffing.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nbcchicago.com/blogs/ward-room/CPS-Cancels-School-Wednesday-as-Teachers-Strike-Continues-563652011.html|title=CPS Cancels Classes Wednesday as Teachers Strike Continues|website=NBC Chicago|language=en|access-date=2019-10-23}}</ref> After negotiations had ended Tuesday evening, several issues remained unresolved, such as class-size caps, the duration of the contract, salaries, and health benefits. At this point, teachers planned to keep the strike going until at least Thursday the 24th, or longer if necessary.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abc7chicago.com/5640234/|title=Chicago Strike: CPS teachers march in Loop during Mayor Lori Lightfoot's address, Chicago Public Schools classes canceled|date=2019-10-23|website=ABC7 Chicago|language=en|access-date=2019-10-23}}</ref> On Wednesday, October 23, 2019, negotiations continued at Malcolm X College. Teachers only picketed in front of schools until 8:00&nbsp;a.m. local time. Then, they proceeded to rally in the downtown Loop and converge in front of the [[Chicago City Hall|city hall]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wgntv.com/2019/10/22/elizabeth-warren-to-rally-with-ctu-as-teachers-strike-enters-6th-day/|title=Wednesday classes canceled as CTU members rally in downtown Chicago|date=2019-10-22|website=WGN-TV|language=en|access-date=2019-10-24}}</ref> Lightfoot presented her 2020 city budget plan Wednesday evening, at the end of the fifth school day of the strike. Emails and phone calls were disseminated to students and parents, informing them that classes were canceled for Thursday, October 24, as both the CTU and CPS still did not expect an agreement any time soon.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chicago.cbslocal.com/2019/10/23/cps-ctu-teachers-strike-sixth-day-classes-cancelled/|title=CPS Cancels Class For Thursday, Following Massive Rally By Striking Teachers Downtown|date=2019-10-23|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-24}}</ref> The following day, on Thursday the 24th, teachers returned to the picket lines at 7:00&nbsp;a.m., and the president of the [[Association of Flight Attendants|Flight Attendant's Union]], [[Sara Nelson (union leader)|Sara Nelson]], was expected to join the striking teachers to show support. CTU also scheduled [[civil disobedience]] training for its members at the CTU headquarters at 3:00&nbsp;p.m., suggesting a prolonged strike.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abc7chicago.com/5643109/|title=Chicago Strike: Negotiations continue for 8th day as CTU plans civil disobedience training. Chance the rapper wore a Chicago Teachers Union shirt on SNL in support.|date=2019-10-24|website=ABC7 Chicago|language=en|access-date=2019-10-24}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* Lyons, John F. ''Teachers and Reform: Chicago Public Education 1929\u20131970.'' Urbana & Chicago: University of Illinois Press, 2008. {{ISBN|978-0-252-03272-1}}.\n\n==External links==\n* CTU {{Official website|http://www.ctulocal1.org}}\n\n===Images===\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140804172721/https://reuther.wayne.edu/node/709 Photo of 1933 teacher uprising] hosted by the Walter Reuther Library at Wayne State\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150202055809/http://reuther.wayne.edu/node/7306 Photo of President Fewkes leading a 1965 CTU meeting] hosted by the Walter Reuther Library at Wayne State\n* [https://www.flickr.com/photos/32225081@N07/with/7072480979/#photo_7072480979 Pictures of the 1980s teacher strikes] posted to Flickr by \"union person\"\n\n[[Category:American Federation of Teachers]]\n[[Category:Chicago Public Schools]]\n[[Category:Education trade unions]]\n[[Category:Organizations based in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Trade unions established in 1937]]\n[[Category:Trade unions in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Chicago Teachers Union| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Union\n|name= Chicago Teachers Union \n|country= [[United States]]\n|affiliation=[[American Federation of Teachers|AFT]], [[Illinois Federation of Teachers|IFT]], [[Chicago Federation of Labor|CFL]], [[AFL-CIO]], [[Illinois AFL-CIO|IL AFL-CIO]]\n|members= 25,000  (2018)\n|full_name= \n|native_name=\n|founded= 1937\n|current= \n|head=[[Jesse Sharkey]] (president)\n|dissolved_date=\n|dissolved_state= \n|merged_into= \n|office= 1901 West Carroll Avenue<br/>[[Chicago, Illinois]] 60612\n|people=[[Margaret Haley]]<br/>[[Jacqueline B. Vaughn]]<br/>[[Karen Lewis (labor leader)|Karen Lewis]]\n|website=[http://www.ctulocal1.org/ ctulocal1.org]\n|footnotes= \n}}\n\nThe '''Chicago Teachers Union''' ('''CTU''') is a [[Trade union|labor union]] representing teachers, paraprofessionals, and clinicians in the [[Chicago Public Schools|Chicago public school system]]. The union has consistently fought for improved pay, benefits, and job security for its members, and it has resisted efforts to vary teacher pay based on performance evaluations. It has also pushed for improvements in the Chicago schools, and since its inception argued that its activities benefited students as well as teachers.<ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), pp. 3\u20134. \"In addition to the issue of unionization, scholars have debated whether teachers joined unions to pursue monetary gains or to reform the public schools. Since teachers founded the AFT in 1916, the organization has portrayed itself as a union fighting for better salaries and benefits for its members and improvements in the public schools. Indeed, teachers' unions across the land asserted that they wanted improved pay and conditions for teachers in order to provide quality education for the students.\"</ref>\n\nThe CTU united several teachers' organizations in Chicago in the wake of a teachers' revolt against banks during the [[Great Depression]]. It was chartered in 1937 as Local 1 of the [[American Federation of Teachers]] (AFT), in which it played a founding role. It was the largest and most active AFT Local until the 1960s.<ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), pp. 1\u20132. \"In the early years of the twentieth century, the center of teacher unionism was found in Chicago. [...]  The CTU attracted a majority of Chicago teachers and remained the largest and most influential AFT local until the 1960s.\"</ref> The CTU won [[collective bargaining]] rights in 1966 and conducted several [[Strike action|strikes]] during the 1970s and 1980s. In September 2012, the union began its first strike in 25 years.\n\nThe CTU is also affiliated with the Illinois Federation of Teachers, the [[Chicago Federation of Labor]], and the [[AFL-CIO]]. It has more than 25,000 members. Current officers come from the Caucus of Rank-and-File Educators, elected in 2010 to replace the longstanding United Progressive Caucus. From that point until her 2018 retirement, [[Karen Lewis (labor leader)|Karen Lewis]] was president. Through a successors election the new officer slate became: President [[Jesse Sharkey]], Vice President Stacy Davis Gates, Recording Secretary Michael Brunson and Financial Secretary Maria Moreno.<ref name=\"CTU Contacts\">{{cite web|title=For Members \u00bb CTU Contacts|url=http://www.ctunet.com/for-members/contacts|publisher=Chicago Teachers Union|accessdate=20 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"CT - Key Players\">{{cite news|title=Key players Sketches of negotiators in teachers contract talks|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2012-09-11/news/ct-met-teachers-strike-thumbnails-20120911_1_alicia-winckler-jesse-sharkey-cps|accessdate=20 September 2012|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=11 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Origins==\n\n===Chicago Teachers Federation===\nThe CTU originated from the Chicago Teachers Federation (CTF), an organization of women elementary school teachers founded in 1897. In its first few years, it ran a successful campaign to increase teacher pay, and its membership grew to 2500.<ref name=\"West 1971\">{{cite web|last=West|first=Lucy|title=Chicago Teachers' Federation records, 1864-1968 (bulk 1897-1968)|url=http://chsmedia.org/media/fa/fa/M-C/CTF-inv.htm|work=Descriptive Inventory for the Collection|publisher=Chicago Historical Society|accessdate=11 September 2012|date=July 1971}}</ref> In 1900, the CTF elected Catherine Goggin and [[Margaret Haley]] as its officers, deciding to pay them the same wages as those made by teachers.<ref name=\"West 1971\" />\n\n[[File:Chicagoteachers1900.jpg|thumb|[[Margaret Haley]] and Catherine Goggin, two early leaders of the CTF, prompted the investigation of corporate [[Tax evasion|tax evaders]] as a means of restoring the city's funds.|262x262px]]\n\nUnder the leadership of Haley and Goggin, the CTF struggled for [[Women's suffrage in the United States|women's suffrage]], for women's rights within the labor movement, and for the right of woman workers to earn as much as their male counterparts.<ref name=\"Rousmaniere - CHS encyc\">{{cite web|last=Rousmaniere|first=Kate|title=Chicago Teachers Federation|url=http://www.encyclopedia.chicagohistory.org/pages/271.html|encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Chicago|publisher=Chicago Historical Society|accessdate=11 September 2012|year=2005}}</ref><ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), p. 7. \"With two-thirds of the teaching workforce female, teacher unionism was firmly located in the context of women's work and women's struggles to enhance the status and rewards of teaching. For most of this century, boards of education denied female teachers equal pay with men, the right to marry, and access to leadership positions in the schools. In Chicago, female elementary school teachers used the union as a vehicle to campaign for equal pay with high school teachers.\"</ref> The CTF also launched a successful campaign against corporate tax evasion, the compensation for which was used to pay back salaries upon which the city had reneged.<ref name=\"West 1971\" />\n\nIn 1902, the CTF joined the [[Chicago Federation of Labor]] (CFL). It was the first time that a teachers' group had affiliated with a larger labor organization.<ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), p. 22.</ref>  In 1916, Haley and the CTF helped to found the [[American Federation of Teachers]] (AFT), in which the CTF became Local 1.<ref name=\"Rousmaniere - CHS encyc\" />  However, the Chicago Board of Education, led by Jacob Loeb, had recently passed a rule against teacher unions:<ref name=\"ILHS Hall of Honor 2007\">{{cite web|title=Hall of Honor|url=http://illinoislaborhistory.com/hall-of-honor/200-2007-hall-of-honor.html?fontstyle=f-smaller|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130126131111/http://illinoislaborhistory.com/hall-of-honor/200-2007-hall-of-honor.html?fontstyle=f-smaller|url-status=dead|archive-date=26 January 2013|year=2007|publisher=Illinois Labor History Society|accessdate=11 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n<blockquote>Membership by teachers in labor unions or in organizations of teachers affiliated with a trade union or a federation or association of trade unions, as well as teachers' organizations which have officers, business agents, or other representatives who are not members of the teaching force, is inimical to proper discipline, prejudicial to the efficiency of the teaching force, and detrimental to the welfare of the public school system.  Therefore, such membership, affiliation, or representation is hereby prohibited.</blockquote>\n\nThis rule, which became known as the Loeb rule, further stated that teachers would be fired unless they stated in writing that they did not belong to any such organization.<ref name=\"Survey - 20 Oct 1915\">{{cite news|title=Shall school teachers join labor unions?|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RfsqAAAAMAAJ&lpg=PA1&ots=5PDkfBnT4M&dq=%22Membership%20by%20teachers%20in%20labor%20unions%20or%20in%20organizations%20of%20teachers%20affiliated%20with%20a%20trade%20union%22&pg=PA1#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=11 September 2012|newspaper=The Survey|date=2 October 1915|publisher=Charity Organization Society of the City of New York|pages=1\u20132}}</ref> The Loeb rule allowed the city to fire 68 teachers, including the CTF leadership, who refused to leave the union.<ref name=\"ILHS Hall of Honor 2007\" /> By 1917, the CTF was forced to withdraw from both the CFL and the AFT.<ref name=\"West 1971\" /><ref name=\"Rousmaniere - CHS encyc\" />\n\nSubsequent passage of the Otis rule placed education in the hands of a centralized Board of Education. However, the board was still appointed by city politicians. In the coming years, the city and School Board were accused of rampant corruption, particularly in connection with two-time mayor [[William Hale Thompson]].<ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), p. 12. \"At no time was this political control of Chicago public education more apparent than under the regime of Republican mayor William H. Thompson. Mayor of the city from 1915 to 1923 and again from 1927 to 1931, Thompson had connections with organized crime and presided over some of the worst political corruption in Chicago's history.\"</ref> Many CPS employees were appointed by the Mayor, and a 1931 study found that Chicago spent more money than any other major city on operations costs outside of education.<ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), p. 13.</ref> The proliferation of bureaucracy was a serious concern: when the Elementary Teachers Union formed in 1928, one of its stated goals was \"freeing of teachers from the increasingly intolerable burden of red tape and clerical work.<ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), p. 21.</ref>\n\n=== Great Depression ===\n\nChicago teachers became exceptionally militant during the Great Depression, when teachers and many of their students faced extreme poverty and miserable school conditions.<ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), p. 9. \"Chicago was one of the only cities in the Great Depression where public school teachers actively challenged the policies of school authorities and built a united teachers' organization, the Chicago Teachers Union (CTU). Although divided by gender, ethnicity, and religion and between lowered paid elementary and higher paid high school teachers, still more than two-thirds of the teachers joined the CTU, making it the largest teachers union in the country.\"</ref><ref name=\"Simpson - 2 Aug 2012\" /> Particularly in the inner city, classrooms were undersupplied and overcrowded. \"Too many city classrooms still resemble enlarged prison cells,\" according to a 1931 report.<ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), p. 20.</ref> The city neglected to pay its teachers on 37 out of 46 paydays.<ref name=\"West 1971\" /> Teachers also claimed of egregious class sizes and poorly maintained schools.<ref name=\"Burbank 1971\" /><ref name=\"The Day - 7 Dec 1931\">{{cite news|title=Chicago Teachers Demand Smaller Units, Shorter Day|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=xpErAAAAIBAJ&sjid=nXEFAAAAIBAJ&pg=5577,2611273&dq=chicago+teachers&hl=en|accessdate=19 September 2012|newspaper=The Day|date=7 December 1931|agency=AP|page=1}}</ref>  Most stayed in the classroom teaching, although one committed suicide.<ref name=\"TNB - 27 April 1933\">{{cite news|title=Chicago School Teacher, Unpaid for Eight Long Months, Kills Self as Promises from the Mayor Halt Demonstrations|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=hppXAAAAIBAJ&sjid=20QNAAAAIBAJ&dq=chicago%20teachers%20union&pg=6637%2C2090447|accessdate=11 September 2012|newspaper=Toledo News-Bee|date=27 April 1933}}</ref> Teachers organized independently to procure food and clothing for their students, giving large sums from their own shrinking paychecks.<ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), p. 32\u201333. \"To alleviate the suffering of the Depression, teachers organized committees within schools to collect and distribute money and clothing to the poorer students and served breakfast to hungry children. During the school year of 1930\u201331, the teachers of Chicago contributed more than $112,000 for food and clothing for their students. Yet teachers agonized because they could not contribute more to student financial welfare.\"</ref>\n\n====Contested municipal reforms====\nOnce again, supporters of the public schools (including Haley) launched a campaign against local tax dodgers, who they said had owed taxes on hundreds of millions of dollars worth of new construction.<ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), p. 29. \"Additionally, local politicians and assessors throughout the 1920s failed to tax major property holders and large corporations. Between 1915 and 1925, as Chicago's population increased by 28 percent and there was unprecedented new construction in the city worth some $200 million a year, the official assessed valuation of property increased by only $29 million per annum.\"</ref> This time, business leaders retaliated, in February 1932 forming a group called the Citizen's Committee on Public Expenditures (CCPE), which pushed the city to cut its education budget.<ref name=\"Burbank 1971\">{{cite journal|last=Burbank|first=Lyman|title=Chicago Public Schools and the Depression Years of 1928\u20131937|journal=Journal of the Illinois State Historical Society|date=Winter 1971|volume=64|url=http://dig.lib.niu.edu/ISHS/ishs-1971winter/ishs-1971winter-365.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100806230641/http://dig.lib.niu.edu/ISHS/ishs-1971winter/ishs-1971winter-365.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=2010-08-06|accessdate=12 September 2012}}</ref> The banks, which controlled millions of dollars worth of city tax anticipation warrants, announced (and possessed) de facto control over city policy. In a statement published in the ''Saturday Evening Post'', railroad president and CCPE secretary Fred Sargent wrote that banks \"positively will not lend money for any municipal function which does not have our active support. This has been a powerful lever in dealing with the really small number of recalcitrants in public office who still cling to a faith in a Santa Claus.\" And: \"business men of Chicago have learned their lesson. We shall not again let the mechanism run wild.\"<ref name=\"Sargent SEP 1933\">{{cite news|last=Sargent|first=Fred W.|title=The Taxpayer Takes Charge|url=http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/articles/21597600/taxpayer-takes-charge|accessdate=21 September 2012|newspaper=Saturday Evening Post|date=14 January 1933|page=21}}. Partly quoted in Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), p. 30. Sargent also advocated an end to income taxes.</ref> Sargent and the CCPE were accused of \"financial fascism\" for taking control of the city government through financial blackmail \"with little regard for the needs of the masses and their children.\"<ref name=\"Stillman 1933\">{{cite journal|last=Stillman|first=Charles B.|title=Financial Fascism in Control|journal=The Phi Delta Kappan|date=February 1933|volume=15|issue=5|pages=132\u2013134|jstor=20258189}}</ref>\n\n====Teachers unhappy====\nTeachers, with support from students and parents, began an escalating campaign to restore funding to the schools and paychecks to the teachers. They believed that Chicago's banks had access to millions of dollars in unpaid taxes that might balance the city's budget; they were angry about the CCPE's explicitly anti-school agenda, and they were also provoked by a $90 million bank bailout from the [[Reconstruction Finance Corporation]] that did nothing to help the schools.<ref name=\"Simpson - 2 Aug 2012\" /> More generally, teachers were alarmed by an apparent corporate attack on education; they believed that the nation's ruling class wanted to dismantle education for the public and reserve it only for the wealthy.<ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), p. 36\u201337. \"Teachers began to express the idea that they were defending democracy and the public education system from self-serving business and political elites. Reflecting a general public optimism with the promise of education, teachers viewed the schools as avenues for social mobility and bulwarks of a more democratic society. [...] Many teachers believed there was a nationwide plot by people of power and wealth to cripple public education and to restrict schooling to those who could afford it.\"</ref>\n\nProtests and petitions mounted from 1931\u20131932. Students planned a solidarity demonstration, and although many were convinced to stay in school, 13,000 students actually walked out.<ref name=\"CSM 6 April 133\">{{cite news|title=Chicago Students Strike in Protest To Help Teachers: Thousands Walk Out of High Schools to Force Paying Back Salaries|newspaper=Christian Science Monitor|date=6 April 1933|id={{ProQuest|513352228}}}}</ref> Teachers became frustrated with union leaders who urged restraint for the teachers and argued amongst each other; new rank-and-file organizations emerged. Historian John F. Lyons describes these groups as key in the development of solidarity among the city's teachers:\n\n<blockquote>Many began to see the weak and divided position of the unions as the main reason for lack of success in the dispute. Accordingly, between 1931 and 1933, ordinary teachers founded a number of temporary groups to unify their ranks and actively pursue their demands. In November 1931, the South Side Teachers organized a number of mass meetings, publicity campaigns, and voting drives, and appealed without success to various teachers' unions to cooperate in framing a legislative program. Three more rank-and-file teachers' organizations emerged in 1932: The Civic Education Association of Chicago, initially organized by teachers from Senn High School on the North Side, aimed \"to bring all of the teachers of Chicago, organized and unorganized, into one effective unit.\" The Chicago Teacher Voter Association set out with the sole aim of campaigning for politicians sympathetic to the teachers' plight. The South Side Teachers called for a boycott of stores, hotels, and other businesses that had participated in the tax strike.<ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), p. 35\u201336.</ref></blockquote>\n\nTeachers increasingly began to feel singled out for bad treatment by the city. This feeling was amplified in March 1933 when teachers learned that, as teacher pay was being further cut by 15%, school janitors had received a secret raise. The city announced furthermore that on the next pay day all municipal employees except teachers would be paid.<ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), p. 38.</ref>\n\n====Teachers revolt====\nIn April 1933, teachers targeted banks in the downtown [[Chicago Loop|Loop]], which they held \"financially responsible\" for the $30 million deficit in teacher payments.<ref name=\"NYT - 25 April 1933\">{{cite news|title=5,000 Chicago Teachers Storm Five Banks; Dawes Heckled as He Argues With Crowd|newspaper=New York Times|date=25 April 1933|agency=AP|id={{ProQuest|100724303}}}}</ref>  On April 24, 1933 (the beginning of spring break), thousands of teachers entered bank offices and began causing mayhem. They chanted \"Pay us! Pay us!\"<ref name=\"Simpson - 2 Aug 2012\" /> At City National Bank, they chanted \"We want Dawes! We Want Dawes!\", referring to bank chairman and recent US vice president [[Charles G. Dawes]]. Dawes appeared, surrounded by guards, and attempted to appease the mob over shouts.<ref name=\"MontGaz 25 April 1933\" /> Police, who had also experienced a number of payless paydays, were reluctant to interfere.<ref name=\"MontGaz 25 April 1933\">{{cite news|title=Chicago Teachers Storm Loop Banks|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=2H8uAAAAIBAJ&sjid=PJkFAAAAIBAJ&dq=chicago%20teachers&pg=5763%2C3096246|accessdate=19 September 2012|newspaper=Montreal Gazette|date=25 April 1933|agency=AP|page=6}}</ref>\n\nTeachers conducted more 'raids' on 27 April, demanding of bankers: \"Pay your taxes!\" and \"We want food!\" After joining city meetings en masse, they proceeded to the Chicago Title and Trust Company, which held $10 million of property taxes in escrow. President Holman Pettibone spoke to the crowd from a second-story window and attempted to convince them that the company owed nothing to the city.<ref name=\"NYT - 27 April 1933\">{{cite news|title=Teachers Stage New Chicago Riot: Over 3,000 Defy Police and Guards to Demand Tax Payments by Bank \u2013 Bank Accounting Ordered \u2013 Trust Company Must Report Funds Held in Escrow For Property Taxes|newspaper=New York Times|date=27 April 1933|page=19|id={{ProQuest|100715239}}}}</ref> (In fact, Chicago Title and Trust did possess $10 million of unpaid property tax money, held in escrow accounts for tax evaders; Pettibone argued that the bank could not legitimately hand them over to the city.)<ref name=\"CDT - 27 April 1933\">{{cite news|title=Mayor and AIDS Take Pay Fight to Springfield: Postpone Action on School Closing \u2013 First Bill Passed \u2013 Board Defers Action on School Closing. Teachers Put on New Demonstration As Officials Seek Pay Funds \u2013 Roosevelt and MacDonald Reach Agreement|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=27 April 1933|pages=1, 6|id={{ProQuest|181382209}}}}</ref> Here, they clashed directly with police and bankers; several teachers were beaten and a large plate-glass window was broken.<ref name=\"WP - 27 April 1933\">{{cite news|title=Unpaid Chicago Police Club Unpaid Teachers in Rioting: Patrolmen, on Horses, Injure Many Women as Hundreds Again Stage Protest in Loop Area for $30,000,000 Due on Pay|newspaper=Washington Post|date=27 April 1933|agency=UP|page=1|id={{ProQuest|150407999}}}}</ref> The [[National Education Association]] telegraphed bankers directly, threatening to move the organization's convention (with its 10,000 attendees) away from Chicago\u2014a potential blow for the upcoming [[World's Fair]].)<ref name=\"LDS - 2 May 1933\">{{cite news|title=Says Teachers Might Embarrass Chicago|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=mcwgAAAAIBAJ&sjid=z2oFAAAAIBAJ&dq=chicago%20teachers&pg=5733%2C2316328|accessdate=19 September 2012|newspaper=Lewiston Daily Sun|date=2 May 1933|agency=AP|page=Eleven}}</ref>\n\nIn early May, bankers agreed to buy tax anticipation warrants from the city. (Practically, this meant the banks were loaning the city money.) Bankers issued a collective statement suggesting that further demonstrations from teachers would provoke them to reverse their decision. Mayor Edward J. Kelly echoed the statement.<ref name=\"LDS 13 May 1933\">{{cite news|title=Bankers Warn Chicago Teachers Not to Parade: Teachers Get pay for Last September and Promise of More Money Soon|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ocwgAAAAIBAJ&sjid=z2oFAAAAIBAJ&dq=chicago%20teachers&pg=2648%2C3059286|accessdate=19 September 2012|newspaper=Lewiston Daily Sun|date=13 May 1933|agency=AP|page=1}}</ref> Yet in July, the school board announced further pay cuts, provoking demonstrations from ''tens'' of thousands of teachers.<ref name=\"Simpson - 2 Aug 2012\">{{cite web|last=Simpson|first=Bob|title=The Chicago Teacher Revolt of 1933|url=http://www.laborheritage.org/?p=2581&iact=hc&vpx=341&vpy=177&dur=474&hovh=192&hovw=260&tx=185&ty=133&sig=108900284445453467695&ei=asJOUIGDPeLm0QGN1oD4BQ&page=2&tbnh=131&tbnw=200&start=7&ndsp=11&ved=1t:429,r:5,s:7,i:119|publisher=Labor Heritage Foundation|accessdate=11 September 2012|date=2 August 2012}}</ref> 25,000 people gathered on July 21, 1933, for a \"Save Our Schools\" protest. Banners read \"Don't let the bankers cheat your children out of an education\" and \"Gratitude\u2014months with no pay\u2014now fired\".<ref name=\"WP 15 July 1933\">{{cite news|title=Unpaid Chicago Teachers Protest Retirement Plan|newspaper=Washington Post|date=15 July 1933|agency=AP|page=2|id={{ProQuest|150369363}}}}</ref>  Teachers marched on [[Grant Park (Chicago)|Grant Park]] and tore down a [[Century of Progress]] banner anticipating the coming [[World's Fair]]. Teachers and parents also sought legal injunctions against the Board of Education. The School Board nevertheless fired hundreds of teachers in September, leaving remaining teachers to teach more classes\u2014of larger size. In October, the city received a $35 million federal loan, which it used to issue back pay.<ref name=\"Burbank 1971\" />\n\n===Consolidation and charter===\nChicago teachers had formed several different unions, some of which were still segregated by gender.<ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), p. 23.</ref> The unrest in the early 1930s served to unite these groups, which previously had difficulty cooperating.<ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), p. 28.</ref> Chicago teachers played an active role in the AFT and retained their status as Local 1. In 1937, Local 1 battled New York's Local 5 over whether the AFT would remain in the [[American Federation of Labor]] (AFL) or join the newer and more inclusive [[Congress of Industrial Organizations]] (CIO).<ref name=\"NYT - 22 Aug 1937\">{{cite news|title=Nation's Teachers to Debate C.I.O. Tie|newspaper=New York Times|date=22 August 1937|page=N5|quote=As preliminary lines formed for the battle over union affiliation, it appeared certain that delegates of New York City Local 5, representing 6,000 members, would take the leadership in the drive for C.I.O. affiliation. It became equally evident that the Chicago delegation, representing 7,000 members, would fight to the last ditch to remain in the A.F.L.|id={{ProQuest|102136795}}}}</ref> (New York's Local 5 was at that time the Teachers' Union, which was soon expelled from the AFT after accusations of communism, and replaced by the more moderate [[United Federation of Teachers]].) Soon after the convention (which decided to stay in the AFL), the Chicago Teachers Union was officially chartered by the AFT as an amalgamation of Chicago's multiple teacher unions in Chicago.<ref name=\"CSM - 30 Oct 1937\">{{cite news|title=Chicago Teachers Form Union To Loosen Grip of Politics|newspaper=Christian Science Monitor|date=30 October 1937|page=4|id={{ProQuest|515388274}}}}</ref><ref name=\"ChiTrib - 13 Oct 1937\">{{cite news|title=A. F. of L. Affiliate Will Charter Teachers' Union|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=13 October 1937|id={{ProQuest|181891987}}}}</ref> At this point about 3,500 teachers were members of the new Local.<ref name=\"CDT - 2 June 1938\" /> By September, it was the largest teachers union in the U.S., with over 8500 members.<ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), p. 44.</ref> The CTF, still under Haley's leadership, remained separate for some years, based on concerns that the CTU would disproportionately represent the interests of males and high school teachers.<ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), p. 45.</ref>\n\n== Before collective bargaining: 1937\u20131967  ==\nWhen the CTU formed, teachers had become disillusioned about their status as a special class of workers. Some elementary school teachers were paid less than janitors, and more teachers came to agree that they experienced discrimination because they were female. (Meanwhile, male teachers felt shortchanged and emasculated.) Teachers also resented the constantly increasing bureaucratic control over their classrooms.<ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), pp. 18\u201321.</ref>\n\n=== Goals  ===\nThe CTU sought [[collective bargaining]] rights early on, but Superintendent William Johnson refused to grant them.<ref name=\"CDT - 2 June 1938\">{{cite news|title=Teachers' Union Rebuffed in Plea For Recognition|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=2 June 1938|page=8|id={{ProQuest|182001977}}}}</ref> The union also targeted evaluations (for teachers who wanted to become principals) that it said were administered in a corrupt fashion.<ref name=\"CDT - 20 May 1938\">{{cite news|title=Air Both Sides in Controversy Over Schools: The School Question|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=20 May 1938|pages=1, 4|id={{ProQuest|181954866}}}}</ref> By 1939, the CTU had more than doubled in size, to 8,500 members, and organized its members for actions such as mass letter-writing.<ref name=\"CDT - 7 June 1939\">{{cite news|title=Teachers Turn on Heat to Pass Pay Boost Bill: Union Starts Letter Wave Toward Springfield|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=7 June 1939|page=6|id={{ProQuest|175298294}}}}</ref>\n\nIn 1948, amid small-scale sickouts and walkouts, the CTU authorized a strike when teachers experienced still more 'payless paydays' due to city neglect.<ref name=\"NYT - 24 Jan 1948\">{{cite news|title=Chicago Teachers Payless 5 Weeks: Threaten to Strike as City Refuses to Use $9,500,000 Reserve For Salaries|newspaper=New York Times|date=24 January 1948|page=13|id={{ProQuest|108122113}}}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT - 25 Jan 1948\">{{cite news|title=Chicago Teachers VOte Strike Call: Walkout Tuesday Sanctioned By Union Unless Pay is Freed and School Budget Passed|url=http://search.proquest.com/docview/108112634/|accessdate=11 September 2012|newspaper=New York Times|date=25 January 1948|page=20}}</ref> The strike was averted hours before it was scheduled to begin, when the school board approved a new budget and announced that the checks due to the teachers had been mailed with all possible haste.<ref name=\"Thompson - 27 Jan 1948\">{{cite news|last=Thompson|first=John|title=Pay Teachers; Strike Off: Aldermen O.K. Record '48 Budget \u2013 Board to Consider Cut in Levy \u2013 Call School Strike Off; Pay Mailed Record Budget is O.K.'d By City|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=27 January 1948|pages=1, 12|id={{ProQuest|177541248}}}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to perennial requests for salary increases, the CTU began demanding more direct changes to Chicago's public schools. It asked the [[Chicago Police Department]] to station an officer in each of Chicago's 43 high schools; CPD refused.<ref name=\"CDT - 22 Sept 1954\">{{cite news|title=Police Refuse to Station Men in High Schools: Reject Request From Teachers' Union|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=22 September 1954|page=1|id={{ProQuest|178798437}}}}</ref> The CTU continued to pursue the school violence issue, insisting that teachers were being attacked by dangerous youths.<ref name=\"CDT - 1 March 1955\">{{cite news|title=Union to Seek More Police in High Schools: Terrorist Attacks Told by Fewkes|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=1 March 1955|page=7|id={{ProQuest|179400663}}}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Teachers 'Hush Up' Violence in Chicago|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=VRQfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EJsEAAAAIBAJ&dq=chicago%20teachers%20union&pg=7252%2C586487|accessdate=11 September 2012|newspaper=The Tuscaloosa News|date=5 February 1965|agency=AP|page=9}}</ref>  During this period the union also sought shorter hours for students and teachers.<ref name=\"CDT - 2 Feb 1954\">{{cite news|title=Teacher Union Fights Longer Day For Pupils: OK's Increase in Hours For Instructors|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=19 February 1954|page=B4|id={{ProQuest|178672818}}}}</ref><ref name=\"CDT - 3 Dec 1954\">{{cite news|title=Teachers Sign Petitions for Shorter Hours|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=3 December 1954|page=A8|id={{ProQuest|178832872}}}}</ref> It also called attention to a mounting teacher shortage, citing over a hundred classrooms without regular or substitute teachers.<ref name=\"CDT - 15 March 1955\">{{cite news|title=Cite Teacher Need as Grade Classes Grow: Shortage is Called More Serious|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=15 March 1955|page=1|id={{ProQuest|178839067}}}}</ref>\n\nDuring this period, Fewkes and the CTU consistently opposed [[merit pay]] policies, proposals which would vary teachers salaries based on evaluations.<ref name=\"CT Fewkes obit\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Teacher Union Head Opposes Merit Ratings|url=http://search.proquest.com/docview/179535769/|accessdate=12 September 2012|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=23 August 1955|page=A10}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Gowran|first=Clay|title=Pay Teachers on Merit Basis? It's Ticklish Topic: Even Some Who Would Benefit Fear System|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=6 March 1959|page=15|id={{ProQuest|182281261}}}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Fewkes Rips Merit Pay Idea For Teachers: Union Chief Says It Won't Work|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=18 March 1962|page=36|id={{ProQuest|183122887}}}}</ref>\n\n=== John Fewkes and anticommunism===\nThe CTU's first president was John Fewkes.<ref name=\"CT Fewkes obit\">{{cite news|title=John M. Fewkes, 91, Teachers Union Founder|last=Heise|first=Kenan|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1992-07-25/news/9203060964_1_chicago-teachers-union-strike-merit-system|accessdate=11 September 2012|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=25 July 1992}}</ref> Fewkes had been the most prominent leader of \"Voluntary Emergency Committee\" (VEC), a male-dominated group that formed in 1933 and gained prominence by advocating and coordinating militant action. The VEC had been aggressive but not radical, and explicitly sought to exclude communists.<ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), pp. 38\u201339.</ref>\n\nThe union, urged on by Fewkes,<ref name=\"CT Fewkes obit\" /> participated in the AFL's anti-communist purges, and in 1941 voted 5,258 to 892 to expel the New York City [[Teachers Union]], the New York College Teachers Union and Philadelphia Teachers Union from the AFT.<ref name=\"CDT - 21 May 1941\">{{cite news|title=Chicago Union Teachers Back Red Expulsions|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=21 May 1941|id={{ProQuest|176484275}}}}</ref> The three expelled Locals were large, representing about one quarter of the AFT's members, but the CTU was larger, and its votes were decisive in accomplishing the expulsion.<ref name=\"NYT - 21 May 1941\">{{cite news|title=Chicago Teachers Vote For Ouster: 5,258 to 892 For Dropping 3 Locals That Union COuncil Accused of Communism|newspaper=New York Times|date=21 May 1941|page=25|id={{ProQuest|106074842}}}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT - 7 June 1941\">{{cite news|title=Federation Votes 3 Teacher Unions Out As Red-Ruled|newspaper=New York Times|date=7 June 1941|pages=1, 32|id={{ProQuest|106067900}}}}</ref>\n\nFewkes remained CTU President for most of this period. He left the CTU in 1943 to serve as AFT president. In 1944, he took a position with the federal [[War Production Board]].<ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), p. 82.</ref> By 1947, he had returned to the CTU for a second term as its president.<ref name=\"CT Fewkes obit\" />  In 1950, the CTU governing board approved a constitutional amendment to remove limitations on presidential terms; John Fewkes was thereby allowed to run again, and remained CTU president until 1966.<ref name=\"CT Fewkes obit\" /><ref name=\"CDT - 22 Nov 1950\">{{cite news|title=Teachers' Union Heads Kill Time Limit on Chief|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=22 November 1950|id={{ProQuest|178046295}}}}</ref>\n\n===Demographics and civil rights===\nMost of Chicago's public school teachers were white single women. Public school teacher was also the most common occupation for black women in Chicago, who were treated by CPS as second-class job candidates: qualified black high school teachers worked in elementary schools or as substitutes; some could not get jobs at all.<ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), p. 15. \"Black teachers also enjoyed fewer career prospects than did white teachers. With only two black high schools in the city, DuSable and Wendell Phillips, the vast majority of black teachers worked in elementary schools even if they were trained for better-paying high school work. Out of 321 black teachers who worked in the Chicago public school system in 1934, 285 of them taught in the elementary schools. With fewer opportunities for African American high school teachers, many qualified teachers from the South had to work as substitutes or take other jobs in Chicago until teaching positions opened up for them.\"</ref> Teachers came from a shifting mix of white-collar and blue-collar families.<ref>Lyons, ''Teachers and Reform'' (2008), pp. 16.</ref>\n\n===Campaign for collective bargaining===\nThe CTU intensified its campaign for [[collective bargaining]] rights in the 1960s, staging huge demonstrations at the Chicago Board of Education.<ref name=\"CDD - 11 Jan 1961\">{{cite news|title=4,000 Teachers Stage Protest March: Pay Hike, Bargaining Top Issues|newspaper=Chicago Daily Defender|date=11 January 1961|pages=1, 2|id={{ProQuest|493808486}}}}</ref> Pressure increased after the New York recognized collective bargaining rights for the UFT in 1961,<ref name=\"Tavel - 23 Aug 1963\">{{cite news|last=Tavel|first=Emile|title=Teachers Demand Bargaining Right: Strike Threat Dangles|url=http://search.proquest.com/docview/510553518/|accessdate=12 September 2012|newspaper=Christian Science Monitor|date=23 August 1963|page=3}}</ref> and the CTU threatened an illegal strike in 1963\u20131964 if the School Board would not grant it the same status.<ref>{{cite news|title=Teacher Union Asks Board to Change Stand: Hint at Strike Vote Next Month|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=7 November 1963|page=C1|id={{ProQuest|89097422}}}}</ref> The city averted a strike by agreeing to negotiate,<ref>{{cite news|title=Strike Vote is Withheld by Teachers: Board Agrees to Bargain \u2013 School Union Delays Balloting on Strike|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=27 February 1964|page=1|id={{ProQuest|179375855}}}}</ref> and, after long delays (including litigation from a rival union, the Chicago Education Association),<ref>{{cite news|last=Yuenger|first=James|title=Delay Ruling on Vote for School Union: Board Asks Time to File Reply|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=9 October 1965|page=N3|id={{ProQuest|170023590}}}}</ref> the CTU became the official bargaining agent of Chicago teachers in April 1966.<ref>{{cite news|last=Banas|first=Casey|title=Union Elected by Teachers as Their Bargaining Agent|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=4 June 1966|page=3|id={{ProQuest|178997581}}}}</ref>\n\n== Internal politics and organization ==\n\n=== Caucus of Rank and File Educators ===\nIn 2010, the Caucus of Rank and File Educators (CORE), led by President Karen Lewis gained control over the CTU by winning 60% of the vote in a run-off election.<ref name=\"Canon - 12 June 2010\">{{cite news|last=Canon|first=Ramsin|title=Caucus of Rank-and-File Educators (CORE) Takes Over Chicago Teachers Union|url=http://gapersblock.com/mechanics/2010/06/12/caucus-of-rank-and-file-educators-core-takes-over-chicago-teachers-union/|accessdate=11 September 2012|newspaper=Gapers Block|date=12 June 2010}}</ref>  CORE ran an aggressive grassroots organizing campaign, and took a strong stance against school privatization.<ref name=\"Canon 2010\">{{cite news|last=Canon|first=Ramsin|title=The Education Revolt: The Chicago Model's Fallout|url=http://gapersblock.com/mechanics/2010/05/03/the-education-revolt-the-chicago-models-fallout/|accessdate=11 September 2012|newspaper=Gapers Block|date=3 May 2010}}</ref> CORE accused the incumbent United Progressive Caucus (UPC) of capitulating to corporate interests, silencing dissent within the union, and collaborating with the city to prevent union outreach at schools.<ref name=\"Abowd - 7 June 2010\">{{cite news|last=Abowd|first=Paul|title=Chicago's Rank and File Educators Well-Positioned Against \"Play it Safe\" Incumbents|url=http://labornotes.org/2010/06/chicagos-rank-and-file-educators-well-positioned-against-play-it-safe-incumbents|accessdate=11 September 2012|newspaper=Labor Notes|date=7 June 2010}}</ref>\n\nCORE quickly took action to distinguish itself from UPC, reaffirm its grassroots support, and launch a campaign to defend public education. The new leadership cut pay for union officers and used the savings to expand outreach.<ref name=\"Sustar - 31 Aug 2012\">{{cite news|last=Sustar|first=Lee|title=Chicago Teachers Draw a Line|url=http://www.indypendent.org/2012/08/31/chicago-teachers-draw-line|accessdate=11 September 2012|newspaper=The Indypendent|date=31 August 2012}}</ref> Former CTU member John A. Ostenburg criticized Lewis and CORE in 2011 for inexperience and political recklessness, arguing that they will not successfully be able to combat Mayor [[Rahm Emanuel]]'s entrenched power.<ref name=\"Ostenburg - 19 Nov 2011\">{{cite news|title=Leading 'Ugly' Not The Answer For Organized Labor, Chicago Teachers Union, Karen Lewis|url=http://www.enewspf.com/component/ijoomla_archive/archive/author/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=28974:leading-quglyq-not-the-answer-for-organized-labor-chicago-teachers-union&catid=88888891&Itemid=88890121|accessdate=11 September 2012|newspaper=ENews Park Forest|date=19 November 2011}}</ref> CORE represented a major bloc of dissent at the 2012 AFT convention, and held signs in protest of [[Race to the Top]] during a speech from Vice President [[Joseph Biden|Joe Biden]].<ref name=\"Scott - 30 July 2012\">{{cite news|last=Scott|first=Norm|title=@AFT - Chicago Teachers Protest RTTT During/After Biden Speech|url=http://ednotesonline.blogspot.com/2012/07/aft-chicago-teachers-protest-rttt.html|accessdate=11 September 2012|newspaper=Ed Notes Online|date=30 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n===2018 merger with Charter Union Local===\nIn spring of 2018, the Chicago Teachers Union and Chicago Association of Charter Teachers and Staff Local 4343 voted to merge, with the charter educators forming a new division within the CTU. On December 4, 2018, CTU members at the Acero charter school network initiated the first strike at a unionized charter school in US history. The strike ended December 9, 2018, in a major victory with the strikers who won sanctuary school protections for their students, enforceable reductions in class size and parity with the existing pay scale at district-run schools.\n\n==Collective bargaining and strikes==\n\n=== Strikes 1968\u20131987 ===\n\nChicago teachers went on strike multiple times in the 1970s and 1980s:<ref name=\"Schmidt - 29 Aug 2012\">{{cite news|last=Schmidt|first=George N.|title=CORE hosts final 'Successful Chicago Strikes' forum following CTU notice of intent to strike.... Veteran teachers describe how CTU overcame racism and thwarted the CPS attempts to 'play the race card'|url=http://www.substancenews.net/articles.php?page=3543|accessdate=12 September 2012|newspaper=Substance News|date=29 August 2012}}</ref> \n* 1968: \"Concerned FTBs\" (long-term substitutes) and others engage in [[Wildcat strike action|wildcat strikes]] against school segregation and racism\u2014particularly systemic unfairness in the certification, hiring, and promotion of black teachers.<ref name=\"Schmidt - 5 March 2012\">{{cite news|last=Schmidt|first=George N.|title=Strikewatch: The first Chicago strikes were 'illegal...' How Chicago teachers make a strike.... The first thing it's about is no longer working on the boss's terms for the boss's offer and taking the boss's insults|url=http://www.substancenews.net/articles.php?page=3124|accessdate=12 September 2012|newspaper=Substance News|date=5 March 2012}}</ref> \n* 1969: Two-day strike results in salary increases, teacher aides, and class size maximum.\n* 1971: Four-day strike results in salary increases and full health benefits.\n* 1973: Two strikes, of 12 and 11 days, yield improved salary, benefits, preparation time, supplies, and class sizes.\n* 1979-1980: Multiple strikes over a payless payday during holiday break in 1979, results in salary increase and improved sick leave and maternity/paternity leave.\n* 1984: Four-day strike results in medical care increase and PAC checkoff.\n* 1985: Two-day strike for salary and sick leave.\n* 1987: Record-breaking 19-day strike under CTU President [[Jacqueline B. Vaughn]] wins raises and improvements to health care.\n\n===2012 strike===\n[[File:2012ChicagoTeachersUnionStrikeMarch.jpg|thumb|left|Striking members of the Chicago Teachers Union marching through the [[Chicago Loop]] on September 11, 2012.|290x290px]]{{Commons category|Chicago teachers strike of 2012|2012 Chicago teachers strike}}Under the leadership of CORE, the CTU pushed hard in negotiations with the city. Early on, the CTU made the decision to decline an offer of pay increases combined with layoffs.<ref name=\"Sustar - 31 Aug 2012\" /> When the city would not agree to the CTU's core demands, including an expansion of programs like art and music at the city's most underfunded high schools, CTU members voted overwhelmingly (90% of teachers and 98% of those who cast ballots) to authorize a strike.<ref name=\"Moran - 28 Aug 2012\">{{cite news|last=Moran|first=Theresa|title=Chicago Teachers Say They'll Strike for the Kids|url=http://labornotes.org/2012/08/chicago-teachers-say-theyll-strike-kids|accessdate=11 September 2012|newspaper=Labor Notes|date=28 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn September 10, 2012, the Chicago Teachers Union began a strike<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timeoutchicagokids.com/things-to-do/hipsqueak-blog/180381/chicago-teachers-union-rally-photos|title=Chicago teachers union rally|publisher=Time Out Chicago Kids|accessdate=September 10, 2012}}</ref> after CTU President Lewis declared that negotiations with the city were not succeeding.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/thetwo-way/2012/09/09/160855857/no-deal-chicago-teachers-to-strike-after-contract-talks-fail|title=No Deal: Chicago Teachers To Strike After Contract Talks Fail|publisher=NPR|date=September 9, 2012|accessdate=September 10, 2012}}</ref> This strike was the CTU's first since  1987, and the first strike ever for many of the teachers involved.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/nation/story/2012/09/9/chicago-teachers-school-board-halt-strike-talks/57720772/1|title=Chicago teachers strike for first time in 25 years|publisher=USA Today|accessdate=September 10, 2012|date=11 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Solidarity - 10 Sept 2012\">{{cite news|title=Windy City Fights Back: Live blogging the Chicago Teachers Strike|url=http://solidarity-us.org/site/node/3695|accessdate=11 September 2012|newspaper=Solidarity|date=10 September 2012|author=Editorial Committee}}</ref>  Regulations required them to make contract negotiations an issue in the strike, and the teachers indeed sought better pay, better benefits, and protections for teachers who lose their jobs due to school closures.<ref name=\"Moran - 28 Aug 2012\" />\n\nThe striking teachers also wanted to call attention to a number of education issues, particularly what they defined as a broad attack on public schooling by corporate privatizers.<ref name=\"DN school model - 10 Sept 2012\">{{cite news|title=Striking Teachers, Parents Join Forces to Oppose \"Corporate\" Education Model in Chicago|url=http://www.democracynow.org/2012/9/10/striking_teachers_parents_join_forces_to|accessdate=10 September 2012|newspaper=Democracy Now!|date=10 September 2012}}</ref>  In particular they demand a decrease in high-stakes testing for students, and an increase in music, art, and gym programs available at public schools.<ref name=\"DN - reforms - 10 Sept 2012\">{{cite news|title=Chicago Public Teachers Stage Historic Strike in Clash with Mayor Rahm Emanuel on Education Reforms|url=http://www.democracynow.org/2012/9/10/chicago_public_teachers_stage_historic_strike|accessdate=10 September 2012|newspaper=Democracy Now|date=10 September 2012}}</ref> They also called for smaller class sizes and paid preparation time.<ref name=\"Moran - 28 Aug 2012\" />\n\nOn September 11, 2012, the Service Employees International Union Local 1 informed companies that some of their members might go on strike with the teachers.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/politics/clout/chi-some-chicago-public-schools-custodians-may-strike-20120911,0,595858.story|title=Some Chicago Public Schools custodians may strike|publisher=The Chicago Tribune|accessdate=September 11, 2012|first=John|last=Byrne}}</ref>\n\nOn September 14, 2012, the teachers reached a tentative agreement with the city, which included preferences for teachers who have been laid off due to a school closing to be hired in another school, and student test scores having less of a role in teacher evaluations than the city had originally planned.<ref name=\"striketentativeend\">{{cite news|title=Chicago teachers reach tentative agreement to end strike|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/decision2012/chicago-teachers-reach-tentative-agreement-to-end-strike/2012/09/14/b0d01452-feae-11e1-8adc-499661afe377_story.html?hpid=z4 | work=The Washington Post | first=Lyndsey|last=Layton|date=15 September 2012}}</ref> This tentative agreement did not hold, however, and the strike continued, at which point Mayor Emanuel announced his intention to seek a legal injunction, forcing teachers back to work.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kelleher |first=James B. |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/09/17/us-usa-chicago-schools-idUSBRE88E0IV20120917 |title=Emanuel's court bid to end strike stalls, teachers call it vindictive |publisher=Reuters |date= 17 September 2012|accessdate=2012-10-05}}</ref> On September 17, 2012, Mayor Emanuel's efforts to end the strike stalled as the walkout went into the second week.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://usnews.nbcnews.com/_news/2012/09/17/13915011-judge-declines-to-expedite-hearing-in-chicago-teacher-strike|title=Judge declines to expedite hearing in Chicago teacher strike|publisher=NBC News|date=September 17, 2012|accessdate= September 18, 2012}}</ref> Delegates from the CTU voted to end the strike on September 18, 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.blogs.cnn.com/2012/09/18/chicago-teachers-vote-to-end-strike/|title=Chicago teachers vote to suspend strike|publisher=CNN|accessdate=18 September 2012|date=18 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/nation/story/2012/09/18/chicago-teachers-are-suspending-seven-day-strike/57799352/1|title=Chicago teachers suspend seven-day strike|publisher=USA Today|accessdate=September 18, 2012|date=18 September 2012}}</ref> Students began their return to the schools on Wednesday, September 19, 2012. The CTU was still required to ratify the contract with the Union's 29,000 teachers.<ref>{{cite news|title=School Days Resume in Chicago as the Lessons From a Strike Are Assessed|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/09/20/us/chicago-strike-ends-and-schoolchildren-return-to-class.html?ref=us|work=The New York Times|date=September 19, 2012|accessdate=September 19, 2012|first1=Monica|last1=Davey|first2=Steven|last2=Greenhouse}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the end of the strike, leaders of the Union held [[town hall meetings]] in major U.S. cities to underscore the belief that community collaboration is key in creating beneficial changes in education, as opposed to top-down imposition by governors or mayors. The Union planned to hold town hall meetings in Chicago, Cleveland, Minneapolis, New Orleans, New York, Philadelphia, Pittsburgh, San Francisco, St. Paul, and Tampa.<ref>{{cite news|title=After Chicago success, teachers unions spread their message|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/education/after-chicago-success-union-leaders-spread-their-message/2012/09/21/cad16290-0424-11e2-9b24-ff730c7f6312_story.html|work=Washington Post|accessdate=September 22, 2012|first=Lyndsey|last=Layton|date=22 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n===2015\u20132016 contract dispute===\nFollowing the expiration of the contract in June 2015, CPS teachers continued to work without a contract for a year while the union and district negotiated. In September 2016, union members voted overwhelmingly to strike if an agreement could not be reached, setting a deadline of October 11. Minutes before midnight on October 10, the district and union reached a tentative agreement, avoiding a strike.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/breaking/ct-chicago-teachers-contract-talks-20161010-story.html |title = Chicago Teachers Union, school board reach tentative contract agreement}}</ref>\n\n=== 2019 strike ===\n{{main|2019 Chicago Public Schools Strike}}\n\n[[File:Chicago Teachers Union Rally 10-14-19 3748 (48906578637).jpg|thumb|364x364px|Chicago teachers marching during a demonstration on October 14, 2019.]]After the expiration of the CPS contract with CTU in June 2019, a contract dispute emerged.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.wttw.com/2019/08/09/fact-finder-s-report-sheds-light-ctu-contract-negotiations-cps|title=Fact-Finder's Report Sheds Light on CTU Contract Negotiations With City|last=|first=|date=2019-08-12|website=WTTW News|language=en|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref> Vermont Senator [[Bernie Sanders]] spoke at a rally hosted by CTU and SEIU Local 73 in preparation of the strike on September 24. On September 27, 2019, CTU members voted to authorize a potential strike starting on October 17 if a contract deal is not reached.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/breaking/ct-chicago-teachers-union-strike-vote-last-day-20190926-ilgd5djc4zcjjp5pj3gusbbxnu-story.html|title=Chicago Teachers Union votes to authorize strike; walkout could begin Oct. 7|last=Pratt|first=Hannah Leone, Gregory|date=2019-09-27|website=chicagotribune.com|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref> The union's top priorities in contract negotiations are reducing classroom size and increasing the number of support staff (such as nurses and social workers).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nbcchicago.com/news/local/Key-Issues-in-Chicago-Teachers-Union-Strike-562933871.html|title=Key Issues in Potential Chicago Teachers Union Strike|last=|first=|date=2019-10-12|website=NBC Chicago|language=en|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref> On October 16, 2019 CPS cancelled classes for October 17, 2019 in anticipation of the CTU strike.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/10/16/770660821/chicago-cancels-public-school-classes-as-teachers-prepare-to-strike|title=Chicago Cancels Public School Classes As Teachers' Strike Looms|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref> CTU delegates officially voted to go on strike hours afterwards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wgntv.com/2019/10/16/last-day-of-negotiations-before-potential-cps-teacher-strike/|title=CTU rejects latest contract proposal, teachers to strike Thursday|date=2019-10-16|website=WGN-TV|language=en|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref> Mayor [[Lori Lightfoot]] announced that CPS would not add any makeup days for any school days lost during the strike, stating that \"There\u2019s no plan to make up any days...We want to make sure we get a deal done.\" At the time, Illinois state law required that all school districts in Illinois include at least 176 days in the school year. Lightfoot's decision broke this mandate, as the 2019\u20132020 school year was ''exactly'' 176 days long. Additionally, it was noted that teachers could lose pay if the strike days were not added back to the district calendar.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/2019/10/3/20897902/cps-teachers-strike-lightfoot-lori-chicago-public-ctu|title=Kids rejoice: CPS won't add makeup days if teachers strike, Lightfoot says|last=Issa|first=Nader|date=2019-10-03|website=Chicago Sun-Times|language=en|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\nOn Thursday, October 17, 2019, teachers took to picket lines early in the morning, and the CTU stated that it planned to resume negotiations with the city at [[Malcolm X College]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/breaking/ct-cps-strike-chicago-teachers-union-updates-20191016-mo2oqq4fxbezxct62kijuujzeq-story.html|title=Chicago Teachers Union strike updates: CPS teachers join picket lines across the city as negotiations are set to resume|last=staff|first=Chicago Tribune|website=chicagotribune.com|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref> Later that afternoon, CPS announced that classes had been cancelled for the following day, as even though negotiations seemed to be progressing, there was no foreseeable agreement in the near feature. On Friday, October 18, 2019, teachers continued on the second day of the strike, meaning that students had attended school two days (Tuesday and Wednesday) out of the five days from October 14\u201318 (CPS students did not go to school on Monday due to the observance of [[Columbus Day]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abc7chicago.com/5627963/|title=Chicago Teachers Strike: Thousands of teachers to return to picket lines for 2nd day Friday, CPS classes remain canceled|date=2019-10-18|website=ABC7 Chicago|language=en|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref> That weekend, CTU and CPS continued negotiating. While both sides noted progress over Saturday, Lightfoot noted that she would be \"...very surprised if classes [would] open on Monday.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/news/2019/10/20/20923461/chicago-teachers-union-strike-day-4-negotiations-continue-monday-classes-uncertain|title=CTU strike, Day 4: Talks continue, but Monday classes still uncertain|last=Wittich|first=Jake|date=2019-10-20|website=Chicago Sun-Times|language=en|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref> The following day, Sunday, October 20, 2019, CPS canceled school for Monday the 21st. Even though tentative agreements had been made on eight points, CPS canceled school for Monday as CTU had not voted to end the strike yet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wgntv.com/2019/10/20/classes-not-anticipated-to-resume-monday-as-teachers-contract-talks-continue/|title=CPS cancels classes Monday as teachers' strike, contract talks continue|date=2019-10-20|website=WGN-TV|language=en|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\nOn Monday, October 21, 2019, CTU members entered the third school day and second calendar week of the strike. Negotiations between CPS and CTU continued, and Lightfoot sent the union a letter asking them to end the strike while negotiations continued. CTU president Jesse Sharkey noted that \"...the letter [from Lightfoot] I received today dashed my hope for a quick settlement.\" That afternoon, Mayor Lightfoot canceled CPS classes for Tuesday, stating that \"...CTU has not scheduled a House of Delegates vote, which would be necessary to end their strike...As a result, it will not be possible to hold classes tomorrow.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wgntv.com/2019/10/21/3rd-day-without-classes-for-cps-students-as-teachers-strike-continues/|title='We are likely not going to see a quick settlement': Tuesday classes canceled as CPS strike drags on|date=2019-10-21|website=WGN-TV|language=en|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref> The next day, Tuesday, October 22, 2019, negotiations continued, and 2020 democratic presidential primary candidate [[Elizabeth Warren]] joined the striking teachers. Later, Mayor Lightfoot canceled CPS classes for Wednesday, October 23, stating once again that \"...CTU has not scheduled a House of Delegates vote, which would be necessary to end their strike...As a result, it will not be possible to hold classes tomorrow.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wgntv.com/2019/10/22/elizabeth-warren-to-rally-with-ctu-as-teachers-strike-enters-6th-day/|title=Wednesday classes canceled as CTU members rally in downtown Chicago|date=2019-10-22|website=WGN-TV|language=en|access-date=2019-10-23}}</ref> It was noted that on Tuesday, negotiations appeared to be \"at an impasse\", and the majority of CTU's 40-person bargaining team was not expected to return to the negotiating table. CTU President Sharkey expressed that the proposed contract did \"...not have adequate enforcement mechanisms on staffing.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nbcchicago.com/blogs/ward-room/CPS-Cancels-School-Wednesday-as-Teachers-Strike-Continues-563652011.html|title=CPS Cancels Classes Wednesday as Teachers Strike Continues|website=NBC Chicago|language=en|access-date=2019-10-23}}</ref> After negotiations had ended Tuesday evening, several issues remained unresolved, such as class-size caps, the duration of the contract, salaries, and health benefits. At this point, teachers planned to keep the strike going until at least Thursday the 24th, or longer if necessary.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abc7chicago.com/5640234/|title=Chicago Strike: CPS teachers march in Loop during Mayor Lori Lightfoot's address, Chicago Public Schools classes canceled|date=2019-10-23|website=ABC7 Chicago|language=en|access-date=2019-10-23}}</ref> On Wednesday, October 23, 2019, negotiations continued at Malcolm X College. Teachers only picketed in front of schools until 8:00&nbsp;a.m. local time. Then, they proceeded to rally in the downtown Loop and converge in front of the [[Chicago City Hall|city hall]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wgntv.com/2019/10/22/elizabeth-warren-to-rally-with-ctu-as-teachers-strike-enters-6th-day/|title=Wednesday classes canceled as CTU members rally in downtown Chicago|date=2019-10-22|website=WGN-TV|language=en|access-date=2019-10-24}}</ref> Lightfoot presented her 2020 city budget plan Wednesday evening, at the end of the fifth school day of the strike. Emails and phone calls were disseminated to students and parents, informing them that classes were canceled for Thursday, October 24, as both the CTU and CPS still did not expect an agreement any time soon.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chicago.cbslocal.com/2019/10/23/cps-ctu-teachers-strike-sixth-day-classes-cancelled/|title=CPS Cancels Class For Thursday, Following Massive Rally By Striking Teachers Downtown|date=2019-10-23|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-24}}</ref> The following day, on Thursday the 24th, teachers returned to the picket lines at 7:00&nbsp;a.m., and the president of the [[Association of Flight Attendants|Flight Attendant's Union]], [[Sara Nelson]], was expected to join the striking teachers to show support. CTU also scheduled [[civil disobedience]] training for its members at the CTU headquarters at 3:00&nbsp;p.m., suggesting a prolonged strike.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abc7chicago.com/5643109/|title=Chicago Strike: Negotiations continue for 8th day as CTU plans civil disobedience training. Chance the rapper wore a Chicago Teachers Union shirt on SNL in support.|date=2019-10-24|website=ABC7 Chicago|language=en|access-date=2019-10-24}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* Lyons, John F. ''Teachers and Reform: Chicago Public Education 1929\u20131970.'' Urbana & Chicago: University of Illinois Press, 2008. {{ISBN|978-0-252-03272-1}}.\n\n==External links==\n* CTU {{Official website|http://www.ctulocal1.org}}\n\n===Images===\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140804172721/https://reuther.wayne.edu/node/709 Photo of 1933 teacher uprising] hosted by the Walter Reuther Library at Wayne State\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150202055809/http://reuther.wayne.edu/node/7306 Photo of President Fewkes leading a 1965 CTU meeting] hosted by the Walter Reuther Library at Wayne State\n* [https://www.flickr.com/photos/32225081@N07/with/7072480979/#photo_7072480979 Pictures of the 1980s teacher strikes] posted to Flickr by \"union person\"\n\n[[Category:American Federation of Teachers]]\n[[Category:Chicago Public Schools]]\n[[Category:Education trade unions]]\n[[Category:Organizations based in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Trade unions established in 1937]]\n[[Category:Trade unions in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Chicago Teachers Union| ]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toSara Nelson(link changed toSara Nelson (union leader)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chicago_Teachers_Union"}
{"title_page": "Abbot Academy", "text_new": "{{Infobox school\n|name = Abbot Academy\n|image = Draper Hall Abbot Academy Andover MA.jpg\n|motto = ''Facem Praetendit Ardentem''<br/>(She Holds Aloft a Burning Torch)\n|established = 1829<ref name=Townsman>Francesca Balboni, Andover Historical Society, Andover Townsman, March 17, 2011, [http://www.andovertownsman.com/local/x1498155410/Andover-Stories-Abbot-Academy-a-leader-in-its-own-right-for-150-years Andover Stories: Abbot Academy a leader in its own right for 150 years], Accessed Aug. 10, 2013</ref>\n|closed = 1973 (merged with [[Phillips Academy]])\n|type = [[Independent school|Independent]], [[Boarding school|Boarding]]\n|gender = Girls\n|head_label = Principal\n|head = Donald Gordon\n|city = [[Andover, Massachusetts|Andover]]\n|state = [[Massachusetts]]\n|country = [[United States]]\n|campus = [[Suburban]]\n|grades = 9\u201312\n|enrollment =\n|faculty =\n|class = 115 seniors (1973)<ref name=Forum1>\"The Abbot Forum\", Abbot Academy, Vol. IV, No. 2, June 1973, p. 22.</ref>\n|ratio =\n|athletics =\n|colors = Light Blue and White {{Color box| #ADD8E6|border=darkgray}}{{Color box| #FFFFFF |border=darkgray}}\n|nickname = Abbot Rabbits\n|coordinates = {{Coord|42.6473|-71.1323 |type:landmark_region:US|display=title}}<!--<ref name=satsig>{{cite web|title=Latitude and Longitude|url=http://www.satsig.net/maps/lat-long-finder.htm|publisher=satsig.net|accessdate=21 October 2013}}</ref>-->\n|pushpin_map = Massachusetts#USA\n|homepage = {{URL|http://www.andover.edu/}}\n}}\n'''Abbot Academy''' (also known as '''Abbot Female Seminary''' and '''AA''') was an [[University-preparatory school|independent boarding preparatory school]] for women boarding and day students in grades 9\u201312 from 1828 to 1973.<ref>NY Times, [https://www.nytimes.com/1886/03/31/archives/needs-of-the-abbot-academy-alumnae-trying-to-raise-150000-for-new.html NEEDS OF THE ABBOT ACADEMY.; ALUMNAE TRYING TO RAISE $150,000 FOR NEW BUILDINGS], Accessed August 10, 2013, \"...&nbsp;the female university at Andover, Mass\"</ref> Located in [[Andover, Massachusetts]], Abbot Academy was notable as one of the first incorporated secondary schools for educating young women in New England.<ref name=Townsman/><ref name = SusanLloyd>Susan McIntosh Lloyd, 1979, [http://eric.ed.gov/?id=ED177747 A Singular School: Abbot Academy, 1828-1973], Accessed Sept. 6, 2013, \u201c...&nbsp;One of the first educational institutions in New England to be founded for girls and women alone, Abbot had by far the longest corporate life of any&nbsp;...\u201d</ref> It merged with [[Phillips Academy]] in 1973<ref>Jonathan Phelps, Lawrence Eagle-Tribune, October 14, 2013, [http://www.eagletribune.com/local/x674145442/Addison-draws-attention-to-Innu-exhibit-with-large-banners Addison draws attention to Innu exhibit with large banners], Accessed Aug. 10, 2013</ref><ref>Amanda Bergeron, Boston Globe, Sept. 6, 2007, [http://www.boston.com/news/globe/obituaries/articles/2007/09/06/barbara_sisson_retired_teacher_active_in_arts/ Barbara Sisson, retired teacher active in arts], Accessed Aug. 10, 2013, \"...&nbsp;Abbot Academy, a boarding school for girls in Andover... 1973, when the school became part of Phillips Academy, Andover&nbsp;...\"</ref> and campus buildings along School Street continue to be used for the combined school. Some Abbot traditions continue at the combined private boarding school such as Parents' Weekend.<ref name=Salton>Alex Salton, thephilippianonline, October 26, 2009, [https://archive.is/20130811101616/http://www.phillipian.net/articles/parents-weekend-tradition-began-abbot-academy Parents\u2019 Weekend Tradition Began with Abbot Academy], Accessed Aug. 10, 2013.</ref> Since the 40th anniversary in 2013 of the merger of the two schools, there has been renewed interest in Abbot's history and traditions.<ref>\"Calling all Alumni from the late '60s to the late '70s!\" in ''Andover the Magazine of Phillips Academy'', Spring, 2013, p. 57.</ref>\n\n== History ==\n{| style=\"float:right; width:25em; font-weight:bold; border:solid 1px #999999; font-size:.9em; line-height:1.3em; margin:0 0 1em 1em;\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\"\n|-style=\"color:#000080; valign=\"top\"\n|Those persons who feel favorably disposed toward the establishment of a FEMALE HIGH SCHOOL in the South Parish of Andover, are requested to meet at Mr. James Locke's, on Tuesday evening next, the 19th inst., at 6 o'clock, P.M.\n|-\n|-font-size:.6em;\" align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"\n|Notice on trees and buildings around Andover, February 15, 1828. Source: Susan Lloyd<ref name = SingularSchool>Source: Susan M. Lloyd, 1979, [https://archive.org/stream/singularschoolab00lloy/singularschoolab00lloy_djvu.txt A Singular School: Abbot Academy, 1828-1973], Accessed Sept. 6, 2013</ref>\n|}\n[[File:SarahAbbotImage.jpg|thumb|Sarah Abbot]]\n[[File:Philena McKeen with Abbot Academy graduates 1864.jpg|thumb|Philena McKeen with graduates in 1864]]\n[[File:Abbot Academy outdoor drama production circa 1874 'Masque of the Flowers'.jpg|thumb|Students performing ''Masque of the Flowers'' circa 1874]]\n[[File:Abbot Academy students behind barrier between Abbot and Phillips Academy circa 1874.jpg|thumb|Students behind a fence separating them from Phillips Academy, circa 1874]]\n[[File:Abbot Academy students on a picnic in 1888.jpg|thumb|Picnic in 1888.]]\nThe school was founded during a time when the prevailing view was that women's education \"should always be relative to men\", with some believing that study of \"higher subjects\" such as [[philosophy]] and [[mathematics]] might render women to be infertile.<ref name = SingularSchool/> One of the first formal discussions to propose a school for young women happened on February 19, 1828.<ref name=NewEnglandMagazine>Annie Sawyer Downs, New England Magazine, 2011, [http://www.newenglandmagazine.com/the-new-england-magazine/vol1-no2jan-1886/abbot-academy/ Abbot Academy] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140302015737/http://www.newenglandmagazine.com/the-new-england-magazine/vol1-no2jan-1886/abbot-academy/ |date=March 2, 2014 }}, Accessed August 10, 2013.</ref> The school was incorporated in 1829 with 70<ref name = SusanLloyd/> or 85<ref name=NewEnglandMagazine/> pupils from eighteen to twenty years of age for the \"exclusive work of educating women\". According to one source, the official opening day was May 6, 1829.<ref name = SusanLloyd/>\n\n{{Quote|...to regulate the tempers, to improve the taste, to discipline and enlarge the minds and form the morals of youth...|Abbot Constitution, 1829<ref name=Townsman/>}}\n\n===The early years===\nThe school received financial support from Sarah Abbot who pledged substantial money, which allowed for loans to begin construction; Sarah Abbot died in 1850 and left a substantial sum for educational purposes.<ref name=NewEnglandMagazine/> After mid-century, Abbot faced several challenges: the addition of a public high school in Andover, followed by the challenges of coping with the [[American Civil War]].<ref name = SingularSchool/> In 1853, the first principalship was offered to a woman, and additional monies were raised for the construction of dormitories.<ref name=NewEnglandMagazine/> In 1859, the \"strong-willed\" but \"ideologically moderate\" McKeen sisters \u2014 headmistress Philena and Phebe\u2014exerted strong leadership by adopting a \"school-home\" approach.<ref name = SingularSchool/> The years were marked by substantial expansion of buildings.<ref name = SingularSchool/> The McKeens fostered the study of [[French language|French]] and [[German language|German]] and introduced a \"systematic oral language program\" on a par with that of [[Harvard University]] and which \"far outdistanced Phillips Academy\", which did not offer any modern language instruction until the mid 1870s.<ref name = SingularSchool/> Under their \"no-nonsense\" leadership, teachers stayed longer, many for ten or more years.<ref name = SingularSchool/>\n\n{{Quote|Abbot had always promised order, but the McKeen sisters delivered it in spades. They loved schedules. Up at 6:00, breakfast at 6:30, clean your room\u2014\u2014and perhaps a teacher's parlor as well. Though four Irish maids also helped out at $1.98 a week, the McKeens considered house work part of education ... Miss McKeen might ask a girl to help her change guest beds, questioning her the while on Butler's Analogy. Between 8:00 and 9:00 a.m. older students often climbed the Hill for a Geology lecture while younger ones did their daily calisthenics, but all must be on hand for the Devotions that formally opened the school day. Before mid-day dinner everyone wore gym suits with pantaloons, and skirts ten inches from the ground. ... Recitations continued till 3:30, then came Recreation Hours, with time for walking in pairs, studying, mending, croquet, or (after 1886) tennis. Supper followed; the evening was an alternation of study hours, \"half-hours\" for individual meditation ... and \"quarters\" for room-to-room visiting. Evening Devotions might mean anything from a hymn sing to a prayerful scolding. Bed at 10:00.|Susan McIntosh Lloyd, in ''A Singular School''<ref name = SingularSchool/>}}\n\nIt was during the late 1800s that the school had a \"golden age\", according to one view.<ref name=Townsman/> The campus was visited by luminaries such as [[Helen Keller]] and her teacher [[Anne Sullivan]] and [[Amos Bronson Alcott]].<ref name=Townsman/> The leadership of Philena and Phebe McKeen was characterized by substantial fundraising and growth.<ref name=Townsman/> According to Susan McIntosh Lloyd, Abbot's curriculum \"may have surpassed that of Phillips\" during these years.<ref name=Townsman/> After 1910, the only structures built were \"gates\".<ref name=Townsman/> The school was like a \"family\" but commanded by women, in which \"women and girls could enjoy one another as persons without self-consciousness or shame.\"<ref name = SingularSchool/>\n[[File:Helenkellerannesullivan1898.jpg|thumb|right|[[Helen Keller]] and her teacher [[Anne Sullivan]] both spoke at Abbot.]]\n[[File:Andover Massachusetts Phillips Academy Abbot campus Draper Hall with circle and tree.JPG|thumb|right|Draper Hall]]\n[[File:Andover Massachusetts Phillips Academy Abbot campus entranceway with Draper Hall in background.JPG|thumb|right|Merrill Memorial Gates (main entrance)]]\n[[File:Andover Massachusetts Phillips Academy Abbot campus building around circle.JPG|thumb|right|McKeen Memorial and Davis Hall]]\n{{Quote|Abbot's women and girls ... One thinks of Victorian women as confined, and so they were. They could not openly initiate friendship with boys or men; they were expected to hide their interest in sex or to subsume it within coquettish formulae, no matter how interested they really were. Partly because of this relative isolation from men, however, loving, lasting friendships between women could quietly thrive, modeled often on the close mother-daughter or sister-sister relationships that existed apart from men's affairs.|Susan McIntosh Lloyd, in ''A Singular School''<ref name = SingularSchool/>}}\n\n===Art education===\n\nThe academy emphasized art education. After starting a small art club in 1871 led by Professor E. A. Park, the academy introduced one of the nation's first ''History of Art'' courses in 1873.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |title= United States of America: Art Education |author=Douglas C. Allen |encyclopedia =[[Grove Art Online]] |accessdate =  }}</ref><ref name=\"Barker2000\">{{cite book|author=Deborah Barker|title=Aesthetics and Gender in American Literature: Portraits of the Woman Artist|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=C9PhiZTqmbUC&pg=PA213|year=2000|publisher=Bucknell University Press|isbn=978-0-8387-5408-5|pages=213\u2013}}</ref> Painting and drawing were taught by professional painter and alumnus<ref>Note: class of 1869</ref> Emily A. Means who had studied with well-known painters in Europe for four years.<ref name=\"Barker2000\"/><ref>{{cite book|title=Journal of Education|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tEohAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA268|year=1898|publisher=Boston University, School of Education|pages=268\u2013}}</ref> Means guided the art department from 1877 to 1892 and later served as principal from 1898 to 1911.<ref name=\"LeonardMarquis1910\">{{cite book|author1=John William Leonard|author2=Albert Nelson Marquis|title=Who's who in America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HiwzAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA2354|year=1910|publisher=Marquis Who's Who|pages=2354\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Kelsey1929\">{{cite book|author=Katharine Roxanna Kelsey|title=Abbot Academy Sketches, 1892-1912|url=https://archive.org/details/abbotacademysket00kels|year=1929|publisher=Houghton Mifflin}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|jstor = 42821783|title = Educational Intelligence|last = |first = |date = 11 May 1911|journal = Journal of Education|volume = 19|issue = 1829|pages = 526\u2013531|doi = |pmid = }}</ref>\n\n===The 1930s through the 1960s===\nThe school went through challenging times during the [[Great Depression]] of the 1930s.<ref name = SingularSchool/> In the Depression's first five years, the school lost approximately $60,000 annually as well as a sharp drop in its real-estate assets, and the school slipped from having 135 boarders in 1929\u201330 to 71 boarders in 1933\u201334.<ref name = SingularSchool/> Despite financial concerns, the school continued to dismiss \"unruly or lazy students\" or those who tucked \"dummies into their beds\" to spend the night at [[Phillips Academy]].<ref name = SingularSchool/> Many other schools folded during the Depression years.<ref name = SingularSchool/> During these years, the school taught the \"basic college preparatory\" program of 3 years of English, 5 years of languages (including 2 or 3 of Latin), 2 or 3 years of mathematics, 1 year of science and 1 year of history, as well as physical education, an \"all school choral class\" and Bible study of one hour a week, but requirements adjusted over time, largely dictated by preferences of college admissions departments.<ref name = SingularSchool/> From [[World War II]] and afterwards, the academy experienced increasing enrollment; ten years after the attack on Pearl Harbor, a third of its teachers were either European born or European educated.<ref name = SingularSchool/> The school opened its doors more widely to minority groups, such as [[African American]] women and [[Jews]].<ref name = SingularSchool/>\n\nAcademic excellence improved. An alumna, Elizabeth Thomas '49, recalled her Abbot teaching as \"the best she has ever had\", with college being easier.<ref name = SingularSchool/> However, during these years, there was a greater space between teachers and students, such that there were no \"out-of-class relationships\" between them; teachers seemed \"miles away\" unless they were enforcing rules about lipstick or patrolling the Phillips campus for errant women or checking mail for return addresses to \"certain Phillips boys.\"<ref name = SingularSchool/> Rules forbade smoking and drinking and sexual activity; one 1954 alumna described a \"whole system of deception\" designed to evade teachers, seen as \"the enemy,\" with deceptions done to get messages to Phillips students, sometimes through day student intermediaries or by messages left in bushes.<ref name = SingularSchool/>\n\n{{Quote|Why was the faculty so intent on having the school go on in that crazy old fashioned way? ... Abbot was the only place I'd heard of in 1949 where 1849 was still preserved.|Elizabeth Marshall, quoted in ''A Singular School''.<ref name = SingularSchool/>}}\n\nHowever, some students appreciated that the rules cleared \"time and space for that ''peaceful collection of self''\".<ref name = SingularSchool/> Nevertheless, applications to the school increased from the 1950s through the 1960s.<ref name = SingularSchool/> During the 1960s, the ratio of applicants to acceptances was three to one.<ref name = SingularSchool/> The 1960s featured rules easing somewhat, with more chaperoned dances, more phone calls and dating as well as \"cattle-market mixers\", but the easing sometimes encouraging girls to find \"ways to be still naughtier.\"<ref name = SingularSchool/> Lloyd described the coming changes:\n\n{{Quote|No school is an island: before 1960, every chapter of Abbot's story had been bound in some degree to the realities and dreams of the larger society. ... the old Abbot had made itself a place apart, especially after the McKeen sisters came, and it did its best to remain so through the early 1960s. During the final decade, the outside world beat upon Abbot's doors with such insistence that they must either be opened up or broken down. The Trustees opened them and the world rushed in like a clumsy repairman, knocking over tables and trampling valuable heirlooms, but also bringing fresh air into musty places, and piling on the floor a heap of lumber and tools with which to build anew.|Susan Lloyd, in ''A Singular School''.<ref name = SingularSchool/>}}\n\nAccording to Lloyd, Abbot Academy seemed to be a \"nineteenth century school\" which was stagnant and insular and limited in comparison with the abrupt societal changes made during the 1960s.<ref name = SingularSchool/> In 1967, there were greater ties between [[Phillips Academy]] and Abbot, including a Phillips-Abbot committee to explore a \"wide range of shared activities\" between the two schools.<ref name = SingularSchool/> Abbot trustee Philip Allen had determined that both schools should merge, but that this was a \"hidden agenda\"; Allen brought in headmaster Donald Gordon, a graduate of Phillips Academy and Yale, to bring \"Abbot up to the point where it could \nbe part of Phillips Academy.\"<ref name = SingularSchool/><ref name = SingularSchool/> Abbot's \"old dress code\" was abolished for a \"neat and clean\" requirement.<ref name = SingularSchool/> The 1969-70 year was \"tumultuous\" nationwide, with student revolts on many college campuses and foreign policy failures abroad.<ref name = SingularSchool/> The following is a description of Abbot campus life in 1969:<ref name = SingularSchool/>\n\n{{Quote|Touch football players romped on the sacred Circle. Not a saddle shoe was to be seen; indeed, one boy and two girls played with no shoes at all, in spite of November. Two pairs of faded blue jeans wandered by, one belted in macrame and filled by a man of bristling beard; he was discussing English papers with the other.|Susan Lloyd in ''A Singular School''<ref name = SingularSchool/>}}\n\n===The 1973 merger===\nThe late 1960s and early 1970s was marked by the merger between the two schools. The merger was brought about by many factors, including the sense of shared history and goals between the two schools, common activities, plus survey research showing that 94% of students in northeastern secondary schools wished for coeducation.<ref name = SingularSchool/> The times \"favored coeducation\"; in 1968, 53 colleges and universities either became coeducational or began coordinate instruction.<ref name = SingularSchool/> While Phillips Academy \"held the cards\" regarding whether the two schools should merge, there was a \"crasser impetus\" from admissions statistics, as Phillips was increasingly being turned down by applicants preferring newly-coeducational competitors such as St. Paul's, Taft, Northfield-Mount Hermon, and Exeter.<ref name = SingularSchool/> Many committee meetings, including discussions between administrators and teachers, happened over a sixteen-month period.<ref name = SingularSchool/> The Phillips headmaster, John Kemper, who had kinship ties with women graduates of Abbot, felt a merger was \"practical, ethical, and educationally sound\", although several times the Phillips Board of Trustees refused to sanction a merger.<ref name = SingularSchool/> The school merged with Phillips Academy on June 28, 1973.<ref name = SusanLloyd/> Many Abbot traditions were included in the combined school, such as having a designated weekend in the fall for parents to visit.\n\n{{Quote|Parents\u2019 Weekend was Abbot\u2019s response to formalize parent visits to the school. In the past, parents would visit the school on many different occasions. The event created one specific weekend for all parents to visit.|Tim Sprattler, 2009<ref name=Salton/>}}\n\n[[File:Abbot Academy students who graduated with the first Andover-Abbot co-educational class of 1974 at their 45th reunion.jpg|thumb|Abbot Academy students who were at the school during the Andover-Abbot merger gather at their 45th reunion. They were members of the first co-educational class of 1974, so they received Andover diplomas, but most came to the school as Abbot students.]]\nAfter the merger, $1 million of Abbot's endowment became the basis for the '''Abbot Academy Association''', which funds various educational programs and projects submitted by students, faculty, and staff.<ref>https://www.andover.edu/About/AbbotAcademyAssociation/Pages/GuidelinesforGrantProposers.aspx</ref><ref>[http://www.andover.edu/About/AbbotAcademyAssociation/Pages/default.aspx Abbot Academy Association]</ref><ref>February 1, 2013, Boston.com, [https://archive.is/20130811101541/http://momsevents.boston.com/andover_ma/events/show/303201527-andover-welcomes-best-selling-author-reza-aslan Andover Welcomes Best-selling Author Reza Aslan], Accessed Aug. 10, 2013, \"...funded by the Abbot Academy Association.\"</ref> Since the first Abbot Grant was awarded in the fall of 1973, nearly 2000 Abbot Grant proposals have been submitted by students and members of the faculty, staff and administration of Phillips Academy. The Abbot Academy Association has funded more than 1400 of these proposals with grants totaling $9,400,000.<ref>https://www.andover.edu/About/AbbotAcademyAssociation/GrantHistory/Pages/default.aspx</ref>  In 2014, the Abbot Academy Association's endowment had grown to $10 million.<ref name=\"LorenGary2\">Loren Gary, \"A Widening Circle: Abbot Academy and the Abiding Significance of Place\", Andover: Phillips Academy, 1997, p. 7.</ref>\n\n== Campus life==\nActivities included the Fidelio Chorus, school government, and the school newspaper. Athletic programs included basketball, crew,<ref>Note: through Phillips Academy</ref> cycling, ballet and modern dance, fencing, soccer, softball, and tennis. In the late 1960s, Abbot's math department set up a paper-tape terminal connected to a computer at [[Merrimack College]] in [[North Andover, Massachusetts]]. This provided the high school students with early BASIC-language computer programming skills. In 1973, the languages taught included English, French, German, Latin, Russian, and Spanish.<ref name=Forum2>\"The Abbot Forum\", Abbot Academy, 1973, p. 9.</ref>\n\n=== Academic prizes ===\nAbbot was a chapter member of the [[Cum Laude Society|Cum Laude Honor Society]]. The school awarded the following student prizes annually:<ref name=Forum4>The Abbot Forum\", Abbot Academy, 1973, pp. 36, 37.</ref>\n{{col-start}}\n{{col-break}}\n* Anna Dawes Prize for History\n* Betsy Waskowitz Rider Art Award\n* Beatrice Farnsworth Powers Art Award\n* Priscilla Bradley Prize for Art\n* Pam Weidenman Prize for Art\n* Ceramics Prize\n* Photography Prize\n* Music Department Award\n* Kate Friskin Award for Music\n{{col-break}}\n* Mathematics Department Prize\n* Science Prize\n* Spanish Department Prize\n* English Department Prize\n* Latin Department Prize\n* Ballet Prize\n* Abbot Athletic Award\n* Isabel Hancock Award\n{{col-end}}\n\nThe Madame Sarah Abbot award was established through a gift from the Abbot Class of 1973. The award is given to a female Phillips Academy senior who \" \u2026 best exemplifies 'strong character, effective leadership and outstanding scholarship.'\"<ref>''The Phillipian'', Vol. CV, No. 25, June 3, 1984, p. 1.</ref>\n\n===School publications===\nIn June 1873, the first issue of the ''Abbot Courant'' was published. This student literary magazine appeared two to three times a year.<ref name=Courant1>''The {{as written|Abbott}} Courant'', Vol. 1, No. 1, June 1873.</ref> Later editions included art work and photographs. In 1992, with a grant from the Abbot Academy Association, the ''Courant'' was revived at Phillips Academy and continues to be published twice a year. In 2002, a 123-page alumni edition was published.<ref name=CourantPA>''The COURANT, Alumni Edition: 10 Years'', Phillips Academy Andover, Fall 2002, p. [6].</ref> The Abbot Academy yearbook was published from 1900 to 1973. Originally known as ''The Abbot Academy Class Book'', the yearbook became ''The Circle'' in 1916 (this is the first year that the double-A logo used on senior class rings appeared on the book cover).<ref name=Circle1900>''Class Book: Published by the ... Senior Class of Abbot Academy, Andover, Massachusetts''.</ref><ref name=Circle1916>''The Abbot Circle Nineteen Hundred and Sixteen'', Senior Class of Abbot Academy, Andover, Massachusetts.</ref> Digital versions of the ''Abbot Courant'' and ''The Circle'' are available through the school Archives and Special Collections.<ref>[http://www.noblenet.org/paarchives/ Abbot Academy Archives and Special Collections: Phillips Academy Andover]</ref>\n\nThe student newspaper was called ''Cynosure''. In 1974, it moved to Phillips where it became a monthly magazine.<ref name=Forum3>\"The Abbot Forum\", Abbot Academy, 1973, p. 25.</ref>\n\n== Traditions ==\nStudents were divided into two groups called ''Gargoyles'' and ''Griffins'' for sports teams and for other purposes that required dividing the students into groups; their colors were green and orange, respectively.<ref>Susan McIntosh Lloyd. \"A Singular School: Abbot Academy 1828-1973\", p. 234.</ref> Dual-color felt beanie hats with an image of a gargoyle or griffin were distributed to students.\n\nThe locally based Clan MacPherson Pipes and Drums led graduation processions on the Abbot Circle.<ref>[http://clanmacpherson.org Clan MacPherson Pipes and Drums]</ref> This tradition continues today at Phillips Academy.<ref>\"Class of 2013 graduates from Phillips Academy\", http://www.andover.edu/about/newsroom/pages/commencement2013.aspx</ref> At graduation, after chapel, Seniors and Junior Middlers (eleventh graders) met in the Senior Courtyard for the Ring Ceremony. (This central garden was completely enclosed by the three sides of Draper Hall with the dining room wall as the fourth side.) By tradition, Junior Mids who purchased Abbot Academy class rings the year before wore them with the \"AA\" insignia upside-down. During the Ring Ceremony, each Junior Mid received a Senior sponsor. The Junior Mid, now recognized as a member of the new Senior class, turned her ring so that the insignia was upright. In 1973, all students who wanted to were allowed to buy Abbot class rings.<ref>''The Abbot Forum'', Vol. IV, Number 2, June 1973, p. 30.</ref>\n\n== Buildings and campus ==\n[[File:Abbot Academy proposed sketch 1829 buildings and grounds Andover Massachusetts.jpg|thumb|right|320px|The campus had three main buildings grouped around a circle, plus a gymnasium, a laundry, and several dormitories. The largest building was Draper Hall. This is the partially implemented 1886 plan by architects Hartwell and Richardson.<ref name=\"LorenGary1\">Loren Gary, \"A Widening Circle: Abbot Academy and the Abiding Significance of Place\", Andover: Phillips Academy, 1997, p. 14.</ref>]]\nIn 1863, the Abbot campus consisted of one acre surrounded by a fence. By 1878, it was approximately 22 acres.<ref>Susan J. Montgomery and Roger G. Reed. \"The Campus Guide. Phillips Academy Andover\", New York: Princeton Architectural Press, 2000. pp. 98\u20139.</ref> Abbot's three main buildings (Abbot Hall, Draper Hall, and McKeen Hall) are listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref name=\"LorenGary3\">Loren Gary, \"A Widening Circle: Abbot Academy and the Abiding Significance of Place\", Andover: Phillips Academy, 1997, p. 5.</ref> The first academy building, Abbot Hall, is an \"exceptional\" early example of the Greek Revival style. It was built in 1828\u201329.<ref>Quote from Montgomery and Reed. \"The Campus Guide. Phillips Academy Andover\", p. 103.</ref> Since 1996, it has housed Phillips Academy's Brace Center for Gender Studies.<ref>The Center was opened through the gift of Donna Brace Ogilvie, Class of 1930, \"History of the Brace Center\", http://www.andover.edu/Academics/BraceCenterforGenderStudies/Pages/History.aspx, Accessed Aug. 16, 2013.</ref> An art gallery was added to the left side of Abbot Hall in 1906\u201307. It was designed by [[Andrews, Jacques, & Rantoul]] of Boston. The art gallery housed the collection of Mrs. Esther Byers.<ref>Montgomery and Reed. \"The Campus Guide. Phillips Academy Andover\", p. 104.</ref> The Merrill Memorial Gates and two side gates (the John P. Taylor and George G. Davis gates) were added in 1921 to the front and sides, respectively, of the Abbot Circle. Designed a few years earlier by the firm of [[McKim, Mead & White]], similar gates appear at [[Harvard University]], [[Princeton University]], and [[Bowdoin College]].<ref>Montgomery and Reed. \"The Campus Guide. Phillips Academy Andover\", p. 102.</ref> The Abbot Circle, around which the main buildings are grouped, was re-dedicated on 3 May 1997.<ref name=\"LorenGary1\" /> The tree-lined Maple Walk, which once connected the dining room at the back of Draper Hall with Phillips Street, remains in use. (The dining room was demolished.)<ref>Gary, p. 12.</ref>\n\n== Headmasters and headmistresses ==\nSchool principals:<ref>[http://www.andover.edu/About/AbbotAcademyAssociation/AboutTheAssociation/Pages/AbbotAcademyPrincipals.aspx Abbot Academy Association]</ref>\n{{col-start}}\n{{col-break}}\n* Charles Goddard 1829\u201331\n* Rev. Samuel Lamson 1832\u201334\n* Rev. Samuel Gilman Brown 1835\u201338<ref name=Monroe1911>{{citation |editor=[[Paul Monroe]] |via=HathiTrust |title= Cyclopedia of Education |publisher=Macmillan |location=New York |year=1911 |url=http://hdl.handle.net/2027/uc2.ark:/13960/t1xd15h17?urlappend=%3Bseq=507 }} 1911-1913</ref>\n* Rev. Lorenzo Lorraine Langstroth 1838\u201339\n* Rev. Timothy Dwight Porter Stone 1839\u201342\n* Rev. Asa Farwell 1842\u201352\n* Peter Smith Byers 1853 (Elected but did not serve)\n* Nancy Judson Hasseltine 1854\u201356\n* Maria Jane Bancroft Brown 1856\u201357\n{{col-break}}\n* Emma L. Taylor 1857\u201359\n* Philena McKeen 1859\u201392\n* Laura Sophia Watson 1892\u201398\n* Emily Adams Means 1898\u20131911\n* Bertha Bailey 1912\u201335\n* Marguerite Capen Hearsey 1936\u201355\n* Mary Hinckley Crane (Mrs. Alexander) 1955\u201366\n* Eleanor Tucker (Acting) 1966\u201368\n* Donald Gordon 1968\u201373\n{{col-end}}\n\nFor further information, consult ''The Philippian'':<ref>[http://issuu.com/phillipian/docs/cxxxv16_abbot_academy_principals \"Abbot Academy Principals\", ''The Phillipian'', Vol. cxxxv No. 16]</ref>\n\n== Distinguished alumnae and faculty==\n\n=== Notable alumnae ===\n[[File:Marsha Kazarosian Portrait 2009 2.jpg|thumb|right|Abbot alumna and lawyer [[Marsha Kazarosian]] represented one of the teenaged defendants in the 1990 [[Pamela Smart]] murder case.]]\n[[File:Priscilla Martel.jpg|thumb|Chef [[Priscilla Martel]] cooked for ''[[60 Minutes]]'' reporter [[Morley Safer]] and Chef [[Jacques Pepin]] at her home in [[Connecticut]].<ref name=twsOctN23>{{cite news\n |author= Elizabeth Maker\n |title= Connecticut at its Best; On an Open Fire, Much More Than Chestnuts\n |newspaper= New York Times\n |date= December 11, 2005\n |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2005/12/11/nyregion/connecticut-at-its-best-on-an-open-fire-much-more-than-chestnuts.html?pagewanted=all\n |accessdate= 2010-10-20\n}}</ref>]]\n* [[Julia Alvarez]] (1967) - Poet, novelist, essayist<ref name=\"Chase\">David Chase, \"Aunt Hattie: Telling Tales\", ''Andover the Magazine of Phillips Academy'', Winter, 2013, p. 19.</ref>\n* [[Julia Constance Fletcher]] - (1867)\n* [[Harriette Newell Woods Baker]] (1833) - Story book author<ref name=\"Chase\" />\n* [[Alice Stone Blackwell]] (1867) - Editor ''[[Woman's Journal]]'', activist, and translator<ref name=\"Long\" />\n* [[Anna Brackett]] - Philosopher, educator\n* [[Charlotte Emerson Brown]] - Clubwoman\n* [[Maria Susana Cummins]] (1845) - Author of international bestseller; domestic fiction writer<ref name=\"Long\">\"Notable Alumni: Long List\", Phillips Academy, http://www.andover.edu/About/NotableAlumni/LongList/Pages/1800s.aspx {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105222945/http://www.andover.edu/About/NotableAlumni/LongList/Pages/1800s.aspx |date=2013-11-05 }}, Accessed Aug. 23, 2013.</ref>\n* [[Wendy Ewald]] (1969) - Photographer and educator, MacArthur Fellowship winner<ref>\"Drop that Name!\", ''Andover Bulletin'', Winter 2004, p. 73.</ref>\n* [[Mary H. Graves]] - Unitarian minister, literary editor, writer<ref name=\"EatonEaton1896\">{{cite book|last1=Eaton|first1=Chester Williams|last2=Eaton|first2=Warren E.|title=Proceedings of the 250th Anniversary of the Ancient Town of Redding, Once Including the Territory Now Comprising the Towns of Reading, Wakefield, and North Reading: With Historical Chapters|url=https://archive.org/details/proceedingsof2501644eato|year=1896|publisher=Loring & Twombly|pages=[https://archive.org/details/proceedingsof2501644eato/page/199 199]\u2013}}</ref>\n* [[Marsha Kazarosian]] (PA 1974) - Attorney\n* [[Lucy R. Lippard]] (1954) - Art theorist<ref name=\"Chase\" />\n* [[Priscilla Martel]] (PA 1974) - Chef and cookbook author<ref>''Andover the Magazine of Phillips Academy'', Winter 2013, p. 53.</ref>\n* [[Sara Nelson (editor)|Sara Nelson]] (PA 1974) - Former editor-in-chief of ''Publishers Weekly''\n* [[Elizabeth Marshall Thomas]] (1949) - Anthropologist<ref name=\"Chase\" />\n* [[Elizabeth Stuart Phelps Ward]] (1858) - Early feminist author<ref name=\"Long\" />\n* [[Kate Douglas Wiggin]] (1873) - Author of ''Rebecca of Sunnybrook Farm''<ref>''Andover the Magazine of Phillips Academy'', Spring 2010, p. 41.</ref>\n* [[Francesca Woodman]] - Photographer<ref name=\"Long\" />\n\nFor additional alumnae, consult ''Notable Alumni: Long List'':<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.andover.edu/About/NotableAlumni/LongList/Pages/default.aspx |title=\"Notable Alumni: Long List\", Phillips Academy |access-date=2013-08-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130812074048/http://www.andover.edu/About/NotableAlumni/LongList/Pages/default.aspx |archive-date=2013-08-12 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\n=== Notable faculty ===\n* [[Emily Hale]], speech and drama, muse of [[T.S. Eliot]]\n* [[Maud Morgan]]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Hartwell and Richardson]] architects\n* [[Phillips Academy]]\n\n== Suggested reading ==\n* Susan McIntosh Lloyd. \"A Singular School: Abbot Academy 1828-1973\", Hanover, NH: Published by Phillips Academy, Andover, 1979.\n* Susan J. Montgomery and Roger G. Reed. \"The Campus Guide. Phillips Academy Andover\", New York: Princeton Architectural Press, 2000.\n* Philena McKeen (Headmistress) - author.\n* {{citation |title= Annual Report...1875-76 |year=1877 |author1= [[Massachusetts Board of Education]] |location=Boston |via= Internet Archive |chapterurl=https://archive.org/stream/annualreportofbo7576mass#page/285/mode/2up |chapter=Report on Academies: Abbot Female Academy |author2=George A. Walton }}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Abbot Academy}}\n* [http://www.noblenet.org/paarchives/ Abbot Academy Archives in Archives and Special Collections: Phillips Academy Andover]\n* [http://andoverhistorical.org/ Andover Historical Society]\n\n{{Phillips Academy}}\n\n[[Category:Boarding schools in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Andover, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Preparatory schools in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Private high schools in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:1829 establishments in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Girls' schools in Massachusetts]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox school\n|name = Abbot Academy\n|image = Draper Hall Abbot Academy Andover MA.jpg\n|motto = ''Facem Praetendit Ardentem''<br/>(She Holds Aloft a Burning Torch)\n|established = 1829<ref name=Townsman>Francesca Balboni, Andover Historical Society, Andover Townsman, March 17, 2011, [http://www.andovertownsman.com/local/x1498155410/Andover-Stories-Abbot-Academy-a-leader-in-its-own-right-for-150-years Andover Stories: Abbot Academy a leader in its own right for 150 years], Accessed Aug. 10, 2013</ref>\n|closed = 1973 (merged with [[Phillips Academy]])\n|type = [[Independent school|Independent]], [[Boarding school|Boarding]]\n|gender = Girls\n|head_label = Principal\n|head = Donald Gordon\n|city = [[Andover, Massachusetts|Andover]]\n|state = [[Massachusetts]]\n|country = [[United States]]\n|campus = [[Suburban]]\n|grades = 9\u201312\n|enrollment =\n|faculty =\n|class = 115 seniors (1973)<ref name=Forum1>\"The Abbot Forum\", Abbot Academy, Vol. IV, No. 2, June 1973, p. 22.</ref>\n|ratio =\n|athletics =\n|colors = Light Blue and White {{Color box| #ADD8E6|border=darkgray}}{{Color box| #FFFFFF |border=darkgray}}\n|nickname = Abbot Rabbits\n|coordinates = {{Coord|42.6473|-71.1323 |type:landmark_region:US|display=title}}<!--<ref name=satsig>{{cite web|title=Latitude and Longitude|url=http://www.satsig.net/maps/lat-long-finder.htm|publisher=satsig.net|accessdate=21 October 2013}}</ref>-->\n|pushpin_map = Massachusetts#USA\n|homepage = {{URL|http://www.andover.edu/}}\n}}\n'''Abbot Academy''' (also known as '''Abbot Female Seminary''' and '''AA''') was an [[University-preparatory school|independent boarding preparatory school]] for women boarding and day students in grades 9\u201312 from 1828 to 1973.<ref>NY Times, [https://www.nytimes.com/1886/03/31/archives/needs-of-the-abbot-academy-alumnae-trying-to-raise-150000-for-new.html NEEDS OF THE ABBOT ACADEMY.; ALUMNAE TRYING TO RAISE $150,000 FOR NEW BUILDINGS], Accessed August 10, 2013, \"...&nbsp;the female university at Andover, Mass\"</ref> Located in [[Andover, Massachusetts]], Abbot Academy was notable as one of the first incorporated secondary schools for educating young women in New England.<ref name=Townsman/><ref name = SusanLloyd>Susan McIntosh Lloyd, 1979, [http://eric.ed.gov/?id=ED177747 A Singular School: Abbot Academy, 1828-1973], Accessed Sept. 6, 2013, \u201c...&nbsp;One of the first educational institutions in New England to be founded for girls and women alone, Abbot had by far the longest corporate life of any&nbsp;...\u201d</ref> It merged with [[Phillips Academy]] in 1973<ref>Jonathan Phelps, Lawrence Eagle-Tribune, October 14, 2013, [http://www.eagletribune.com/local/x674145442/Addison-draws-attention-to-Innu-exhibit-with-large-banners Addison draws attention to Innu exhibit with large banners], Accessed Aug. 10, 2013</ref><ref>Amanda Bergeron, Boston Globe, Sept. 6, 2007, [http://www.boston.com/news/globe/obituaries/articles/2007/09/06/barbara_sisson_retired_teacher_active_in_arts/ Barbara Sisson, retired teacher active in arts], Accessed Aug. 10, 2013, \"...&nbsp;Abbot Academy, a boarding school for girls in Andover... 1973, when the school became part of Phillips Academy, Andover&nbsp;...\"</ref> and campus buildings along School Street continue to be used for the combined school. Some Abbot traditions continue at the combined private boarding school such as Parents' Weekend.<ref name=Salton>Alex Salton, thephilippianonline, October 26, 2009, [https://archive.is/20130811101616/http://www.phillipian.net/articles/parents-weekend-tradition-began-abbot-academy Parents\u2019 Weekend Tradition Began with Abbot Academy], Accessed Aug. 10, 2013.</ref> Since the 40th anniversary in 2013 of the merger of the two schools, there has been renewed interest in Abbot's history and traditions.<ref>\"Calling all Alumni from the late '60s to the late '70s!\" in ''Andover the Magazine of Phillips Academy'', Spring, 2013, p. 57.</ref>\n\n== History ==\n{| style=\"float:right; width:25em; font-weight:bold; border:solid 1px #999999; font-size:.9em; line-height:1.3em; margin:0 0 1em 1em;\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\"\n|-style=\"color:#000080; valign=\"top\"\n|Those persons who feel favorably disposed toward the establishment of a FEMALE HIGH SCHOOL in the South Parish of Andover, are requested to meet at Mr. James Locke's, on Tuesday evening next, the 19th inst., at 6 o'clock, P.M.\n|-\n|-font-size:.6em;\" align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"\n|Notice on trees and buildings around Andover, February 15, 1828. Source: Susan Lloyd<ref name = SingularSchool>Source: Susan M. Lloyd, 1979, [https://archive.org/stream/singularschoolab00lloy/singularschoolab00lloy_djvu.txt A Singular School: Abbot Academy, 1828-1973], Accessed Sept. 6, 2013</ref>\n|}\n[[File:SarahAbbotImage.jpg|thumb|Sarah Abbot]]\n[[File:Philena McKeen with Abbot Academy graduates 1864.jpg|thumb|Philena McKeen with graduates in 1864]]\n[[File:Abbot Academy outdoor drama production circa 1874 'Masque of the Flowers'.jpg|thumb|Students performing ''Masque of the Flowers'' circa 1874]]\n[[File:Abbot Academy students behind barrier between Abbot and Phillips Academy circa 1874.jpg|thumb|Students behind a fence separating them from Phillips Academy, circa 1874]]\n[[File:Abbot Academy students on a picnic in 1888.jpg|thumb|Picnic in 1888.]]\nThe school was founded during a time when the prevailing view was that women's education \"should always be relative to men\", with some believing that study of \"higher subjects\" such as [[philosophy]] and [[mathematics]] might render women to be infertile.<ref name = SingularSchool/> One of the first formal discussions to propose a school for young women happened on February 19, 1828.<ref name=NewEnglandMagazine>Annie Sawyer Downs, New England Magazine, 2011, [http://www.newenglandmagazine.com/the-new-england-magazine/vol1-no2jan-1886/abbot-academy/ Abbot Academy] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140302015737/http://www.newenglandmagazine.com/the-new-england-magazine/vol1-no2jan-1886/abbot-academy/ |date=March 2, 2014 }}, Accessed August 10, 2013.</ref> The school was incorporated in 1829 with 70<ref name = SusanLloyd/> or 85<ref name=NewEnglandMagazine/> pupils from eighteen to twenty years of age for the \"exclusive work of educating women\". According to one source, the official opening day was May 6, 1829.<ref name = SusanLloyd/>\n\n{{Quote|...to regulate the tempers, to improve the taste, to discipline and enlarge the minds and form the morals of youth...|Abbot Constitution, 1829<ref name=Townsman/>}}\n\n===The early years===\nThe school received financial support from Sarah Abbot who pledged substantial money, which allowed for loans to begin construction; Sarah Abbot died in 1850 and left a substantial sum for educational purposes.<ref name=NewEnglandMagazine/> After mid-century, Abbot faced several challenges: the addition of a public high school in Andover, followed by the challenges of coping with the [[American Civil War]].<ref name = SingularSchool/> In 1853, the first principalship was offered to a woman, and additional monies were raised for the construction of dormitories.<ref name=NewEnglandMagazine/> In 1859, the \"strong-willed\" but \"ideologically moderate\" McKeen sisters \u2014 headmistress Philena and Phebe\u2014exerted strong leadership by adopting a \"school-home\" approach.<ref name = SingularSchool/> The years were marked by substantial expansion of buildings.<ref name = SingularSchool/> The McKeens fostered the study of [[French language|French]] and [[German language|German]] and introduced a \"systematic oral language program\" on a par with that of [[Harvard University]] and which \"far outdistanced Phillips Academy\", which did not offer any modern language instruction until the mid 1870s.<ref name = SingularSchool/> Under their \"no-nonsense\" leadership, teachers stayed longer, many for ten or more years.<ref name = SingularSchool/>\n\n{{Quote|Abbot had always promised order, but the McKeen sisters delivered it in spades. They loved schedules. Up at 6:00, breakfast at 6:30, clean your room\u2014\u2014and perhaps a teacher's parlor as well. Though four Irish maids also helped out at $1.98 a week, the McKeens considered house work part of education ... Miss McKeen might ask a girl to help her change guest beds, questioning her the while on Butler's Analogy. Between 8:00 and 9:00 a.m. older students often climbed the Hill for a Geology lecture while younger ones did their daily calisthenics, but all must be on hand for the Devotions that formally opened the school day. Before mid-day dinner everyone wore gym suits with pantaloons, and skirts ten inches from the ground. ... Recitations continued till 3:30, then came Recreation Hours, with time for walking in pairs, studying, mending, croquet, or (after 1886) tennis. Supper followed; the evening was an alternation of study hours, \"half-hours\" for individual meditation ... and \"quarters\" for room-to-room visiting. Evening Devotions might mean anything from a hymn sing to a prayerful scolding. Bed at 10:00.|Susan McIntosh Lloyd, in ''A Singular School''<ref name = SingularSchool/>}}\n\nIt was during the late 1800s that the school had a \"golden age\", according to one view.<ref name=Townsman/> The campus was visited by luminaries such as [[Helen Keller]] and her teacher [[Anne Sullivan]] and [[Amos Bronson Alcott]].<ref name=Townsman/> The leadership of Philena and Phebe McKeen was characterized by substantial fundraising and growth.<ref name=Townsman/> According to Susan McIntosh Lloyd, Abbot's curriculum \"may have surpassed that of Phillips\" during these years.<ref name=Townsman/> After 1910, the only structures built were \"gates\".<ref name=Townsman/> The school was like a \"family\" but commanded by women, in which \"women and girls could enjoy one another as persons without self-consciousness or shame.\"<ref name = SingularSchool/>\n[[File:Helenkellerannesullivan1898.jpg|thumb|right|[[Helen Keller]] and her teacher [[Anne Sullivan]] both spoke at Abbot.]]\n[[File:Andover Massachusetts Phillips Academy Abbot campus Draper Hall with circle and tree.JPG|thumb|right|Draper Hall]]\n[[File:Andover Massachusetts Phillips Academy Abbot campus entranceway with Draper Hall in background.JPG|thumb|right|Merrill Memorial Gates (main entrance)]]\n[[File:Andover Massachusetts Phillips Academy Abbot campus building around circle.JPG|thumb|right|McKeen Memorial and Davis Hall]]\n{{Quote|Abbot's women and girls ... One thinks of Victorian women as confined, and so they were. They could not openly initiate friendship with boys or men; they were expected to hide their interest in sex or to subsume it within coquettish formulae, no matter how interested they really were. Partly because of this relative isolation from men, however, loving, lasting friendships between women could quietly thrive, modeled often on the close mother-daughter or sister-sister relationships that existed apart from men's affairs.|Susan McIntosh Lloyd, in ''A Singular School''<ref name = SingularSchool/>}}\n\n===Art education===\n\nThe academy emphasized art education. After starting a small art club in 1871 led by Professor E. A. Park, the academy introduced one of the nation's first ''History of Art'' courses in 1873.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |title= United States of America: Art Education |author=Douglas C. Allen |encyclopedia =[[Grove Art Online]] |accessdate =  }}</ref><ref name=\"Barker2000\">{{cite book|author=Deborah Barker|title=Aesthetics and Gender in American Literature: Portraits of the Woman Artist|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=C9PhiZTqmbUC&pg=PA213|year=2000|publisher=Bucknell University Press|isbn=978-0-8387-5408-5|pages=213\u2013}}</ref> Painting and drawing were taught by professional painter and alumnus<ref>Note: class of 1869</ref> Emily A. Means who had studied with well-known painters in Europe for four years.<ref name=\"Barker2000\"/><ref>{{cite book|title=Journal of Education|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tEohAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA268|year=1898|publisher=Boston University, School of Education|pages=268\u2013}}</ref> Means guided the art department from 1877 to 1892 and later served as principal from 1898 to 1911.<ref name=\"LeonardMarquis1910\">{{cite book|author1=John William Leonard|author2=Albert Nelson Marquis|title=Who's who in America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HiwzAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA2354|year=1910|publisher=Marquis Who's Who|pages=2354\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Kelsey1929\">{{cite book|author=Katharine Roxanna Kelsey|title=Abbot Academy Sketches, 1892-1912|url=https://archive.org/details/abbotacademysket00kels|year=1929|publisher=Houghton Mifflin}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|jstor = 42821783|title = Educational Intelligence|last = |first = |date = 11 May 1911|journal = Journal of Education|volume = 19|issue = 1829|pages = 526\u2013531|doi = |pmid = }}</ref>\n\n===The 1930s through the 1960s===\nThe school went through challenging times during the [[Great Depression]] of the 1930s.<ref name = SingularSchool/> In the Depression's first five years, the school lost approximately $60,000 annually as well as a sharp drop in its real-estate assets, and the school slipped from having 135 boarders in 1929\u201330 to 71 boarders in 1933\u201334.<ref name = SingularSchool/> Despite financial concerns, the school continued to dismiss \"unruly or lazy students\" or those who tucked \"dummies into their beds\" to spend the night at [[Phillips Academy]].<ref name = SingularSchool/> Many other schools folded during the Depression years.<ref name = SingularSchool/> During these years, the school taught the \"basic college preparatory\" program of 3 years of English, 5 years of languages (including 2 or 3 of Latin), 2 or 3 years of mathematics, 1 year of science and 1 year of history, as well as physical education, an \"all school choral class\" and Bible study of one hour a week, but requirements adjusted over time, largely dictated by preferences of college admissions departments.<ref name = SingularSchool/> From [[World War II]] and afterwards, the academy experienced increasing enrollment; ten years after the attack on Pearl Harbor, a third of its teachers were either European born or European educated.<ref name = SingularSchool/> The school opened its doors more widely to minority groups, such as [[African American]] women and [[Jews]].<ref name = SingularSchool/>\n\nAcademic excellence improved. An alumna, Elizabeth Thomas '49, recalled her Abbot teaching as \"the best she has ever had\", with college being easier.<ref name = SingularSchool/> However, during these years, there was a greater space between teachers and students, such that there were no \"out-of-class relationships\" between them; teachers seemed \"miles away\" unless they were enforcing rules about lipstick or patrolling the Phillips campus for errant women or checking mail for return addresses to \"certain Phillips boys.\"<ref name = SingularSchool/> Rules forbade smoking and drinking and sexual activity; one 1954 alumna described a \"whole system of deception\" designed to evade teachers, seen as \"the enemy,\" with deceptions done to get messages to Phillips students, sometimes through day student intermediaries or by messages left in bushes.<ref name = SingularSchool/>\n\n{{Quote|Why was the faculty so intent on having the school go on in that crazy old fashioned way? ... Abbot was the only place I'd heard of in 1949 where 1849 was still preserved.|Elizabeth Marshall, quoted in ''A Singular School''.<ref name = SingularSchool/>}}\n\nHowever, some students appreciated that the rules cleared \"time and space for that ''peaceful collection of self''\".<ref name = SingularSchool/> Nevertheless, applications to the school increased from the 1950s through the 1960s.<ref name = SingularSchool/> During the 1960s, the ratio of applicants to acceptances was three to one.<ref name = SingularSchool/> The 1960s featured rules easing somewhat, with more chaperoned dances, more phone calls and dating as well as \"cattle-market mixers\", but the easing sometimes encouraging girls to find \"ways to be still naughtier.\"<ref name = SingularSchool/> Lloyd described the coming changes:\n\n{{Quote|No school is an island: before 1960, every chapter of Abbot's story had been bound in some degree to the realities and dreams of the larger society. ... the old Abbot had made itself a place apart, especially after the McKeen sisters came, and it did its best to remain so through the early 1960s. During the final decade, the outside world beat upon Abbot's doors with such insistence that they must either be opened up or broken down. The Trustees opened them and the world rushed in like a clumsy repairman, knocking over tables and trampling valuable heirlooms, but also bringing fresh air into musty places, and piling on the floor a heap of lumber and tools with which to build anew.|Susan Lloyd, in ''A Singular School''.<ref name = SingularSchool/>}}\n\nAccording to Lloyd, Abbot Academy seemed to be a \"nineteenth century school\" which was stagnant and insular and limited in comparison with the abrupt societal changes made during the 1960s.<ref name = SingularSchool/> In 1967, there were greater ties between [[Phillips Academy]] and Abbot, including a Phillips-Abbot committee to explore a \"wide range of shared activities\" between the two schools.<ref name = SingularSchool/> Abbot trustee Philip Allen had determined that both schools should merge, but that this was a \"hidden agenda\"; Allen brought in headmaster Donald Gordon, a graduate of Phillips Academy and Yale, to bring \"Abbot up to the point where it could \nbe part of Phillips Academy.\"<ref name = SingularSchool/><ref name = SingularSchool/> Abbot's \"old dress code\" was abolished for a \"neat and clean\" requirement.<ref name = SingularSchool/> The 1969-70 year was \"tumultuous\" nationwide, with student revolts on many college campuses and foreign policy failures abroad.<ref name = SingularSchool/> The following is a description of Abbot campus life in 1969:<ref name = SingularSchool/>\n\n{{Quote|Touch football players romped on the sacred Circle. Not a saddle shoe was to be seen; indeed, one boy and two girls played with no shoes at all, in spite of November. Two pairs of faded blue jeans wandered by, one belted in macrame and filled by a man of bristling beard; he was discussing English papers with the other.|Susan Lloyd in ''A Singular School''<ref name = SingularSchool/>}}\n\n===The 1973 merger===\nThe late 1960s and early 1970s was marked by the merger between the two schools. The merger was brought about by many factors, including the sense of shared history and goals between the two schools, common activities, plus survey research showing that 94% of students in northeastern secondary schools wished for coeducation.<ref name = SingularSchool/> The times \"favored coeducation\"; in 1968, 53 colleges and universities either became coeducational or began coordinate instruction.<ref name = SingularSchool/> While Phillips Academy \"held the cards\" regarding whether the two schools should merge, there was a \"crasser impetus\" from admissions statistics, as Phillips was increasingly being turned down by applicants preferring newly-coeducational competitors such as St. Paul's, Taft, Northfield-Mount Hermon, and Exeter.<ref name = SingularSchool/> Many committee meetings, including discussions between administrators and teachers, happened over a sixteen-month period.<ref name = SingularSchool/> The Phillips headmaster, John Kemper, who had kinship ties with women graduates of Abbot, felt a merger was \"practical, ethical, and educationally sound\", although several times the Phillips Board of Trustees refused to sanction a merger.<ref name = SingularSchool/> The school merged with Phillips Academy on June 28, 1973.<ref name = SusanLloyd/> Many Abbot traditions were included in the combined school, such as having a designated weekend in the fall for parents to visit.\n\n{{Quote|Parents\u2019 Weekend was Abbot\u2019s response to formalize parent visits to the school. In the past, parents would visit the school on many different occasions. The event created one specific weekend for all parents to visit.|Tim Sprattler, 2009<ref name=Salton/>}}\n\n[[File:Abbot Academy students who graduated with the first Andover-Abbot co-educational class of 1974 at their 45th reunion.jpg|thumb|Abbot Academy students who were at the school during the Andover-Abbot merger gather at their 45th reunion. They were members of the first co-educational class of 1974, so they received Andover diplomas, but most came to the school as Abbot students.]]\nAfter the merger, $1 million of Abbot's endowment became the basis for the '''Abbot Academy Association''', which funds various educational programs and projects submitted by students, faculty, and staff.<ref>https://www.andover.edu/About/AbbotAcademyAssociation/Pages/GuidelinesforGrantProposers.aspx</ref><ref>[http://www.andover.edu/About/AbbotAcademyAssociation/Pages/default.aspx Abbot Academy Association]</ref><ref>February 1, 2013, Boston.com, [https://archive.is/20130811101541/http://momsevents.boston.com/andover_ma/events/show/303201527-andover-welcomes-best-selling-author-reza-aslan Andover Welcomes Best-selling Author Reza Aslan], Accessed Aug. 10, 2013, \"...funded by the Abbot Academy Association.\"</ref> Since the first Abbot Grant was awarded in the fall of 1973, nearly 2000 Abbot Grant proposals have been submitted by students and members of the faculty, staff and administration of Phillips Academy. The Abbot Academy Association has funded more than 1400 of these proposals with grants totaling $9,400,000.<ref>https://www.andover.edu/About/AbbotAcademyAssociation/GrantHistory/Pages/default.aspx</ref>  In 2014, the Abbot Academy Association's endowment had grown to $10 million.<ref name=\"LorenGary2\">Loren Gary, \"A Widening Circle: Abbot Academy and the Abiding Significance of Place\", Andover: Phillips Academy, 1997, p. 7.</ref>\n\n== Campus life==\nActivities included the Fidelio Chorus, school government, and the school newspaper. Athletic programs included basketball, crew,<ref>Note: through Phillips Academy</ref> cycling, ballet and modern dance, fencing, soccer, softball, and tennis. In the late 1960s, Abbot's math department set up a paper-tape terminal connected to a computer at [[Merrimack College]] in [[North Andover, Massachusetts]]. This provided the high school students with early BASIC-language computer programming skills. In 1973, the languages taught included English, French, German, Latin, Russian, and Spanish.<ref name=Forum2>\"The Abbot Forum\", Abbot Academy, 1973, p. 9.</ref>\n\n=== Academic prizes ===\nAbbot was a chapter member of the [[Cum Laude Society|Cum Laude Honor Society]]. The school awarded the following student prizes annually:<ref name=Forum4>The Abbot Forum\", Abbot Academy, 1973, pp. 36, 37.</ref>\n{{col-start}}\n{{col-break}}\n* Anna Dawes Prize for History\n* Betsy Waskowitz Rider Art Award\n* Beatrice Farnsworth Powers Art Award\n* Priscilla Bradley Prize for Art\n* Pam Weidenman Prize for Art\n* Ceramics Prize\n* Photography Prize\n* Music Department Award\n* Kate Friskin Award for Music\n{{col-break}}\n* Mathematics Department Prize\n* Science Prize\n* Spanish Department Prize\n* English Department Prize\n* Latin Department Prize\n* Ballet Prize\n* Abbot Athletic Award\n* Isabel Hancock Award\n{{col-end}}\n\nThe Madame Sarah Abbot award was established through a gift from the Abbot Class of 1973. The award is given to a female Phillips Academy senior who \" \u2026 best exemplifies 'strong character, effective leadership and outstanding scholarship.'\"<ref>''The Phillipian'', Vol. CV, No. 25, June 3, 1984, p. 1.</ref>\n\n===School publications===\nIn June 1873, the first issue of the ''Abbot Courant'' was published. This student literary magazine appeared two to three times a year.<ref name=Courant1>''The {{as written|Abbott}} Courant'', Vol. 1, No. 1, June 1873.</ref> Later editions included art work and photographs. In 1992, with a grant from the Abbot Academy Association, the ''Courant'' was revived at Phillips Academy and continues to be published twice a year. In 2002, a 123-page alumni edition was published.<ref name=CourantPA>''The COURANT, Alumni Edition: 10 Years'', Phillips Academy Andover, Fall 2002, p. [6].</ref> The Abbot Academy yearbook was published from 1900 to 1973. Originally known as ''The Abbot Academy Class Book'', the yearbook became ''The Circle'' in 1916 (this is the first year that the double-A logo used on senior class rings appeared on the book cover).<ref name=Circle1900>''Class Book: Published by the ... Senior Class of Abbot Academy, Andover, Massachusetts''.</ref><ref name=Circle1916>''The Abbot Circle Nineteen Hundred and Sixteen'', Senior Class of Abbot Academy, Andover, Massachusetts.</ref> Digital versions of the ''Abbot Courant'' and ''The Circle'' are available through the school Archives and Special Collections.<ref>[http://www.noblenet.org/paarchives/ Abbot Academy Archives and Special Collections: Phillips Academy Andover]</ref>\n\nThe student newspaper was called ''Cynosure''. In 1974, it moved to Phillips where it became a monthly magazine.<ref name=Forum3>\"The Abbot Forum\", Abbot Academy, 1973, p. 25.</ref>\n\n== Traditions ==\nStudents were divided into two groups called ''Gargoyles'' and ''Griffins'' for sports teams and for other purposes that required dividing the students into groups; their colors were green and orange, respectively.<ref>Susan McIntosh Lloyd. \"A Singular School: Abbot Academy 1828-1973\", p. 234.</ref> Dual-color felt beanie hats with an image of a gargoyle or griffin were distributed to students.\n\nThe locally based Clan MacPherson Pipes and Drums led graduation processions on the Abbot Circle.<ref>[http://clanmacpherson.org Clan MacPherson Pipes and Drums]</ref> This tradition continues today at Phillips Academy.<ref>\"Class of 2013 graduates from Phillips Academy\", http://www.andover.edu/about/newsroom/pages/commencement2013.aspx</ref> At graduation, after chapel, Seniors and Junior Middlers (eleventh graders) met in the Senior Courtyard for the Ring Ceremony. (This central garden was completely enclosed by the three sides of Draper Hall with the dining room wall as the fourth side.) By tradition, Junior Mids who purchased Abbot Academy class rings the year before wore them with the \"AA\" insignia upside-down. During the Ring Ceremony, each Junior Mid received a Senior sponsor. The Junior Mid, now recognized as a member of the new Senior class, turned her ring so that the insignia was upright. In 1973, all students who wanted to were allowed to buy Abbot class rings.<ref>''The Abbot Forum'', Vol. IV, Number 2, June 1973, p. 30.</ref>\n\n== Buildings and campus ==\n[[File:Abbot Academy proposed sketch 1829 buildings and grounds Andover Massachusetts.jpg|thumb|right|320px|The campus had three main buildings grouped around a circle, plus a gymnasium, a laundry, and several dormitories. The largest building was Draper Hall. This is the partially implemented 1886 plan by architects Hartwell and Richardson.<ref name=\"LorenGary1\">Loren Gary, \"A Widening Circle: Abbot Academy and the Abiding Significance of Place\", Andover: Phillips Academy, 1997, p. 14.</ref>]]\nIn 1863, the Abbot campus consisted of one acre surrounded by a fence. By 1878, it was approximately 22 acres.<ref>Susan J. Montgomery and Roger G. Reed. \"The Campus Guide. Phillips Academy Andover\", New York: Princeton Architectural Press, 2000. pp. 98\u20139.</ref> Abbot's three main buildings (Abbot Hall, Draper Hall, and McKeen Hall) are listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref name=\"LorenGary3\">Loren Gary, \"A Widening Circle: Abbot Academy and the Abiding Significance of Place\", Andover: Phillips Academy, 1997, p. 5.</ref> The first academy building, Abbot Hall, is an \"exceptional\" early example of the Greek Revival style. It was built in 1828\u201329.<ref>Quote from Montgomery and Reed. \"The Campus Guide. Phillips Academy Andover\", p. 103.</ref> Since 1996, it has housed Phillips Academy's Brace Center for Gender Studies.<ref>The Center was opened through the gift of Donna Brace Ogilvie, Class of 1930, \"History of the Brace Center\", http://www.andover.edu/Academics/BraceCenterforGenderStudies/Pages/History.aspx, Accessed Aug. 16, 2013.</ref> An art gallery was added to the left side of Abbot Hall in 1906\u201307. It was designed by [[Andrews, Jacques, & Rantoul]] of Boston. The art gallery housed the collection of Mrs. Esther Byers.<ref>Montgomery and Reed. \"The Campus Guide. Phillips Academy Andover\", p. 104.</ref> The Merrill Memorial Gates and two side gates (the John P. Taylor and George G. Davis gates) were added in 1921 to the front and sides, respectively, of the Abbot Circle. Designed a few years earlier by the firm of [[McKim, Mead & White]], similar gates appear at [[Harvard University]], [[Princeton University]], and [[Bowdoin College]].<ref>Montgomery and Reed. \"The Campus Guide. Phillips Academy Andover\", p. 102.</ref> The Abbot Circle, around which the main buildings are grouped, was re-dedicated on 3 May 1997.<ref name=\"LorenGary1\" /> The tree-lined Maple Walk, which once connected the dining room at the back of Draper Hall with Phillips Street, remains in use. (The dining room was demolished.)<ref>Gary, p. 12.</ref>\n\n== Headmasters and headmistresses ==\nSchool principals:<ref>[http://www.andover.edu/About/AbbotAcademyAssociation/AboutTheAssociation/Pages/AbbotAcademyPrincipals.aspx Abbot Academy Association]</ref>\n{{col-start}}\n{{col-break}}\n* Charles Goddard 1829\u201331\n* Rev. Samuel Lamson 1832\u201334\n* Rev. Samuel Gilman Brown 1835\u201338<ref name=Monroe1911>{{citation |editor=[[Paul Monroe]] |via=HathiTrust |title= Cyclopedia of Education |publisher=Macmillan |location=New York |year=1911 |url=http://hdl.handle.net/2027/uc2.ark:/13960/t1xd15h17?urlappend=%3Bseq=507 }} 1911-1913</ref>\n* Rev. Lorenzo Lorraine Langstroth 1838\u201339\n* Rev. Timothy Dwight Porter Stone 1839\u201342\n* Rev. Asa Farwell 1842\u201352\n* Peter Smith Byers 1853 (Elected but did not serve)\n* Nancy Judson Hasseltine 1854\u201356\n* Maria Jane Bancroft Brown 1856\u201357\n{{col-break}}\n* Emma L. Taylor 1857\u201359\n* Philena McKeen 1859\u201392\n* Laura Sophia Watson 1892\u201398\n* Emily Adams Means 1898\u20131911\n* Bertha Bailey 1912\u201335\n* Marguerite Capen Hearsey 1936\u201355\n* Mary Hinckley Crane (Mrs. Alexander) 1955\u201366\n* Eleanor Tucker (Acting) 1966\u201368\n* Donald Gordon 1968\u201373\n{{col-end}}\n\nFor further information, consult ''The Philippian'':<ref>[http://issuu.com/phillipian/docs/cxxxv16_abbot_academy_principals \"Abbot Academy Principals\", ''The Phillipian'', Vol. cxxxv No. 16]</ref>\n\n== Distinguished alumnae and faculty==\n\n=== Notable alumnae ===\n[[File:Marsha Kazarosian Portrait 2009 2.jpg|thumb|right|Abbot alumna and lawyer [[Marsha Kazarosian]] represented one of the teenaged defendants in the 1990 [[Pamela Smart]] murder case.]]\n[[File:Priscilla Martel.jpg|thumb|Chef [[Priscilla Martel]] cooked for ''[[60 Minutes]]'' reporter [[Morley Safer]] and Chef [[Jacques Pepin]] at her home in [[Connecticut]].<ref name=twsOctN23>{{cite news\n |author= Elizabeth Maker\n |title= Connecticut at its Best; On an Open Fire, Much More Than Chestnuts\n |newspaper= New York Times\n |date= December 11, 2005\n |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2005/12/11/nyregion/connecticut-at-its-best-on-an-open-fire-much-more-than-chestnuts.html?pagewanted=all\n |accessdate= 2010-10-20\n}}</ref>]]\n* [[Julia Alvarez]] (1967) - Poet, novelist, essayist<ref name=\"Chase\">David Chase, \"Aunt Hattie: Telling Tales\", ''Andover the Magazine of Phillips Academy'', Winter, 2013, p. 19.</ref>\n* [[Julia Constance Fletcher]] - (1867)\n* [[Harriette Newell Woods Baker]] (1833) - Story book author<ref name=\"Chase\" />\n* [[Alice Stone Blackwell]] (1867) - Editor ''[[Woman's Journal]]'', activist, and translator<ref name=\"Long\" />\n* [[Anna Brackett]] - Philosopher, educator\n* [[Charlotte Emerson Brown]] - Clubwoman\n* [[Maria Susana Cummins]] (1845) - Author of international bestseller; domestic fiction writer<ref name=\"Long\">\"Notable Alumni: Long List\", Phillips Academy, http://www.andover.edu/About/NotableAlumni/LongList/Pages/1800s.aspx {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105222945/http://www.andover.edu/About/NotableAlumni/LongList/Pages/1800s.aspx |date=2013-11-05 }}, Accessed Aug. 23, 2013.</ref>\n* [[Wendy Ewald]] (1969) - Photographer and educator, MacArthur Fellowship winner<ref>\"Drop that Name!\", ''Andover Bulletin'', Winter 2004, p. 73.</ref>\n* [[Mary H. Graves]] - Unitarian minister, literary editor, writer<ref name=\"EatonEaton1896\">{{cite book|last1=Eaton|first1=Chester Williams|last2=Eaton|first2=Warren E.|title=Proceedings of the 250th Anniversary of the Ancient Town of Redding, Once Including the Territory Now Comprising the Towns of Reading, Wakefield, and North Reading: With Historical Chapters|url=https://archive.org/details/proceedingsof2501644eato|year=1896|publisher=Loring & Twombly|pages=[https://archive.org/details/proceedingsof2501644eato/page/199 199]\u2013}}</ref>\n* [[Marsha Kazarosian]] (PA 1974) - Attorney\n* [[Lucy R. Lippard]] (1954) - Art theorist<ref name=\"Chase\" />\n* [[Priscilla Martel]] (PA 1974) - Chef and cookbook author<ref>''Andover the Magazine of Phillips Academy'', Winter 2013, p. 53.</ref>\n* [[Sara Nelson]] (PA 1974) - Former editor-in-chief of ''Publishers Weekly''\n* [[Elizabeth Marshall Thomas]] (1949) - Anthropologist<ref name=\"Chase\" />\n* [[Elizabeth Stuart Phelps Ward]] (1858) - Early feminist author<ref name=\"Long\" />\n* [[Kate Douglas Wiggin]] (1873) - Author of ''Rebecca of Sunnybrook Farm''<ref>''Andover the Magazine of Phillips Academy'', Spring 2010, p. 41.</ref>\n* [[Francesca Woodman]] - Photographer<ref name=\"Long\" />\n\nFor additional alumnae, consult ''Notable Alumni: Long List'':<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.andover.edu/About/NotableAlumni/LongList/Pages/default.aspx |title=\"Notable Alumni: Long List\", Phillips Academy |access-date=2013-08-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130812074048/http://www.andover.edu/About/NotableAlumni/LongList/Pages/default.aspx |archive-date=2013-08-12 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\n=== Notable faculty ===\n* [[Emily Hale]], speech and drama, muse of [[T.S. Eliot]]\n* [[Maud Morgan]]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Hartwell and Richardson]] architects\n* [[Phillips Academy]]\n\n== Suggested reading ==\n* Susan McIntosh Lloyd. \"A Singular School: Abbot Academy 1828-1973\", Hanover, NH: Published by Phillips Academy, Andover, 1979.\n* Susan J. Montgomery and Roger G. Reed. \"The Campus Guide. Phillips Academy Andover\", New York: Princeton Architectural Press, 2000.\n* Philena McKeen (Headmistress) - author.\n* {{citation |title= Annual Report...1875-76 |year=1877 |author1= [[Massachusetts Board of Education]] |location=Boston |via= Internet Archive |chapterurl=https://archive.org/stream/annualreportofbo7576mass#page/285/mode/2up |chapter=Report on Academies: Abbot Female Academy |author2=George A. Walton }}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Abbot Academy}}\n* [http://www.noblenet.org/paarchives/ Abbot Academy Archives in Archives and Special Collections: Phillips Academy Andover]\n* [http://andoverhistorical.org/ Andover Historical Society]\n\n{{Phillips Academy}}\n\n[[Category:Boarding schools in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Andover, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Preparatory schools in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Private high schools in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:1829 establishments in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Girls' schools in Massachusetts]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toSara Nelson(link changed toSara Nelson (editor)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abbot_Academy"}
