{"title_page": "List of Phillips Academy alumni", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\nThe following is a list of notable past students of [[Phillips Academy]] (also known as Phillips Andover and Andover) and of the former Abbot Academy (Phillips became coeducational in 1973 by merging with its [[sister school]]). Andover alumni are sometimes called Old Phillipians.{{Citation needed|date=November 2009}}\n\n{{compact ToC|side=yes|top=yes|num=yes}}__NOTOC__\n\n==A==\n*[[Hafsat Abiola]], Nigerian political activist; winner of 1999 Women to Watch Award from the Association of Women's Development (graduated 1992)\n*[[Joseph Carter Abbott]], [[Union Army]] general; North Carolina congressman and lawyer\n*[[Ernie Adams (American football)|Ernie Adams]], Director of Football Research, New England Patriots (graduated 1971)\n*[[Chris Agee]], poet, essayist and editor living in Ireland (graduated 1974)\n*[[Wallace M. Alexander]] (1869-1939), heir, corporate director, philanthropist<ref>Allen L. Chickering, 'Wallace M. Alexander, 1869-1939', ''California Historical Society Quarterly'', Vol. 18, No. 4 (Dec., 1939), pp. 379-381 [https://www.jstor.org/discover/10.2307/25160849?uid=3737536&uid=2129&uid=2&uid=70&uid=4&sid=21104722658647]</ref>\n*[[Jonathan Alter]], senior editor and columnist at ''[[Newsweek]]'' (graduated 1975)<ref name=tws>{{cite news| author = Staff writer| title = Heffner Adds More Guests for Next Two WPAA Live Political Broadcasts| publisher = Phillips Academy| date = January 24, 2008| url = http://www.andover.edu/About/Newsroom/Pages/HeffnerAddsMoreGuestsforNextTwoWPAALivePoliticalBroadcasts.aspx| accessdate = 2009-08-15| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100604162109/https://www.andover.edu/About/Newsroom/Pages/HeffnerAddsMoreGuestsforNextTwoWPAALivePoliticalBroadcasts.aspx| archivedate = June 4, 2010}}</ref>\n*[[Julia Alvarez]], author (graduated 1967)\n*[[Adelbert Ames, Jr.]], scientist\n*[[Carl Andre]], minimalist artist (graduated 1953)\n*[[James T. Austin]], 22nd [[Massachusetts Attorney General]] (graduated 1794)\n\n==B==\n*[[Thomas J. Baldrige]]<!--note, some sources have \"Baldridge\"-->, Pennsylvania Attorney General and Superior Court President Judge (graduated 1892)\n*[[Sullivan Ballou]], [[Union Army|Union Soldier]] (graduated 1849)\n*[[Charles Barber (author)|Charles Barber]], author on mental health and psychiatric issues\n*[[John Barres]], current Roman Catholic [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Rockville Centre|Bishop of Rockville Centre]]\n*[[Robin Batteau]], composer, singer-songwriter (graduated 1969?)<ref>{{Cite web | title = Buskin & Batteau, Joyous Reprise | first1 = Richard | last1 = Cuccaro | url = http://acousticlive.com/acoustic_live/October_2009.html | work = Acoustic Live | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130508185548/http://acousticlive.com/acoustic_live/October_2009.html | archive-date=May 8, 2013 | quote = Robin's high school was the prep school at Andover, MA. | access-date = April 11, 2013 | url-status = dead}}</ref>\n*[[James Phinney Baxter]], former president of [[Williams College]] and Pulitzer Prize winner (graduated 1918)\n*[[Willow Bay]], CNN news anchor (graduated 1981)\n*[[Henry C. Beck III]], CEO [[The Beck Group]]<ref>{{cite journal | title = Phillips Bulletin, Phillips Academy, Andover, 2003-2004 | journal = Phillips Bulletin | via = [[Mocavo]] | date = 2004 | volume = 97-98 | page = 531 | url = http://www.mocavo.com/Phillips-Bulletin-Phillips-Academy-Andover-2003-2004-Volume-97-98/763361/531|access-date=June 22, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304115420/http://www.mocavo.com/Phillips-Bulletin-Phillips-Academy-Andover-2003-2004-Volume-97-98/763361/531 | archive-date = March 4, 2016 | url-status = dead}}</ref> (graduated 1973)\n*[[Bruce Beemer]], former Pennsylvania Attorney General and current Pennsylvania Inspector General (graduated 1987)\n*[[Bill Belichick]], coach of New England Patriots (graduated 1971)\n*[[James Bell (New Hampshire)|James Bell]], New Hampshire politician and lawyer\n*[[Charles R. Bentley]], glaciologist and geophysicist\n*[[John Berman]], [[CNN]] senior news anchor and journalist (graduated 1990)\n*[[Michael Beschloss]], historian (graduated 1973)\n*[[Hiram Bingham III]], archaeologist; rediscovered ruins of [[Machu Picchu]] (graduated 1894)\n*[[David B. Birney]], Union General in the American Civil War\n*[[H. G. Bissinger|H.G. \"Buzz\" Bissinger]], author of ''[[Friday Night Lights: A Town, a Team and a Dream|Friday Night Lights]]'' and Pulitzer Prize\u2013winning journalist (graduated 1972)\n*[[Les Blank]], award-winning independent documentary filmmaker (graduated 1954)\n*[[Humphrey Bogart]], actor (attended 1918; expelled)\n*[[Paul Bremer]], diplomat notable for his role as Administrator of the [[Coalition Provisional Authority]] of Iraq following the 2003 invasion (graduated 1959)\n*[[Johnny Broaca]], professional baseball player\n*[[Richard H. Brodhead|Richard Brodhead]], president of [[Duke University]] (graduated 1964)\n*[[John Horne Burns]], author (graduated 1933)\n*[[Edgar Rice Burroughs]], author (student until 1894, then transferred to [[Michigan Military Academy]])\n*[[George H. W. Bush]], 41st U.S. President (graduated 1942)\n*[[George W. Bush]], 43rd U.S. President (graduated 1964)<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.bushchildhoodhome.org/family_history | title = History and research | website = George W. Bush Childhood Home | access-date = October 29, 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Jeb Bush]], Governor of Florida (graduated 1971)\n\n==C==\n*[[Norman Cahners]], publisher and athlete; qualified for 1936 Olympics but boycotted because games were held in Nazi Germany\n*[[Jonathan G. Callahan]], former Wisconsin assemblyman\n*[[Johnson N. Camden Jr.]], former [[United States]] [[Senator]] from [[Kentucky]]\n*[[Isaac N. Carleton]], educator and a president of the [[American Institute of Instruction]] (graduated 1855)\n*[[Lincoln Chafee]], former Rhode Island senator (graduated 1971)\n*[[Otis Chandler]], former publisher of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' (graduated 1946)\n*[[Chang Hee-jin]], South Korean Olympic swimmer (graduated 2005)\n*[[Thomas Chapin]], jazz saxophonist\n*[[Sarah Chayes]], expert in religious studies and former [[Kandahar]] field director (graduated 1980)\n*[[Susan Chira]], editor, ''[[The New York Times]]'' (graduated 1976)\n*[[George M. Church]], professor of genetics, Harvard Medical School; pioneer of human genetics (graduated 1972)<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://arep.med.harvard.edu/gmc/ |title = GMC}}</ref>\n*[[Sloane Citron]], magazine publisher (graduated 1974)\n*[[Stephen Carlton Clark]], art collector and philanthropist; founder of the [[Baseball Hall of Fame]] (graduated 1899?)\n*[[Christian Clemenson]], Emmy Award-winning film and television actor (graduated 1976)<ref>{{cite web | title=Christian Clemenson Biography | url=http://www.abcmedianet.com/web/showpage/showpage.aspx?program_id=001654&type=clemenson | publisher=ABC Medianet | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20081120080651/http://www.abcmedianet.com/web/showpage/showpage.aspx?program_id=001654&type=clemenson | archivedate = November 20, 2008}}</ref>\n*[[Harlan Cleveland]], [[United States Permanent Representative to NATO|U.S. Ambassador to NATO]] under President Lyndon B. Johnson (graduated 1934)\n*[[Olivia Coffey]], won the gold medal in the [[quad sculls]] at the [[2015 World Rowing Championships]] as well as competed in [[2016 Summer Olympics]] & [[The Boat Race 2018]].\n*[[Raymond C. Clevenger]], judge for the [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit]] (graduated 1955)\n*[[Thomas Cochran (banker)|Thomas Cochran]], banker and philanthropist to Phillips Academy (graduated 1890)\n*[[William Sloane Coffin]], reverend and peace activist (graduated 1942)\n*[[Donald B. Cole]], instructor in history and dean of Phillips Exeter Academy (graduated 1940)\n*[[Frank Converse]], actor (graduated 1956)\n*[[Michael Copley]], musician\n*[[Joseph Cornell]], sculptor (graduated 1921)\n*[[Justin Cronin]], author (graduated 1980)\n*[[Bill Cunliffe]], Grammy Award-winning composer, arranger, and jazz pianist (graduated 1974)<ref name=twsJun7c>{{cite news\n |title= Grammy Awards: List of Winners: Music |newspaper= The New York Times |quote= Instrumental Arrangement ... \u201cWest Side Story Medley,\u201d Bill Cunliffe |date= January 31, 2010 |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2010/02/01/arts/music/01grammylist.html?pagewanted=all |accessdate= 2010-06-07}}</ref>\n*[[Peter Currie (businessman)|Peter Currie]], Netscape executive, investor, and charter trustee of Phillips Academy (graduated 1974)<ref name=twsOctE11>{{cite news |title= Yu, Zuckerberg and the Facebook fallout |work= Reuters |quote= In a back-to-the-future move, former Netscape CFO Peter Currie will be the key adviser to Facebook about financial matters |date= Apr 1, 2009 |url= http://blogs.reuters.com/mediafile/2009/04/01/yu-zuckerberg-and-the-facebook-fallout/ |accessdate= 2010-10-14}}</ref><ref name=twsOctEfassf>{{cite magazine |author= Executive profile |title= Currie Capital LLC |magazine= Bloomberg Businessweek |quote= Mr. Peter L. S. Currie is the President at Currie Capital LLC |year= 2010 |url= http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=87505&privcapId=23090617&previousCapId=19153&previousTitle=Benchmark%20Capital |accessdate= 2010-10-14}}</ref>\n\n==D==\n*[[William Damon]], author, psychologist, and [[Stanford University]] educator (graduated 1963)\n*[[Lucy Danziger]], editor-in-chief of ''[[Self (magazine)|Self]]'' magazine (graduated 1978)\n*[[John Darnton]], Pulitzer Prize-winning foreign correspondent for the ''[[New York Times]]'' (graduated 1960)\n*[[Robert Darnton]], historian (graduated 1957)\n*[[Benjamin Darrow]], New York district attorney (graduated 1879)\n*[[Justin Whitlock Dart, Jr.]], advocate for the rights of disabled people (graduated 1949)\n*[[Jonathan Dee]], author (graduated 1980)\n*[[Dana Delany]], actress (graduated 1974)\n*[[Zak DeOssie]], professional football player for the [[New York Giants]]; Super Bowl-winning long snapper (graduated 2003)\n*[[Norman Dodd]], banker, financial adviser and head Investigator for the [[Reece Committee]] (graduated 1918) <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.andover.edu/about/notablealumni/longlist/Pages/1900s.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-04-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407080817/http://www.andover.edu/about/notablealumni/longlist/pages/1900s.aspx |archivedate=2014-04-07 }}</ref>\n*[[Tim Draper]], American [[venture capital]] investor and founder of [[Draper Fisher Jurvetson]] (DFJ)\n*[[Warren Fales Draper (publisher)|Warren Fales Draper]], publisher, educator, and philanthropist; significant donor to Phillips Academy; namesake of Draper Hall and Draper Cottage (graduated 1843)\n*[[Bill Drayton]], entrepreneur, coined the phrase \"[[social entrepreneur]]\"\n*[[Charles Duits]], writer<ref>{{cite book | last = Duits | first = Charles | title = La vie le fard de Dieu | publisher = Le bois d'Orion| year = 1994| url = }}</ref>\n*[[Teddy Dunn]], actor (graduated 1999)\n\n==E==\n*[[Carol Edgarian]], author (graduated 1980)\n*[[Alonzo Elliot]], composer\n*[[Trey Ellis]], novelist, screenwriter (graduated 1980)\n*[[Sam Endicott]], singer-songwriter and vocalist for ''The Bravery'' (graduated 1992)<ref name=twsOctQXakj>{{cite news\n |title       = Notable alumni -- long list\n |publisher   = Phillips Academy\n |quote       = Sam Endicott -- Singer-songwriter & instrumentalist; a founder & lead vocalist for The Bravery; record and music video director & producer\n |year        = 1992\n |url         = http://www.andover.edu/about/notablealumni/longlist/Pages/1900s.aspx\n |accessdate  = 2010-10-08\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20140407080817/http://www.andover.edu/about/notablealumni/l