d head Investigator for the [[Reece Committee]] (graduated 1918) <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.andover.edu/about/notablealumni/longlist/Pages/1900s.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-04-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407080817/http://www.andover.edu/about/notablealumni/longlist/pages/1900s.aspx |archivedate=2014-04-07 }}</ref>\n*[[Tim Draper]], American [[venture capital]] investor and founder of [[Draper Fisher Jurvetson]] (DFJ)\n*[[Warren Fales Draper (publisher)|Warren Fales Draper]], publisher, educator, and philanthropist; significant donor to Phillips Academy; namesake of Draper Hall and Draper Cottage (graduated 1843)\n*[[Bill Drayton]], entrepreneur, coined the phrase \"[[social entrepreneur]]\"\n*[[Charles Duits]], writer<ref>{{cite book | last = Duits | first = Charles | title = La vie le fard de Dieu | publisher = Le bois d'Orion| year = 1994| url = }}</ref>\n*[[Teddy Dunn]], actor (graduated 1999)\n\n==E==\n*[[Carol Edgarian]], author (graduated 1980)\n*[[Alonzo Elliot]], composer\n*[[Trey Ellis]], novelist, screenwriter (graduated 1980)\n*[[Sam Endicott]], singer-songwriter and vocalist for ''The Bravery'' (graduated 1992)<ref name=twsOctQXakj>{{cite news\n |title       = Notable alumni -- long list\n |publisher   = Phillips Academy\n |quote       = Sam Endicott -- Singer-songwriter & instrumentalist; a founder & lead vocalist for The Bravery; record and music video director & producer\n |year        = 1992\n |url         = http://www.andover.edu/about/notablealumni/longlist/Pages/1900s.aspx\n |accessdate  = 2010-10-08\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20140407080817/http://www.andover.edu/about/notablealumni/longlist/pages/1900s.aspx\n |archivedate = 2014-04-07\n}}</ref>\n*[[David Ensor (journalist)|David B. Ensor]], CNN correspondent (graduated 1969)\n*[[Walker Evans]], photographer (graduated 1922)\n\n==F==\n*[[Charles Finch]], author (graduated 1998)\n*[[Charles B. Finch]], businessman and political activist\n*[[Tom Finkelpearl]], NYC commissioner of cultural affairs (graduated 1974)<ref>''Andover'' magazine, [http://issuu.com/phillipsacademy/docs/andovermagazinespring2014/56 The Buzz], Retrieved July 3, 2015 (see fourth column, middle)</ref>\n*[[Paul Finnegan]] co-founder of [[Madison Dearborn Partners]](graduated 1971)<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://harvardmagazine.com/2013/11/cross-country-by-ski |title = Cross-country by Ski|date = October 15, 2013}}</ref>\n*[[David Fishelson]], Broadway producer, playwright, filmmaker (graduated 1974)\n*[[Charles L. Flint]], lawyer, educator, first Secretary of the Massachusetts Board of Agriculture, fourth president of the [[University of Massachusetts Amherst|University of Massachusetts]] and one of its original founders (graduated 1854)\n*[[Thomas C. Foley]], former U.S. Ambassador to Ireland (graduated 1971)\n*[[John Murray Forbes]], railroad entrepreneur and philanthropist who re-established [[Milton Academy]]\n*[[Theodore J. Forstmann]], billionaire businessman and philanthropist\n*[[Hollis Frampton]], avant-garde filmmaker, photographer, and theoretician (attended 1951 to 1954; never received diploma)\n*[[Peter Franchot]], State Comptroller of Maryland\n*[[Andy Frankenberger]], poker champion\n*[[Ziwe Fumudoh]], comedian (graduated 2010)\n\n==G==\n*[[Robert A. Gardner (golfer)|Robert A. Gardner]], two-time [[U.S. Amateur]] golf champion\n*[[Jeffrey Garten]], dean of the [[Yale School of Management]] (graduated 1964)\n*[[Isaac Wheeler Geer]], railroad executive\n*[[A. Bartlett Giamatti]], president of [[Yale University]] and seventh Major League Baseball Commissioner (graduated 1956)\n*[[Stephanie Gosk]], journalist and correspondent for NBC News (graduated 1990)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://phillipsacademy.smugmug.com/StudentLife/2017-18/Stephanie-Gosk-90-at-ASM/ |title = Stephanie Gosk '90 at ASM |website=The Official Photo Galleries of Andover |accessdate=28 October 2019}}</ref>\n*[[David Graeber]], professor of anthropology; anarchist\n*[[Anthony Grafton]], noted scholar (graduated 1967)\n*[[Glenn H. Greenberg]], Managing Director and Founder of Brave Warrior Advisors\n*[[Richard Theodore Greener]], first African-American to graduate from [[Harvard College]] (graduated 1865)\n*[[G. Lauder Greenway]], Chairman, [[Metropolitan Opera Association]], and Director, [[New York Philharmonic]]. Long time companion of [[Ailsa Mellon Bruce]] (graduated 1925 [Bachelor], 1930 [PhD])\n*[[James Greenway]], Curator, [[Museum of Comparative Zoology]] at [[Harvard University]], renowned [[Ornithologist]], Lt. Commander [[U.S. Navy]], Intelligence Officer with the [[Office of Naval Intelligence]] (graduated 1926)\n*[[John Campbell Greenway]], General, [[U.S. Army]], [[Rough Riders|Rough Rider]], Intelligence officer with the [[Office of Naval Intelligence]], Mining Magnate (graduated 1895 [PhB])\n*[[David L. Gunn]], former president of [[Amtrak]] (graduated 1955)\n*[[Philip F. Gura]], William S. Newman Distinguished Professor of American Literature and Culture, [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]] (graduated 1968)\n\n==H==\n* [[Roderick Stephen Hall]], OSS agent murdered by the SS in February 1945 (graduated 1934)<ref name=\"Hall\" >{{cite web |url=https://www.cia.gov/news-information/featured-story-archive/2010-featured-story-archive/oss-heroes-stephen-hall.html |title=Roderick Stephen Hall: The Saboteur of Brenner Pass|publisher=[[Central Intelligence Agency]] |date= 30 September 2010|website= |access-date=12 September 2018 |language=German |trans-title=}}</ref>\n*[[Garnet Hathaway]], ice hockey forward for the NHL\u2019s Washington Capitals (graduated 2010)\n*[[Peter Halley]], artist (graduated 1971)\n*[[George Hamlin]], tenor; Victor recording artist 1905\u20131916 (class of 1889)<ref name=twsAprF>{{cite news\n |title        = About -- 1800s\n |publisher    = Andover\n |quote        = Tenor; Victor recording artist [1905-1916]\n |date         = 2011-04-06\n |url          = http://www.andover.edu/about/notablealumni/longlist/Pages/1800s.aspx\n |accessdate   = 2011-04-06\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20131105222945/http://www.andover.edu/About/NotableAlumni/LongList/Pages/1800s.aspx\n |archive-date = 2013-11-05\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref>\n*[[Julian Hatton]], abstract landscape artist (graduated 1974)\n*[[Brian Henson]], president of Jim Henson Productions (graduated 1982)\n*[[Frank Lauren Hitchcock]], MIT mathematician (graduated 1892?)\n*[[Oliver Wendell Holmes, Sr.]], author (graduated 1825)\n*[[Fred A. Howland]], [[Secretary of State of Vermont]] and President of [[National Life Insurance Company]] (graduated 1883)<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Smith |first=Arthur L. J. |date=January 20, 1916 |title=President F. A. Howland: New Executive Head of the National Life of Montpelier; Succeeding the Late J. A. De Boer |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hfMgAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA46 |magazine=The Spectator: An American Weekly Review of Insurance |location=New York, NY |publisher=The Spectator Company |page=34}}</ref>\n*[[Thomas J. Hudner, Jr.]], U.S. Navy officer and [[Medal of Honor]] recipient (graduated 1943)\n*[[Chris Hughes]], co-founder of [[Facebook]]; publisher and editor-in-chief of ''[[The New Republic]]'' (graduated 2002)\n*[[Angela Hur]], author (graduated 1998)<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Class Notes, Class of 1998|date=Spring\u2013Summer 2007|accessdate=2008-03-14|last=Niarchos|first=Zoe|publisher=Phillips Academy|url=http://www.alumniconnections.com/olc/pub/PAA/cpages/chapterpage.jsp?chapter=38&org=PAA|postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref>\n\n==I==\n*[[Robert S. Ingersoll|Robert Ingersoll]], former [[United States Deputy Secretary of State]] under Presidents Richard Nixon and Gerald Ford (graduated 1933)\n\n==J==\n*[[Thomas H. Jackson]], former president of the [[University of Rochester]] (graduated 1968)\n*[[Clay Johnson III]], deputy director of the [[United States Office of Management and Budget]] (graduated 1964)\n*[[Osgood Johnson]], 5th Principal of Phillips Academy (graduated 1823)\n\n==K==\n*Stefan Kaluzny, co-founder of [[Sycamore Partners]], (graduated 1984)<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.andover.edu/news/2017/four-new-trustees-appointed-to-phillips-academy-board | title=Four new trustees appointed to Phillips Academy Board| date=October 21, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Peter Kapetan]] (1956\u20132008), Broadway actor, singer, and dancer (graduated 1974)<ref name=twsNovV12>{{cite news\n |title= In Memoriam\n |publisher= Northwestern University\n |quote= Peter Kapetan (C78), 51, New York City, June 4. An actor, singer and dancer, Mr. Kapetan enjoyed a theater career that spanned almost three decades. He most recently appeared on Broadway in The Wedding Singer as a Ronald Reagan impersonator and ensemble member...\n |date= Winter 2008\n |url= http://www.northwestern.edu/magazine/winter2008/alumninews/inmemoriam.html\n |accessdate= 2010-11-22\n}}</ref>\n* [[Marsha Kazarosian]], trial attorney (graduated 1974)<ref name=tws2W24>{{cite news\n |title= Peers elect Kazarosian state bar secretary\n |work= The Haverhill Gazette\n |quote= ... Marsha V. Kazarosian has been elected secretary of the Massachusetts Bar Association ... She is a graduate of Phillips Academy in Andover....\n |date= September 9, 2010\n |url= http://www.hgazette.com/business/x192548612/Peers-elect-Kazarosian-state-bar-secretary\n |accessdate= 2012-03-23\n}}</ref>\n* [[R. Crosby Kemper Jr.]], American banker and philanthropist, namesake of the [[Kemper Museum of Contemporary Art]]\n* [[Charles West Kendall]], U.S. Representative, lawyer, and newspaper editor\n* [[John F. Kennedy, Jr.]], publisher, son of former U.S. president John F. Kennedy (graduated 1979)\n* [[Max Kennedy]], author (expelled)<ref>{{cite book | url=https://archive.org/details/reflections00bush | url-access=registration | page=[https://archive.org/details/reflections00bush/page/236 236] | quote=andover max kennedy. | title=Reflections: Life After the White House | publisher=Scribner | date=October 12, 2004 | accessdate=11 January 2019 | author=Barbara Bush| isbn=9780743255820 }}</ref> \n* [[Patrick J. Kennedy]], former U.S. Representative from Rhode Island (graduated 1986)\n* [[Vanessa Kerry]], physician and health care administrator who founded the non-profit, [[Seed Global Health]], daughter of [[John Kerry]]. \n* [[Rahim Aga Khan|Prince Rahim Aga Khan]], son of the [[Aga Khan IV]] (graduated 1990)\n* [[Victor Kiam|Victor K. Kiam]], businessman and owner of the [[New England Patriots]] (graduated 1944)\n* [[Brian Kibler]], game designer and professional ''[[Magic: the Gathering]]'' player\n* [[Tracy Kidder]], Pulitzer Prize winner for ''Soul of the New Machine'' (graduated 1963)<ref>{{cite web | title=Phillips Academy - Notable Alumni - Literature, Publishing & Journalism | url=http://wwwdev.andover.edu/About/Notable%20Alumni/Pages/LiteraturePublishingJournalism.aspx | publisher=Phillips Academy | year=2009 | accessdate=2009-06-10 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://archive.is/20090620014733/http://wwwdev.andover.edu/About/Notable%20Alumni/Pages/LiteraturePublishingJournalism.aspx | archivedate=2009-06-20 }}</ref>\n* Earl Killian, computer scientist with over 25 patents (graduated 1974)<ref name=twsNovZ95d>{{cite news\n |title= Technical Advisory Board\n |publisher= Stretch\n |quote= Earl has many areas of expertise including computer architecture, DSP, compilers, operating systems and networking. He is the former Chief Architect of Tensilica and Silicon Graphics MIPS division, and Co-founder of QED (acquired by PMC-Sierra). As one of the original architects of the MIPS processor and the microarchitect of the Tensilica processor, he assists Stretch in its processor direction. With a plethora of patents and publications and his deep knowledge of the semiconductor industry, Earl is a true asset to the TAB.\n |date= 2010-11-26\n |url= http://www.stretchinc.com/corporate/board.php\n |access