tress<ref>{{cite news | last = Vilkomerson | first = Sara | title = Wilde At Heart | newspaper = [[The New York Observer]] | date = April 11, 2007 | url = http://www.observer.com/2007/wilde-heart |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071211231244/http://www.observer.com/2007/wilde-heart |access-date=October 29, 2019 |archive-date=December 11, 2007 | url-status = dead}}</ref>\n* [[Dick Wolf]], Emmy Award-winning television producer of ''[[Miami Vice]]'' and ''[[Law & Order franchise|Law & Order]]''\n* [[Dudley Wolfe]], yachtsman, skier and mountaineer (asked to leave 1916)<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Jordan | first1 = Jennifer | title = The last man on the mountain : the death of an American adventurer on K2 | pages = [https://archive.org/details/lastmanonmountai00jenn/page/33 33\u201334] | date = 2010 | publisher = [[W. W. Norton & Company]] | isbn = 9780393077780 | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/lastmanonmountai00jenn/page/33 }}</ref>\n* [[Francesca Woodman]], photographer\n* [[Leonard Woods (college president)|Leonard Woods]], fourth president of [[Bowdoin College]]\n* [[Christopher A. Wray]], [[Director of the Federal Bureau of Investigation|Director of the FBI]]<ref name=HeavyWray>{{cite web | title = Christopher Wray: 5 Fast Facts You Need to Know | last = Cleary | first = Tom | website = [[Heavy.com]] | date = May 30, 2017 | url = https://heavy.com/news/2017/05/christopher-chris-wray-ray-fbi-director-us-attorney-comey-bio/ |access-date= June 8, 2017}}</ref><ref name=GuardianWray>{{cite news | title = Who is Christopher Wray, Trump's pick to replace Comey as FBI director? | last1 = Beckett | first1 = Lois | last2 = Swaine | first2 = Jon | newspaper = [[The Guardian]] | date = June 7, 2017 | url = https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2017/jun/07/christopher-wray-donald-trump-fbi-director-james-comey |access-date= June 8, 2017}}</ref><ref name=NYTWrayMarriage>{{cite news | title = Helen G. Howell Weds C. A. Wray | newspaper = [[The New York Times]] | date = August 13, 1989 | url = https://www.nytimes.com/1989/08/13/style/helen-g-howell-weds-c-a-wray.html |access-date= June 8, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Philip K. Wrigley]], manufacturer of Wrigley's Chewing Gum (graduated 1915)\n* [[Timothy Wynter]], competed in the [[2016 Summer Olympics]].\n\n==Y==\n*[[Tachi Yamada]], president of the Global Health Program, [[Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation]] (graduated 1963)<ref name=twsNovA55>{{cite news\n |author= Adam Bryant (interviewer), Adam Bryant\n |title= Talk to Me. I'll Turn Off My Phone.\n |newspaper= The New York Times\n |quote= This interview with Tachi Yamada, M.D., president of the Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation\u2019s Global Health Program, ... His outlook was always international. Very early, he sent me to the United States. I was 15. He sent me to a boarding school, Andover.\n |date= February 27, 2010\n |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2010/02/28/business/28corner.html\n |accessdate= 2010-11-01\n}}</ref>\n*[[Jesse Colin Young]], musician (expelled)\n\n==Z==\n*[[Dan Zanes]], member of ''[[The Del Fuegos]]''; celebrated children's music writer (graduated 1979)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20091020043357/http://wwwdev.andover.edu/About/Notable%20Alumni/Pages/default.aspx List of Alumni from Andover.edu]\n\n{{Phillips Academy}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of grade school alumni in Massachusetts|Phillips Academy]]\n[[Category:Phillips Academy alumni|*]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toSara Nelson(link changed toSara Nelson (editor)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Phillips_Academy_alumni"}
{"title_page": "Ore Oduba", "text_new": "[[File:Ore Oduba.jpg|thumb|Ore Oduba in Noughts + Crosses]]\n'''Ore Oduba'''  (born 17 November 1985)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/profiles/4PM8ZqC3Pd5swPd2DFCc8n1/ore-oduba|title=Strictly Come Dancing - Ore Oduba - BBC One|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=17 December 2016}}</ref><ref name=BBCNewsR>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/cbbcnews/hi/newsid_7550000/newsid_7556400/7556408.stm |publisher=BBC News |title=All about Ore |date=12 August 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2016-11-19/who-is-ore-oduba-strictly-come-dancing-2016-contestant-guide|title=Who is Ore Oduba? Strictly Come Dancing 2016 contestant guide|work=Radio Times|accessdate=17 December 2016}}</ref> is a British television and radio presenter and musical theatre actor, best known for winning the [[Strictly Come Dancing (series 14)|fourteenth series]] of [[BBC One]]'s ''[[Strictly Come Dancing]]'' in 2016.\n\nHe presented the [[BBC]] children's news programme ''[[Newsround]]'' from 2008 until 2013. In 2018 he hosted the game show ''[[And They're Off!]]'' in aid of [[Sport Relief]]. Oduba also presents the BBC One game show ''Hardball''.\n\nIn 2019 he began a musical theatre career, starring in the UK Tour of [[Grease (musical)|Grease]]. He also starred alongside [[Jason Manford]] in [[Curtains (musical)|Curtains the Musical]]. He made his West End debut in January 2020. \n\n==Early life and education==\nOduba was born in [[London]] to [[British Nigerian|Nigerian]] parents. He was educated at [[Dumpton School]], then [[Canford School]], a [[co-educational]] [[independent school]] for both boarding and day pupils in the village of [[Canford Magna]], near to the market town of [[Wimborne Minster]] in [[Dorset]], in southwest England.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Barber|first1=Marilyn|title=Strictly finalist Ore Oduba is a former pupil of Dumpton and Canford schools in Wimborne|url=http://www.blackmorevale.co.uk/strictly-finalist-ore-oduba-is-a-former-pupil-of-dumpton-and-canford-schools-in-wimborne/story-29980019-detail/story.html|accessdate=19 December 2016|publisher=Blackmore Vale|date=13 December 2016}}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He studied Sports Science and Social Science at [[Loughborough University]] and graduated in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lboro.ac.uk/alumni/news/2016/alumnus-ore-oduba-takes-to-the-strictly-stage.html|title=2016 - Alumnus Ore Oduba takes to the Strictly stage - Loughborough Alumni|publisher=Loughborough University|accessdate=17 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Career ==\nOduba had always aimed for a career in sports broadcasting,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ideastap.com/IdeasMag/the-knowledge/ore-oduba-interview|title=Ore Oduba, TV presenter|publisher=IdeasTap|accessdate=16 October 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170805104215/http://www.ideastap.com/IdeasMag/the-knowledge/ore-oduba-interview|archivedate=5 August 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> and initially joined [[The Network]], an [[Edinburgh]] television festival scheme.\n\nOduba joined ''[[Newsround]]'' in August 2008, following the departure of [[Lizo Mzimba]] and [[Laura Jones (journalist)|Laura Jones]]. His first role on the programme was as a reporter and breakfast bulletin presenter. He was quickly promoted to deputy presenter in 2009, filling in for main presenter [[Sonali Shah]] in her absence. In 2010, he joined Shah to begin presenting the main ''[[Newsround]]'' bulletin double-headed. This continued until Shah's departure in November 2011. He was later joined by reporters Leah Gooding and Hayley Cutts. As part of his role he also presented spin-off show ''[[Sportsround]]''. He became the main presenter in October 2008 when the show relaunched. He presented until its cancellation in 2010. The show was replaced by ''[[Match of the Day Kickabout]]'' which Oduba also presents. Oduba left ''Newsround'' in 2013.\n\nOduba formerly presented the sport for ''[[BBC Breakfast]]'' and [[BBC Radio 5 Live]]. He has also presented and reported on British Olympic Dreams along with former ''Newsround'' co-presenter Sonali Shah. Oduba began a debut presenting solo on the morning slot for the [[2014 Commonwealth Games]] on [[BBC One]] and [[BBC Sport]].\n\nOduba regularly appeared on CBBC studio presentation following his ''Newsround'' shift. He was also a guest on CBBC shows including ''[[Sam & Mark's TMi Friday]]'', ''[[Hacker Time]]'' and ''[[All Over the Place (TV series)|All Over the Place]]''.\n\nIn the lead up to the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] Oduba presented a programme called ''Ultimate Sports Day'' for CBBC. He also co-presents live cinema relays from the [[Royal Opera House]], [[Covent Garden]], with former [[ballerina]] [[Darcey Bussell]].\n\nOn 2 March 2013, Oduba and Sonali Shah appeared on the BBC's ''[[Let's Dance for Comic Relief]]'', dancing to ''[[Hey Ya!]]'' by ''[[Outkast]]''. They were eliminated and did not get through to the final.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/profiles/3mJ9xN6BvCZ3SyZ2641klvL/ore-sonali|title=Ore & Sonali|work=Let's Dance for Comic Relief|publisher=BBC One|accessdate=16 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe played the role of Nathan in ''[[Hacker Time]]'' on [[CBBC]]. Since 2015, he has guest presented numerous episodes of ''[[The One Show]]''.\n\nFrom 2015\u201316, he was a presenter on ''[[The National Lottery Draws]]'' on Saturday evenings and he presented the 2015 ''[[New Year Live]]'' programme on BBC One.\n\nFrom 7 March 2016, Oduba took part in a challenge for ''[[Sport Relief]]'', called \"Hell on High Seas\", in which he sailed 1,000 miles from [[Belfast]] to [[London]] with five other celebrities including [[Alex Jones (Welsh presenter)|Alex Jones]] and [[Suzi Perry]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportrelief.com/whats-going-on/hell-on-high-seas|title=Hell on High Seas|publisher=Sport Relief|accessdate=16 October 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018035619/http://www.sportrelief.com/whats-going-on/hell-on-high-seas|archivedate=18 October 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://home.bt.com/news/bt-life/x-11364043857543|title=Celebrity crew set sail around the UK for the BT Sport Relief Challenge: Hell on High Seas|publisher=BT|accessdate=16 October 2016}}</ref> In 2016, he also presented ''[[Sport Relief 2016|Sport Relief: Clash of the Titans]]'' with [[Dan Walker (broadcaster)|Dan Walker]]. He presented coverage of the [[2016 Summer Olympics]] on [[BBC Four]] throughout August 2016.\n\nBetween October 2012 and May 2017 he presented the daytime BBC One insurance fraud documentary programme ''Claimed and Shamed''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.curvemedia.com/claimed-and-shamed|title=Curve Media TV Production|publisher=Curve Media|accessdate=17 December 2016}}</ref> In November 2016, Oduba guest presented an episode of ''[[This Morning (TV programme)|This Morning]]'' with [[Holly Willoughby]] on [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]. He returned to present a second episode with Willoughby in March 2017 and a third with [[Davina McCall]] in February 2018.\n\nIn 2016 Oduba participated in the [[Strictly Come Dancing (series 14)|fourteenth series]] of ''[[Strictly Come Dancing]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/strictlycomedancing/entries/d77143c8-ab28-4040-ab06-c7728f685221|title=Presenting our fourth Strictly celebrity\u2026 Ore Oduba|date=11 August 2016|publisher=BBC|accessdate=16 October 2016}}</ref> where he was partnered with [[Joanne Clifton]]. The couple's [[American Smooth]] to \"[[Singin' in the Rain (song)|Singin' in the Rain]]\" won praise from Patricia Ward, widow of [[Gene Kelly]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/national/article/Widows-praise-for-Strictlys-Ore-Oduba-like-blessing-from-Gene-Kelly-himself-f7f08fe7-3600-42dd-821b-3af4688cf5bc-ds|title=Widow's praise for Strictly's Ore Oduba like 'blessing from Gene Kelly himself'|work=North West Evening Mail|date=13 October 2016|accessdate=17 December 2016}}</ref> In the fourth week the couple were awarded a score of 39 points out of 40 for their [[Jive (dance)|jive]] to \"[[Runaway Baby]]\" by [[Bruno Mars]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/stayingin/tvfilm/strictly-come-dancing-2016-ore-oduba-receives-first-10s-of-the-series-as-daisy-lowes-sexy-rumba-a3370231.html%5B|title=Ore Oduba receives first 10s of this year's Strictly Come Dancing for 'jaw-dropping' jive|date=15 October 2016 |work=London Evening Standard |accessdate=16 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/strictly-come-dancing-ore-oduba-first-ten_uk_58033742e4b0ee3352125a15|title='Strictly' Judges Give Their First 10s This Series... But Not To Danny Mac!|date=16 October 2016|work=Huffington Post|accessdate=16 October 2016}}</ref> In the final, on 17 December, after the couple scored the maximum 40 points for both their showdance and their [[Jive (dance)|jive]], they were announced as the winners.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/strictly-come-dancing-final-who-won-danny-max-louise-redknapp-ore-oduba-a7481811.html|title=Ore Oduba crowned winner of Strictly Come Dancing 2016|date=17 December 2016|work=The Independent|accessdate=17 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 Oduba sat in for [[Claudia Winkleman]] and [[Steve Wright (DJ)|Steve Wright]], on their respective [[BBC Radio 2]] shows, on a number of occasions.\n\nIn 2018, Oduba presented Saturday night game show ''[[Sport Relief|And They're Off! For Sport Relief]]'' on [[BBC One]]. Subsequently, he co-hosted the main coverage of [[Sport Relief|Sport Relief 2018]] live on BBC One. Also that year he presented ''Britain's Favourite Walks: Top 100'' alongside [[Julia Bradbury]] for [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]. Oduba hosts the [[BBC One]] game show ''Hardball''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2018/dan-mcgolphin-hardball-chase-the-case|title=BBC - Dan McGolpin announces exciting new factual and entertainment commissions for BBC One Daytime - Media Centre|publisher=BBC|accessdate=28 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nOduba embarked on his musical theatre debut in 2019, playing the role of ''Teen Angel'' in the UK tour of [[Grease (musical)|Grease]]. He shared the role with singer [[Peter Andre]]. Following that he starred as ''Aaron Fox'' in the European Premiere of [[Kander and Ebb|Kander and Ebb's]] [[Curtains (musical)|Curtains the Musical]] alongside [[Jason Manford]] and [[Carley Stenson]]. The production later transferred to London's Wyndhams Theatre where Oduba made his West End debut.\n\nIn 2020, Oduba played the role of news anchor Akintola in BBC One drama [[Noughts + Crosses]], a television adaptation of the novels by author [[Malorie Blackman]].\n\n==Personal life and credits==\nOduba married TV researcher Portia in November 2015 and in January 2018, Portia gave birth to a baby boy named Roman Oduba.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hellomagazine.com/celebrities/2016112034720/ore-oduba-celebrates-first-wedding-anniversary-with-wife-portia/|title=Ore Oduba celebrates first wedding anniversary with wife Portia|work=[[Hello! (magazine)|Hello!]]|accessdate=17 December 2016|date=20 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2017 he received an Honorary Doctorate from [[Loughborough University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lboro.ac.uk/news-events/news/2017/july/ore-oduba-honorary-degree/|title=Strictly Come Dancing star receives Honorary Doctorate from Loughborough University|publisher=Loughborough University|accessdate=10 November 2017}}</ref> In November 2017 he received an Honorary Doctorate of Arts from [[Bournemouth University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.bournemouth.ac.uk/news/2017-11-08/honorary-doctorate-ore-oduba|title=Honorary Doctorate Ore Oduba|publisher=Bournemouth University|accessdate=10 November 2017}}</ref> He is a lifelong supporter of [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]\n\n'''TV'''  \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#b0c4de; text-align:center;\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Channel\n|- \n| 2008-2013\n|''[[Newsround]]''\n| rowspan=\"4\" | Presenter\n| rowspan=\"4\" |[[CBBC (TV channel)|CBBC]]\n|- \n| 2008\u20132010\n|''[[Sportsround]]''\n|- \n| 2011\u20132013\n|''[[Match of the Day Kickabout]]''\n|- \n| 2012\n|''Ultimate Sports Day''\n|-  \n| 2013\n|''[[Let's Dance for Comic Relief]]''\n| Contestant\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[BBC One]]\n|- \n| 2011-2016\n|''[[BBC Breakfast]]''\n| Sport presenter\n|-\n| 2014\n|''[[All Over the Place (TV series)|All Over the Place Australia]]''\n| Co-presenter\n|[[CBBC (TV channel)|CBBC]]\n|- \n| 2015\u2014\n|''[[The One Show]]''\n| Guest presenter\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[BBC One]]\n|-  \n| 2015\n|''[[EastEnders Live Week|EastEnders: Backstage Live]]''\n| Co-presenter\n|-  \n| 2015\u20132016\n|''[[The National Lottery Draws]]''\n| Main presenter\n|-  \n| 2015-2016\n|''[[Victoria Derbyshire (TV programme)|Victoria Derbyshire]]''\n| Sport presenter\n|[[BBC Two]]\n|-  \n| 2015\n|''[[New Year Live]]''\n| Presenter\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[BBC One]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" |2016\n|''[[Sport Relief 2016|Sport Relief: Clash of the Titans]]''\n| Co-presenter\n|-\n|''[[Sport Relief 2016|Hell on High Seas]]''\n| Participant\n|-  \n|''[[2016 Summer Olympics|Olympics 2016]]''\n| Presenter\n|[[BBC]]\n|-  \n|''[[Strictly Come Dancing]]''\n| Participant\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[BBC One]]\n|- \n| rowspan=\"2\" |2016-2017\n|''Claimed and Shamed''\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Presenter\n|-  \n|''[[London Marathon|London Marathon Highlights]]''\n|[[BBC Two]]\n|-  \n| 2016-2018\n|''[[This Morning (TV programme)|This Morning]]''\n| Guest presenter\n|[[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" |2017\n|''[[BBC Young Dancer]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2017/young-dancer-line-up-grand-final|title=BBC - BBC Young Dancer 2017 line-up revealed ahead of BBC Two Grand Final|publisher=BBC|accessdate=22 April 2017}}</ref>''\n| rowspan=\"3\" | Co-presenter\n|[[BBC Two]]\n|-\n|''[[One Love Manchester]]''\n|[[BBC One]]\n|-\n|''World Athetics Championships 2017''\n|[[BBC One]]/[[BBC Two]]\n|-\n|''[[The National Lottery Draws#National Lottery Stars|The National Lottery Awards]]''\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Presenter\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[BBC One]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" |2018\n|''[[And They're Off!]]''\n|-\n|''Britain's Favourite Walks: Top 100''\n| Co-presenter\n|[[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]\n|-\n|''Hardball''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2018/dan-mcgolphin-hardball-chase-the-case?|title=BBC - Dan McGolpin announces exciting new factual and entertainment commissions for BBC One Daytime - Media Centre|publisher=BBC|accessdate=28 May 2018}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Presenter\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[BBC One]]\n|-\n|''The royal wedding of [[Prince Harry]] and [[Meghan Markle]]''\n|}\n\n'''Television guest appearances'''\n{{div col |colwidth=30em}}\n*''[[Hacker Time]]'' (2011)\n*''[[The Dog Ate My Homework (TV series)|The Dog Ate My Homework]]'' (2014)\n*''[[Celebrity Mastermind]]'' (2014)\n*''[[Play to the Whistle]]'' (2017)\n*''[[Extra Gear]]'' (2017)\n*''[[Weekend (talk show)|Weekend]]'' (2017)\n*''[[Celebrity Juice]]'' (2017)\n*''[[The Crystal Maze|The Crystal Maze: Celebrity Special]]'' (2017)\n*''[[Dara O Briain's Go 8 Bit]]'' (2017)\n*''[[Partners in Rhyme]]'' (2017)\n*''[[Comedy Playhouse#Series Seventeen .282017.29|Tim Vine Travels in Time]]'' (2017)\n*''[[Antiques Road Trip|Celebrity Antiques Road Trip]]'' (2017)\n*''[[Would I Lie to You? (TV series)|Would I Lie to You?]]'' (2017)\n*''[[Through the Keyhole]]'' (2018)\n*''[[Catchphrase (UK game show)|Celebrity Catchphrase]]'' (2018)\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Radio===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#b0c4de; text-align:center;\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Station\n|- \n| rowspan=2|2017\u2014\n| ''[[Claudia Winkleman|Claudia on Sunday]]'' \n| rowspan=\"3\" | Stand-in presenter\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[BBC Radio 2]]\n|- \n| ''[[Steve Wright in the Afternoon]]'' \n|-\n|2018-\n|Drive-time\n|- \n|}\n\n===Stage===\n\n[[Strictly Come Dancing|Strictly come dancing the live  Tour]] 2017: contestant\n\nStrictly come dancing the live Tour 2018: host\n\nStrictly come dancing the live  Tour 2019: host\n\nThe Strictly Tour includes participants from the previous year's television series.{{citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\n''Teen Angel'' in 2019 UK Tour of [[Grease (musical)|Grease]].\n\n''Aaron Fox'' in 2019/20 UK Tour and West End productions of [[Curtains (musical)|Curtains the Musical]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://oreodubaofficial.com/ Official website]\n*[https://twitter.com/OreOduba Official Twitter]\n*{{IMDb name|4775638}}\n\n{{Strictly Come Dancing}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2011}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oduba, Ore}}\n[[Category:Alumni of Loughborough University]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Newsround presenters]]\n[[Category:People educated at Canford School]]\n[[Category:English television presenters]]\n[[Category:BBC sports presenters and reporters]]\n[[Category:English people of Nigerian descent]]\n[[Category:Black British television personalities]]\n[[Category:Strictly Come Dancing winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Ore Oduba\n| image              = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1985|11|17|df=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[London]], [[England]], United Kingdom\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| occupation         = Television Presenter and Actor\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Portia Oduba|2015}}\n| children           = 1\n| birthname          = \n| URL                = http://oreodubaofficial.com\n| credits            = {{nowrap|''[[Newsround]]''<br>''[[BBC Sport]]''<br>''Claimed and Shamed''<br>''[[Match of the Day Kickabout]]''<br>''[[The One Show]]''<br>''[[The National Lottery Draws]]''<br>''[[Strictly Come Dancing]]''<br>''[[And They're Off!]]''''<br>''Hardball''<br>\"[[Noughts + Crosses]]\"}}\n}}\n'''Ore Oduba'''  (born 17 November 1985)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/profiles/4PM8ZqC3Pd5swPd2DFCc8n1/ore-oduba|title=Strictly Come Dancing - Ore Oduba - BBC One|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=17 December 2016}}</ref><ref name=BBCNewsR>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/cbbcnews/hi/newsid_7550000/newsid_7556400/7556408.stm |publisher=BBC News |title=All about Ore |date=12 August 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2016-11-19/who-is-ore-oduba-strictly-come-dancing-2016-contestant-guide|title=Who is Ore Oduba? Strictly Come Dancing 2016 contestant guide|work=Radio Times|accessdate=17 December 2016}}</ref> is a British television and radio presenter and musical theatre actor, best known for winning the [[Strictly Come Dancing (series 14)|fourteenth series]] of [[BBC One]]'s ''[[Strictly Come Dancing]]'' in 2016.\n\nHe presented the [[BBC]] children's news programme ''[[Newsround]]'' from 2008 until 2013. In 2018 he hosted the game show ''[[And They're Off!]]'' in aid of [[Sport Relief]]. Oduba also presents the BBC One game show ''Hardball''.\n\nIn 2019 he began a musical theatre, starring in the UK Tour of [[Grease (musical)|Grease]]. He also starred alongside [[Jason Manford]] in [[Curtains (musical)|Curtains the Musical]]. He made his West End debut in January 2020. \n\n==Early life and education==\nOduba was born in [[London]] to [[British Nigerian|Nigerian]] parents. He was educated at [[Dumpton School]], then [[Canford School]], a [[co-educational]] [[independent school]] for both boarding and day pupils in the village of [[Canford Magna]], near to the market town of [[Wimborne Minster]] in [[Dorset]], in southwest England.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Barber|first1=Marilyn|title=Strictly finalist Ore Oduba is a former pupil of Dumpton and Canford schools in Wimborne|url=http://www.blackmorevale.co.uk/strictly-finalist-ore-oduba-is-a-former-pupil-of-dumpton-and-canford-schools-in-wimborne/story-29980019-detail/story.html|accessdate=19 December 2016|publisher=Blackmore Vale|date=13 December 2016}}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He studied Sports Science and Social Science at [[Loughborough University]] and graduated in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lboro.ac.uk/alumni/news/2016/alumnus-ore-oduba-takes-to-the-strictly-stage.html|title=2016 - Alumnus Ore Oduba takes to the Strictly stage - Loughborough Alumni|publisher=Loughborough University|accessdate=17 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Career ==\nOduba had always aimed for a career in sports broadcasting,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ideastap.com/IdeasMag/the-knowledge/ore-oduba-interview|title=Ore Oduba, TV presenter|publisher=IdeasTap|accessdate=16 October 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170805104215/http://www.ideastap.com/IdeasMag/the-knowledge/ore-oduba-interview|archivedate=5 August 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> and initially joined [[The Network]], an [[Edinburgh]] television festival scheme.\n\nOduba joined ''[[Newsround]]'' in August 2008, following the departure of [[Lizo Mzimba]] and [[Laura Jones (journalist)|Laura Jones]]. His first role on the programme was as a reporter and breakfast bulletin presenter. He was quickly promoted to deputy presenter in 2009, filling in for main presenter [[Sonali Shah]] in her absence. In 2010, he joined Shah to begin presenting the main ''[[Newsround]]'' bulletin double-headed. This continued until Shah's departure in November 2011. He was later joined by reporters Leah Gooding and Hayley Cutts. As part of his role he also presented spin-off show ''[[Sportsround]]''. He became the main presenter in October 2008 when the show relaunched. He presented until its cancellation in 2010. The show was replaced by ''[[Match of the Day Kickabout]]'' which Oduba also presents. Oduba left ''Newsround'' in 2013.\n\nOduba formerly presented the sport for ''[[BBC Breakfast]]'' and [[BBC Radio 5 Live]]. He has also presented and reported on British Olympic Dreams along with former ''Newsround'' co-presenter Sonali Shah. Oduba began a debut presenting solo on the morning slot for the [[2014 Commonwealth Games]] on [[BBC One]] and [[BBC Sport]].\n\nOduba regularly appeared on CBBC studio presentation following his ''Newsround'' shift. He was also a guest on CBBC shows including ''[[Sam & Mark's TMi Friday]]'', ''[[Hacker Time]]'' and ''[[All Over the Place (TV series)|All Over the Place]]''.\n\nIn the lead up to the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] Oduba presented a programme called ''Ultimate Sports Day'' for CBBC. He also co-presents live cinema relays from the [[Royal Opera House]], [[Covent Garden]], with former [[ballerina]] [[Darcey Bussell]].\n\nOn 2 March 2013, Oduba and Sonali Shah appeared on the BBC's ''[[Let's Dance for Comic Relief]]'', dancing to ''[[Hey Ya!]]'' by ''[[Outkast]]''. They were eliminated and did not get through to the final.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/profiles/3mJ9xN6BvCZ3SyZ2641klvL/ore-sonali|title=Ore & Sonali|work=Let's Dance for Comic Relief|publisher=BBC One|accessdate=16 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe played the role of Nathan in ''[[Hacker Time]]'' on [[CBBC]]. Since 2015, he has guest presented numerous episodes of ''[[The One Show]]''.\n\nFrom 2015\u201316, he was a presenter on ''[[The National Lottery Draws]]'' on Saturday evenings and he presented the 2015 ''[[New Year Live]]'' programme on BBC One.\n\nFrom 7 March 2016, Oduba took part in a challenge for ''[[Sport Relief]]'', called \"Hell on High Seas\", in which he sailed 1,000 miles from [[Belfast]] to [[London]] with five other celebrities including [[Alex Jones (Welsh presenter)|Alex Jones]] and [[Suzi Perry]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportrelief.com/whats-going-on/hell-on-high-seas|title=Hell on High Seas|publisher=Sport Relief|accessdate=16 October 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018035619/http://www.sportrelief.com/whats-going-on/hell-on-high-seas|archivedate=18 October 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://home.bt.com/news/bt-life/x-11364043857543|title=Celebrity crew set sail around the UK for the BT Sport Relief Challenge: Hell on High Seas|publisher=BT|accessdate=16 October 2016}}</ref> In 2016, he also presented ''[[Sport Relief 2016|Sport Relief: Clash of the Titans]]'' with [[Dan Walker (broadcaster)|Dan Walker]]. He presented coverage of the [[2016 Summer Olympics]] on [[BBC Four]] throughout August 2016.\n\nBetween October 2012 and May 2017 he presented the daytime BBC One insurance fraud documentary programme ''Claimed and Shamed''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.curvemedia.com/claimed-and-shamed|title=Curve Media TV Production|publisher=Curve Media|accessdate=17 December 2016}}</ref> In November 2016, Oduba guest presented an episode of ''[[This Morning (TV programme)|This Morning]]'' with [[Holly Willoughby]] on [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]. He returned to present a second episode with Willoughby in March 2017 and a third with [[Davina McCall]] in February 2018.\n\nIn 2016 Oduba participated in the [[Strictly Come Dancing (series 14)|fourteenth series]] of ''[[Strictly Come Dancing]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/strictlycomedancing/entries/d77143c8-ab28-4040-ab06-c7728f685221|title=Presenting our fourth Strictly celebrity\u2026 Ore Oduba|date=11 August 2016|publisher=BBC|accessdate=16 October 2016}}</ref> where he was partnered with [[Joanne Clifton]]. The couple's [[American Smooth]] to \"[[Singin' in the Rain (song)|Singin' in the Rain]]\" won praise from Patricia Ward, widow of [[Gene Kelly]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/national/article/Widows-praise-for-Strictlys-Ore-Oduba-like-blessing-from-Gene-Kelly-himself-f7f08fe7-3600-42dd-821b-3af4688cf5bc-ds|title=Widow's praise for Strictly's Ore Oduba like 'blessing from Gene Kelly himself'|work=North West Evening Mail|date=13 October 2016|accessdate=17 December 2016}}</ref> In the fourth week the couple were awarded a score of 39 points out of 40 for their [[Jive (dance)|jive]] to \"[[Runaway Baby]]\" by [[Bruno Mars]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/stayingin/tvfilm/strictly-come-dancing-2016-ore-oduba-receives-first-10s-of-the-series-as-daisy-lowes-sexy-rumba-a3370231.html%5B|title=Ore Oduba receives first 10s of this year's Strictly Come Dancing for 'jaw-dropping' jive|date=15 October 2016 |work=London Evening Standard |accessdate=16 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/strictly-come-dancing-ore-oduba-first-ten_uk_58033742e4b0ee3352125a15|title='Strictly' Judges Give Their First 10s This Series... But Not To Danny Mac!|date=16 October 2016|work=Huffington Post|accessdate=16 October 2016}}</ref> In the final, on 17 December, after the couple scored the maximum 40 points for both their showdance and their [[Jive (dance)|jive]], they were announced as the winners.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/strictly-come-dancing-final-who-won-danny-max-louise-redknapp-ore-oduba-a7481811.html|title=Ore Oduba crowned winner of Strictly Come Dancing 2016|date=17 December 2016|work=The Independent|accessdate=17 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 Oduba sat in for [[Claudia Winkleman]] and [[Steve Wright (DJ)|Steve Wright]], on their respective [[BBC Radio 2]] shows, on a number of occasions.\n\nIn 2018, Oduba presented Saturday night game show ''[[Sport Relief|And They're Off! For Sport Relief]]'' on [[BBC One]]. Subsequently, he co-hosted the main coverage of [[Sport Relief|Sport Relief 2018]] live on BBC One. Also that year he presented ''Britain's Favourite Walks: Top 100'' alongside [[Julia Bradbury]] for [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]. Oduba hosts the [[BBC One]] game show ''Hardball''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2018/dan-mcgolphin-hardball-chase-the-case|title=BBC - Dan McGolpin announces exciting new factual and entertainment commissions for BBC One Daytime - Media Centre|publisher=BBC|accessdate=28 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nOduba embarked on his musical theatre debut in 2019, playing the role of ''Teen Angel'' in the UK tour of [[Grease (musical)|Grease]]. He shared the role with singer [[Peter Andre]]. Following that he starred as ''Aaron Fox'' in the European Premiere of [[Kander and Ebb|Kander and Ebb's]] [[Curtains (musical)|Curtains the Musical]] alongside [[Jason Manford]] and [[Carley Stenson]]. The production later transferred to London's Wyndhams Theatre where Oduba made his West End debut.\n\nIn 2020, Oduba played the role of news anchor Akintola in BBC One drama [[Noughts + Crosses]], a television adaptation of the novels by author [[Malorie Blackman]].\n\n==Personal life and credits==\nOduba married TV researcher Portia in November 2015 and in January 2018, Portia gave birth to a baby boy named Roman Oduba.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hellomagazine.com/celebrities/2016112034720/ore-oduba-celebrates-first-wedding-anniversary-with-wife-portia/|title=Ore Oduba celebrates first wedding anniversary with wife Portia|work=[[Hello! (magazine)|Hello!]]|accessdate=17 December 2016|date=20 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2017 he received an Honorary Doctorate from [[Loughborough University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lboro.ac.uk/news-events/news/2017/july/ore-oduba-honorary-degree/|title=Strictly Come Dancing star receives Honorary Doctorate from Loughborough University|publisher=Loughborough University|accessdate=10 November 2017}}</ref> In November 2017 he received an Honorary Doctorate of Arts from [[Bournemouth University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.bournemouth.ac.uk/news/2017-11-08/honorary-doctorate-ore-oduba|title=Honorary Doctorate Ore Oduba|publisher=Bournemouth University|accessdate=10 November 2017}}</ref> He is a lifelong supporter of [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]\n\n'''TV'''  \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#b0c4de; text-align:center;\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Channel\n|- \n| 2008-2013\n|''[[Newsround]]''\n| rowspan=\"4\" | Presenter\n| rowspan=\"4\" |[[CBBC (TV channel)|CBBC]]\n|- \n| 2008\u20132010\n|''[[Sportsround]]''\n|- \n| 2011\u20132013\n|''[[Match of the Day Kickabout]]''\n|- \n| 2012\n|''Ultimate Sports Day''\n|-  \n| 2013\n|''[[Let's Dance for Comic Relief]]''\n| Contestant\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[BBC One]]\n|- \n| 2011-2016\n|''[[BBC Breakfast]]''\n| Sport presenter\n|-\n| 2014\n|''[[All Over the Place (TV series)|All Over the Place Australia]]''\n| Co-presenter\n|[[CBBC (TV channel)|CBBC]]\n|- \n| 2015\u2014\n|''[[The One Show]]''\n| Guest presenter\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[BBC One]]\n|-  \n| 2015\n|''[[EastEnders Live Week|EastEnders: Backstage Live]]''\n| Co-presenter\n|-  \n| 2015\u20132016\n|''[[The National Lottery Draws]]''\n| Main presenter\n|-  \n| 2015-2016\n|''[[Victoria Derbyshire (TV programme)|Victoria Derbyshire]]''\n| Sport presenter\n|[[BBC Two]]\n|-  \n| 2015\n|''[[New Year Live]]''\n| Presenter\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[BBC One]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" |2016\n|''[[Sport Relief 2016|Sport Relief: Clash of the Titans]]''\n| Co-presenter\n|-\n|''[[Sport Relief 2016|Hell on High Seas]]''\n| Participant\n|-  \n|''[[2016 Summer Olympics|Olympics 2016]]''\n| Presenter\n|[[BBC]]\n|-  \n|''[[Strictly Come Dancing]]''\n| Participant\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[BBC One]]\n|- \n| rowspan=\"2\" |2016-2017\n|''Claimed and Shamed''\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Presenter\n|-  \n|''[[London Marathon|London Marathon Highlights]]''\n|[[BBC Two]]\n|-  \n| 2016-2018\n|''[[This Morning (TV programme)|This Morning]]''\n| Guest presenter\n|[[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" |2017\n|''[[BBC Young Dancer]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2017/young-dancer-line-up-grand-final|title=BBC - BBC Young Dancer 2017 line-up revealed ahead of BBC Two Grand Final|publisher=BBC|accessdate=22 April 2017}}</ref>''\n| rowspan=\"3\" | Co-presenter\n|[[BBC Two]]\n|-\n|''[[One Love Manchester]]''\n|[[BBC One]]\n|-\n|''World Athetics Championships 2017''\n|[[BBC One]]/[[BBC Two]]\n|-\n|''[[The National Lottery Draws#National Lottery Stars|The National Lottery Awards]]''\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Presenter\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[BBC One]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" |2018\n|''[[And They're Off!]]''\n|-\n|''Britain's Favourite Walks: Top 100''\n| Co-presenter\n|[[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]\n|-\n|''Hardball''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2018/dan-mcgolphin-hardball-chase-the-case?|title=BBC - Dan McGolpin announces exciting new factual and entertainment commissions for BBC One Daytime - Media Centre|publisher=BBC|accessdate=28 May 2018}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Presenter\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[BBC One]]\n|-\n|''The royal wedding of [[Prince Harry]] and [[Meghan Markle]]''\n|}\n\n'''Television guest appearances'''\n{{div col |colwidth=30em}}\n*''[[Hacker Time]]'' (2011)\n*''[[The Dog Ate My Homework (TV series)|The Dog Ate My Homework]]'' (2014)\n*''[[Celebrity Mastermind]]'' (2014)\n*''[[Play to the Whistle]]'' (2017)\n*''[[Extra Gear]]'' (2017)\n*''[[Weekend (talk show)|Weekend]]'' (2017)\n*''[[Celebrity Juice]]'' (2017)\n*''[[The Crystal Maze|The Crystal Maze: Celebrity Special]]'' (2017)\n*''[[Dara O Briain's Go 8 Bit]]'' (2017)\n*''[[Partners in Rhyme]]'' (2017)\n*''[[Comedy Playhouse#Series Seventeen .282017.29|Tim Vine Travels in Time]]'' (2017)\n*''[[Antiques Road Trip|Celebrity Antiques Road Trip]]'' (2017)\n*''[[Would I Lie to You? (TV series)|Would I Lie to You?]]'' (2017)\n*''[[Through the Keyhole]]'' (2018)\n*''[[Catchphrase (UK game show)|Celebrity Catchphrase]]'' (2018)\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Radio===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#b0c4de; text-align:center;\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Station\n|- \n| rowspan=2|2017\u2014\n| ''[[Claudia Winkleman|Claudia on Sunday]]'' \n| rowspan=\"3\" | Stand-in presenter\n| rowspan=\