{"title_page": "O, The Oprah Magazine", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox magazine\n| title           = O, The Oprah Magazine\n| image_file      = O, The Oprah Magazine, July 2012.jpg\n| image_size      = \n| image_alt       = \n| image_caption   = July 2012 cover of ''O''\n| editor          = Lucy Kaylin\n| editor_title    = Editor\n| previous_editor = \n| staff_writer    = \n| frequency       = Monthly\n| total_circulation     = 2,395,496<ref>{{cite web |url=http://abcas3.accessabc.com/ecirc/magtitlesearch.asp |title= eCirc for Consumer Magazines |date= June 30, 2013 |publisher= [[Audit Bureau of Circulations (North America)|Audit Bureau of Circulations]]|accessdate=November 27, 2015}}</ref>\t\n|circulation_year = 2014\n| category        = [[Women's magazine]]\n| company         = [[Hearst Communications]]\n| firstdate       = {{start date and age|2000|4|19}}\n| country         = USA\n| based           = \n| language        = English\n| issn            = 1531-3247\n| website         = {{URL|http://Oprah.com/omagazine}}\n}}\n\n'''''O, The Oprah Magazine''''', sometimes simply abbreviated to '''''O''''', is a monthly magazine founded by [[Oprah Winfrey]] and [[Hearst Communications]] and primarily marketed at women.\n\n==Overview==\nIt was first published on April 19, 2000. {{As of|2004|alt=As of June 2004}}, its average paid circulation was over 2.7 million copies, two thirds by [[subscription]]. A South African edition was first published in April 2002; according to the South African Advertising Research Foundation, its average readership was over 300,000. The editor of the South African edition is Samantha Page.<ref>[http://www.saarf.co.za/topmags.htm ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050209072542/http://www.saarf.co.za/topmags.htm |date=February 9, 2005 }}</ref>  While most US magazine sales declined in 2009, ''O'' Magazine increased its newsstand sales by 5.8 percent to 662,304 copies during the second half of the year.<ref name=dlvam7o>{{cite web|url=http://www.cleveland.com/business/index.ssf/2010/02/us_magazine_circulation_falls.html |title=U.S. magazine circulation falls 9% at newsstands |publisher=cleveland.com |accessdate=April 19, 2012}}</ref>  The magazine's newsstand sales fell 15.8% during the first half of 2010,<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704388504575419202376842786 | work=The Wall Street Journal | first=Russell | last=Adams | title=Magazine Circulation Falls Further | date=August 10, 2010}}</ref> while its subscription circulation increased,<ref name=piimpaz>[http://www.thewrap.com/media/column-post/newsstand-magazine-sales-slide-19986?page=0,0 Newsstand Magazine Sales Slide]; The Wrap; Dylan Stableford; August 9, 2010</ref> and sales fell 8.2% in the later half of the year.<ref>{{cite web|last=Moses |first=Lucia |url=http://www.adweek.com/news/press/circulation-news-not-good-big-magazine-publishers-126575 |title=Circulation News Not Good for Big Magazine Publishers |publisher=Adweek |accessdate=April 19, 2012}}</ref>\n\nSince its inception, Oprah has appeared on the cover of each issue. The first shared cover is her April 2009 issue in which she appears with the [[First Lady]] [[Michelle Obama]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oprah.com/article/omagazine/20090223-orig-michelle-obama-oprah |title=Michelle Obama's Oprah Interview \u2013 O Magazine Cover with Obama |publisher=Oprah.com |accessdate=April 19, 2012}}</ref> The second shared cover is with fellow daytime host [[Ellen DeGeneres]] on the December 2009 issue.  Four separate covers were shot for this special holiday issue.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oprah.com/survey/omagazine/200912-omag-cover-poll |title=Which O Magazine Cover With Oprah and Ellen Do You Like Best? |publisher=Oprah.com |accessdate=April 19, 2012}}</ref> The December issue of ''O'' hit newsstands on November 12, 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oprah.com/article/omagazine/200912-omag-ellen-degeneres-oprah-cover |title=Ellen DeGeneres' O Magazine Cover \u2013 Ellen and Oprah |publisher=Oprah.com |date=October 13, 2009 |accessdate=April 19, 2012}}</ref>\n''O, the Oprah Magazine'' serves 63.6% [[Caucasian race|Caucasian]], 29.8% [[African-American]], 8.8% [[Hispanic]], 1.8% [[Asian people|Asian]] and 6.6% other women. It is directed towards a median age of 47.9, median home value of $214,281, median [[Household income|HHI]] of $68,911, and median IEI of $38,756.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.omediakit.com/r5/home.asp|title=O Media Kit|website=www.omediakit.com}}</ref>\n\nThe mission statement of O Magazine presented by O Media Kit<ref>{{cite web|title=O Media Kit|url=http://www.omediakit.com/r5/home.asp?initial_file=home-layout-2018.asp|website=www.omediakit.com|accessdate=19 January 2018}}</ref> is to ''\"Live Your Best Life\"''. They also stated in their mission statement, \"As the only magazine devoted to personal growth, ''O, The Oprah Magazine'' engages and addresses every aspect of a woman's life - from beauty and style, to food, health, and more. We inspire, motivate and celebrate our reader's journeys to live their best life.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=O Media Kit|url=http://www.omediakit.com/r5/home.asp?initial_file=home-layout-2018.asp#mission|website=www.omediakit.com|accessdate=19 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Digital editions==\nThe December 2010 issue of ''The Oprah Magazine''<ref>{{cite web|title=O, The Oprah Magazine - Oprah.com|url=http://www.oprah.com/app/o-magazine.html|website=Oprah.com|accessdate=19 January 2018|language=en-us}}</ref> was the first released digitally through the magazine's [[iPad]] app.<ref name=\"htanna\">{{cite web|title=The Oprah Magazine debuts on iPad|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/magazines/2010/11/oprah-magazine-ipad-store|work=iPad app info added|accessdate=November 17, 2010}}</ref> The app features exclusive videos of Oprah, allows readers to preview and purchase books presented in the magazine's Reading Room and O List sections, and gives users the ability to purchase monthly or yearly subscriptions. Individual issues are also available for download through the app.<ref>{{cite web|title=Oprah Magazine's iPad App|url=http://www.oprah.com/omagazine/Oprah-Magazines-iPad-App_3}}</ref>\n\n==Staff==\nIn July 2009, Susan Casey became the editor-in-chief of the magazine. Before joining, she was the development editor of [[Time Inc.]]. Casey was editor-in-chief of ''[[Sports Illustrated Women]]'', editor-at-large for Time Inc., and [[creative director]] of ''[[Outside (magazine)|Outside]]''. Casey wrote ''[[The New York Times]]'' bestseller ''[[The Devil's Teeth: A True Story of Obsession and Survival Among America's Great White Sharks]]'', and ''The Wave''.\n\nIn September 2009, the magazine hired former ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'' editor-in-chief [[Sara Nelson (editor)|Sara Nelson]] as books editor at ''O''.<ref name=twsOctK32d>{{cite news\n |author= Keith J. Kelly\n |title= Casey's at the bat at ''O, The Oprah Magazine''\n |work=New York Post\n |quote= assumed by Sara Nelson, the mag's new book director...\n |date= September 11, 2009\n |url= http://www.nypost.com/p/news/business/item_BrTQNjjs4wmQL4bRcl19KN\n |accessdate=October 5, 2010\n}}</ref><ref name=twsOctK32a>{{cite news\n |author= Keith j. kelly\n |title= Oprah's ''O'' in overhaul\n |work=New York Post\n |quote= Sara Nelson was named books editor...\n |date= September 10, 2009\n |url= http://www.nypost.com/p/news/business/item_EwKYr7ffcgwz3KvTK2fYfL\n |accessdate=October 5, 2010\n}}</ref><ref name=twsOctJ14>{{cite news\n |author= Lynn Neary\n |title= How To Sell A Book? Good Old Word Of Mouth\n |publisher= National Public Radio\n |quote=  Sara Nelson, book editor at Oprah's O magazine, said ...\n |date= September 10, 2010\n |url= https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=129757766\n |accessdate=October 5, 2010\n}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2013, Lucy Kaylin was promoted to editor-in-chief, replacing Susan Casey.<ref>[http://observer.com/2013/04/lucy-kaylin-rises-to-editor-in-chief-at-o-the-oprah-magazine/#ixzz3bUGIrTKR Lucy Kaylin Rises to Editor in Chief at O, The Oprah Magazine]; ''New York Observer''; April 28, 2013</ref>\n\n==Books==\n{{update|date=February 2016}}\nIn 2015, the magazine teamed up with Flatiron Books of St. Martin's Press and published a series of inspirational books, including ''O's Little Book of Happiness'' and, in 2016, ''O's Little Book of Love & Friendship''.\n\n==Public perception==\n{{Expand section|date = March 2011}}\n\nIn a March 2001 article entitled \"O Positive\", Noreen O'Leary argued that Winfrey was well on her way to influencing the content of [[List of women's magazines|women's magazines]] beyond her own, just as she has helped reshape daytime TV and the world of book publishing.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0BDW/is_10_42/ai_71559754/?tag=content;col1 | work=Brandweek | first=Noreen | last=O'Leary | title=O Positive \u2013 O, The Oprah Magazine, profile \u2013 Statistical Data Included | year=2001}}</ref>\n\n==Brockmeyer lawsuit==\nIn April 2001, Oprah Winfrey and the Hearst Corporation were sued for trademark infringement by Ronald Brockmeyer, the publisher of ''[[\u00abO\u00bb|\u00abO\u00bb Magazine]]'', a German [[erotic]] periodical which predated Winfrey's magazine by several years. In a March 2003 decision, Judge [[John Koeltl]] dismissed the suit, citing the different content of the two magazines in addition to the irregular publication schedule and minimal American sales of the German magazine.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* Official magazine websites: [http://www.oprah.com/omagazine.html Oprah Winfrey] and [http://www.hearst.com/magazines/o-the-oprah-magazine.php Hearst]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20030413064806/http://www.themagazineguys.com/oprah/index.html Magazine summary], including [[Audit Bureau of Circulations (North America)|ABC Circulation]] information and [[mission statement]]\n* [http://popwatch.ew.com/2010/06/16/oprah-gives-magazine-staffers-10k-each Oprah gives ''O'' magazine staffers $10K each to celebrate 10th anniversary]\n\n{{Oprah Winfrey}}\n{{Hearst}}\n\n[[Category:American monthly magazines]]\n[[Category:American women's magazines]]\n[[Category:Hearst Communications publications]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 2000]]\n[[Category:Oprah Winfrey]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox magazine\n| title           = O, The Oprah Magazine\n| image_file      = O, The Oprah Magazine, July 2012.jpg\n| image_size      = \n| image_alt       = \n| image_caption   = July 2012 cover of ''O''\n| editor          = Lucy Kaylin\n| editor_title    = Editor\n| previous_editor = \n| staff_writer    = \n| frequency       = Monthly\n| total_circulation     = 2,395,496<ref>{{cite web |url=http://abcas3.accessabc.com/ecirc/magtitlesearch.asp |title= eCirc for Consumer Magazines |date= June 30, 2013 |publisher= [[Audit Bureau of Circulations (North America)|Audit Bureau of Circulations]]|accessdate=November 27, 2015}}</ref>\t\n|circulation_year = 2014\n| category        = [[Women's magazine]]\n| company         = [[Hearst Communications]]\n| firstdate       = {{start date and age|2000|4|19}}\n| country         = USA\n| based           = \n| language        = English\n| issn            = 1531-3247\n| website         = {{URL|http://Oprah.com/omagazine}}\n}}\n\n'''''O, The Oprah Magazine''''', sometimes simply abbreviated to '''''O''''', is a monthly magazine founded by [[Oprah Winfrey]] and [[Hearst Communications]] and primarily marketed at women.\n\n==Overview==\nIt was first published on April 19, 2000. {{As of|2004|alt=As of June 2004}}, its average paid circulation was over 2.7 million copies, two thirds by [[subscription]]. A South African edition was first published in April 2002; according to the South African Advertising Research Foundation, its average readership was over 300,000. The editor of the South African edition is Samantha Page.<ref>[http://www.saarf.co.za/topmags.htm ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050209072542/http://www.saarf.co.za/topmags.htm |date=February 9, 2005 }}</ref>  While most US magazine sales declined in 2009, ''O'' Magazine increased its newsstand sales by 5.8 percent to 662,304 copies during the second half of the year.<ref name=dlvam7o>{{cite web|url=http://www.cleveland.com/business/index.ssf/2010/02/us_magazine_circulation_falls.html |title=U.S. magazine circulation falls 9% at newsstands |publisher=cleveland.com |accessdate=April 19, 2012}}</ref>  The magazine's newsstand sales fell 15.8% during the first half of 2010,<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704388504575419202376842786 | work=The Wall Street Journal | first=Russell | last=Adams | title=Magazine Circulation Falls Further | date=August 10, 2010}}</ref> while its subscription circulation increased,<ref name=piimpaz>[http://www.thewrap.com/media/column-post/newsstand-magazine-sales-slide-19986?page=0,0 Newsstand Magazine Sales Slide]; The Wrap; Dylan Stableford; August 9, 2010</ref> and sales fell 8.2% in the later half of the year.<ref>{{cite web|last=Moses |first=Lucia |url=http://www.adweek.com/news/press/circulation-news-not-good-big-magazine-publishers-126575 |title=Circulation News Not Good for Big Magazine Publishers |publisher=Adweek |accessdate=April 19, 2012}}</ref>\n\nSince its inception, Oprah has appeared on the cover of each issue. The first shared cover is her April 2009 issue in which she appears with the [[First Lady]] [[Michelle Obama]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oprah.com/article/omagazine/20090223-orig-michelle-obama-oprah |title=Michelle Obama's Oprah Interview \u2013 O Magazine Cover with Obama |publisher=Oprah.com |accessdate=April 19, 2012}}</ref> The second shared cover is with fellow daytime host [[Ellen DeGeneres]] on the December 2009 issue.  Four separate covers were shot for this special holiday issue.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oprah.com/survey/omagazine/200912-omag-cover-poll |title=Which O Magazine Cover With Oprah and Ellen Do You Like Best? |publisher=Oprah.com |accessdate=April 19, 2012}}</ref> The December issue of ''O'' hit newsstands on November 12, 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oprah.com/article/omagazine/200912-omag-ellen-degeneres-oprah-cover |title=Ellen DeGeneres' O Magazine Cover \u2013 Ellen and Oprah |publisher=Oprah.com |date=October 13, 2009 |accessdate=April 19, 2012}}</ref>\n''O, the Oprah Magazine'' serves 63.6% [[Caucasian race|Caucasian]], 29.8% [[African-American]], 8.8% [[Hispanic]], 1.8% [[Asian people|Asian]] and 6.6% other women. It is directed towards a median age of 47.9, median home value of $214,281, median [[Household income|HHI]] of $68,911, and median IEI of $38,756.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.omediakit.com/r5/home.asp|title=O Media Kit|website=www.omediakit.com}}</ref>\n\nThe mission statement of O Magazine presented by O Media Kit<ref>{{cite web|title=O Media Kit|url=http://www.omediakit.com/r5/home.asp?initial_file=home-layout-2018.asp|website=www.omediakit.com|accessdate=19 January 2018}}</ref> is to ''\"Live Your Best Life\"''. They also stated in their mission statement, \"As the only magazine devoted to personal growth, ''O, The Oprah Magazine'' engages and addresses every aspect of a woman's life - from beauty and style, to food, health, and more. We inspire, motivate and celebrate our reader's journeys to live their best life.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=O Media Kit|url=http://www.omediakit.com/r5/home.asp?initial_file=home-layout-2018.asp#mission|website=www.omediakit.com|accessdate=19 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Digital editions==\nThe December 2010 issue of ''The Oprah Magazine''<ref>{{cite web|title=O, The Oprah Magazine - Oprah.com|url=http://www.oprah.com/app/o-magazine.html|website=Oprah.com|accessdate=19 January 2018|language=en-us}}</ref> was the first released digitally through the magazine's [[iPad]] app.<ref name=\"htanna\">{{cite web|title=The Oprah Magazine debuts on iPad|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/magazines/2010/11/oprah-magazine-ipad-store|work=iPad app info added|accessdate=November 17, 2010}}</ref> The app features exclusive videos of Oprah, allows readers to preview and purchase books presented in the magazine's Reading Room and O List sections, and gives users the ability to purchase monthly or yearly subscriptions. Individual issues are also available for download through the app.<ref>{{cite web|title=Oprah Magazine's iPad App|url=http://www.oprah.com/omagazine/Oprah-Magazines-iPad-App_3}}</ref>\n\n==Staff==\nIn July 2009, Susan Casey became the editor-in-chief of the magazine. Before joining, she was the development editor of [[Time Inc.]]. Casey was editor-in-chief of ''[[Sports Illustrated Women]]'', editor-at-large for Time Inc., and [[creative director]] of ''[[Outside (magazine)|Outside]]''. Casey wrote ''[[The New York Times]]'' bestseller ''[[The Devil's Teeth: A True Story of Obsession and Survival Among America's Great White Sharks]]'', and ''The Wave''.\n\nIn September 2009, the magazine hired former ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'' editor-in-chief [[Sara Nelson]] as books editor at ''O''.<ref name=twsOctK32d>{{cite news\n |author= Keith J. Kelly\n |title= Casey's at the bat at ''O, The Oprah Magazine''\n |work=New York Post\n |quote= assumed by Sara Nelson, the mag's new book director...\n |date= September 11, 2009\n |url= http://www.nypost.com/p/news/business/item_BrTQNjjs4wmQL4bRcl19KN\n |accessdate=October 5, 2010\n}}</ref><ref name=twsOctK32a>{{cite news\n |author= Keith j. kelly\n |title= Oprah's ''O'' in overhaul\n |work=New York Post\n |quote= Sara Nelson was named books editor...\n |date= September 10, 2009\n |url= http://www.nypost.com/p/news/business/item_EwKYr7ffcgwz3KvTK2fYfL\n |accessdate=October 5, 2010\n}}</ref><ref name=twsOctJ14>{{cite news\n |author= Lynn Neary\n |title= How To Sell A Book? Good Old Word Of Mouth\n |publisher= National Public Radio\n |quote=  Sara Nelson, book editor at Oprah's O magazine, said ...\n |date= September 10, 2010\n |url= https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=129757766\n |accessdate=October 5, 2010\n}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2013, Lucy Kaylin was promoted to editor-in-chief, replacing Susan Casey.<ref>[http://observer.com/2013/04/lucy-kaylin-rises-to-editor-in-chief-at-o-the-oprah-magazine/#ixzz3bUGIrTKR Lucy Kaylin Rises to Editor in Chief at O, The Oprah Magazine]; ''New York Observer''; April 28, 2013</ref>\n\n==Books==\n{{update|date=February 2016}}\nIn 2015, the magazine teamed up with Flatiron Books of St. Martin's Press and published a series of inspirational books, including ''O's Little Book of Happiness'' and, in 2016, ''O's Little Book of Love & Friendship''.\n\n==Public perception==\n{{Expand section|date = March 2011}}\n\nIn a March 2001 article entitled \"O Positive\", Noreen O'Leary argued that Winfrey was well on her way to influencing the content of [[List of women's magazines|women's magazines]] beyond her own, just as she has helped reshape daytime TV and the world of book publishing.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0BDW/is_10_42/ai_71559754/?tag=content;col1 | work=Brandweek | first=Noreen | last=O'Leary | title=O Positive \u2013 O, The Oprah Magazine, profile \u2013 Statistical Data Included | year=2001}}</ref>\n\n==Brockmeyer lawsuit==\nIn April 2001, Oprah Winfrey and the Hearst Corporation were sued for trademark infringement by Ronald Brockmeyer, the publisher of ''[[\u00abO\u00bb|\u00abO\u00bb Magazine]]'', a German [[erotic]] periodical which predated Winfrey's magazine by several years. In a March 2003 decision, Judge [[John Koeltl]] dismissed the suit, citing the different content of the two magazines in addition to the irregular publication schedule and minimal American sales of the German magazine.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* Official magazine websites: [http://www.oprah.com/omagazine.html Oprah Winfrey] and [http://www.hearst.com/magazines/o-the-oprah-magazine.php Hearst]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20030413064806/http://www.themagazineguys.com/oprah/index.html Magazine summary], including [[Audit Bureau of Circulations (North America)|ABC Circulation]] information and [[mission statement]]\n* [http://popwatch.ew.com/2010/06/16/oprah-gives-magazine-staffers-10k-each Oprah gives ''O'' magazine staffers $10K each to celebrate 10th anniversary]\n\n{{Oprah Winfrey}}\n{{Hearst}}\n\n[[Category:American monthly magazines]]\n[[Category:American women's magazines]]\n[[Category:Hearst Communications publications]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 2000]]\n[[Category:Oprah Winfrey]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toSara Nelson(link changed toSara Nelson (editor)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/O,_The_Oprah_Magazine"}
{"title_page": "Matthew Labyorteaux", "text_new": "{{short description|American film, television, and voice actor}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox person \n|name    = Matthew Labyorteaux\n|image   = Little House on the Prairie Katy Kurtzman Matthew Laborteaux 1977 No 2.jpg\n|caption = Labyorteaux and [[Katy Kurtzman]] on ''[[Little House on the Prairie (TV series)|Little House on the Prairie]]'', 1977\n|birth_name = Matthew Charles Labyorteaux\n|birth_date = {{Birth date|1966|12|8|mf=yes}}\n|birth_place = [[Los Angeles|Los Angeles, California]], U.S.\n|death_date = {{Death date|2020|4|20|mf=yes}} (aged 53)\n|death_place = [[Cerritos, California]]\n|occupation = Actor\n|years_active = 1972\u2013present\n|known_for = Role of [[List of Little House on the Prairie characters#The Ingalls family|Albert Quinn Ingalls]] on ''Little House on the Prairie''\n}}\n\n'''Matthew Charles Labyorteaux''' (born December 8, 1966) is an [[Americans|American]] film, television and voice actor.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Reilly|first=S.|editor-last=Donovan|editor-first=H|editor-link=Hedley Donovan|date=September 11, 1978|title=Landon's ''Little'' Kids|journal=[[People (magazine)|People Weekly]]|volume=10|issue=11|pages=92\u201396 |publisher=[[Time Inc.|Time]]|location=[[Chicago|Chicago, IL]]|issn=0093-7673 |url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20071697,00.html|accessdate=August 31, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Harris|first=H.|editor-last=Roberts|editor-first=E. L., Jr|editor-link=Gene Roberts (journalist)|date=December 20, 1981|title=Laborteaux Trio: Matt, Pat, and Mom|journal=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]|page=TV04|publisher=[[John S. Knight|J. S. Knight]] |location=Philadelphia, PA|issn=0885-6613|url=http://www.melissasueandersonfan.com/LABORTEAUX%20TRIO.pdf|format=PDF|accessdate=July 15, 2012}}</ref> In many of his credits, his last name is spelled as \"'''Laborteaux'''\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0479612/|title=Matthew Labyorteaux|publisher=IMdb|accessdate=August 22, 2015}}</ref> He is also credited as '''Matthew Charles''' for his work in animation.\n\nHe may be best known for portraying [[List of Little House on the Prairie characters#The Ingalls family|Albert Quinn Ingalls]]<ref name=\"Matthew Labyorteaux Biography\">{{cite web|title=Matthew Labyorteaux|url=http://www.biography.com/people/matthew-labyorteaux|website=Biography.com |accessdate=August 22, 2015}}</ref> on  ''[[Little House on the Prairie (TV series)|Little House on the Prairie]]'' from 1978\u201383. He is also known as the voice of Jaden Yuki and The Supreme King in ''[[Yu-Gi-Oh! GX]]'' from 2005\u201308.\n\n==Career==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=November 2016}}\nLabyorteaux began working in commercials at the age of seven, having been discovered while accompanying his older brother, [[Patrick Labyorteaux]], to a casting call. He shortly thereafter landed his first dramatic role in ''[[A Woman Under the Influence]]'', where he played one of [[Peter Falk]] and [[Gena Rowlands]]' children.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Notes From The Wasteland: A Special Friendship|last=Norton|first=Paula|date=7 February 1976|work=Argus-Courier|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nAside from his tenure on ''Little House on the Prairie'', Labyorteaux also starred in the short-lived television series ''[[The Red Hand Gang]]'' (1977) and ''[[Whiz Kids (TV series)|Whiz Kids]]'' (1983\u201384), in addition to several [[Television film|made-for-television movies]]. His most prominent film role was in [[Wes Craven]]'s ''[[Deadly Friend]]'' (1986) as Paul Conway, a young genius who resurrects a dead girl using an [[artificial intelligence]] [[microchip]] from a [[robot]] he created that had previously been destroyed by a malicious neighbor.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=\u2019Deadly Friend\u2019 Slows Flow of Gore|last=Goldstein|first=Patrick|date=14 October 1986|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nHe made guest appearances on numerous television shows, including ''[[The Rookies]]'', ''[[The Bob Newhart Show]]'', ''[[Mulligan's Stew]]'', ''[[Lou Grant (TV series)|Lou Grant]]'', ''[[Here's Boomer]]'' ([[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]] of ''The Red Hand Gang''), ''[[The Love Boat]]'', ''[[Simon & Simon]]'' ([[crossover (fiction)|crossover]] episode with ''Whiz Kids''), ''[[Highway to Heaven]]'', ''[[Night Court]]'', ''[[Paradise (TV series)|Paradise]]'', and ''[[Silk Stalkings]]''.\n\nMore recently, Labyorteaux has worked as a [[Voice acting|voice actor]], providing characterizations in [[video game]]s and [[Animation|animated]] features, [[Dubbing (filmmaking)#Automated Dialogue Replacement/post-sync|additional dialogue recording]] in film and television, and [[voice-over]] in [[Advertising|advertisements]].\n\n==Personal life==\nLabyorteaux was born in Los Angeles and adopted by interior designer and talent agent Ronald Labyorteaux (1930\u201392) and actress Frances Marshall (1927\u20132012). He is the younger brother of [[Patrick Labyorteaux|Patrick]], also adopted and also an actor, and Jane. \n\nLabyorteaux is a skilled video game player. In October 1981, he finished in 10th place for ''[[Centipede (video game)|Centipede]]'' at the [[Atari, Inc.]] world championships. In April 1982, he became the United States ''[[Pac-Man]]'' champion at a ''[[People (magazine)|People]]''-sponsored tournament, with a score of 1,200,000.<ref name=\"softline198209\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1982&pub=6&id=7|title=Pac-Man Champ: Ready on the Set|work=Softline|date=September 1982|accessdate=July 27, 2014|pages=9}}</ref>\n\nIn 1992, Matthew and Patrick founded the Youth Rescue Fund (which was partnered with Los Angeles Youth Supportive Services), a charity organization that assists young people in crisis, and they have since engaged in [[fundraising]] for youth [[Emergency shelter|shelters]] across the U.S. The organization is no longer active.\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Notes\n|-\n|1974\n|''[[A Woman Under the Influence]]''\n|Angelo Longhetti\n|\n|-\n|1978\n|''[[King of the Gypsies (film)|King of the Gypsies]]''\n|Middle Dave\n|\n|-\n|1986\n|''[[Deadly Friend]]''\n|Paul Conway\n|\n|-\n|1998\n|''[[Mulan (1998 film)|Mulan]]''\n|rowspan=\"3\" | Additional Voices\n|\n|-\n|2006\n|''[[Everyone's Hero]]''\n|\n|-\n|2009\n|''[[Bride Wars]]'' \n|\n|-\n|2011\n|''[[Yu-Gi-Oh!: Bonds Beyond Time]]'' \n|Jaden Yuki (voice)\n|English dub\n|-\n|2013\n|''[[The Wind Rises]]''\n|rowspan=\"2\" | Additional Voices\n|English dub\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Next Gen (film)|Next Gen]]''\n|\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Notes\n|-\n|1975\n|''[[The Rookies]]''\n|Jody Gifford\n|Episode: \"Lamb to the Slaughter\"\n|-\n|1975\n|''[[Phyllis (TV series)|Phyllis]]''\n|Child\n|Episode: \"There's No Business Like No Business\"\n|-\n|1976;<br>1978\u201383\n|''[[Little House on the Prairie (TV series)|Little House on the Prairie]]''\n|[[List of Little House on the Prairie characters#The Ingalls Family|Albert Quinn Ingalls]], Young [[Charles Ingalls]]\n|89 episodes\n|-\n|1976\n|''[[Special Treat|NBC Special Treat]]''\n|Billy\n|Episode: \"Papa and Me\"\n|-\n|1976\n|''[[The Practice (1976 TV series)|The Practice]]''\n|Pete\n|Episode: \"Judy Sinclair\"\n|-\n|1976\n|''[[Doc (1975 TV series)|Doc]]''\n|David\n|Episode: The Death of a Turtle\n|-\n|1976\n|''[[The Bob Newhart Show]]''\n|Richie\n|Episode: \"My Boy Guillermo\"\n|-\n|1977\n|''A Circle of Children''\n|Brian O'Connell\n|Television film\n|-\n|1977\n|''[[Most Wanted (1976 TV series)|Most Wanted]]''\n|Billy Joe Nelson\n|Episode: \"The Tunnel Killer\"\n|-\n|1977\n|''[[Mulligan's Stew]]''\n|Duane\n|Episode: \"Biggest Mansion\"\n|-\n|1977\n|''[[The Red Hand Gang]]''\n|Frankie\n|12 episodes\n|-\n|1977\n|''[[Tarantulas: The Deadly Cargo]]''\n|Matthew Beck\n|Television film\n|-\n|1977\n|''[[Mary Hartman, Mary Hartman]]''\n|Johnny Doe / Wild Child\n|23 episodes\n|-\n|1978\n|''Killing Stone''\n|Christopher Stone\n|Television film\n|-\n|1979\n|''[[List of Little House on the Prairie episodes#Season 6 .281979.E2.80.931980.29|Little House Years]]''\n|Albert Ingalls\n|Television film\n|-\n|1979\n|''[[Lou Grant (TV series)|Lou Grant]]''\n|Mark Donner\n|Episode: \"Kids\"\n|-\n|1980\n|''[[Here's Boomer]]''\n|Jesse\n|Episode: \"Jailbreak\"\n|-\n|1980\n|''The Aliens Are Coming''\n|Timmy Garner\n|Television film\n|-\n|1982\n|''[[The Love Boat]]''\n|Chip Bronson\n|Episode: \"Winning Isn't Everything\"\n|-\n|1983\n|''[[List of Little House on the Prairie episodes#Post-series movie specials .281983.E2.80.931984.29|Little House: Look Back to Yesterday]]''\n|Albert Ingalls\n|Television film\n|-\n|1983\n|''[[Simon & Simon]]''\n|Richie Adler\n|Episode: \"Fly the Alibi Skies\"\n|-\n|1983\u201384\n|''[[Whiz Kids (TV series)|Whiz Kids]]''\n|Richie Adler\n|18 episodes\n|-\n|1985\n|''[[Amazing Stories (1985 TV series)|Amazing Stories]]''\n|Andy\n|Episode: \"Fine Tuning\"\n|-\n|1985\n|''[[Highway to Heaven]]''\n|Matt Haynes\n|Episode: \"The Right Thing\"\n|-\n|1986\n|''[[Shattered Spirits]]''\n|Ken Mollencamp\n|Television film\n|-\n|1988\n|''[[Hotel (U.S. TV series)|Hotel]]''\n|Mark Daniels\n|Episode: \"Double Take\"\n|-\n|1989\n|''[[Night Court]]''\n|Bobby Johnson\n|2 episodes\n|-\n|1990\n|''[[Paradise (TV series)|Paradise]]''\n|Sam Devitt\n|Episode: \"The Coward\"\n|-\n|1991\n|''The Last to Go''\n|Nathan Holover\n|Television film\n|-\n|1991\n|''[[Silk Stalkings]]''\n|Jason Dietz\n|Episode: \"Dirty Laundry\"\n|-\n|1993\n|''[[Barbarians at the Gate (film)|Barbarians at the Gate]]''\n|Teenage [[F. Ross Johnson]]\n|Television film\n|-\n|1995\n|''[[Aaahh!!! Real Monsters]]''\n|Rob, Chuck (voices)\n|Episode: \"Eau de Krumm/O'Lucky Monster\"\n|-\n|2005\u201306\n|''[[G.I. Joe: Sigma 6]]''\n|Scott Abernathy (voice)\n|7 episodes\n|-\n|2005\u201308\n|''[[Yu-Gi-Oh! GX]]''\n|Jaden Yuki/The Supreme King (voice)\n|155 episodes\n|-\n|2007\n|''[[Winx Club]]''\n|Nabu (voice)\n|6 episodes\n|}\n\n===Video games===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n|-\n|2003\u201304\n|''[[.hack (video game series)|.hack]]'' series\n|Additional Voices\n|-\n|2006\n|''[[Thrillville]]''\n|Adult Male #1, Announcer\n|-\n|2007\n|''[[Thrillville: Off the Rails]]''\n|Accountant, Adult Male #1, Announcer, Tank Player\n|-\n|2011\n|''[[Star Wars: The Old Republic]]'' \n|Additional Voices\n|-\n|2012\n|''[[Kinect Star Wars]]''\n|Gold 5, Padawan #2\n|-\n|2013\n|''[[Gangstar Vegas]]''\n|Male Casino Dealer, Radio Ads\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[Yu-Gi-Oh! Duel Links]]''\n|Jaden Yuki, Jaden/Yubel\n|}\n\n==Accolades==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Association\n! Category\n! Work\n! Result\n|-\n|1983\n|rowspan=3| [[Young Artist Awards]]\n|Best Young Actor in a Drama Series\n|''Little House on the Prairie''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 1984\n|Best Young Actor in a New Television Series\n|''Whiz Kids''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|Best Young Actor in a Drama Series\n|''Little House on the Prairie''\n|{{nom}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Matthew Labyorteaux}}\n*{{IMDb name|0479612}}\n*{{ann|people|id=48983|name=Matthew Charles}}\n*{{ann|people|id=132888|name=Matthew Labyorteaux}}\n*[http://littlehouseontheprairie.com/about-patrick-laborteaux-and-matthew-laborteaux/ About Patrick Laborteaux and Matthew Laborteaux]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Labyorteaux, Matthew}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:American adoptees]]\n[[Category:American male child actors]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male voice actors]]\n[[Category:American people of French-Canadian descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Los Angeles]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American film, television, and voice actor}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox person \n|name    = Matthew Labyorteaux\n|image   = Little House on the Prairie Katy Kurtzman Matthew Laborteaux 1977 No 2.jpg\n|caption = Labyorteaux and [[Katy Kurtzman]] on ''[[Little House on the Prairie (TV series)|Little House on the Prairie]]'', 1977\n|birth_name = Matthew Charles Labyorteaux\n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1966|12|8|mf=yes}}\n|birth_place = [[Los Angeles|Los Angeles, California]], U.S.\n|occupation = Actor\n|years_active = 1972\u2013present\n|known_for = Role of [[List of Little House on the Prairie characters#The Ingalls family|Albert Quinn Ingalls]] on ''Little House on the Prairie''\n}}\n\n'''Matthew Charles Labyorteaux''' (born December 8, 1966) is an [[Americans|American]] film, television and voice actor.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Reilly|first=S.|editor-last=Donovan|editor-first=H|editor-link=Hedley Donovan|date=September 11, 1978|title=Landon's ''Little'' Kids|journal=[[People (magazine)|People Weekly]]|volume=10|issue=11|pages=92\u201396 |publisher=[[Time Inc.|Time]]|location=[[Chicago|Chicago, IL]]|issn=0093-7673 |url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20071697,00.html|accessdate=August 31, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Harris|first=H.|editor-last=Roberts|editor-first=E. L., Jr|editor-link=Gene Roberts (journalist)|date=December 20, 1981|title=Laborteaux Trio: Matt, Pat, and Mom|journal=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]|page=TV04|publisher=[[John S. Knight|J. S. Knight]] |location=Philadelphia, PA|issn=0885-6613|url=http://www.melissasueandersonfan.com/LABORTEAUX%20TRIO.pdf|format=PDF|accessdate=July 15, 2012}}</ref> In many of his credits, his last name is spelled as \"'''Laborteaux'''\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0479612/|title=Matthew Labyorteaux|publisher=IMdb|accessdate=August 22, 2015}}</ref> He is also credited as '''Matthew Charles''' for his work in animation.\n\nHe may be best known for portraying [[List of Little House on the Prairie characters#The Ingalls family|Albert Quinn Ingalls]]<ref name=\"Matthew Labyorteaux Biography\">{{cite web|title=Matthew Labyorteaux|url=http://www.biography.com/people/matthew-labyorteaux|website=Biography.com |accessdate=August 22, 2015}}</ref> on  ''[[Little House on the Prairie (TV series)|Little House on the Prairie]]'' from 1978\u201383. He is also known as the voice of Jaden Yuki and The Supreme King in ''[[Yu-Gi-Oh! GX]]'' from 2005\u201308.\n\n==Career==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=November 2016}}\nLabyorteaux began working in commercials at the age of seven, having been discovered while accompanying his older brother, [[Patrick Labyorteaux]], to a casting call. He shortly thereafter landed his first dramatic role in ''[[A Woman Under the Influence]]'', where he played one of [[Peter Falk]] and [[Gena Rowlands]]' children.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Notes From The Wasteland: A Special Friendship|last=Norton|first=Paula|date=7 February 1976|work=Argus-Courier|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nAside from his tenure on ''Little House on the Prairie'', Labyorteaux also starred in the short-lived television series ''[[The Red Hand Gang]]'' (1977) and ''[[Whiz Kids (TV series)|Whiz Kids]]'' (1983\u201384), in addition to several [[Television film|made-for-television movies]]. His most prominent film role was in [[Wes Craven]]'s ''[[Deadly Friend]]'' (1986) as Paul Conway, a young genius who resurrects a dead girl using an [[artificial intelligence]] [[microchip]] from a [[robot]] he created that had previously been destroyed by a malicious neighbor.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=\u2019Deadly Friend\u2019 Slows Flow of Gore|last=Goldstein|first=Patrick|date=14 October 1986|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nHe made guest appearances on numerous television shows, including ''[[The Rookies]]'', ''[[The Bob Newhart Show]]'', ''[[Mulligan's Stew]]'', ''[[Lou Grant (TV series)|Lou Grant]]'', ''[[Here's Boomer]]'' ([[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]] of ''The Red Hand Gang''), ''[[The Love Boat]]'', ''[[Simon & Simon]]'' ([[crossover (fiction)|crossover]] episode with ''Whiz Kids''), ''[[Highway to Heaven]]'', ''[[Night Court]]'', ''[[Paradise (TV series)|Paradise]]'', and ''[[Silk Stalkings]]''.\n\nMore recently, Labyorteaux has worked as a [[Voice acting|voice actor]], providing characterizations in [[video game]]s and [[Animation|animated]] features, [[Dubbing (filmmaking)#Automated Dialogue Replacement/post-sync|additional dialogue recording]] in film and television, and [[voice-over]] in [[Advertising|advertisements]].\n\n==Personal life==\nLabyorteaux was born in Los Angeles and adopted by interior designer and talent agent Ronald Labyorteaux (1930\u201392) and actress Frances Marshall (1927\u20132012). He is the younger brother of [[Patrick Labyorteaux|Patrick]], also adopted and also an actor, and Jane. \n\nLabyorteaux is a skilled video game player. In October 1981, he finished in 10th place for ''[[Centipede (video game)|Centipede]]'' at the [[Atari, Inc.]] world championships. In April 1982, he became the United States ''[[Pac-Man]]'' champion at a ''[[People (magazine)|People]]''-sponsored tournament, with a score of 1,200,000.<ref name=\"softline198209\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1982&pub=6&id=7|title=Pac-Man Champ: Ready on the Set|work=Softline|date=September 1982|accessdate=July 27, 2014|pages=9}}</ref>\n\nIn 1992, Matthew and Patrick founded the Youth Rescue Fund (which was partnered with Los Angeles Youth Supportive Services), a charity organization that assists young people in crisis, and they have since engaged in [[fundraising]] for youth [[Emergency shelter|shelters]] across the U.S. The organization is no longer active.\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Notes\n|-\n|1974\n|''[[A Woman Under the Influence]]''\n|Angelo Longhetti\n|\n|-\n|1978\n|''[[King of the Gypsies (film)|King of the Gypsies]]''\n|Middle Dave\n|\n|-\n|1986\n|''[[Deadly Friend]]''\n|Paul Conway\n|\n|-\n|1998\n|''[[Mulan (1998 film)|Mulan]]''\n|rowspan=\"3\" | Additional Voices\n|\n|-\n|2006\n|''[[Everyone's Hero]]''\n|\n|-\n|2009\n|''[[Bride Wars]]'' \n|\n|-\n|2011\n|''[[Yu-Gi-Oh!: Bonds Beyond Time]]'' \n|Jaden Yuki (voice)\n|English dub\n|-\n|2013\n|''[[The Wind Rises]]''\n|rowspan=\"2\" | Additional Voices\n|English dub\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Next Gen (film)|Next Gen]]''\n|\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Notes\n|-\n|1975\n|''[[The Rookies]]''\n|Jody Gifford\n|Episode: \"Lamb to the Slaughter\"\n|-\n|1975\n|''[[Phyllis (TV series)|Phyllis]]''\n|Child\n|Episode: \"There's No Business Like No Business\"\n|-\n|1976;<br>1978\u201383\n|''[[Little House on the Prairie (TV series)|Little House on the Prairie]]''\n|[[List of Little House on the Prairie characters#The Ingalls Family|Albert Quinn Ingalls]], Young [[Charles Ingalls]]\n|89 episodes\n|-\n|1976\n|''[[Special Treat|NBC Special Treat]]''\n|Billy\n|Episode: \"Papa and Me\"\n|-\n|1976\n|''[[The Practice (1976 TV series)|The Practice]]''\n|Pete\n|Episode: \"Judy Sinclair\"\n|-\n|1976\n|''[[Doc (1975 TV series)|Doc]]''\n|David\n|Episode: The Death of a Turtle\n|-\n|1976\n|''[[The Bob Newhart Show]]''\n|Richie\n|Episode: \"My Boy Guillermo\"\n|-\n|1977\n|''A Circle of Children''\n|Brian O'Connell\n|Television film\n|-\n|1977\n|''[[Most Wanted (1976 TV series)|Most Wanted]]''\n|Billy Joe Nelson\n|Episode: \"The Tunnel Killer\"\n|-\n|1977\n|''[[Mulligan's Stew]]''\n|Duane\n|Episode: \"Biggest Mansion\"\n|-\n|1977\n|''[[The Red Hand Gang]]''\n|Frankie\n|12 episodes\n|-\n|1977\n|''[[Tarantulas: The Deadly Cargo]]''\n|Matthew Beck\n|Television film\n|-\n|1977\n|''[[Mary Hartman, Mary Hartman]]''\n|Johnny Doe / Wild Child\n|23 episodes\n|-\n|1978\n|''Killing Stone''\n|Christopher Stone\n|Television film\n|-\n|1979\n|''[[List of Little 